<SLUG> BC-SAMARITAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN-TOTING CITIZEN ASSISTSPOLICE CAPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He drives a late-model Kia with a National Rifle Association
decal on the front window and ``Keep Honking, I'm Reloading''
emblazoned on the license-plate holder.
</P>
<P>
   He packs heat to work every night at his security-guard job and
has never hesitated to use it.
</P>
<P>
   So, a burly 27-year-old man named Rory Vertigan was the last guy
that three Mexican nationals arrested in the shooting death of
Phoenix police Officer Marc Atkinson wanted to see in their
rear-view mirror at the murder scene near 30th Avenue and Thomas
Road late Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After the suspects pointed their weapons at him, Vertigan opened
fire with his 9 mm Glock, raking the vehicle with 14 rounds and
wounding one of the men in the back. When the man opened his door
and tried to run from the vehicle, Vertigan tackled him.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan's valor was widely applauded in Phoenix police circles
for allowing officers to quickly catch up with and arrest the three
men.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Harold Hurtt was effusive in his praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That individual is one of the true heroes of our time,'' Hurtt
said. ``He realizes the officer is in trouble. Without regard for
his own personal safety, he confronted these individuals, engaged
in a gunbattle. He put his life on the line for an officer and a
fellow human being.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement Saturday, Vertigan said he was only
reacting to ``what I thought was the right thing to do.'' He said
he figured he had to do something after watching Atkinson being
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I confronted the individuals in the white vehicle, they
turned their guns on me. I was given no choice but to defend myself
with my weapon,'' Vertigan said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's something he's never hesitated to do, said Marilyn
Greenwood, Vertigan's sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had to use it a couple of times on his job,'' Greenwood
said. ``But I don't know if he's really hit anybody before.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood and Vertigan's mother, Joanne Vertigan, said that Rory
Vertigan was driving in that area after running an errand and
dropping his boss off at home. Vertigan manages an apartment
complex near 27th Avenue and Glendale Avenue during the day and
works as a security guard at night, Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Rory Vertigan had followed the suspects' white Lincoln
Continental for a short distance and saw them stop. He also stopped
about 50 feet behind the suspects' vehicle. One of the men got out
and fired numerous rounds at Atkinson, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The three men then turned their attention to Vertigan, Greenwood
said. After weapons were pointed at him, Vertigan pulled out his
Glock, stuck it out the driver's-side window with his left hand and
fired several rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants then slammed their car into reverse and struck
Vertigan's front bumper, leaving their license-plate number
imprinted in dust. They pulled forward and Vertigan continued
firing, striking one of the men with a round that went through the
back window and the seat in which he was sitting, Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he emptied the clip with 14 shots and all of them went
inside the car. He thought that was pretty good since he shot quite
a few of them with his off hand, hanging out the window,''
Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan saw one of the men fleeing the scene out of the corner
of his eye before he tackled the man he shot, she said, adding that
he told her that he never saw the third suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan had designs on being a policeman as a child in Tucson
and had taken law-enforcement classes at Pima Community College,
his sister and mother said.
</P>
<P>
   But after managing a Tucson fast-food restaurant for a couple
years, Vertigan decided to embark upon a career as a private
investigator. He also dabbled in security-guard work, providing
security at three Miss Arizona Pageants in the early 1990s, Joanne
Vertigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan had been working at his current jobs for the past six
years, Greenwood said, and has been cited by the city for his work
in Block Watch organizations along the 27th Avenue corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwood said that her brother also has had a concealed-weapons
permit for several years and had just had it renewed shortly before
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Vertigan, who was interviewed throughout the day Saturday by
police detectives, thanked police for providing professional
counseling ``so that I can better deal with the stress I incurred
during this traumatic event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need time for healing,'' he said in his prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
