<HEADLINE>
SWIMMER HALL DIAGNOSED WITH DIABETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Olympic gold and silver medalist Gary Hall Jr. is
contemplating retirement from swimming after learning last week
that he has diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm considering retirement at this point,'' said Hall, who
withdrew from this week's national championships in New York after
he was told by a family physician that diabetes is the reason he
has begun to suffer from bouts of fatigue and dizziness. ``It's not
just for any one event. It's for a whole string of events.''
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes is just the latest blow in Hall's career since 1996,
when he finished second to Russian sprinter Alexander Popov in a
couple of memorable Olympic duels and then anchored two gold
medal-winning relays for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hall was suspended for three months last summer by the
International Olympic Committee after the IOC ruled that he tested
positive for marijuana. The test and the IOC ruling were
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Hall eventually won an 11th-hour court order in Phoenix that
allowed him to compete in September in a World Cup meet at Baylor
University. He went on to win the 50-meter freestyle over Brazil's
Fernando Scherer, the world's top-ranked sprinter this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspension still cost him a lucrative endorsement deal
with Speedo.
</P>
<P>
   Hall always has been at odds with USA Swimming, a U.S. Olympic
Committee organization that runs the sport nationally. Some coaches
and officials have been unhappy with Hall's offbeat, go-it-alone
style.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1998 World Championships at Perth, Australia, he faced
a disciplinary hearing for alleged transgressions of a conduct
code. One of the charges involved his decision to wear a wig for
the team picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole string of events has made me wonder,'' said Hall,
who had been training at Arizona State in an attempt to retain the
50- and 100-meter freestyle titles he won at last spring's
nationals. ``I don't enjoy it anymore. I really don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 24, said he will think through his options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to retreat, look at the future and try to come up
with a strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he decides to continue at swimming's highest level, he will
have to learn how live and train with diabetes. Hall's agent, Janey
Miller, said he has started insulin injections and is working on
stabilizing his blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learning to adjust to this new situation and hopes to be
back in the pool soon,'' Miller said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he saw his physician after feeling weak nine days ago.
He said he also had suffered from unusual fatigue after workouts
during the past couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arms would shake, and I thought that maybe it was just from
hard training,'' Hall said. ``At the time, I thought that was good.
But maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is considered to be perhaps America's greatest swimming
talent. He has been projected as a gold medal contender at the 2000
Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 at Atlanta, one of his memorable performances came on
the anchor leg of the 400-meter freestyle relay. Hall was timed at
47.45 seconds, the fastest relay split in history.
</P>
<P>
   In the individual 100 freestyle, his best time, 48.81, puts him
among a handful of men ever to have gone faster than 49. In the
individual event, nobody has been faster than 48. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
