</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-BLAZERS-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAIL BLAZERS CHECK EGOS, FILL ROLE OF TITLE CONTENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In a strange NBA season known for missed shots and a
missing person, there actually is some news that proves the game
itself has not gone on a Dennis Rodman walkabout.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, meeting them is probably not what the struggling Suns
have in mind tonight at America West Arena. The Suns are in need of
a little R&AMP;R at this point. But the Los Angeles Clippers aren't
available.
</P>
<P>
   So, ready or not, the Suns will have take their chances against
the Blazers for the second time in four nights. If Thursday night's
result _ a 97-84 Portland victory _ is any indication, the Suns
don't have much of chance. Nonetheless, there is admiration.
</P>
<P>
   In the Blazers, there is plenty to admire.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, they were the problem children of the NBA.
Jail Blazers and Bail Raisers.
</P>
<P>
   But in this shortened season, old problems have vanished. The
Blazers have gone from trouble to the top. How did it happen?
There's nothing magic about it. Rodman's hair styles change and the
crossover dribble replaces the slam as the flavor of the day, but
the game's fundamentals stay the same. The Blazers have been
preaching unselfishness, depth, defense and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Boring? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But the old ethics are as ruthlessly efficient as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say that it's easy, and the bottom line is that it's
not over,'' said Blazers Coach Mike Dunleavy, who is among the
leading candidates for Coach of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Blazers appear to be maturing at a pace that
makes them real contenders. They have the league's best record, and
there's no sign that they are about to slip from the perch. Above
all, the old problem kids have learned to trim the sails on their
egos.
</P>
<P>
   The value of roles within a larger system has been a key to the
Portland success. What's more, that has allowed Dunleavy to
distribute playing time throughout his deep roster. In a compressed
season with four and five games a week, Portland's talented, rested
bench has been able to overwhelm fatigued opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come at you with wave after wave,'' Suns center Luc
Longley said. ``It's as if they have 20 talented guys sitting on
that bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Portland's roster isn't any larger than any other in
the league. But with an acceptance of diminished minutes and
changing roles, Longley's count is accurate in one respect: The
Blazers throw more combinations onto the floor than any other NBA
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys have embraced the idea of winning,'' said Dunleavy,
whose club plays a ferocious perimeter defense that starts with
Isaiah Rider and former University of Arizona star Damon Stoudamire
and continues with Jim Jackson, Stacey Augmon, Greg Anthony, Walt
Williams and Kelvin Cato. ``The fact is that we have a lot of
depth. Because guys are playing well, there are going to be nights
when one guy gets more minutes than another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens to be at your position, you just have to check
your ego at the door and be satisfied with the fact that we're
winning. That's what it takes to win. So far, it's worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of Portland's success came through player
acquisitions. The Blazers do not have a lottery draft pick of their
own. But through trades or free agency, General Manager Bob
Whitsitt put together a team that includes 10 players who were
lottery picks of other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and count them: Rider, Stoudamire, starting forward
Brian Grant, Rasheed Wallace, Williams, Jackson, Anthony, Augmon,
Carlos Rogers and Bonzi Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of them arrived in Portland marked by some difficult
times at other NBA stops. Call it a mark of maturity. The result is
a team that can play a front line that averages nearly 7 feet. It
also can play its own version of small ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe one or two combinations aren't working, but we can go
with so many,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   For the opposition, it's a rigged game of Russian roulette.
There's a bullet in every chamber. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
