<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-US-MEXICO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S SOCCER TEAM NEEDS TUNEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It begins here, today, at the Rose Bowl.
Whether it ends here in July is a little less certain than it was a
short time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the U.S. national team still is favored to win Women's World
Cup '99, which will conclude with the championship match at the
Rose Bowl. There is no need to panic and perform a complete
overhaul, even if there were enough time, which there isn't. But as
the team embarks on its ``Road to Pasadena'' tour, a tuneup
certainly is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Today's match with Mexico is the first stop on the tour. The
game begins at 3 p.m. (Arizona time) and will be the opener of a
doubleheader, with East Valley native Greg Vanney's Los Angeles
Galaxy and the Dallas Burn of MLS to follow. The U.S. team will
play eight other matches before the World Cup begins June 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games are key to us fine-tuning and preparing for the
biggest challenge that this team has ever faced,'' U.S. Coach Tony
DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   The tour was supposed to be highlighted by Mia Hamm's
record-setting 108th international goal, or maybe even a
celebration of her having set the mark during the Algarve Cup two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamm failed to tally in Portugal, leaving her three behind
former Italian star Elisabetta Vignotto's international
goal-scoring record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mia had a very good performance,'' DiCicco said after
a practice session Saturday. ``It's just that because of the
incredible year she had last year, she is the object of a lot of
attention on the soccer field. She may not have scored, but she had
some assists, and she drew attention so other players could have
opportunities. That's what Mia's game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm wasn't the only American shut out during the Cup. In fact,
if not for a four-goal outburst against Finland and Tiffeny
Milbrett's Cup-high four tallies, the U.S. team might have left
Portugal in shame instead of in second place.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. team enters today's match with a 6-1-1 record
in 1999, the lack of scoring might be a concern. Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' DiCicco said. ``Teams have just
not been playing very open games against us, and we've run up
against some very good goalkeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is one of the weaker teams that qualified for the World
Cup, and the U.S. team posted convincing victories the three
previous times the teams have met.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico appears to be on the rise, having defeated Argentina
in a two-game playoff to earn the final World Cup berth. In that
series, Mexico started six Mexican-Americans, including sensational
midfielder Laurie Hill of West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they went out and looked for help from some of the
better Mexican-American players, so they won't be the same team we
faced last time,'' DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no disrespect to Mexico, I'm more concerned about my team.
We need to go out with the right mentality, and we have to
execute.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
