<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT PAYS PRICE IN BID FOR 3RD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who were the big winners and the big losers at last week's NHL
trading deadline?
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, Buffalo, San Jose and the Coyotes all helped
themselves, joining Colorado and Philadelphia, which made earlier
moves by acquiring stars  &UR; Theo Fleury and  &UR; Mark Recchi,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes got the scoring punch they wanted at center on the
second line by stealing  &UR; Robert Reichel away from the Islanders.
The Sharks got stronger by adding  &UR; Vincent Damphousse. And the
Sabres improved by bringing in  &UR; Joe Juneau from Washington and
 &UR; Rhett Warrener from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings, of course, made the most noise, blowing away the
rest of the league by not only picking up  &UR; Ulf Samuelsson from the
Rangers, but then by trading for Chicago Blackhawks defenseman
 &UR; Chris Chelios, who reportedly asked to be dealt. After that, they
made two separate deals with Tampa Bay and acquired  &UR; Wendel Clark
and then  &UR; Bill Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it and I've been in this
business for 30 years,'' Detroit Coach Scotty Bowman said. ``I
think it gives us a better feeling in the room that this team means
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings gave up a ton in loading themselves up to make a
couple more runs at the Stanley Cup. Two first-round picks to
Chicago and a great young player in  &UR; Anders Ericksson, a former
first-round pick himself, for the 37-year-old Chelios. A
second-round pick and goalie
 &UR; Kevin Hodson to Tampa for the 32-year-old Clark. A second- and
third-round pick to New York for the 35-year-old Samuelsson. A
conditional pick to Tampa for the 32-year-old Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Detroit doesn't own a single pick in the first three
rounds of the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sit here and tell you we're not going to miss what we
gave up,'' Red Wings General Manager  &UR; Ken Holland said. ``But if
you want to win, that's what you have to do. Look at what Colorado
gave up for Fleury, and he isn't signed beyond this year.''
</P>
<P>
   They're hilariously happy in Hockeytown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the confidence (to try to win a third straight Cup),
but playing the way we have all year, probably not,'' wing  &UR; Darren
McCarty said. ``But none of that matters now.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't guarantee the Red Wings of scoring a championship hat
trick, but they definitely become one of the favorites again. Too
bad Dallas didn't do more than add  &UR; Derek Plante, who might not
play above the fourth line, and reacquire oldster  &UR; Benoit Hogue.
The Stars could have used more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff-bound Pittsburgh, Carolina, Boston and New Jersey did
next to nothing, which was a surprise. But the biggest
disappointment has to be Calgary, a club very alive in the
postseason race despite trading away Fleury, which only picked up
 &UR; Tom Chorske from the Capitals _ hardly a payoff for how hard the
Flames players have been working. &QL; 
Trade Day memories &QL; 
Mighty Ducks forward  &UR; Jim McKenzie, a former Coyote, remembers
sweating it out four years ago on the last day of the trading
deadline while he was playing in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With about an hour to go before the deadline passes, his
telephone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped out of my skin and grabbed the phone,'' McKenzie
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only teammate  &UR; Gord Donnelly, calling to see whether he
needed a ride to practice. Knowing how nervous McKenzie was,
Donnelly couldn't resist calling again about 10 minutes later. This
time, he wanted to know whether McKenzie wanted to stop for some
coffee on the way.
</P>
<P>
   You know what's coming next, right? Ten minutes later, the phone
rings again, and McKenzie is furious.
</P>
<P>
   Only it wasn't Donnelly. It was Stars General Manager  &UR; Bob
Gainey, who after listening to the unsuspecting McKenzie rant and
rave, politely told him, ``You've been traded to Pittsburgh.'' &QL; 
Dom and dumber &QL; 
You'll never guess what Buffalo Sabres goalie  &UR; Dominik Hasek did
last week.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of a friend, tennis player  &UR; Petr Korda, the
two-time Hart Trophy winner actually asked and received permission
from the club to travel all the way to Germany to consult with a
Munich physician about his nagging groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is not an early April Fool's joke. We are not making
this up.
</P>
<P>
   Please. Like they're aren't any qualified doctors a little
closer to seek for a second opinion? That the Sabres even let him
go is an absolute joke.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. The plane ride alone couldn't have helped his
pulled muscle. But forget that. Before he left, Hasek already had
returned from the injured list and played three straight
outstanding games, reporting little to no pain afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dom, 95 percent is not good enough,'' General Manager
Darcy Regier said. ``He's intent on getting back to 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek flew back Friday night and was in nets for Saturday's game
against the Pittsburgh Penguins, stopping 36 of 37 shots in a 1-1
tie. &QL; 
LA Confidential &QL; 
In the world of free agency, Los Angeles Kings General Manager
 &UR; Dave &UR; Taylor was saying the other day, teams generally have to
commit to shelling out more dollars and more years than they
usually think a player is worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in a lot of cases,'' Taylor said, ``you don't get a fair
return for your investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with defenseman  &UR; Steve Duchesne, whom the
Kings lured away from St. Louis with a four-year contract worth $15
million. After scoring only four goals and adding 19 assists in 60
games, and getting beat too often in his own zone, the Kings
decided to place the veteran on waivers.
</P>
<P>
   When nobody was silly enough to pick him up, the club bought
Duchesne out of his contract, eating $4.25 million, and then
shipped him to Philadelphia for  &UR; Dave Babych and a draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a very difficult, very expensive lesson,'' Taylor
said. ``I don't know if you will see us too active in the free
agent market in the future.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602- 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
