<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN RETURN AS OWNER WOULD BE PERFECT FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You just knew  &UR; Michael Jordan couldn't stay out of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   He may have hung up his Airs, but it appears Jordan is close to
returning to the league as an owner of the Charlotte Hornets. The
``Charlotte Observer'' reported Saturday that Jordan and the club's
current owner,  &UR; George Shinn, are negotiating such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA confirmed it by releasing a statement from
Commissioner
 &UR; David Stern, which said Jordan is seeking 50 percent of the club.
It would seem to be the perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan gets back into the game, and he does it in North
Carolina, where he grew up and led the University of North Carolina
to an NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Shinn, who is fighting a civil action that accuses him of sexual
assault and a divorce action, can go back to Florida, save 7.5
percent on the transaction in sales tax and remain in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets once were one of the most popular teams in the
league. While they never went deep into the playoffs, they had some
on-court success and their merchandise was among the best-selling
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   But Shinn, who has sought a new arena, was cheap. He let  &UR; Alonzo
 &UR; Mourning go to Miami because he didn't want to pay him. He let
 &UR; Vlade
 &UR; Divac and  &UR; Matt Geiger exit last summer because he didn't want to
pay them, either. The club recently unloaded All-Star  &UR; Glen Rice,
and Coach
 &UR; Dave Cowens resigned this year in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has the money to make it work. He reportedly generates
annual endorsement income of about $45 million. The club reportedly
is valued at about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one catch. It's difficult to imagine Jordan taking
anything less than controlling interest in the team. A 50-50 split
doesn't make sense. The guess here is that Jordan will have
control, or he won't make the deal. &QL; 
He's high on Phil &QL; 
Miami Coach  &UR; Pat Riley took a little swipe at  &UR; Phil Jackson, the
former Bulls coach who is spending his time working with
presidential hopeful &UR; Bill Bradley, after Jackson suggested that
this season's NBA champion will be tainted by a season shortened to
50 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it's the effect of that window pane he took in
'70, I just really do,'' Riley said, referring to a street name for
LSD. ``Those synapses don't fire like they used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a non-active right now. He should have no opinion about
the NBA. He's not in it. He would love it to be tainted because
he's the only one that's tasted victory the last six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Well actually,  &UR; Rudy Tomjanovich tasted it twice in Houston.
Maybe Riles ran into that ``window pane'' somewhere along the way. &QL; 
Oooooops &QL; 
Atlanta's  &UR; Alan Henderson was fined $3,500 by the league for
throwing a ball over the lower stands at the Georgia Dome during a
loss to Milwaukee. But the fine didn't hurt nearly as much as this:
The ball struck the face of  &UR; Nancy Mutombo, the 13-year-old
daughter of Henderson's teammate,  &UR; Dikembe Mutombo. She was not
seriously hurt but was treated at a first aid station, where she
remained for the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a freak thing,'' said Dikembe Mutombo, who accepted
Henderson's apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it wasn't serious, no matter who it was,''
Henderson said. &QL; 
Promises, promises &QL; 
After another humiliating loss, this time to Cleveland, Boston
Coach &UR; Rick Pitino said he'd had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to stay positive, upbeat, but that was humiliating
defense,'' Pitino said. ``I've seen the Washington Generals play
defense better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team that I haven't raised my voice this year and I
understand the lockout has prevented us from teaching the little
things of the game. There reaches a point, though, and I won't be
humiliated. Yes, it's all well and good that next year is next
year, but I'm going to watch this film and if people are
humiliating the Boston Celtics, they're not going to play anymore.
It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino added that he could win more games with a Continental
Basketball Association team that is good on defense. Then he
started the same players in Boston's next game. &QL; 
Keep the Candy &QL; 
Toronto Coach  &UR; Butch Carter is thanking his stars and the NBA
lottery every time he watches rookie  &UR; Vince Carter create another
highlight and take another step toward the Rookie of the Year
award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get bigger,''  &UR; Butch Carter said. ``So we
probably would have drafted (7-l center)  &UR; Michael Olowokandi.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers drafted Olowokandi with the first overall pick, and
they have the league's worst record. The Raptors drafted North
Carolina's
 &UR; Antawn Jamison at No. 4 and traded him for Tar Heel teammate  &UR; Vince
 &UR; Carter, picked at No. 5 by Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were playing the Clippers the other night,'' Butch
Carter said, ``I turned, looked at my assistant coaches and said,
`If we had taken Olowokandi, we would have been fired by now.'' &QL; 
New tune &QL; 
 &UR; Scottie Pippen has softened his stance somewhat about being left
out of the offense in Houston. He sounded off after Houston lost a
game in Phoenix and complained that he wasn't involved.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says he wasn't campaigning for more shots, just
opportunities to have the ball in his hands, to score or create for
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty much what it was _ it's not about me trying to
do anything offensively, asking for more shots or anything,''
Pippen said. ``It's more about the opportunity to be involved and
helping to get everybody else set up and sort of get some type of
rhythm to our offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better. I feel like I'm being utilized, and I'm
able to be a big part of the team's offense. I think it's made a
difference to our team. It was probably my fault more so than
anything. But this has allowed me to have more leadership and
control of the games.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Pippen knew exactly what he was saying, and he
got the desired results. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at 444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
