<HEADLINE>
STAPLETON BECOMING AN ALL-AROUND FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He usually toils in relative anonymity, but
all-purpose Coyote  &UR; Mike Stapleton has been making himself noticed
lately.
</P>
<P>
   He has four goals in the past seven games, including the game
winner against Anaheim on March 13, and is a goal away from tying
his career high (10).
</P>
<P>
   ``We can use him at all three positions: center, left wing or
right wing,'' Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld said. ``He has done a
tremendous job of killing penalties for us, and he really has
scored some important goals. He has been a very valuable
contributor to the team all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the season it has been in a defensive role, along with
 &UR; Bob Corkum, Juha Ylonen and  &UR; Mike Sullivan. Through the injuries to
Ylonen and Corkum and to Sullivan, Mike has been there and has
carried the load on the penalty kill. We use  &UR; (Jeremy) Roenick and
 &UR; (Keith)
 &UR; Tkachuk with the other guys out, but Mike has been the constant.
Plus, if we had injuries during a game to our defensive corps, we
can even put him back at the blue line. He did that last year.'' &QL; 
OK debut &QL; 
The Coyotes wasted little time putting defenseman  &UR; Stan Neckar to
work. Obtained just before Monday's trading deadline from the New
York Rangers, he played Thursday night against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finished his checks well, kept it clear in front of the net
and put some people on the seat of their pants,'' Schoenfeld said.
``He hasn't played in a while, so I would expect his game to
continue to improve. I thought it was a good first game for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Neckar played in only 18 games with the Rangers. &QL; 
Power fade &QL; 
With the Coyotes' power play struggling at 12.2 percent, which is
second worst in the NHL, some have suggested that opponents' lack
of respect for the unit has allowed them to take liberties.
</P>
<P>
   Almost to a man, the Coyotes scoff at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a team has a man advantage, it provides them with a
better chance to score, so teams aren't going to purposely take
penalties,'' defenseman  &UR; Keith Carney said. ``Most of the time it's
the same guys killing penalties, so you don't want to wear them
down, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld has a slightly different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might be a little less cautious, but I don't think it
goes the other way where they are more careless, if that makes any
sense,'' he said. ``We play a lot of teams with their power play
struggling, and I don't say this is a night when we can take six
minors. You're putting yourself at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say we're playing Nashville, which has a bad power play. I'm
thinking their best chance of beating us is to get a couple of
power-play goals. We don't want to give them free opportunities.
You want to make your opponent earn everything. Earn the ice. Earn
scoring chances. Don't want to give them a free chance by missing
an assignment, being lazy or by taking an undisciplined or
retaliatory penalty. That never changes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
