<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON ENJOYS TAKING RELIEF ROUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - Diamondbacks pitcher  &UR; Brian Anderson pitched the ninth
inning Saturday for his first save of the spring in a 3-1 victory
over a split squad of San Francisco Giants that included  &UR; Barry
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he loved the rush he got from closing. He said he
had saved a game one other time in his major league career, but
that was a three-inning gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've got, I'm just laying it out full bore,'' he
said. ``I don't have to pace myself for seven innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter said he'd like to see Anderson pitch in
back-to-back games before the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But he said not to read anything into Anderson's closing role.
 &UR; Gregg
 &UR; Olson, who saved 30 games last season, has been bothered by
tendinitis in his wrist and forearm but is close to being back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with Gregg Olson as our closer, but this gives us
another option if it doesn't work out with Oly,'' Showalter said. &QL; 
Castillo released &QL; 
Right-hander  &UR; Frank Castillo, a non-roster invitee, was released.
Showalter and General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola met with Castillo
after the game. Showalter said he hoped another club would pick up
Castillo, who spent eight seasons in the majors and had a 3.97
earned-run average and no decisions in 11 innings this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get a strong recommendation from us for anyone who wants
to inquire about him,'' Showalter said. ``He's the definition of a
pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said there was too much pitching depth at Triple-A
Tucson to option Castillo down to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo left immediately after the news and couldn't be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Another roster move could happen today.
</P>
<P>
   The club has 35 players, including injured outfielder  &UR; Tony
Womack, who is expected to open the season on the disabled list.
Showalter needs to cut to 25 by next week. &QL; 
Still waiting &QL; 
The team awaits the arrival of Korean pitching phenom  &UR; Byung-Hyun
Kim, who is expected to join soon. Like today, they hope. But the
20-year-old won't be thrust onto the mound immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, a right-hander who helped lead the Korean nationals to the
final of the World Championships in Italy, could land anywhere from
the opening-day roster to Double-A El Paso. &QL; 
Kicking back &QL; 
Outfielder  &UR; Luis Gonzalez settled into third baseman  &UR; Matt
Williams' black leather recliner that sits in the spring training
clubhouse. Williams, who plans to move the chair into the Bank One
Ballpark clubhouse for the season, got the chair last week to take
pressure off the lumbar area in his back. Williams had the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take advantage of when he's not here,'' Gonzalez
said. &QL; 
Shortstops &QL; 
Starter  &UR; Randy Johnson said his groin felt better. Showalter said
he would decide today whether Johnson would take ``a work day'' on
Monday. He is tentatively scheduled to start Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
