<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE-FOR-AN-EYE BALL ISN'T PRETTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Whether it's an elbow in the paint or a chop block out
of an official's view, retaliation has become an accepted part of
sports. But this beanball business tends to bring out the worst in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it was Diamondbacks pitcher  &UR; Rich Batchelor's plunk
of Chicago Cubs second baseman  &UR; Mickey Morandini, which was fueled
by  &UR; Rod
 &UR; Beck's beaning of  &UR; Travis Lee. Follow? (Translation: Nyah nyah nyah
nyah nyah.)
</P>
<P>
   The bench-clearing shoving exchange wasn't even the worst part.
It was the sight of the Cubs'  &UR; Tyler Houston standing on the top
step of the dugout clapping as Arizona trainers tended to
Batchelor, who had just been nailed in the leg by a  &UR; Sammy Sosa
line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation was at the heart of verbal warfare between Seattle
reliever  &UR; Jose Paniagua and Anaheim designated hitter  &UR; Phil
 &UR; Nevin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two had to be separated after the game because Nevin was
irked when Paniagua sailed a fastball over his head. The previous
hitter,
 &UR; Orlando Palmeiro, stole a meaningless base late in the 9-3 Seattle
win.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Nevin said, ``I don't forget. He better hope he doesn't
run into me outside the field. I'm the type of guy who doesn't back
down from anything. If we do, he ain't going to pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was telling me he's got my number. I'll give him my home
phone number. Let him come over to my house. People like him are a
. . . disgrace to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dates to remember (if you like potential brawls): April 16, when
the Mariners visit Anaheim, and June 7, when the Diamondbacks host
the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of tempers, White Sox pitcher  &UR; Jaime Navarro lost his
after outfielders  &UR; Chris Singleton and  &UR; Jeff Abbott let a fly ball
drop between them.
</P>
<P>
   After glaring at his teammates, Navarro slammed a cooler and
threw a few things in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see Jaime staring at us,'' Abbott told reporters,
``but I've seen it before. It used to bother me, but it doesn't
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest position battle in the Cactus League remains the
Angels' starting job at third.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Troy Glaus has been dominating at the plate, but  &UR; Dave Hollins,
who has been slowed by a hamstring injury, has a guaranteed $2.4
million contract. If Glaus wins, a Hollins trade appears to be a
real possibility.
</P>
<P>
   If Colorado center field prospect  &UR; Jody Gerut seems a little
preoccupied, there's a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Gerut, who was drafted in the second round, came to spring
training needing to complete a take-home exam in his human
sexuality course (no jokes, please) and to write a 20-page paper on
Soviet patent law.
</P>
<P>
   The completion would enable him to get his degree from Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   To fans who inquired why  &UR; Barry Bonds,  &UR; J.T. Snow and
 &UR; Jeff Kent didn't play with San Francisco on Monday at Municipal
Stadium, here's the answer: lighting concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want (Bonds) getting hit upside the head with
those lights,'' Giants Manager  &UR; Dusty Baker said. ``It's simple.
J.T. hasn't played much, so his reaction time isn't going to be the
same. Same thing with Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the club was informed before the game that new
lights had been installed, Baker didn't want to take a chance.
</P>
<P>
   From the feeling-old department:  &UR; Chuck Finley is beginning his
``14th'' season with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's part of the game, but all these trade rumors
flying around have to be wearing on infielder  &UR; Fernando Vina.
</P>
<P>
   Saw Seattle's 6-foot-11 prospect  &UR; Ryan Anderson throw three
innings against the Cubs on Friday. Wow.
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitcher  &UR; Tim Belcher has been awarded the start for the
opener against Cleveland on April 6.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox still have not announced a fifth starter to join
 &UR; Mike Sirotka,  &UR; Jim Parque,  &UR; James Baldwin and  &UR; John Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro may be the guy, but  &UR; Scott Eyre,  &UR; Carlos Castillo and
 &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Beirne also want a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what we've seen,  &UR; Jay Buhner is close to realizing his
goal: starting in right field on opening day. Let's not forget he
underwent  &UR; Tommy John surgery on his right elbow only seven months
ago. &QL; 
Staff writer Paola Boivin can be reached at 602-444-8956 or at
Paola.Boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
