<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD     03-28 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE SHAKEN BY THE INTENSITY OF LATEST RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Subs to update, reorganize and rewrite; this story is now on
page 1 of The New York Times.)  
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Residents of Belgrade, the Serbian
capital, said Saturday that for the first time since the NATO
bombing started, large explosions had occurred in the city before
air raid sirens sounded, giving credence to NATO assertions that
Yugoslavia's integrated air defense system has been damaged, even
around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, for the first time, everyone in Belgrade felt the
real impact of the war,'' said Vesna Prlja, who runs a tourist
agency. ``Everyone could see the big explosions in the central city
and the suburbs. People use the mornings to try to get some
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   And with the price of gasoline rising more than sevenfold and a
prominent Serbian journalist arrested Saturday for offending new
censorship rules, the citizens of Belgrade appear considerably
shaken after the heaviest night of NATO bombing in and around the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   During daylight at about 4:45 p.m., there was a loud explosion
on the western edge of Belgrade, and at around 7 Saturday night,
the street lights were suddenly extinguished, presumably by the
authorities, leaving the city dark and eerie.
</P>
<P>
   This correspondent, ordered to leave Serbia on Thursday and
refused re-entry at the border with Croatia on Friday, was able to
return early Saturday morning from the Hungarian border with the
help of the federal information minister, Deputy Prime Minister Vuk
Draskovic. Draskovic, a relatively liberal nationalist, has been
trying to reverse the order for deportation of journalists from
NATO countries that was originally issued by the Serbian
information minister, Alexander Vucic.
</P>
<P>
   All of Serbia's television channels played patriotic themes
Saturday. There was news coverage of NATO attacks and of protests
against them in Greece and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic, after meeting the Ukrainian
defense and foreign ministers, described NATO's attack on
Yugoslavia as criminal and said, ``It is the duty of all free
countries to stand up to the military despotism of NATO, led by the
United States, which is destroying the United Nations system and
represents the most serious threat to international peace and
security since World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   After a steady diet of patriotic films, all seven channels also
showed the film ``Wag the Dog'' many times Saturday, following the
example of television in Iraq during the early days of American air
strikes there in December. The movie is about an American president
who pretends to attack a foreign country to divert attention from a
sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But there was very little information on events in Kosovo and no
way for ordinary citizens to hear Western charges of a full-scale
offensive by Serbian forces against ethnic Albanians there or
accusations that large numbers of civilian men are being rounded up
and killed by Serbian Interior Ministry soldiers and police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it possible for Western correspondents, expelled from
Kosovo and hampered by police checkpoints and roadblocks, to judge
the situation there easily. Attempts to telephone Pristina were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
