A7006 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-PRAC-A     03-28 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-PRAC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARD GROWS INTO STARTING JOB  
 EX-LINEBACKER ADDS 70 POUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago,  &UR; Kyle Kosier was a 6-foot-6, 215-pound
linebacker. These days, he's a 6-6, 285-pound guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom's really (ticked),'' the Glendale Cactus High School
product said about his constant need for new clothes. ``But I guess
I've just finally grown into my body.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore left guard was a surprise addition to the
offensive line's first team in Arizona State's first spring
scrimmage on Saturday. Junior  &UR; Korey Ramsay, who didn't play
because of a shoulder injury, is expected to have first crack at
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Kosier on the first team were  &UR; Scott Peters, who has
moved to center,  &UR; Marvel Smith at left tackle,  &UR; Victor Leyva at
right tackle and
 &UR; Thomas Schmidt at right guard.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of offensive line recruits will give the Sun Devils
some much-needed depth and possibly force some competition at the
guard spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to adjust to the technique,'' said Kosier, who
played defensive end last season. ``I'm used to flying out on the
ball, but now I have to wait for it to come to me. People think
it's an easy transition to offensive line, but it's not at all.'' &QL; 
A real who's who &QL; 
A crowd of nearly 400 watched the scrimmage, including high school
coaches who were taking part in a clinic with ASU's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few recruits who will join the Sun Devils in August also
were there, including offensive lineman  &UR; Regis Crawford, from San
Diego Morse High;  &UR; Frank Maddox, a tight end from Celina (Texas)
High; and linebacker  &UR; Jamall Anderson and cornerback  &UR; Nijrell
Eason, teammates at Long Beach City College.
</P>
<P>
   Eason and Anderson said they made the 5{-hour drive from Los
Angeles just so they could watch the scrimmage.  &QL; 
Scrimmage highlights &QL; 
If Saturday is any indication, the Sun Devils will be throwing to
their backs often.  &UR; Gerald Green and  &UR; Davaren Hightower caught
several passes, and Hightower found his way into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end  &UR; Quincy Yancy intercepted a pass from 6-4
quarterback
 &UR; Matt Cooper, whose potential was obvious although he said he was
disappointed with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he's not even thinking about Camp Tontozona, when a
battle for the backup job is expected to brew between him and  &UR; John
 &UR; Leonard, a transfer from El Camino Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Quick hit &QL; 
The Sun Devils filled a hole in their 2000 schedule by securing
Colorado State for a Sept. 16 meeting in Tempe. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7007 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD     03-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BELGRADE, Yugoslavia: were unsuccessful.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 10 years ago this week that Milosevic, then president of
Serbia, stripped away Kosovo's autonomy, causing celebrations in
Belgrade and protests by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   None of a dozen people interviewed had seen or heard statements
taped by President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Censorship has been strict here under the rules laid down by
Vucic, the Serbian information minister, who is a member of the
strongly nationalist Vojislav Seselj party. NATO is normally
referred to as ``criminal,'' and Clinton and Albright are labeled
``killers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to reliable Serbs, a prominent Serbian journalist,
Dragoslav Rancic, a senior contributing editor of the weekly
magazine Nin, was arrested Saturday for an article about Milosevic
and his negotiating style that was considered to have broken
censorship rules.
</P>
<P>
   While the magazine had passed censorship, its editor, Stevan
Niksic, was told after printing that there were ``second
thoughts.'' The magazine was distributed anyway, and police
arrested Rancic at his home at 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Editors were also informed Saturday that they must provide first
editions of newspapers to Vucic's ministry every night for
approval. Most newspapers either are not appearing at all or are in
smaller, cheaper editions. Glas Javnosti, for instance, dropped its
price in half. The only newspaper to appear in its usual size is
the government-run Politika.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Politika had a full-page advertisement in
Serbo-Croatian and English from workers of the Zastava automobile
and weapons factory in Kragujevac, north of Belgrade, which has
been a NATO target.
</P>
<P>
   The Zastava employees announced that 38,000 people worked there
and informed NATO that an attack at any time would kill several
thousand people working on wartime shifts. The ad gave the
longitude and latitude of the factory and said workers and their
families would hold rallies there, to make any death toll higher.
</P>
<P>
   Even on another bright and sunny day, the streets were much
emptier, of both cars and people, than on a normal Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are exhausted with tension and little sleep because of
the nightly bombings and the need to tramp down to the shelters,''
said Ms. Prlja, who said her tourist agency has ``not so many
tourists these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline and diesel fuel are being rationed, with many stations
closed. The price of gasoline has risen to about 5 German marks a
liter, or more than $10 a gallon, while the value of the Yugoslav
dinar on the black market fell Saturday to less than one-tenth of a
mark. The cost of a liter of gasoline was about 7 dinars a week ago
and about 55 dinars Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The price of imported items like coffee also increased, but
there were plentiful stocks of cooking oil, bread and other food
products.
</P>
<P>
   At a party Saturday in a central Belgrade apartment, Dejan, a
29-year-old medical student, said that what frightened him the most
was the prospect of mobilization into the armed forces. He said he
had been ``sent an invitation to join the army reserve,'' but had
not been living at home, so the invitation could not be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Bojan, 26, a veterinary student, said he slept in different
apartments to avoid mobilization. He also likes spending time in
different air raid shelters, because ``you meet a different class
of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dejan complained jocularly that ``NATO only seems to bomb when
we sit down to lunch or dinner'' and added that an air raid siren
was only 50 yards from his apartment. But he said he spent time
every day telephoning friends abroad to find out more about events
than he could learn here.
</P>
<P>
   Zaklina, a 31-year-old gynecologist, said she found herself
``calmer than in peacetime.'' But life is boring with all the
alerts, she said, ``and young children and kids have a lot of
traumas, because they move them to shelters.'' She said the
Americans were ``completely crazy,'' adding, ``This is Europe and
not Iraq, and they shouldn't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said life in
her building's shelter was now well organized, with cots assembled,
men's and women's toilets arranged, a small generator installed and
a ham radio operator entertaining nearly 100 people who gathered
there.
</P>
<P>
   Ham radio operators exchanged a lot of information but were not
careful, she said. When one operator asked, ``Is there any
indication of a nuclear attack?'' another broke in to say, ``For
God's sake, watch what you're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   When a bomb hit a missile factory or fuel depot on the edge of
Belgrade Friday night, causing a large fire, television announced
that the acrid fumes released from the fuel were not toxic, but
cautioned residents to shut their windows. In the shelter,
originally built for nuclear attack, cries went up to shut the two
heavy steel doors, while others complained that if that was done,
it would be impossible to leave the shelter to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a doctor appeared on television to tell people that
feeling sick to the stomach was a common reaction to anxiety just
now and was not necessarily a reaction to the chemical fumes. If
eyes began to burn, however, he said, people should bathe them, and
he gave instructions.
</P>
<P>
   There were also renewed attacks on a large base 10 miles
northwest of Belgrade at Batajnica. During a drive past the base
Saturday, two MIG-29s, perhaps decoys, were visible by the side of
the road, as were numerous military communication trucks and mobile
radars. Traffic was diverted from the highway, raising speculation
that the road itself might be used for takeoffs and landings.
</P>
<P>
   Near Nova Pazova, there was another MIG-29, covered with
camouflage material; numerous men who appeared to be in their
mid-50s were dressed in new military uniforms, suggesting the
mobilization of reserves, and men were putting tape on the large
display windows of an electrical goods shop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
