<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS MAY WEAR FAVORITE HAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington Redskins Coach  &UR; Norv Turner thinks a lot of pro
football publications will pick the Cardinals to win the NFC East
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the up and coming team,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that knowing the Cardinals lost starting offensive
tackle
 &UR; Lomas Brown to the Cleveland Browns in free agency and could lose
starting outside linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller, who also is an
unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But he also thinks the Dallas Cowboys, NFC East champions last
season, would be the safer pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas has 10 players as good or better than anyone else at
those positions,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin, whose team knocked Dallas out of
the playoffs, thinks the Cowboys, 10-6 last season, deserve to be
the division favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas won it (last) year and still has the core of that
team,'' Tobin said. ``Those guys still play with a high degree of
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmitt (running back  &UR; Emmitt Smith) &UR; had as good a year as he
has had in a while. Their offensive line still is better than most
people's offensive lines.  &UR; Deion (Sanders) is better than almost
anyone's cornerback. Who else in the division has the people they
do?''
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel, former offensive coordinator
of the Cardinals, thinks the Cowboys have the advantage over the
other teams in the division because of veteran quarterback  &UR; Troy
Aikman, who has won three Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also still have  &UR; Michael Irvin, Emmitt Smith and Deion
Sanders,'' Fassel said. ``Along with Troy, that's four potential
Hall of Famers. Nobody else has that.'' &QL; 
Close race &QL; 
Fassel thinks the NFC East race will be tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we beat Dallas in one of our two games with them, there
would have been a three-way tie for the division title last season,
but we would have been in the playoffs,'' said Fassel, whose team
swept the Cardinals and finished 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any of three teams (the Cowboys, Giants and Cardinals)
could win it. This has been a crazy division. Two years ago, a guy
gave me a frame for my wall with stories in which every
publication, 16 publications, picked us last. Nobody else was
picked last, yet we won the division.'' &QL; 
Killer schedule &QL; 
The Giants started the season 4-8 a year ago in playing a
first-place schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel knows the Cardinals, who advanced to the playoffs a year
ago with a fifth-place schedule, will be tested this season playing
one of the toughest schedules in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals play nine games against playoff teams _ Atlanta,
San Francisco, Green Bay, the New York Jets, New England Patriots,
Buffalo Bills, Miami Dolphins and two against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the schedule came out, everybody talked about us playing
Denver, San Francisco, Green Bay and Kansas City,'' Fassel said.
``Nobody said anything about Atlanta, and they reached the Super
Bowl. With that kind of schedule, you don't get any breaks. You're
faced with being on top of your game week in and week out.'' &QL; 
Saving money &QL; 
The St. Louis Rams freed up $2.125 million by cutting former
Cardinals linebacker  &UR; Eric Hill, who signed a two-year, $5.25
million contract a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who signed a two-year deal with the Chargers on Friday,
finished the season with 86 tackles, sixth on the team. He was
effective in stopping the run on short-yardage and goal-line
situations.
</P>
<P>
   He never was a favorite of Rams Coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil, who was
upset that Hill missed much of training camp because of a back
problem. Then in the season opener against New Orleans, Hill
suffered a broken hand that affected his play for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric took a long time to get playing at the level we brought
him in to play,'' Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Hill suffered a fractured lowered leg in the opener for
the Cardinals at Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil said he couldn't take a chance that Hill would get hurt
early in the season again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the situation is here,'' Vermeil said. ``We've got
to win football games, and I don't want to sit around eight games
and say, `My gosh, he's still not playing well.'' &QL; 
Mock drafts &QL; 
``The Sporting News''' draft publication has the Cardinals taking
North Carolina State wide receiver  &UR; Torry Holt with the eighth pick
overall and Eastern Michigan offensive tackle  &UR; Lonnie Shelton at
No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro Football Weekly's'' draft expert has the Cardinals picking
Brigham Young offensive tackle  &UR; John Tait, a Tempe McClintock High
School graduate, at No. 8 and Louisiana State defensive tackle
 &UR; Anthony
 &UR; McFarland at No. 21. &QL; 
Short shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay fans aren't endorsing a story in the ``Milwaukee
Journal'' ``Sentinel'' that the Packers build a domed stadium to
replace Lambeau Field in 10 to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dome? Are you nuts?'' wrote reader  &UR; John Greene of Chippewa
Falls, Wis. ``Here's a little bit of history. No dome team has ever
won a Super Bowl. That's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals players earned a combined $1.56 million during the
playoffs, $25,202 per player.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State's Holt ran the 40-yard dash in 4.3 seconds
at his private workout on Wednesday, showing he was fully recovered
from his minor knee injury. &QL; 
Includes information from other media resources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
