<HEADLINE>
DUKE DARES DESTINY  
 BLUE DEVILS WIN RARE CLOSE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Were there any doubts that Duke would be
where it is now, 40 minutes removed from an NCAA championship that
resounds with inevitability?
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, there were.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State, which came into Saturday night's national
semifinal against the Blue Devils brandishing Big Ten regular
season and tournament championships, a 22-game win streak and the
No. 1 seed in the Midwest Region, was somewhat skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans believed they would have something to say about
Duke's apparent date with destiny. And they did. Lots. But in the
big picture, it still amounted to little more than a whisper,
drowned out by Duke's awesome talent. The Blue Devils held on to
win, 68-62, at Tropicana Field and move to the NCAA championship
game Monday against Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, Duke (36-1) and UConn are the only teams to have
been ranked No. 1 in both major polls this season.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (33-5) lived up to its tough, ornery, battling
persona, whittling a 14-point deficit early in the second half and
then pretty much outplaying the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Duke had won its past 13 games by an average of 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Duke guard Trajan Langdon whether the
Spartans were the ``bump in the road'' that might have been
expected, Coach Mike Krzyzewski felt compelled to jump in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a second,'' he said. ``Michigan State is the No. 2 team
in the country (in the final regular season poll). They are not a
bump in the road. They are a great basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, is Duke. Few teams can withstand the type of body
shots the Spartans dish out. But few teams are like the Blue
Devils. The No. 1 seed in the East Region and the top-seeded team
in the entire tournament weathered the assault. Duke's lead shrunk
to three, but the Blue Devils never buckled and won for the 32nd
straight time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get so close,'' Michigan State point guard Mateen Cleaves
said. ``You can kind of see it. You feel yourself coming back, but
we couldn't get over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves had the type of game for which he has become known _
5-for-16 shooting, 10 assists and lots of overall court sense and
leadership. The 6-foot-2, 195-pound junior even took a charge from
Elton Brand, Duke's 6-8, 260-pound sophomore terror.
</P>
<P>
   But except for forward Andre Hutson (6 for 8), the rest of the
Spartans, like Cleaves, had trouble finding the basket. Michigan
State shot barely over 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play very good defense,'' Cleaves said. ``I think we
missed some shots we should have hit, but you do have to give Duke
credit for the defense they play.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Michigan State some credit, too. After falling behind,
34-22, with 18:37 left, the Spartans crept back. It was 51-48,
Duke, with 8:33 remaining and Brand on the bench with three fouls.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon, the Blue Devils' No. 2 scorer right behind Brand, was
having a tough game offensively. He finished with seven points. But
right there, the senior guard showed what makes him and his team
special by stepping out and hitting a three-point basket that gave
Duke a six-point lead and some breathing space.
</P>
<P>
   ``A critical, critical shot,'' Spartans Coach Tom Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the biggest shot of the game,'' Krzyzewski said.
``That's why we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand, with 18 points, carried most of the scoring load on his
broad back. He made 7 of 10 shots and knew when to get rid of the
ball when he was double-teamed, which was often.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he gets the ball down low, it's like he's going to score
every time,'' said Michigan State forward Antonio Smith, who fouled
out trying to guard Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Brand played much better than in the first meeting between the
teams in December in Chicago. Duke also won that one by six. Brand
had 12 points and three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans outrebounded Duke, 41-25, in the first game, but
the Blue Devils had four more rebounds this time. They also went to
the foul line 27 times, converting only 14 attempts. Michigan State
was 6 for 11 from the line. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
