<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-OHIO-ST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN ENDS OHIO STATE'S TURNAROUND SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ This was strange, foreign territory for
Coach Jim Calhoun and his Connecticut Huskies. And yet, there was
something familiar about it, too.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's 64-58 win over Ohio State at Tropicana Field on Saturday
was Calhoun's 19th straight victory over Buckeyes Coach Jim
O'Brien, the prior 18 happening when O'Brien was coach at Boston
College. But that's just trivia. This is not: UConn, which never
before had appeared in a Final Four, will play for the NCAA
championship on Monday against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   UConn (33-2) relied on its usual weapons, forward Richard
Hamilton and a nasty man-to-man defense keyed by guard Ricky Moore,
to end a Buckeyes season in which they turned a last-place finish
in the Big Ten into something special in O'Brien's second season.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, the 6-foot-6 junior All-America forward, sliced and
diced the Buckeyes defense for 24 points. His last two were the
most important, a pull-up jumper with 1:42 left that extended
UConn's lead to six.
</P>
<P>
   The way Ohio State (27-9) was shooting, that would be enough.
The Huskies, who started the tournament as the No. 1 seed in the
West, held the Buckeyes to 8 for 33 (24.2 percent) in the second
half after Ohio State made half its first-half shots.
</P>
<P>
   A main Ohio State weakness, foul shooting, also was exposed as
it was 9 for 18 from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who wears gold sneakers but for the most part sacrifices
flash for a down-and-dirty style of defense, held Scoonie Penn, the
potent Buckeyes point guard, to 11 points on 3-for-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Scoonie goes, so goes Ohio State,'' said Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie went nowhere. The Buckeyes, who came in as the fourth
seed from the South Region, went home.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a 6-foot-2 senior, said his first objective had been
taking away Penn's drives to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Penn was a great offensive player, and he was going to
come out and attack me today,'' Moore said. ``I prepared to come
out and attack him defensively. . . . I just wanted him to shoot
tough shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn, a 5-10 junior transfer from Boston College who
orchestrated Ohio State's climb from the basement, said of Moore,
``He didn't let me breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun was even more explicit, invoking a favorite expression
to describe Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' said Calhoun, ``he cut the head of the dragon
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore's teammates helped out on Penn, and they also did rather
well defending the other half of Ohio State's lethal 1-2 punch,
Michael Redd. Together, Penn and Redd had scored more than half of
Ohio State's points in the tournament. But Redd also had trouble.
The 6-6 lefty sophomore made 7 of 18 shots and scored 15 points,
his lowest output in more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hamilton, along with sophomore point guard Khalid
El-Amin, took care of the offense. Hamilton became only the second
UConn player to exceed 2,000 points in a career.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin shot a tidy 8 for 15 _ mostly by passing up long jumpers
and taking the ball to the basket _ for 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw the opening, we just took it,'' El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone apparently took Penn's No. 12 jersey before the game
because he couldn't find it when he returned to the dressing room
after his pre-game warm-up. He came out wearing No. 35, ``but I
don't think that had (anything) to do with the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UConn opened a nine-point lead late in the first half, but the
Buckeyes closed to within one at halftime. Ohio State missed 14 of
its first 17 shots of the second half, allowing UConn to take a
51-41 lead with 11:48 to go.
</P>
<P>
   A transition basket by Redd closed the Buckeyes to within three
with 4:16 to play, but El-Amin answered with a basket in traffic.
After Ohio State made it 59-55, UConn center Jake Voskuhl nearly
lost the ball out of bounds. El-Amin had the presence of mind to
call timeout, then Hamilton scored as the shot clock was winding
down for the game's big basket. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
