r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTTSDALE-MAYOR-AZR &LR;      03-28 2384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTTSDALE-MAYOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE MAYOR FIGHTS CRITICS, SEEKS TO CARVE OUT LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two packages of nylons are crammed into the Volvo's glove box. A
bottle of hair spray is wedged between the center console and the
driver's seat. Cranberry nail polish rattles in a side pocket.
</P>
<P>
   These are more than beauty aids to Scottsdale Mayor Sam Campana,
the woman at the helm of the Valley's version of Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   They're political tools.
</P>
<P>
   Campana runs a city where image _ including the image of the
statuesque blonde known Valleywide as ``Mayor Sam'' _ is
everything, and she knows how unforgiving the public can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be mayor for a thousand days, but it's the one day
that you have a run in your nylons that they'll report it,''
Campana said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind her coiffed locks and ever-retouched nails is a woman who
knows what she wants for her city. She smiles coyly as she doggedly
takes on adversaries, from a neighboring mayor she accuses of
meddling in her city's business to residents who accuse her of
favoring developers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the woman who so carefully tends Scottsdale's image is
starting the last year of her term and launching her Campana 2000
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She's also in a place she never wanted to be _ on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Campana endorses a controversial hockey arena proposal for Los
Arcos Mall in south Scottsdale. She's sparring with Phoenix Mayor
Skip Rimsza over state tax breaks for theme parks and sports
complexes. And her city is the target of federal and state probes
into alleged wrongdoing in the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Campana, 51, leads a sharply divided City Council,
and her every move is dissected by some of the most boisterous
anti-establishment forces this wealthy city has ever seen. She
struggles to shrug off high-profile flubs, including her infamous
calls to 911 for directions to city functions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most daunting is the shadow of her beloved predecessor
looming over her. Campana marches in the boot steps of Scottsdale's
most revered figure, the late Mayor Herb Drinkwater, but she never
tries to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   She knows better than to try to compete with the legacy of a
Stetson-sporting, horseback-riding political master who could
persuade the most skeptical of foes to see things his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter who took over the reins after Herb, they would've
had a difficult time,'' said state Rep. Carolyn Allen,
R-Scottsdale, a friend of Campana for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   So Campana works tirelessly _ past midnight most days _ to carve
her own legacy and shed stereotypes that have haunted her since she
sat on the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how hard she tries to sculpt one image of herself,
another clings to her. Observers call her a lightning rod for
mockery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sam has done a few things that were needlessly hurtful
to herself,'' said Vern Swaback, a prominent Scottsdale architect.
``It's the Dan Quayle kind of circumstance of saying something
which is easily handled with ridicule.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when public officials face intense scrutiny, however,
the odds are stacked against Campana, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of those stories would hang on her neck so
heavily if it weren't for the atmosphere in which we are working,''
Swaback said.
</P>
<P>
   Campana, a former tomboy from Idaho who admires ``sassy,
irreverent'' women, is proud of funneling more females into the
city's power structure. She boasts of competitiveness and
endurance, insisting she can conquer practically anything after 47
hiking trips through the Grand Canyon. She invites an elitist image
by traveling in high society and arts and cultural circles.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she exhibits a girlish fragility.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Campana took office, then-Police Chief Michael
Heidingsfeld gently scolded her for calling 911 several times to
ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   The blunder earned her a mention on national late-night talk
shows and even sparked urban legends: During a recent convention in
Kansas City, false rumors surfaced that her hotel room number was
911. Her daily schedules, drawn up by aides, now include explicit
directions to events.
</P>
<P>
   Although privately dismayed by the public panning and stinging
nicknames (her 911ness, Mayor 911 Campana), she jokes about it
publicly.
</P>
<P>
   A carful of wayward tourists recently pulled up to City Hall and
asked her how to get to a nearby museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' Campana teased. ``You're asking ``me'' for
directions? This is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also been bedeviled by other slip-ups: She mentioned
during a council meeting that beer is not sold after the third
quarter of a hockey game. She later learned that hockey games last
three periods. A thief last year swiped a borrowed $15,000
turquoise necklace and bracelet and city-issued cellular phone. The
mayor, always in a hurry, left them on the seat of a city-owned car
in her driveway.
</P>
<P>
   And, after one day at the National League of Cities Conference
in Kansas City, Mo., she headed to New York City to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Campana shrugs off the gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to,'' she said. ``I don't know everything. You can see
in a mayor's day how many opportunities there are to say the wrong
thing, make a wrong turn. Really, I'm not mistake-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said Campana is hurt when the attacks turn ``so very
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But she is a woman who seems to me to get up every day, she's
cheerful and optimistic by nature, and she continues to keep as
positive an attitude as anybody I know,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Which must be difficult for a woman facing potential political
disaster to the south, to the north, and to the center of the city.
</P>
<P>
   She is head cheerleader for a proposal to build a $624 million
hockey arena, conference and entertainment complex at the failing
Los Arcos Mall at Scottsdale and McDowell roads. She has lobbied
hard for changes in a state stadium district law that would sweeten
a tax incentive for the arena complex.
</P>
<P>
   A top Smithsonian Institution official criticized Campana for
overstating the museum's involvement in a proposed $1 billion
Scottsdale redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury has been meeting for months to determine
whether high-level police and city officials improperly pressured
Club Tribeca, a nightclub frequented by minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the state Attorney General's Office is investigating
allegations that the City Council consistently flouts the state
Open Meeting Law. Residents have complained that the council
illegally makes decisions and discusses public business behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Critics blame Campana for explosive growth, which began under
Drinkwater's watch and has crescendoed under hers.
</P>
<P>
   When she ran for mayor in 1996, she declared growth as her top
issue. Some say she failed by continuing to allow major
developments to intensify in north Scottsdale. She supported the
unsuccessful Amberjack development on the city's largest remaining
private stretch of desert despite fierce objections to the
project's density and golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say she offered too little too late, declaring in
her annual State of the City speech in February that she would
reduce the city's projected growth by one-third. They contend it is
developers, not the city, who are opting to put in fewer homes on
stretches of high-priced desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the mayor to take credit for what the private market has
done, when in fact they are rejecting the density that she helped
them get, really shows how myopic she is,'' said attorney Alan
Kaufman, a frequent opponent of Campana and leader of the
anti-arena effort.
</P>
<P>
   Campana defends her record, saying she has been at the forefront
of a massive, unprecedented effort to preserve thousands of acres
of the city's desert foothills.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists also laud the mayor's support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the tremendous success we are having in
Scottsdale, when it comes to protecting actual land for this
preserve, Sam has always been there when we needed her,'' said
Carla, executive director of the McDowell Sonoran Land Trust who
uses only her first name.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mayor's most notable accomplishments, not
surprisingly, have involved the arts. She helped bring a traveling
Smithsonian exhibit to the empty Scottsdale Galleria in 1997, and
she has helped shape Scottsdale's new Museum of Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Campana also points to polls in which Scottsdale residents
consistently have given the city and its police top ratings.
</P>
<P>
   She says her harshest critics simply do not know her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know me as a mayor,'' Campana said, ``but they do not
know me as a mother, as an arts advocate, as a women's advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Campana never had political goals. She grew up in Filer, Idaho _
population 800 _ and figured she'd eventually become a teacher or a
nurse, a wife, a mother. Never a mayor.
</P>
<P>
   After briefly attending a private college in Helena, Mont.,
Campana headed for Arizona with plans to teach Catholic school.
Instead, she moved into a small Scottsdale apartment and worked as
a hostess at a popular Scottsdale haunt, Reubens Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A regular customer at the restaurant introduced her to his
attorney, Richard Campana. Six months later, she married Richard, a
close friend of then-Mayor Drinkwater and a corporate attorney who
would eventually sit on the City Council. She was 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I married Richard, I'd never met an attorney, and I'd
never met an elected official,'' she said. ``After Richard was
(elected) to the City Council, I had to go back and ask if there
was even a mayor in Filer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a councilman's wife, Campana had no desire to plunge
into politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the best wife and the best mother and the best cook and
learned to cook Italian and speak it. I loved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And although she volunteered and helped with local campaigns,
she avoided policymaking or strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women didn't do that in those days,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She stumbled onto the political scene when she and her husband
divorced in 1983. She needed a job, and Arizonans for Cultural
Development, a non-profit arts advocacy group, was looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they needed an executive director that knew arts and
politics, that was me,'' she said. ``They just took a chance on me,
because it really had been 15 years since I had worked.''
</P>
<P>
   She had found her passion.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of three helped launch the Scottsdale Arts Center
Association and served as a fellow for the National Endowment for
the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, she ran for City Council, eager to dip into the
political world that had become part of her home life.
</P>
<P>
   She was somewhat of a maverick in her two terms on the council,
and she got her first taste of the controversy that continues to
swirl about her.
</P>
<P>
   An audit found that Scottsdale reimbursed Campana for charges
that the city already had paid on her city-issued credit card.
Campana called the discrepancies a mistake, reimbursed the city and
completed her term.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving office, she focused on family and the arts for a
couple of years. Then Drinkwater made the shocking announcement
that he was retiring after a dozen years as Mr. Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Campana huddled with family and friends and decided to take a
stab at succeeding a legend. Drinkwater, who learned he had cancer
shortly after announcing his retirement, died Dec. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Campana's trademark stamina sustained her through the campaign.
She stumped during the day, fixed dinner and helped her teenage son
conjugate verbs in the evening, then engaged in late-night strategy
sessions with her campaign manager, eldest daughter Cassidy, then
24.
</P>
<P>
   The mother-daughter team mounted a flashy, sophisticated
campaign. They raised more than $150,000 from powerful developers,
arts supporters and politicians, the very people who would define
the shape the city has taken on her watch. It is that dedication
and loyal cadre of supporters who, observers say, will make it
difficult to unseat Campana.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she remains as energetic as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Awake by 5:30 a.m., she treks partway up the east face of
Camelback Mountain three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, the mayor emerged from her home sporting a
Scottsdale T-shirt, black stretch pants and a large-brimmed hat of
red cloth. She speed-walked and jogged three miles from her home
near Scottsdale Fashion Square to the base of Camelback's Cholla
Trail, all before a 7:30 a.m. breakfast meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Her days are packed with working breakfasts, public appearances,
meetings and dinner engagements. She hunkers in her office until 2
a.m. some days, skimming documents, returning calls and mulling
city business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Sam is very focused on her health, her career, her friends,''
said Cathy Eden, a friend and former legislator who is a
Rural/Metro vice president. ``And she has enough energy for about
10 people. It's almost scary how much energy she has.''
</P>
<P>
   Campana once persuaded Eden to hike the Grand Canyon's Bright
Angel Trail with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she gets excited about something, she wants everybody
else to be excited about it,'' Eden said.
</P>
<P>
   As for her personal life, Campana is intensely private about her
long-term relationship with surgeon Lee Ansel.
</P>
<P>
   She does not hold back, however, about her kids.
</P>
<P>
   A single mother, she prides herself on the way she raised her
three children. She brags about her two daughters, who graduated
from private schools and are working in the Valley, and her son
Richie, who's preparing for college.
</P>
<P>
   She thrives on close friendships, including a small group of
women from across the country with whom she travels each year.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, she loves to shop.
</P>
<P>
   Campana says spending time with children is her favorite part of
her days. She read to kindergartners at a Scottsdale elementary
school recently, bantering with her tiny constituents and noticing
a list of guidelines on the classroom wall. One caught her eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw up there `sense of humor,' '' she told the sea of little
faces. ``That's what saves me when I'm the mayor. Sometimes when
things get so hard, I just have to have a sense of humor.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Alexa Haussler can be reached at 444-7481 or at
alexa.haussler &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
