<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-WNBA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABL DEMISE GIVES WNBA OPENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ With the start of training camp less than seven weeks
away, the third-year WNBA has much to accomplish to capitalize on
its sole possession of the U.S. women's pro basketball market.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides expect a collective bargaining agreement between the
players' first-year union and the league to be struck by mid-April,
especially since the players lost much of their leverage with the
demise of the American Basketball League in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in a position where we're going to make six figures.
That's not reality,'' said Rebecca Lobo, one of the few players who
does earn that much as one of three marquee names around which the
WNBA was first promoted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 average player salary of $30,000 probably will increase
minimally, but nowhere near the ABL average of $80,000, which made
that league player-friendly but accelerated its bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues include improved year-round health and retirement
benefits and a limitation on the number of ABL players to be
absorbed, which the league opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league wants the best product, but a little bit of loyalty
is owed to the women who sacrificed some,'' Lobo said.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, executive director of the National Basketball
Players Association, has attended the few bargaining sessions that
have been held.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like to see is (WNBA President) Val Ackerman and
someone from the union put in a room and get it done,'' said Lobo,
a forward for the New York Liberty. ``Now it's like 15 people in
the room, seven lawyers from each side and a few of us players
sitting there thinking, `What are these lawyers talking about?' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of expansion teams in Orlando and Minnesota
and the possibility of a 12th roster spot _ another item under
negotiation _ the WNBA could add 34 player jobs for 144 total.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an ABL player limit (2-3 per team) is imposed, the
competitive impact of their availability on the WNBA and college
seniors will be great.
</P>
<P>
   Only Tennessee forward Chamique Holdsclaw and Alabama guard
Dominique Canty, unaccountably left off the Kodak All-America team,
are rated as first-round locks for the WNBA draft April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Teams will opt for the pro/international experience of the
former ABL players such as Yolanda Griffith (Sacramento) and
Natalie Williams (Utah), expected to be the second and third picks
after the Washington Mystics select Holdsclaw, a four-time
All-American.
</P>
<P>
   Two former ABL players, probably Katie Smith (Minnesota) and
Shannon Johnson (Orlando), are to be allocated to the expansion
teams before an expansion draft April 6.
</P>
<P>
   If so, guard Dawn Staley, who jumped from the ABL to the WNBA
late last summer, would go into the regular draft and perhaps be
available at No. 4 to Los Angeles, which covets her.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA runner-up Mercury has the 10th, 22nd, 34th and 46th
picks in the four-round draft, but as the deepest team in the
league, it first must worry about the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the existing 10 teams will lose one player to either
Orlando or Minnesota after protecting six. Phoenix is not allowed
an exemption for Michelle Griffiths, who is pregnant and won't play
this season, so it has to decide whether to protect the Australian
forward or risk losing her in submitting its protected list
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Each expansion team already has been allocated one player:
Kristin Folkl (Minnesota) and Nykesha Sales (Orlando).
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Peck, whose Purdue team plays for the NCAA title
tonight, is moving to the pros as Orlando's coach-general manager,
while Brian Agler, coach of the two-time ABL champion Columbus
Quest, holds the same titles with Minnesota. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
