<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7015 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRL-QUALIFYING-AZ     03-28 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-QUALIFYING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY SPEEDS TO WORLDCOM 200 MARK  
 PACK OF DRIVERS TOPS TRACK QUALIFYING BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There was Greg Ray. And, then, there was everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, team owner John Menard's handpicked choice to replace
departed Pep Boys Indy Racing League poster boy Tony Stewart, was
one of nine Pep Boys Indy Racing League drivers to break the
one-lap qualifying record Saturday at Phoenix International
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   But no one roared through the MCI WorldCom 200 proceedings as
fast as Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Ray drove as if he were being chased by a hungry wolf. He
stopped the electronic timer at 20.323 seconds, which when
converted into speed, translates into a blurry 177.139 mph lap.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dismore, the next best qualifier, might as well have been
in an ox cart. He was about 2{ mph slower at 174.622 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Ray) keeps that up in the race, he'll lap the field,''
said Glendale's Billy Boat, who at 169.731 mph, will need
binoculars to spot Ray at the start of today's race.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes. Just 12 months ago, Jeff Ward
was king of PIR's asphalt hill with a 172.753 mph lap.
</P>
<P>
   That would have put Ward in the fifth row this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fabulous,'' said Ray, who captured the first pole of his IRL
career in only his second start for Menard. ``This is what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   It was what it was all about Saturday. Today what it will be
about is whose machine is faster for 200 laps, not one.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray has been conspicuously quick throughout the weekend and
has given little indication he'll run into any red lights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   Race day always hasn't been kind to this IRL stalwart. Stewart
may have won a driving title and three races for Menard, but he
also could write a book on the number of times he's been in
position to win, only to be brought down by a balky motor or some
other stinking breakage.
</P>
<P>
   Team Menard often has been Team Tylenol.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, everything appears to be hunky-dory.
</P>
<P>
   Knock on wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we tested here (last month) for the `Test in the West',
Scott (Goodyear) and (Dismore) were very close to us,'' Ray said.
``Then, the conditions changed a lot (Saturday from Friday, when it
was cooler). I think our team just did a little better job of
changing with the conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, expects Ray to keep up such a pace in the race.
Not even Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore, too, is not overly discourage at the gap in qualifying
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't match (Ray) on a one-lap flyer,'' Dismore
said. ``But we were in our race set-up mode. I'm pleasantly
surprised. I'm a little disappointed to be in second place
three-tenths (seconds) off (Ray), but you have to look at what
tires he's on. We think he's on tires that get an incredible amount
of grip for a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear and Roberto Moreno, who's making his IRL debut,
comprise the second row.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, defending champion Scott Sharp, Donnie Beechler, Scott
Harrington, Tyce Carlson and Raul Boesel complete the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   All but Boesel bettered the old qualifying mark, but with Ray
delivering his best faster-than-a-speeding-bullet impression, it
didn't mean squat.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, Menard was all smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a totally dedicated racer,'' Menard said in a slight dig
toward Stewart, who tooks his immense talents to the NASCAR Winston
Cup circuit. ``He doesn't have a lot of other things getting in his
way. He's very focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wanted somebody who was easy to work with. (Stewart)
certainly is a good racer. But we had differences as far as sponsor
dealings. He didn't like doing a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, however, loved to race.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Ray, whose next trip into victory lane also will be
his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a driver's standpoint, I couldn't be in a better
position,'' said Ray, 36, who lives in Plano, Texas. ``It's a dream
come true.''
</P>
<P>
   A dream that could become even dreamier in a few more hours. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
