<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7017 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NCAA-TITLE-PREVU-     03-28 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-TITLE-PREVU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE'S IDOL HAS 1 GOAL LEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Everyone in Indiana knows Stephanie White-McCarty
colors her hair and has since she was a junior in high school.
</P>
<P>
   But then everyone in Indiana knows everything about its favorite
daughter, including the fact that she has never won a championship
at any level.
</P>
<P>
   Until tonight if No. 1-ranked Purdue (33-1) beats Purdue East,
aka Duke (29-6) with two starters and a coach who are out of the
Boilermakers plant.
</P>
<P>
   White-McCarty mania exceeds even that showered on former
collegiate scoring champion Cindy Blodgett by all of Maine,
including horrormeister Stephen King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say her name is in the same category as Bobby
Knight, Larry Bird and God in Indiana,'' Purdue Coach Carolyn Peck
said.
</P>
<P>
   White-McCarty defers on the latter _ ``I'm definitely not like
God, let me just tell you that,'' _ and, like any good Hoosier,
takes pride in the other comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to watch other people,'' she said. ``I watched Larry
Bird, and he wasn't the most athletic, but he did a lot of things
that helped contribute to his team. Bobby Knight is a great coach,
and I like to watch his teams. They're very disciplined, they go
out and work hard every day. I like to watch a lot of players and
see the things they do on and off the floor and take from each.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly Jennifer Azzi, the Tennessee defectee who returned
to Knoxville to win a national title with Stanford in 1990. Now
White-McCarty is in Azzi's Bay territory and just one game away
from the same accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' she said. ``I was talking to (teammate) Kelly
Komara because her team always beat mine in high school in the
Sweet Sixteen or the Elite Eight. It would be a great way to go
out. If it didn't happen, I think we would still realize we've done
some great things, and I've had an opportunity to play with a lot
of great players and most importantly to be around a lot of great
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially her running mate, Ukari Figgs, who stuck with Purdue
when Lin Dunn, the coach who recruited them, was fired after their
freshman season, launching a staggering talent exodus.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players were released from letters of intent, including
Michele VanGorp and Nicole Erickson, who followed former Purdue
assistant Gail Goestenkors to Duke and Summer Erb, who reached the
1998 Final Four with North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to stay because I didn't want to leave,''
White-McCarty said. ``Brent was the main reason. I was maybe not
going to play basketball, but I was going to stay and go to school
at Purdue. Everything goes through your mind, but I wanted to be
around my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent McCarty, her husband, recently completed a football career
at Division III Wabash College.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came out the same year Chamique (Holdsclaw) did,'' Peck
said. ``Sometimes I think people forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, more important, that it was the 5-foot-11 White-McCarty and
not the 6-2 Holdsclaw who was the consensus 1994-95 national prep
Player of the Year off a season in which she averaged 36.9 points
and 13.1 rebounds for Seeger Memorial High School in West Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw carried Tennessee to an unprecedented three
consecutive national titles and repeated this year as the
collegiate Player of the Year. But she and the Volunteers bowed out
one game shy of a fourth Final Four, returning the stage to
White-McCarty, who averages 20.5 points and 5.5 rebounds and had
the first triple-double in school history in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because Chamique's done so much for the
game and she's a phenomenal player and a great person,''
White-McCarty said. ``She's someone you can sit down and have a
conversation with for hours. But it's exciting that we're here.
It's two new teams in the championship game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
