<HEADLINE>
NEW FACE GETS POLE FOR F2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It was love at first sight for French Canadian
 &UR; Marc-Antoine Camirand.
</P>
<P>
   Camirand, last season's U.S. Formula 2000 Rookie of the Year, on
Saturday grabbed the pole position for today's F2000 event at
Phoenix International Raceway with a record 130 mph lap.
</P>
<P>
   Camirand missed the PIR stop last year and is making career
start No. 1 on a 1-mile oval. He did compete twice at Lowe's Motor
Speedway (Charlotte, N.C.) and at Atlanta Motor Speedway, both
1.5-mile ovals, last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try and run fast,'' Camirand said.
</P>
<P>
   Camirand was plenty fast in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   So was  &UR; Rolando Quintanilla (128.92 mph) of Mexico, who will
share the front row with Camirand.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie  &UR; Mark E. Dismore (128.48), whose father,  &UR; Mark A.
 &UR; Dismore, will start today's Indy Racing League event from the
outside front row, qualified third fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Although both races are today, father may be too nervous to
watch son. Dismore Sr. suffered several multiple fractures in a
horrifying crash in during practice for the 1991 Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may just sit in the motorhome,'' the elder Dismore said.
``Honestly, I don't want to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is nothing new to the younger Dismore, who is 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in Go-Kart, he never really liked watching,'' the son
said. ``I know he'll be a jumble of nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   The older Dismore, however, did give his son plenty of help in
his search to find the quickest route around the oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me a lot with (finding the lines),'' the younger
Dismore said. ``If not for (my dad), I don't think I would have
qualified third.'' &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Five NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series drivers ( &UR; Ron Hornaday,
Jack &UR; Sprague, Rick Carelli, Joe Ruttman and  &UR; Butch Miller) have
competed in every truck race (99) since the circuit's inception. If
one of them wins next week's race at Evergreen (Wash.) Speedway, he
will receive a $100,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone will put $10,000 in the pocket of every Indy Racing
League driver leading Lap 99 at races this season. There's one
catch. The driver has be running with Firestone rubber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rusty Wallace, whose little brother,  &UR; Mike, won the NASCAR
Winston West race, will sign autographs Monday from 2 p.m. to 4
p.m. at Action Performance Companies Inc., at 4707 E. Baseline
Road. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
