<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TRUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNADAY TAKES HIS TIME, TAKES 1ST  
 GRABS LEAD LATE ON SMART MOVE WITH PIT CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DEWAYNE SMITH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - After his win Saturday in the Chevy Trucks NASCAR 150
at Phoenix International Raceway, Ron Hornaday said he felt he was
home again.
</P>
<P>
   He should feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the California native, who resides in Mooresvile, N.C.,
had only one Craftsman Truck Series win under his belt at Phoenix
before Saturday, he has long been a local favorite since his days
doing battle in Southwest Tour and Winston West stock-car circuits
on the one-mile layout.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, the truck series' two-time champion and winningest
driver with 24 victories, started fifth and didn't go to the front
until lap 79, the last of five drivers to run out front.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last restart was very important,'' said Hornaday, who
pilots the NAPA Auto Parts Chevrolet owned by Winston Cup champion
Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a clear track ahead of me while the others were caught
up together and had to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday, who stayed on the track during a two-lap caution to
pick up the lead, had received left-side tires and fuel during a
previous caution for laps 63 through 69.
</P>
<P>
   The finish was nearly a replay of last spring's Craftsman Truck
Series battle when Hornaday, 40, scored his first truck victory at
PIR. He finished ahead of second-place Jack Sprague of Spring Lake,
Mich., after the two swapped paint in a major battle.
</P>
<P>
   Although the door-to-door battle didn't materialize this time,
Sprague, who started from the pole, didn't have enough truck to
overhaul Hornaday after being penalized a lap for jumping the
restart on the first caution period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a bad mistake on the restart and passed on the left
side before the start/finish line,'' said Sprague, who drives the
GMAC Financial Services Chevrolet. ``I just dummied up.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, who like Hornaday, jumped into a Winston West stock car
to finish fourth after the truck event, has had lots of success at
PIR, winning three consecutive races in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague credits his crew with his finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were off sequence (pit stops) all day and each time we
would have to go all the way to the back and come all the way back
up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then about 20 laps to go I got into the wall because of the
stuff on the windshield and I couldn't see a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With his spring battle still in mind, Hornaday wasn't about to
count out Sprague despite all his hardships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't write Jack Sprague off when he went a lap down,''
said Hornaday. ``If he wants it back, he'll get it back. He races
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of about 13,000 was treated to an opening-lap
spectacle not often seen at PIR as three cars came down the front
straight side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague, second-place starter Rick Crawford of Mobile, Ala., and
third-place starter Kevin Harvick of Bakersfield, Calif., were door
handle to door handle at the end of the first lap.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Houston of Hickory, N.C., made it an all-Chevrolet top
three finish when he placed third in his Cat Rental Store-sponsored
mount. He did his best to overhaul Hornaday from lap 79 until
Sprague passed him on lap 125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we had a wicked start,'' said Houston about his run
from his 12th place starting position. ``We got out of sync (pit
stops), but it actually worked out well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
