<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO RIVER IS OPTION FOR ANGLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Arizona Game and Fish Department obviously is
aware that there are going to be problems for anglers because of
extremely dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   San Carlos, Horseshoe and Roosevelt lakes will be hit badly. The
first two may dry up.
</P>
<P>
   And there'll be real problems in the mountains. Few lakes
probably will go dry, but many of them may get so low that weed
growth, which helps rob the water of oxygen, and warm water may
threaten trout. Forget all but a few streams. There won't be much
flowing.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-year drought that culminated in 1986, a few lakes
went dry, boat ramps didn't reach the water and even mountain lakes
weren't exempt. Deer populations continued to decline because of
unfavorable weather conditions. Last year, the number of permits
declined to a record low. There were few quail, again because of
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish was hit hard. It's financial base has no state tax
money. It's financed primarily by license sales. It gets some
Heritage Fund money and some federal excise taxes on the sale of
sporting goods.
</P>
<P>
   The number of anglers purchasing fishing licenses dropped
drastically. Hunting licenses did the same.
</P>
<P>
   It's worse this year, and Game and Fish faces a real financial
problem. But at least it's being more aggressive this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can't fish here, they will somewhere else,'' said
Larry Riley, fisheries chief for the department. ``We need to
direct them to other kinds of fishing _ places they don't normally
fish here in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those areas is the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, Wyoming and Utah also have had less snowpack than
usual, but it's not as bad as in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service has estimated that those states
have 88 percent of normal snowpack and that spring runoff is at 84
percent, with more snow possible. That's a lot better than Arizona,
which may face its driest year ever.
</P>
<P>
   Releases at Glen Canyon Dam, which backs up Lake Powell, have an
average flow now of about 14,000 cubic feet per second. In April
and May the average releases should by about 12,000 cfs.
</P>
<P>
   That should translate into fairly good lake levels from Powell
to Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Mead had two good years of water, and pro fishermen say it
is the best fishing they've ever seen there.
</P>
<P>
   The high lake levels from the wet years flooded brush and trees
at Mead, producing huge crops of bass and forage fish. Expect many
2- to 5-pound largemouth this year with plentiful striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Mohave, which is remote with few places to launch, will get
little pressure once you get a few miles away from Davis Dam. The
catch rate isn't as good as other lakes on the river, but the
striped bass and largemouth sizes often are better. And there's no
competition for places to fish.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, of course, will be good. Anything from walleye to
smallmouth bass to striped bass should be good.
</P>
<P>
   And just below it's dam, the 16 miles of tailwater trout fishery
called Lees Ferry already is excellent and could continue through
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be hot _ Lees Ferry is like a pizza oven with the cliffs
of Glen Canyon radiating _ but the cold water makes in more than
bearable.
</P>
<P>
   With problems on the desert lakes causing doubts, the Colorado
River would be a good alternative. &QL; 
Urban lake popular &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The state's urban fishing program has been popular for years. It
allows urbanites to fish close to home.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the lakes are stocked with catfish during the summer
and rainbow trout in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   But when an urban lake was established a year ago in the low
mountains at Payson, its use exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   A seasonal fishery was set up in Green Valley Lakes. Last year,
the department stocked 9,000 trout into the lake from October
through May. There is no catfish stocking.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Swanson, the Game and Fish biologist in charge of the
program, said youth use of the lake was much higher than
anticipated. The lake is used primarily by Payson residents, but
there is growing use by Phoenix area residents. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 for at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
