<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH MARS TRACK OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN LEE  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. -- The opening of the Irwindale Speedway was
marred Saturday afternoon by the death of a race car driver on the
track, just hours before inaugural ceremonies were to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Diemert, 23, was driving around the track when the
accident occurred, Irwindale police Lt. Rick Woodmansee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he was making laps and crashed in turn four,''
Woodmansee said Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Diemert was extracted from the wreck and airlifted to Arcadia
Methodist Hospital with head injuries at about 2:15 p.m.,
Supervising County Fire Dispatcher Diana Aronson said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, an Oregon resident, was pronounced dead on arrival
at the hospital, Woodmansee said. There was no estimate on how fast
he was traveling at the time of the crash, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Powell, a Salt Lake City resident who owns a car competing
this weekend at the speedway, said she witnessed the accident. It
appeared that Diemert hit another car and then slammed into the
wall near the ticket sales and administration office, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit (the wall) twice and ended up upside down,'' Powell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses confirmed Powell's account, saying Diemert tried
to avoid a stalled car in turn three before hitting the wall twice.
</P>
<P>
   The brand new white wall around the race track was scarred by
black marks near the place where Powell said the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred before the spectator gates opened. Despite
the crash, the scheduled 6 p.m. inaugural ceremonies -- which
featured local elected officials, fireworks and the USC marching
band -- went ahead without any mention of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason, because it happened much earlier during
practice,'' speedway spokesman Doug Stokes said. ``It's very
unfortunate that it happened on the first day of the first race.''
</P>
<P>
   A capacity crowd of enthusiastic auto racing fans filled the
6,500-seat grandstand, with most unaware of the tragedy. Families
brought blankets to ward off the chilly breeze that left the white
``Irwindale Speedway'' flags fluttering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a clean track,'' Cerritos racing fan Rod
Masselink said as he waited outside the grandstand for a friend.
``It looks like they went first class.''
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Fulmer, a Glendora resident who has helped organize a
race car series that will compete on the track, said she thought
the speedway was wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all good seats,'' Fulmer said, referring to the
grandstand. ``You can see the whole track.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Shireman, another Glendora resident who works with Fulmer
on the racing series, agreed, saying seats at the oval speedway
track are better than the seats at the larger California Speedway
in Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those seats bite, because you can't see the back
straightaway,'' he said. Shireman added that it will be far more
convenient to get to the Irwindale Speedway than some of the other
places race car fans go to around California.
</P>
<P>
   Both Shireman and Fulmer said they believe there's a lot of
support for auto racing in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the stands,'' Fulmer said. ``People have been waiting
for a facility like this. I think racing's coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Staff Writer Keith Lair contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0029EST &QL; 
