A7027 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-LADN     03-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE SURVIVES A SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG. Fla. _ For 18 tantalizing seconds, Michigan
State had a chance, a good chance, the chance so many thought would
never come. When Charlie Bell hit two free throws with 8:33
remaining, pulling the Spartans within three points, the improbable
seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State's supporters roared, Duke's fans grew silent, and
the ghosts of upsets past whisked through Tropicana Field like a
cool breeze.
</P>
<P>
   And then, Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Too much Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Trajan Langdon punctured Michigan State's momentum with a
cold-blooded 3-pointer, William Avery drained another, and within
minutes the relentless, unforgiving Blue Devils were in command.
Game, set, semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a dagger in your heart when you make a run and they
hit a shot like that,'' Bell said after Duke's 68-62 victory
Saturday in front of 41,340 fans.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, in a corner of the stadium, Connecticut's
players and fans watched the Blue Devils secure their 37th victory,
tying the NCAA record. As the final obstacle in Duke's pursuit of
immortality, they should be afraid, very afraid.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State played a great second half. It executed its
offense, it played superb defense, and it contested every rebound
and loose ball. But the Spartans weren't perfect, and that was the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Against Duke, there's no such thing as margin for error. Great
isn't good enough, and the chances of Connecticut playing a perfect
game are slimmer than Ally McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Michigan State's physical, grinding style is a natural
antidote for Duke's open-court mastery, Connecticut plays at Duke's
pace, and that's asking for a beating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The type of game and the type of team we played (Saturday)
makes it even more worthwhile,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said.
``It was really as fulfilling a win as we've had all year because
they're so good.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Michigan State may have given Connecticut a
blueprint for containing the Blue Devils. Instead of double-teaming
Elton Brand underneath and leaving open Duke's 3-point shooters,
the Spartans played a standard man-to-man against Brand and
shadowed Langdon, Avery and Shane Battier on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the decision not to double-team (Brand) a lot,''
Michigan State coach Tom Izzo said. ``It's a matter of picking your
poison. You want to get killed inside or get killed outside? We'd
rather give up two than three.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Duke shot 30.8 percent from 3-point range _ 10
percent below normal _ and Langdon was limited to three baskets.
Brand was exquisite with 18 points and 15 rebounds, but he couldn't
do it alone. When he charged into Mateen Cleaves for his fourth
foul with 10 minutes left, the Spartans responded as if granted a
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Hutson scored from the low post, Morris Peterson tipped in
an errant free throw and Bell hit two from the line. It was 51-48
Duke, and the Trop, as locals call it, was rocking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel it, you feel it coming back,'' Cleaves said. ``We got
so close, but we couldn't get over that hump.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brand on the bench and the game within reach, Michigan
State's Jason Klein missed a 3-pointer, then Cleaves traveled and
missed a jumper. Against anyone else, the Spartans could have
survived the miscues. But Duke pounced with back-to-back 3-pointers
and Avery's runner in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it was 59-50, then 64-52, and the Blue Devils were a game
from their crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they're the No.1 team in the country,'' Izzo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
