<HEADLINE>
COACH K: ROLL TAPE AND REBOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Duke prepared for Michigan State with two
words: Roll tape.
</P>
<P>
   When the teams met Dec. 2 in the Great Eight in Chicago,
Michigan State outrebounded the Blue Devils 41-25 and grabbed an
astounding 25 offensive rebounds. Although Duke survived 73-67,
coach Mike Krzyzewski worried that a repeat rebounding performance
Saturday night could fuel a Final Four upset.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Krzyzewski ordered Duke's video team to make
a tape of Michigan State's offensive rebounds. Then he showed it to
the players and emphasized rebounding in practice every day.
</P>
<P>
   They got the point.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils outrebounded Michigan State by four Saturday in
their 68-62 victory. What's more, they grabbed 28 of the 46
rebounds available on their defensive end. Yes, Michigan State got
second shots _ 22 second-chance points, to be exact _ but it did
not get enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach made it a point of interest to get on the boards and
block out,'' said Duke center Elton Brand, who had 15 rebounds.
``We did.''
</P>
<P>
   Backcourt battle: Connecticut guards Khalid El-Amin and Richard
Hamilton are usually the most talked-about backcourt in any game
they play. But this week, Ohio State's tandem of Scoonie Penn and
Michael Redd got most of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our pride stepped up a little bit,'' El-Amin said.
``We felt threatened that they were trying to outdo us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and El-Amin dominated in the Huskies' 64-58 victory.
They combined for 42 points (66 percent of Connecticut's total)
while Redd and Penn combined for 26 points (45 percent of the team
total).
</P>
<P>
   A look ahead: Duke and Connecticut haven't met since 1995, when
the Huskies won 90-86 on a neutral court.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Blue Devils are 3-0 against Connecticut in NCAA
Tournament play, including an Elite Eight win in 1990 and a Sweet
16 victory in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``One assistant coach has been assigned to Duke for two days,
and one assistant has been assigned to Michigan State for two
days,'' Huskies coach Jim Calhoun said. ``We've done a lot. We
already have a breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll need it.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: When the Buckeyes arrived in St. Petersburg,
Penn's No. 12 jersey was missing. He wore No. 35 instead.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has defeated Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien in 19
consecutive games, dating to O'Brien's tenure at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State and Connecticut combined for 122 points _ the lowest
total for a national semifinal since the shot clock was introduced
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is 32-6 in tournament play in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1993 (North Carolina-Michigan), two No.
1 seeds will meet in the championship game.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Division I history, the men's and women's
teams from the same school will play for the national title.
(Duke's women play Purdue today in San Jose.)
</P>
<P>
   Only one school in any division has won the men's and women's
titles in the same year: Central Missouri State, a Division II
team, in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-28 2583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS READY TO SHOW HIS STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite the things you've heard about Heisman Trophy
winner Ricky Williams ``sliding'' down in the draft, there will be
a standing-room-only crowd of NFL scouts at his private workout
Tuesday in San Diego, because all of that supposed ``sliding'' can
be erased with one sizzling 40 time, which the 244-pound Williams
may well be primed to produce.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what you hear about quarterbacks Tim Couch,
Donovan McNabb, Daunte Culpepper, and Akili Smith, Williams is seen
by most scouts as one of the two best players, regardless of
position, in the draft _ the other being Georgia cornerback Champ
Bailey. That's why Indianapolis general manager Bill Polian, who is
on record saying he hates private workouts, will be in San Diego
even though he has Marshall Faulk in his backfield.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk has rushed for more than 1,000 yards four times in his
five NFL seasons, yet Williams is so talented that the Colts could
end up trading Faulk to draft him with the fourth pick on the first
round. Or they might trade the pick to someone who wants Williams
badly enough to pay a king's ransom for the right to pay Williams a
king's ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The latter would seem more likely, and there is no shortage of
suitors, yet the fact that Polian will attend Williams's workout
has given some draft watchers cause to wonder about Indianapolis's
true intentions. A year ago, the only individual workout Polian
attended was Peyton Manning's; this year only Williams and Bailey
(last week) were on his agenda, although his scouts have fanned out
across the country to attend many others.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Polian bother looking at Williams when he already has
Faulk? Ask Saints coach Mike Ditka, who went on record during the
NFL owners' meetings offering to trade his entire draft (six picks)
to move up and get the Texas All-American and now reportedly has
sweetened the offer to either the Colts or the Eagles (who pick
second) with two more high picks _ possibly including his No. 1 _
from the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a big difference-maker right away,'' Ditka said
in Phoenix. ``(Texas coach) Mack Brown told me he's Earl Campbell
with speed. He said he's the best football player he's ever seen.
That's a pretty good statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a special player who comes out only once in a
while, like Campbell was, like Walter Payton was.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka coached Payton in Chicago, so he has first-hand knowledge
of greatness in running backs, and his opinion on Williams is
shared by many despite the somewhat off-putting manner with which
Williams handled himself at the combine. He came in 19 pounds
overweight, refused to work out, left early, and was less than
cooperative with the staff. He also raised a few eyebrows among the
old white men who run the NFL when he showed up surrounded by a
crew of would-be rap singers.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams are concerned about Williams's decision to sign on
with Master P as his representative rather than a more conventional
sports agent, but his contract actually will be handled by Leland
Hardy and Andy Curtain, two agents certified by the NFL Players
Association. (By the way, Master P earned $56.5 million last year
from No Limit Records, so he must know a thing or two about
managing money, if not necessarily young football players.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, veteran agent Ed Cunningham recently sent an e-mail to
Williams's mother saying he believed her son's value was dropping
because of his association with Master P and his rapper friends,
even though Williams was exemplary on and off the field last year
at Texas as he broke Tony Dorsett's all-time college rushing
record.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to set some minds at ease, Williams reversed himself
after saying he would not do any workouts before the draft,
agreeing to Tuesday's session at which he will run the 40, lift
weights, do the vertical leap, and run other drills. He also
decided to meet with interested teams April 7-9 for personal
interviews, as many college players do.
</P>
<P>
   One team that says it isn't ready to trade up for Williams is
the Rams, who could use a productive back after being badly burned
when they drafted troubled Nebraska runner Lawrence Phillips two
years ago. Coach Dick Vermeil said it would not be best for his
team. That's easy for him to say _ even though his leading rusher a
year ago was June Henley, who gained only 313 yards after starting
the year on the practice squad _ because Vermeil should be in
position to grab Miami's Edgerrin James, the draft's consensus
second-best back, with the sixth pick.
</P>
<P>
   The team you should most want to see get into this race is right
down the road in Foxborough. Even if three quarterbacks go at the
top of the draft, as some experts predict, the Colts still seem
more likely to take Southern Cal linebacker Chris Claiborne or
trade the pick than to go for Williams because they have so many
needs more glaring than running back. If a trade is their
inclination, and the Patriots are smart, New England should
consider packaging its two first-round choices and whatever else it
takes to move up and get Williams.
</P>
<P>
   With his size and speed, Williams may be the only kind of back
who can excel with New England's suspect run blocking because he
can make yards on his own. When you also consider what New England
has gotten out of the 19 picks it made the past two years, quality
seems more important than quantity, and Williams certainly
represents quality at a position where there are only two
high-profile players available.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of slow but steady decline, Bob Kraft's team
needs to make a bold move next month if it is to stay in the
running for the Super Bowl trophy he covets. Certainly their offer
would have to be a blockbluster because the Colts, for obvious
reasons, would rather see Williams running in New Orleans than New
England.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots must find out what Polian's price is _ and exceed
it, if necessary _ because they're not going anywhere with Sedrick
Shaw carrying the ball. Or Darick Holmes, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In case you're keeping score, Master P is the fourth music
industry type to try his hand at the sports agent business. MC
Hammer, Sean ``Puff Daddy'' Combs, and Def Jam founder Russell
Simmons all got in. And got out. But Master P's No Limit Sports
Management has also signed four NBA players, including Boston's Ron
Mercer, who were previously handled by some of the most respected
agents in the NBA . . . Here's how things have changed for the
worse in sports. The presidents of the Rams and Chiefs, as well as
the heads of baseball's Cardinals and Royals, have sent out a
letter opposing a Missouri ballot initiative that would make
concealed handguns legal in the state because they fear it could be
a danger to the players, fans, and referees at games. NFLPA
president Gene Upshaw also issued a statement opposing the bill for
the same reason. Remember when all a fan wanted was an autograph? .
. . The Patriots may say that offseason workouts are unimportant,
but Bennie Thompson would argue the point. The veteran safety and
Pro Bowl special teams player was irate last week when only 34 of
his 58 Ravens teammates showed up to begin their 16-week offseason
program. He was most upset that the team's highest-paid players _
Ray Lewis, Jonathan Ogden, Tony Siragusa, and Rod Woodson _ were
absent and have made minimal appearances in the past. ``The same
people who don't attend workouts are the ones who run up to the
media during the season and complain about how we're losing and we
don't have enough commitment,'' Thompson said. ``Football is not a
six-month-a-year job. Football is year-round and it starts in the
weight room. All those guys who make millions need to stop talking
so much and show leadership. If the shoe fits, put it on.'' It
would fit more than a few men wearing Patriot uniforms the past two
seasons . . . After losing a team-record 13 games last season, the
Eagles are not only the laughingstock of Philadelphia but even
became the butt of a German airline's ad. Lufthansa's new print
campaign to promote daily nonstop service between Philly and a hub
in Frankfort that allows for travel to 100 other cities reads:
``Escape to over 100 cities where nobody makes jokes about the
Eagles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the Oregon quarterback, took quick learning to new
heights when he lifted his score on the Wonderlic intelligence test
from a 16 earlier this year to a 37 at the combine last month. This
brought some skeptical looks from the league's personnel directors,
many of whom already believed Smith was the second-best quarterback
prospect regardless of his test scores. An AFC coach in the market
for a young quarterback went so far as to suggest that Smith had
been given the answers but Leigh Steinberg, who represents Smith,
insists it was merely a case of preparation. ``We had him
coached,'' Steinberg said. ``Players today have personal trainers,
nutritionists, speed coaches. Given the position, it only made
sense to prepare him for the test. In a quarterback, intelligence
is as important as 40 time. He had an SAT preparation book and I
had him coached. He met with the guy one time. I wasn't there but I
know he was coached on test-taking, not the answers. I know he
didn't take it seriously the first time. I don't see why improving
his test score should hurt him. The worst-case scenario is that
somebody prepared to take that test. What does that tell you? I
took a class before I took the LSAT. Was I coached or not? Of
course I was.'' Steinberg believes Smith, Couch, and McNabb will be
the first three players drafted. ``Being the No. 1 pick is not
something you can campaign for,'' Steinberg said. ``But I know
Akili has the best arm and throwing motion in this draft. When he
throws, he looks like a pitching machine coming over the top. He
has an arm where he can throw forever. He's the best natural talent
for the future.'' Some scouts wonder about Smith, though, fearing
he may have been a one-year wonder at Oregon. He excelled last
season after barely playing the year before following a
record-breaking career in junior college . . . An NFC personnel
head said that if Couch had come out a year ago, he would have been
rated clearly behind both Manning and Ryan Leaf. An AFC head coach
laughed at Larry Kennan's recent remark that Couch throws the deep
ball better than Drew Bledsoe. ``Sure he does,'' the coach said.
``But that's not Bledsoe's strong point. You notice he didn't say
Couch was a better passer than Bledsoe.'' The big question about
Couch is whether he has the arm to throw the 20-yard out, which
Kennan insists is no problem . . . Kennan, the Patriots'
ex-offensive coordinator and present head of the newly formed
assistant coaches union, has taken on the role of quarterback
consultant for some of the draft's best prospects. He is working
with Couch and UCLA's Cade McNown after being approached by
super-agent Tom Condon in the offseason. ``I'd had some dealings
with Tom, and when I had all that time off after I left the
Patriots, he asked if I'd like to work with his quarterbacks if he
got any,'' said Kennan. ``He wanted me to run their workouts for
the scouts and help prepare them. I gave them each a program
designed to get them ready for the scouts' workouts. They're taking
the existing system and making it work for them. If you can train
six or seven weeks for the combine and dramatically improve your
draft position, why not do it? Not everyone can make a drastic
improvement, but some can. It says something about the guy, too,
doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how far the mighty have fallen. A year ago, former
Harvard Business School professor Michael McCaskey was president of
the Bears. After years of operating failures that came to a head
when he botched the negotiations to sign ex-Bears assistant Dave
McGinnis as head coach this winter, McCaskey was demoted and has
new responsibilities. He's in charge of the landscaping being done
at Halas Hall, the team's training facility in Lake Forest, Ill. .
. . If the Saints can't run the ball this year, no one will say
Ditka and club president Bill Kuharich haven't been trying. New
Orleans has three former No. 1 picks on its line, plus top-paid
free agent Wally Williams at left guard. Williams joins center
Jerry Fontenot and ex-No. 1s Chris Naeole (right guard), Willie
Roaf (left tackle), and Kyle Turley (right tackle) . . .
Realignment was again discussed during the owners' meetings, and
when the league gets to 32 teams Steelers owner Dan Rooney would
like to see eight divisions of four teams each that would play six
games within the division, eight with common opponents, and two
other games that could be used, for instance, to preserve
traditional rivalries . . . Remember quarterback Chris Miller, who
was driven out of football three years ago after repeated
concussions? He recently passed a physical for the Seahawks and is
also talking with the Bears, Lions, and Chiefs about a possible
comeback . . . After losing more than 20 starters since the dawn of
free agency, the Steelers finally fell upon hard times last year.
That has head coach Bill Cowher scrambling. Word is he's trying to
lure Will Wolford out of retirement to play left tackle on passing
downs. Pittsburgh offered free agent Wayne Gandy a four-year, $13.2
million contract but he has yet to accept . . . Word is former
Kansas City coach Marty Schottenheimer is in line to take over the
Redskins if prospective owners Ed and Howard Milstein and Daniel
Snyder ever get approval from the NFL to complete their $800
million purchase. Their effort was put on hold for another 30 days
at the owners' meeting while they try to satisfy the NFL's
questions about their financing. The situation has left present
head coach Norv Turner and GM Charley Casserly in limbo. Casserly
was in the worst of spots during the owners' meetings because he
was there under orders from the trust that controls the team to
vote for the Milstein group, even though he was likely voting for
three guys who were going to fire him . . . Adam Vinatieri should
thank his lucky stars he stayed in New England instead of trying to
kick at the new stadium in Cleveland. The wind off Lake Erie has
proven so fierce that architects added $6 million wind screens to
try to block it . . . The Browns opened their first offseason
conditioning program with 70 players on hand. The one missing
player was tight end Irv Smith, a single parent who was back in
Arizona caring for his seven-month-old child, who had a 103-degree
temperature. Here's how hard the new Browns are working to get
their players in town for the program. They not only have the usual
weights and strength coach but also provide breakfast and lunch
prepared by a team nutritionist, a karate expert for stretching
work, a speed coach, and VCRs in front of the exercise bikes so
players can view game films while sweating. ``We have to do
everything we can to keep as many players here in the offseason as
we can,'' Palmer said. ``Some players will test us on that and some
of them will be playing elsewhere.'' For those in New England
saying you can't ``force'' attendance, there's how you do it.
Unemployment insurance . . . By the way, Cleveland's program runs
15 weeks and pays only $70 per workout, with a minimum of three a
week to get paid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
