<HEADER>
A7032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     03-28 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANKLED BY RANKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On May 29, International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion Felix Trinidad will defend his title on HBO against former
IBF junior middleweight champion Vincent Pettway at Roberto
Clemente Stadium in Puerto Rico. Pettway is the IBF's No. 1-rated
welterweight, so the fight is a mandatory defense, one Trinidad
cannot avoid without losing his title and one HBO must televise or
lose its contractual hold on Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   The show must go on, all sides say, and so it will, but in truth
this is no mandatory title defense at all. It is a mandatory
mismatch, to be kind _ a mandatory execution, to be accurate. The
Vincent Pettway who will enter that ring in San Juan is no more the
No. 1 welterweight in the world than you are.
</P>
<P>
   Well shop-worn at 33, according to experts, he is not the
Pettway who was once junior middleweight champion, and how he
became the IBF's No. 1 contender for the 147-pound title is
difficult to fathom, impossible to logically explain, and
illustrative of the ills that are eating away at boxing's
credibility and moving the sport closer and closer to a federal
takeover that would be welcome by many who love it.
</P>
<P>
   This is an old story that has been repeated for decades and one
not meant to demean Pettway, who has had a long and admirable
career. It is simply a story the public needs to hear to understand
how boxing is too often run these days.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight
unification debacle that ended with Holyfield losing to Lewis but
retaining his title when the fight was scored a draw, many things
have been written and said about boxing. There has been much
speculation about judges being paid off and fights being fixed. A
week ago in this corner, an attempt was made to show how judges and
referees are influenced not by payoffs but by the simple fact that
they work at the pleasure of boxing's three crime families _ the
IBF, World Boxing Council, and World Boxing Association _ and have
their fees and expenses taken care of by promoters. Either can
freeze an official out of work, so when they have such power, there
is no need to bribe them.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say it never happens or to argue that such
influence-peddling is not bribery by a different name. It is just
to make clear that how it's done today is difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is, far more college basketball games
than prizefights have been fixed in the past four decades. More
college basketball games have been fixed by Boston College players
alone, as a matter of fact, than by promoters like Don King, yet no
one doubts that Monday night's NCAA championship game will be on
the up and up regardless of what odd thing might happen. But the
same benefit of the doubt seldom goes to boxing when problems arise
and never when they arise in a fight promoted by King.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to argue that boxing has a higher moral standing
than college basketball (although if you've been watching what's
been going on at Minnesota over the last decade, maybe so). It is
just to point out that the way fights get fixed today is not to pay
someone to take a dive but simply to make matches like Trinidad vs.
Pettway, Roy Jones Jr. vs. Ricky Frazier, Oscar De La Hoya vs.
Patrick Charpentier, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The chief culprits in this shabby exercise of mandatory
mismatches designed to take care of favored promoters are the
people responsible for rating fighters and sanctioning title
matches. The IBF is no more guilty of this (and no less so) than
the WBC or the WBA, but it is the one that made Pettway No. 1, so
it is as good a fight as any to use as an example.
</P>
<P>
   Pettway is a 33-year-old former world champion with a 42-6-1
record. On the surface he would appear far more legitimate a
challenger than many who have preceded him, but that's part of the
trick. If an organization is smart, it doesn't put a Charpentier in
as No. 1, as the WBC did. Rather, it puts in a guy with good
pedigree who is no longer fit competition for an elite fighter.
</P>
<P>
   When HBO accepted the bout, senior vice president Lou DiBella,
who signed off on it, knew Pettway had a decent record and was a
former world champion. What he didn't know, and frankly couldn't do
anything about even if he did, was that the IBF's mandatory
challenger for one of the best punchers in the world had been
stopped by Paul Vaden on Aug. 12, 1995, 11 months after first
winning the junior middleweight title. Pettway was then stopped by
Terry Norris in a WBC-WBA title fight six months later. Since that
fight on Feb. 24, 1996, here is what Pettway has done to convince
the IBF he is the No. 1 welterweight contender in the world:
</P>
<P>
   --Moved down from 154 pounds to 147, the welterweight limit.
</P>
<P>
   --Won a 10-round decision three months after the Norris loss
from Benji Singleton, a fighter with a career record of 20-46-4 who
is 7-28-3 since he fought Pettway.
</P>
<P>
   --Stopped a fighter named Harold Bennett five months later, on
Oct. 23, 1996. Bennett's record is 18-20-2; he was knocked out in
his last four fights and seven of his last 11 dating back to the
Pettway match.
</P>
<P>
   --Did not fight for 14 months after the Bennett win, then
captured a 10-round decision from Gerald Reed, a fighter with a
15-24-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   So drained by this experience, Pettway needed another 14 months
off before he faced Reed a second time on Feb. 6 of this year,
again winning a 10-round decision from a guy who is now 4-20-3 in
his last 27 fights.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did I mention that Pettway just happens to be promoted by
King?
</P>
<P>
   The last fact seems to be the only way Pettway became a
contender again, although Darrell Peoples, chairman of the IBF
Ratings Committee, did his best to argue otherwise Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Said Peoples, ``Pettway is a former IBF champion with a good
record.'' So is Larry Holmes, but does that make him the No. 1
heavyweight in the world?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Pettway was due to fight Trinidad and stepped aside
or what have you (to allow the Trinidad-Pernell Whitaker fight),''
Peoples continued. ``Let me explain this to you. We can only rate
those people we receive information on and as far as it goes,
Pettway has a good record and has been staying active.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying active is one criterion by which the IBF says it rates
its fighters, but not everyone would consider a guy who's had two
fights with the same stiff in the past 28 months active. Joe Louis
hasn't been much more active the past 28 months and he's been dead
since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the IBF recently adopted a policy that said you could not
become the No. 1 contender without beating another ranked fighter.
The IBF keeps its No. 1 ranking vacant now after a fighter holding
the ranking loses a fight. When two ranked fighters meet, the
winner vaults into that slot. That is how young Fernando Vargas
became the IBF junior middleweight champion. First he beat Anthony
Stephens to become No. 1 and then destroyed Yory Boy Campas for the
title. That is how the system is supposed to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made that policy change because guys were moving up through
attrition instead of fighting,'' said Peoples. ``We wanted to
justify our No. 1 ranking by seeing the guy beat someone else in
our ratings, someone in the top 15. We adopted that in the last
year or so, so I guess Pettway got to No. 1 before we adopted the
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't think so, because 18 months ago Pettway was 10 months
into his first 14-month layoff, which not even the IBF could
construe as active. If the time frame was only a year ago, Pettway
was two months removed from his first win over the never-ranked
Reed, nearly two years removed from having faced a rated fighter,
and nearly four years removed from having beaten a rated fighter
(Simon Brown in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   So how'd he become No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at his record and he didn't even fight a stiff in
1998,'' a well-known matchmaker said. ``There's a dozen young
welterweights you've never heard of who deserve that ahead of
Pettway but they aren't promoted by Don King.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a champion who isn't much, who's unknown himself
like half these guys, you can get away with this kind of stuff. But
when you have a high-profile champion, you can't have an unknown
No. 1 who can't fight, like Charpentier, or a shot one like
Pettway. Pettway had a legitimate career. He was a world champion
for a while, but he's a shot, shot guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But TV has to accept the fight because it's a mandatory and
then the public sees a mismatch that lasts a round or two and it
hurts boxing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are simply the facts of one sad case and the facts of life
for one sad sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to force a rapid rematch between Lewis and Holyfield
have predictably slowed; it now appears a November date is likely.
The fighters have agreed to accept $15 million each, and King is
still saying the bout can be made for September but Lewis's
promoters disagree. Panos Eliades and Dino Duva have begun to
explore sites in Great Britain, either the new Millennium Stadium
in Cardiff, Wales, that was just built to house the rugby World Cup
in October, or Ibrox Park, home of the Glasgow Rangers soccer club
in Scotland. Millennium Stadium has a roof, so it is a possibility
for an outdoor fight if the bout could be made by October. But Las
Vegas remains the leading candidate because whoever promotes the
fight will need a huge site fee to cover the purses of Holyfield
and Lewis. Who promotes it could be a sticking point as well. King
holds a contract saying he is to promote any rematch, but Duva is
claiming he had so many problems in the first fight that King will
have to accept a fee and let him do the promotion. That is
unlikely, even though other boxing chieftains believe it will be
difficult to legitimize the outcome if King is the promoter.
Lastly, HBO has yet to agree to any financial deal, although one
will come eventually because neither fighter has anybody else to
fight that the public would accept until the issue between them is
settled . . . Holyfield showed the kind of fighter he has always
been by agreeing to a $5 million pay cut within days after the
first fight. Say what you will of him, he did the same thing to get
his shot at Mike Tyson, taking $4 million less than the Duvas were
insisting on when they still represented him. That is the
difference between him and Lewis and why he fought every major
heavyweight of his time while Lewis had faced none until Holyfield.
Lewis's people were never willing to risk short-term money for
long-term gain, so he did not fight Riddick Bowe, George Foreman,
or Tyson. Holyfield fought, and beat, all of them . . . Holyfield,
by the way, told the BBC last week that he would not admit he'd
lost to Lewis. ``We both did not do enough to be called undisputed
champion,'' he said. ``It wasn't a great day for me, but I got
through it.'' . . . As much as I love Muhammad Ali, how could he
call Holyfield-Lewis ``the biggest fix in fight history''? He
fought Ken Norton three times and hasn't beaten him yet but got two
wins. And ask Jimmy Young if he truly lost his fight to Ali. The
people who write these letters and put Ali's name on them should be
a little more careful how they use the greatest fighter in history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
