<SLUG> BC-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SWEEPS WORLD AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 FIGURE SKATING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI _ She was pumping her fist in triumph before the music
even stopped. Maria Butyrskaya knew the only way she wouldn't win
the world figure skating title here Saturday was if she fell splat
on her bottom _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   So when she ended her four minutes upright and unflawed inside
Hartwall Areena, Butyrskaya knew she'd made history. No Russian
woman had ever won the global crown, and no country had ever won
all four titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going on . . . I don't even know how I
skated,'' babbled the 26-year-old Butyrskaya after she had
dethroned two-time champion Michelle Kwan, who climbed out of
fourth to salvage the silver medal ahead of Julia Soldatova, the
17-year-old Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Butyrskaya's victory capped a marvelous week for the Motherland,
which also claimed the men's (Alexei Yagudin), pairs (Elena
Berezhnaya-Anton Sikharulidze), and dance (Anjelika Krylova-Oleg
Ovsyannikov) titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done this many times in Europeans, but we didn't
believe it was possible in Worlds,'' said Elena Tchaikovskaya, who
coaches both Butyrskaya and Soldatova. ``But now, you see, we take
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block had always been the women, who had won only
four world medals until last year. But once the Russians stopped
diverting promising girls into pairs and dance, their Moscow-based
women's team blossomed. Russia now has the deepest program on the
planet. Viktoria Volchkova finished 10th Saturday and the Russians
left two world-class women home in defending silver medalist Irina
Slutskaya and Elena Sokolova.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they weren't counting on gold here, not after
Uzbekistan's Tatiana Malinina beat Butyrskaya a fortnight ago at
the Grand Prix final in St. Petersburg. And they'd seen little of
Kwan, who skipped the Grand Prix season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We planned to take two medals, but we don't know how looks
Kwan,'' said Tchaikovskaya. ``When we come here, we see she is in
not-so-good form.''
</P>
<P>
   When the defending champ, congested and woozy, began missing
jumps in practice, the Russians began dreaming about a golden
sweep. When Kwan crashed on a double axel in Friday's short
program, they stopped worrying about her and started worrying about
Butyrskaya, who has a history of folding when the global spotlight
comes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``How this fantastic woman, this fantastic skater could not do
in performance _ it is nonsense,'' said Tchaikovskaya. So
Tchaikovskaya went to work on her pupil's fragile psyche and a
bolder, more confident Butyrskaya emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day by day, was work,'' Tchaikovskaya said. ``But she now
believes she can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Butyrskaya's recent bare-bottomed pose in the Russian
edition of Playboy was her symbolic breakthrough, but she was a
different skater once she survived a shaky qualifying round here.
And so was Kwan, who admitted that she let her illness get into her
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cold probably hit harder mentally than physically,'' she
said. ``My confidence level was a little down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan came here hoping to be the first woman since Katarina Witt
to win three titles in four years. But once she went splat in the
short program, Kwan was hoping just to stay on the awards podium.
And Butyrskaya knew she had a priceless cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan couldn't win unless the Russian finished third in the long
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' Butyrskaya conceded, ``but I knew I could be
second and still win.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Butyrskaya skated cleanly with only sixth-place Anna
Rechnio of Poland remaining, she knew she had the title. But Kwan,
waiting backstage, didn't know she was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the dressing room with the door shut,'' she said. ``I
heard a lot of screaming, but I didn't hear the marks.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, Kwan decided when she took the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about winning or losing,'' she told herself. ``It's
about skating.''
</P>
<P>
   Her skating was far from perfect _ Kwan did a sloppy triple lutz
combination and singled her double axel _ but her artistry was
enough to lift her into second place and a fourth consecutive world
medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough week for me, a lot of ups and downs,'' Kwan
said. ``But I'm really proud of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her silver plus a remarkable seventh-place finish by 13-year-old
Sarah Hughes were enough to assuage the Americans' worst fears _
that they would lose a spot for next year's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a blast out there, a party on the ice,'' exulted Hughes,
the youngest skater in the field.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Russians who were popping the champagne at day's
end, toasting the woman who enabled them to run the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we won't give the title away any more,'' Butyrskaya
mused.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
