u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB-BASEBALLNOTEBOOK-B     03-28 2511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-BASEBALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARM CROP IS READY TO PRODUCE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Here's a baker's dozen of rookies who are
expected to make an impact around the major leagues this season:
</P>
<P>
   1. J.D. Drew, Cardinals. They may boo him in Philadelphia,
because he spurned the Phillies, but he ranks second only to Mark
McGwire as the Redbirds' attraction. There's no ceiling for this
guy.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bruce Chen, Braves. Lefthander had a slow start in camp, but
Atlanta was so confident he was ready to join baseball's best
rotation that it traded Denny Neagle to the Reds. Drafted at 16 out
of Panama, Chen draws high marks for his intelligence and maturity.
</P>
<P>
   3. Mitch Meluskey, Astros. Switch-hitting catcher prompted
Houston to deal Brad Ausmus to the Tigers. Meluskey, 25, hit .353
for Triple A New Orleans, with power (17 home runs).
</P>
<P>
   4. Eric Chavez, A's. Third baseman was Baseball America's Minor
League Player of the Year after hitting a combined .327 with 33
home runs and 126 RBIs. The lefthanded hitter is a leading
candidate to succeed teammate Ben Grieve as AL Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   5. Carlos Guillen, Mariners. One of three players acquired by
Seattle in the Randy Johnson deal, this second baseman has batted
close to .400 this spring and will be Seattle's leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   6. Gabe Kapler, Tigers. The team's minor league player of the
year at Double A Jacksonville has been so impressive this spring
that there has been speculation that the Tigers would trade Bobby
Higginson. Club says no, but Kapler could force his way into the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   7. Carlos Beltran, Royals. Switch-hitting native of Puerto Rico
started last season in Single A ball; at 21, he figures to be
Kansas City's starting center fielder on Opening Day. Beltran has
outstanding speed and sound defensive instincts.
</P>
<P>
   8. Trot Nixon, Red Sox. He's had an up-and-down spring
offensively, but if he isn't too hard on himself, he should do fine
in right-field platoon.
</P>
<P>
   9. Christian Guzman, Twins. Another Dominican shortstop, this
20-year-old was at Double A New Britain last season but his play
this spring is forcing manager Tom Kelly to consider rushing him to
the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   10. Marlon Anderson, Phillies. Second baseman's speed and
extra-base power (32 doubles, 14 triples, 16 home runs for
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre) have this 25-year-old cracking the Phillies'
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   11. Warren Morris, Pirates. Pittsburgh cleared second baseman
Tony Womack from the roster for Morris, who was supposed to be a
year away but may turn Elvis (Mike Benjamin) back into a
utilityman.
</P>
<P>
   12. Braden Looper, Marlins. He's hit 100 miles an hour on the
radar gun, which is why Florida insisted he be part of the Edgar
Renteria deal with the Cardinals. Righthander will be used in setup
role this season, but has closer stuff.
</P>
<P>
   13. Roy Halladay, Blue Jays. Righthander threw a one-hitter
after September callup. At 6 feet 6 inches and 205 pounds, the
21-year-old probably will begin the season in the bullpen, but may
crack the rotation by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of New England's richest gifts to the game, George
``Birdie'' Tebbetts, a former catcher, manager, GM, and scout, died
at age 86 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Burlington, Vt., raised in Nashua, N.H., and a graduate
of Providence College (with a degree in philosophy), Tebbetts
played 14 seasons, four with the Red Sox (1947-50), and also
managed the Reds, Braves, and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette's assistant, Eddie Haas, fractured his leg while
playing for the Braves in the late '50s, when Tebbetts was general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made sure someone came to see me every day when I was in
the hospital,'' Haas said. ``Either he came himself, or his wife
came, or he sent someone from the club. He treated me great. He was
a great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Tebbetts's last job in baseball was as a ``master'' scout for
the expansion Florida Marlins, whose scouting director, Gary
Hughes, hired some of the game's most legendary talent hunters to
track minor league players prior to the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Tebbetts told a story of coming home to New Hampshire to play
for a semipro team in a Sunday ballgame _ the kind of mill-town
game that Connie Mack, the owner of the Philadelphia Athletics,
would let his players take part in to pocket some extra cash.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Lefty Grove, the Hall of Fame pitcher, was promised
$10 for every batter he struck out. College player George Tebbetts
was to be his catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first nine pitches he threw during warmups, I caught about
three,'' Tebbetts said. ``The others hit my glove and bounced 6
feet away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scared me. There was no backstop, and the grandstand was
very close. A lady said to me, `Son, you better get the ballplayer
who's going to catch the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That made me so damn mad. Even if he threw bullets, I was
going to catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Grove struck out 19 and told Tebbetts _ who'd
slightly adjusted the way he held his glove to catch Grove's rising
fastball _ that he would recommend him to Mack. But Tebbetts
already had committed to the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years later I get up in Fenway Park and Grove was
pitching,'' Tebbetts said. ``I got a hit, and he looks over to
first base and says, `I guess I'm a pretty good scout.' I just hung
my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time up, he knocked me on my butt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haas, incidentally, once pinch-hit for Henry Aaron and claims he
was the last man to manage Joe DiMaggio in a game. There is a
catch, of course. Haas said he was managing in the last old-timers
game in which DiMaggio played. As for hitting for Aaron, that
happened in an exhibition game, when Fred Haney was managing the
Braves and noticed that Steve Dalkowski, the lefthander noted for a
high-velocity fastball and a total inability to control it, had
taken the mound. Said Haas, ``Haney saw Dalkowski throw a couple to
the screen while warming up, turned to the bench and said, `Aaron,
sit down. Haas, you're hitting.' '' . . . Wind beneath their wings:
Last season the Cubs went 51-31 at Wrigley Field, the first time
since 1984, when they won the NL East, that they won 50 or more
games in the Friendly Confines. The Cubs PR staff broke down the
team's record with regard to the wind conditions, and the results
may surprise you. First of all, the wind was blowing in more than
twice the number of games it was blowing out (54-22), contrary to
Wrigley's reputation as a hitter's paradise. The Cubs' record was
31-23 when the wind was blowing in, 15-7 when it was blowing out.
On the six days when there was a crosswind, the Cubs were 5-1. The
number of runs per game nearly doubled (14.5 to 8.3) on the days
the Bleacher Bums had the wind in their faces . . . The chances of
Todd Hundley being ready to catch for the Dodgers by Opening Day
are increasingly remote. As recently as Tuesday, Hundley caught a
bullpen session for Darren Dreifort and threw the ball back to the
pitcher only half the time. On every other pitch, Hundley flipped
the ball to physical therapist Pat Screnar, who threw the ball back
to Dreifort. ``I'm sure there are some Dodgers fans back in LA who
are pushing the panic button right now,'' Hundley said. ``But
everything is going to work out fine.'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson and GM Kevin Malone are making contingency plans to carry
three catchers at the start of the season: Hundley, plus rookies
Angel Pena and Paul LoDuca. There's also a chance Hundley will
begin the season on the DL. ``If we have to do that, we have to do
that,'' Hundley said. ``That's better than rushing it and playing
two days, then having to take two months off. After any surgery,
you're never going to be the same. You have to do your best to
manage it. That's what we're doing.'' . . . More LA blues: Dodgers
outfielder Gary Sheffield, who recently made noise about wanting to
retire, even though he still has five years left on his six-year,
$61 million contract, was named in a paternity suit in Broward
County, Fla. If the allegations are true, Garrett Wan-Dre Sheffield
would be the player's fourth child with four different women, none
of whom he has married . . . With catcher Carlos Hernandez lost for
the season because of a ruptured Achilles' tendon, the only
positional starters back for the Padres team that won the NL
pennant last season are right fielder Tony Gwynn, shortstop Chris
Gomez, first baseman Wally Joyner, and second baseman Quilvio
Veras. With Kevin Brown a Dodger and Joey Hamilton traded to the
Blue Jays, the pitching rotation returns only Andy Ashby and
Sterling Hitchcock. Woody Williams came from the Blue Jays in the
Hamilton deal, while Matt Clement and Stan Spencer spent most of
last season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder, while watching a Sox game from Fort Myers, how you
could make your lawn look as impossibly green as the perfectly
manicured field at City of Palms Park? ``Good luck and a big
pocketbook,'' says Jimmy Collins, the head groundskeeper for the
last seven years at the ballpark. ``It just takes good, proper,
solid maintenance.'' The infield grass at City of Palms is GN-1
(Greg Norman-1), the outfield Certified 419 Bermuda. The infield
dirt, a mixture of sand and clay, is straight from central Florida.
Collins uses liquid nitrogen as his fertilizer, once a week. ``No
matter how often you fertilize, even if it's once every two months,
you have to do it on a consistent basis,'' he said. ``Your lawn
gets used to being fed, and the more you feed it, the better it
looks.'' Collins, 31, grew up in Lakeland, Fla., across the street
from Joker Marchant Stadium, spring home of the Tigers. ``As a kid,
I used to go over and beg to take down the flag,'' Collins said.
``They used to let us ride the mower. We used to shag foul balls,
too, for a dollar a ball or a bag of french fries. I never dreamed
I'd become a groundskeeper.'' . . . Duquette says he has little
interest in Hideo Nomo, released last week by the Mets. Nomo's
velocity isn't what it was when he starred for the Dodgers, and
hitters are laying off his split-fingered fastball, which breaks
out of the strike zone. Duquette's interest in Kevin Appier seems
to be waning, even though the Royals' ace had his best outing of
the spring Friday, when his velocity was consistently in the 88-90
m.p.h. range. It could be a negotiating ploy on Duquette's part. He
thinks the Royals want too much in return. Royals GM Herk Robinson
is seeking at least two quality prospects for Appier, who at the
moment is slated to pitch against the Red Sox in the season opener
April 5 . . . Steve Fisher, hired Friday to coach the San Diego
State basketball team, may just be keeping the seat warm for Gwynn.
The Aztecs' most famous alum said he'd like to return to his alma
mater as coach of either the basketball or baseball team. ``If one
of those two jobs is open when I'm finished playing, I wouldn't
hesitate going for it,'' Gwynn said. ``I'd get on the horn and call
in all my markers. And I've got plenty of markers.'' Gwynn came to
San Diego State from Long Beach on a basketball scholarship in 1977
and was a point guard on two of San Diego State's top-scoring
teams. In 1981, he was drafted by both the Padres (third round) and
the then-San Diego Clippers (10th round) of the NBA . . . So, how
does Cardinals manager Tony La Russa plan to handle the PR
catastrophe any time McGwire takes a day off? He says he intends to
use Shawon Dunston and Willie McGee, a beloved figure in St. Louis,
at first base. ``I can't wait to do this (McGee at first),'' said
La Russa. ``I want to do it on a weekend in St. Louis when there
are 45,000 people there and somebody else hits third. Say, Ray
Lankford hits third and people say, `Uh-oh, Mark is not playing.'
Eric Davis is hitting fourth, and hitting fifth and playing first,
Willie McGee. There's no doubt in my mind that they wouldn't boo
Willie McGee.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As improbable as it seems, Holyoke's Mark Wohlers, who last
summer lost the ability to throw the ball over the plate, is a
serious contender to reclaim his closer role. Kerry Ligtenberg, who
ended last season as the closer, needs elbow surgery, and a couple
of fine outings this spring by Wohlers put him very much back in
the picture. But lefthander John Rocker remains Bobby Cox's primary
option . . . Gary DiSarcina's broken arm has not healed as quickly
as he would have liked. The Angels shortstop will remain in a cast
for another week at least. He was put on the 15-day disabled list
and is probably out until mid-April at least. Jeff Huson and Andy
Stankiewicz are the leading candidates for the shortstop job, but
the Angels are also talking to San Diego about a possible deal in
which Phil Nevin would go to the Padres for Ed Giavanola or Andy
Sheets . . . Mo Vaughn may prove to be Angels savior, but he can't
put an end to their bizarre history of injuries. Besides DiSarcina,
pitcher Jason Dickson has a torn labrum in his right shoulder and
is out for the season, joining second baseman Justin Baughman
(broken leg that will require a second operation) and relievers Pep
Harris and Mike James (both reconstructive elbow surgery). ``You
don't ever get used to losing key players, and I'm getting pretty
sick of this,'' manager Terry Collins said. ``You arrive in the
morning and find one guy is out for a month and another guy is out
for three or four months at least. You just want to stop playing
and wait until April, but we'll play through it. We'll find a way
to get through it, as usual.'' . . . It took only one spring
training for the Mariners' trade of Johnson to tilt a little more
favorably toward Seattle. All three players the Mariners acquired
from Houston are likely to make the team. Guillen is having a
terrific spring, hitting close to .400, and will be the team's
second baseman and leadoff hitter. Rookie Freddy Garcia figures to
be the No. 3 starter, and John Halama may be the only lefty in the
bullpen. ``We thought when we made that trade last summer that we
were being unduly criticized,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``There
were unknown names, so I understand. Wait until people see what
they can do.'' The Astros, meanwhile, were left empty-handed when
Johnson signed as a free agent with the Diamondbacks . . . The
Phillies haven't moved off their refusal to trade ace Curt
Schilling, whom the Cleveland Indians make no secret of coveting.
There's a mutual admiration there. ``That club,'' Schilling said,
``is the surest lock of any team in baseball to be playing in
October. More so even than the Yankees because of the division
they're in.'' Schilling got the hard sell on the Indians during
last fall's tour of Japan with other major leaguers. Manny Ramirez
and Mike Jackson of the Indians were members of that team, which
was managed by Mike Hargrove. ``Players talk,'' Schilling said. ``I
stood in the outfield a lot with Mike Jackson and talked about
their club. They have careers as salesmen after they get out of
baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
