<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB-ORIOLES-CUBA-BOS &LR;      03-28 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-ORIOLES-CUBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES GAME A MAJOR BREAKTHROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Julio Puig Gay waits for just the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   Arms folded tightly, he leans on his back foot while his eyes
carefully survey the scene.
</P>
<P>
   He says nothing until . . . he . . . hears . . . those . . .
words. Now!
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Cuban baseball players are the best!'' Puig, 35,
yells with the full force of his lungs as he thrusts his arms in
front of him. ``But things have changed. We don't even use the same
bats anymore, so we don't know how we'll do against the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   There. Puig executes a perfectly timed shout, as precise as a
sacrifice bunt, and sparks another round of ear-piercing debates at
La Esquina Caliente, a section of Havana's Central Park known as
the Hot Corner, where dozens of men and a few women spend
sweltering afternoons arguing about sports.
</P>
<P>
   The heat at the corner has been blistering lately, mostly over
baseball, which has been Cuba's passion since American troops and
mill workers brought the game to this island more than a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   These days the cacophony of voices can be heard debating the
merits of wooden bats versus aluminum; of the Havana Industrials
versus their cross-island rivals from Santiago de Cuba in this
week's national playoffs, and of Sunday's exhibition game between a
Cuban all-star team and the Baltimore Orioles, the first time in 40
years a major league team has played here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say this is an exhibition game, but it's really a test
for Cuba's baseball,'' said Giselle Olivas, 45, who stopped by the
corner for a few rounds of arguments on her way home. ``We don't
want to see players practice, we want them to play as hard as they
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The fanatics at La Esquina and the hundreds of other informal
sports clubs throughout the country insist that Sunday's game is
about pelota _ baseball _ and not government policies. But they are
acutely aware of the politics surrounding the event.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 37-year-old US economic embargo on Cuba, which
dates back to the Cuban Missile Crisis of 1962, US companies,
including major league teams, have been prohibited from recruiting
and doing business here. Although Canada has no such ban, major
league rules extend to the Montreal Expos and the Toronto Blue
Jays.
</P>
<P>
   But decades of isolation and economic hardship have not
diminished Cuba's appetite for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, about 40,000 screaming fans packed the Estadio
Latinoamericano in the capital to catch the opening game of the
national playoffs between Havana and Santiago de Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   There was no organ or flashing signs telling them when to cheer,
but the spectators, who paid 10 or 20 cents a ticket, created their
own soundtrack. They banged on drums or cowbells. They honked
horns, whistled, and chanted. Young and old alike constantly yelled
at players about how to hit, throw, and run.
</P>
<P>
   Play was delayed briefly before the bottom of the second inning
by an announcement about baseball's ``importance to the
revolution,'' and to remind fans about proper behavior and that
alcohol was not permitted in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba produces some of the most skilled players and its teams
have regularly dominated world amateur competitions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many Cubans have defected to the United States in
recent years and have reached the grandes ligas, most notably Tampa
Bay pitcher Rolando Arrojo, Florida Marlins pitcher Livan
Hernandez, the 1997 World Series MVP, and his half-brother Orlando
``El Duque'' Hernandez, who pitches for the World Series champion
New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Although state-controlled media seldom print stories about major
league teams, mostly to censor information about Cuban players who
have defected, the most ardent fans keep up by reading box scores
from other newspapers that are smuggled into the country.
</P>
<P>
   One 27-year-old man, who asked not to be identified, said he
managed to peek at ESPN at the hotel where he works.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles owner Peter Angelos began negotiating a Cuba series for
his team three years ago, and it appeared it would never happen
until President Clinton relaxed some of the embargo's rules in
January.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal nearly fell apart again amid disputes over how the
proceeds would be distributed. Eventually, both the US and Cuban
governments decided to use the funds to benefit baseball and sports
programs in each country.
</P>
<P>
   The teams will conclude their series in Baltimore next month.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, though, has stirred controversy, particularly among
Cuban-Americans and others in the United States who oppose Fidel
Castro's Communist government. In an interview last week with the
Fort Lauderdale Sun Sentinel, Marlins owner John Henry questioned
whether the Orioles were using the Cuba trip to quietly scout Cuban
players, a charge Oriole officials deny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are already signs that other teams want to follow the
Orioles' lead. The Anaheim Angels reportedly applied to the US
Treasury Department last month for permission to negotiate with the
Cuban government for a game next year.
</P>
<P>
   When they take the field Sunday afternoon at the Estadio
Latinoamericano, Cuba's 50,000-seat stadium that stands out like a
precious jewel in a city filled with faded and dilapidated
buildings, the Orioles will be the first US professional team to
play here since the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers played
two spring training games in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, in what many consider to have been the last
match between a Cuban team and a professional US squad, the Havana
Sugar Kings beat the Triple A Minneapolis Millers in the seventh
game of the Junior World Series. The Millers' second baseman was
future Red Sox great Carl Yastrzemski.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cubans are also fretting about the Baltimore series, but
not for political reasons. Their concern is timing.
</P>
<P>
   Because Sunday's game is taking place during the middle of the
national playoffs, some of the country's best and most experienced
players _ such as Antonio Pacheco, German Mesa, and Oreste Kindelan
_ won't be in Cuba's all-star lineup.
</P>
<P>
   And it's only been a few weeks since Cuban teams have stopped
using aluminum bats _ to comply with changes in international rules
and to prepare for the Orioles. Fans argue the players have not had
enough time to make the adjustment to wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, I don't think it's the best time to play each
other,'' said Jorge Marroga, a 37-year-old Havana resident who sat
sipping homemade rum with a half-dozen other men in another
informal sports club in the Barrio Chino neighborhood. ``We like to
play against anyone, but I don't think we have a major league-type
team right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others back at La Esquina grumble that they won't be able
to see the game Sunday. Most of the tickets have been given out to
the media _ including more than 300 from the United States _ and to
special guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ones here who deserve to go because we know about
baseball,'' said Eddie Jimenez. ``I guess this is capitalism. But
that's OK, because we all still have baseball in our blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
