<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-LIPTONCHAMPIONSHI     03-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT TO KRAJICEK AS MEN HAVE THEIR DAY 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ They were the warmup act for the Sisters
Sledgehammer, a couple of European guys determinedly entertaining a
sunburnt full-house gathering of 14,000 at Crandon Park with their
zinging strings.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither had been expected to play the title-round gig
when the Lipton began its 11-day run, world No. 7 Richard Krajicek,
the new champ _ 4-6, 6-2, 6-1, 7-5 _ and No. 74 Sebastien Grosjean,
perhaps a new factor in tennis, made the best of their 2 1/2 hours
on the asphalt stage.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Saturday they were strictly second racket to Venus
and Serena, the hammering sisters who occupy the historic main
event Sunday afternoon. That's all anybody's talking about. It's
Williams Time now on this isle across the bay from Miami as the
sinewy teen-agers, Venus the elder at 18, swing at each other for
the family title as well as the Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly sisters have clashed for titles here and there
before, but never in this century for such a prominent prize: The
Lipton is among the planet's leading 10 tennis events. You'd have
to go back to the baptismal Wimbledon of 1884 to find female
siblings _ Maud and Lillian Watson _ battling for a major. Maud,
19, won.
</P>
<P>
   To leap into the final, No. 16 Serena and No. 6 Venus on Friday
had to take care of foes familiar with No. 1. Serena, defying
deficits of 0-4 and 2-5 in the first and second sets, bumped
current leading lady Martina Hingis, 6-4, 7-6 (7-3). Venus then
blotted Hingis's predecessor, Steffi Graf, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be Venus if she puts her mind to it,'' says papa Richard
Williams. ``But Serena is playing the best tennis on the circuit
right now'' _ riding a 16-match streak.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, the Frying Dutchman with the boiling serve (24 aces),
was nearly fried himself in the 89-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struggling,'' he said. ``I haven't been eating well,
been feeling weakened. I thought I had sunstroke in the semis
against (Thomas) Enqvist. I'm happy I didn't have to go to a fifth.
As it was I played economic, short points, conserved my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   But his serve, plus deft volleying, carried him in the crunches
against the bouncy 20-year-old Frenchman, who seemed Tom Thumb in
the company of the 6-foot-5-inch Krajicek. Eight inches shorter,
Grosjean countered Krajicek's power with speed afoot and low,
dipping backhand returns that won him the opening set _ and almost
projected him into a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Grosjean held a set point (4-5, 30-40) to get himself even for a
stretch run, and had a look at a second serve. Not a good look.
Instead of high velocity, Krajicek went for high bounce at low
speed. ``An aggressive kicker,'' he called it, spinning
malevolently, bounding far above Grosjean's backhand, and setting
up the victor for a volley and smash. That was the critical point.
</P>
<P>
   Grosjean, whose name translates as ``big John,'' was for a time
considered too small to receive financial support from the French
Federation. But he grew in prowess to become the world's top junior
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite player was Stefan Edberg, but I play more like
Michael Chang,'' laughed he who pushed Carlos Moya off the No. 1
perch in the fourth round, and beat ex-French Open champ Gustavo
Kuerten in the second.
</P>
<P>
   As the third unseeded finalist in the Lipton's 15 years, he was
unable to equal the winning feat of similarly disregarded champ Tim
Mayotte of Springfield, Mass., in 1985. But Grosjean boosted his
ranking to No. 45 _ ``very happy, my first time in the top 50'' _
and says he'll probably play in August at Boston, where he beat
Jonas Bjorkman, then a top-10 guy, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, conqueror of Pete Sampras in the quarters, advances to
a career high of No. 4. His meeting with Grosjean evoked the old
crapshooting cry of ``Baby needs a new pair of shoes!'' Both he and
Grosjean became fathers recently, and shoes should be no problem.
Even as the warmup act, they did OK: $360,000 for Krajicek,
$190,000 for his victim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
