<HEADER>
A7038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-28 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA'S ACT TOUGH TO FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ After joining the PGA Tour in 1981 out
of Long Beach State, Mark O'Meara built a reputation as a steady
player. After all, a record five victories in the Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am said he could play.
</P>
<P>
   But his story took a sudden turn last year. O'Meara won the
Masters with a birdie-par-birdie-birdie finish; only Arnold Palmer
had ever birdied the last two holes to win at Augusta. Then O'Meara
went to the British Open at Royal Birkdale and beat Brian Watts in
the four-hole playoff for those tied after 72 holes. At age 41, he
became the oldest man to win two major championships in one year.
He was named the PGA Tour's Player of the Year, beating out young
turks David Duval and Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is pretty darn good,'' said O'Meara, who started off
72-73 at The Players Championship. ``It was a very special year for
me, just to break through. Last year was tremendous. I'm trying to
do the best I can this year, and I have gotten off to a reasonable
start.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who became a father figure to Orlando neighbor Woods
before stealing a little bit of the spotlight from him last year,
was asked how he could top Player of the Year honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't,'' he said. ``I'm not going to lie to you. Last year
was a special year, and if things don't go as well this year, so
what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've had a pretty solid career, a consistently good
career. I want to play well, because I play for my pride. I should
also enjoy the moment, too. I needed to enjoy what happened to me
last year and what has happened to me throughout my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the cut last week (at Bay Hill) and I was
disappointed. I'm not going to eat myself up over it. I am 42.
There's no need to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to play well, for me and for my family and friends.
But whether I can move on to the next level and play well at the US
Open and the PGA Championship would complete an unbelievable run. I
feel I've been improving. I didn't necessarily strike it last year
as good as I have in other years, but I did the right things at the
right time and hit the right shots and made the right putts under
crucial moments.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has been an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing him win the Masters in the fashion he did and knowing
when I am playing with him that it is kind of challenging, I think
that challenge has been something that helped push me and elevate
me a little bit,'' said O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm playing with Tiger, he's bombing it by me and I've
got to figure some way to bring my game up a couple of notches.
It's had a pretty big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing O'Meara doesn't crave is the attention Woods draws,
especially from the young. Woods also has been criticized for an
occasional tantrum on the course, something Arnold Palmer brought
up at Bay Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger understands he has made a few mistakes,'' said
O'Meara. ``I think he knows when he slams his driver in the ground
on national TV he has made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine all of you have made mistakes at 22 or 23. If he
walked off the tee with a smile on his face, you'd better start
worrying a little bit. He has a little bit of a temper, but he
wouldn't be the player he is today if he didn't. I saw Davis Love
hit a sprinkler head on the 17th (at Bay Hill), and I don't see
guys ripping him. It's unfortunate Tiger is in the position he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's under the microscope, but I think he's handled it pretty
well considering he's 23. Hopefully he'll learn from his mistakes.
There is a lot of pressure applied on him constantly, day in and
day out, on the course and off the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a movie with my wife and Tiger the other night. The
three of us went into a McDonald's and some girl behind the counter
spotted him. She let out the biggest yell you have ever heard. It
scared the living daylights out of me. She just freaked out. Since
she's screaming, the whole mall knows that Tiger's there. That is
the price that Tiger has to pay for the fame that he has.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Caddie Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, who recently parted ways with
Woods, said reports of a loud exchange between the two in a parking
lot at Riviera after the Nissan Open were greatly exaggerated.
``There were no loud words,'' said Cowan, who tried unsuccessfully
to get work at TPC. ``The media blew it all out of proportion.''
Cowan said he might take the summer off to play golf. He's thinking
of a return to the links courses of Ireland, where he went last
year and encouraged Woods to go on the way to the British Open . .
. Cowan was in attendance Wednesday night when the Professional
Caddies Association Worldwide held its first Caddie Hall of Fame
induction at the World Golf Village on the outskirts of St.
Augustine. The ceremony was held at the new statue of Francis
Ouimet, who was inducted along with Angelo Argea, Squeeky Medlen,
and Peter Coleman. Argea caddied for Jack Nicklaus. Medlen, who
died two years ago after a long bout with cancer, worked for Nick
Price. Coleman worked for Nancy Lopez and Seve Ballesteros. Ouimet
caddied at The Country Club before winning the 1913 US Open there;
the scholarship fund in his memory celebrated its 50th anniversaty
at a gathering in Boston's Back Bay a couple of weeks ago . . .
Willie Peterson, who carried the bag for Nicklaus in five of his
six Masters championships in the era when players were required to
employ a club caddie from Augusta, died a week ago in New York.
Nicklaus continued to look after him, on occasion putting up bail
money when Peterson was jailed in Augusta for infractions usually
associated with the consumption of alcohol. When Peterson gave up
drinking and became somewhat destitute, Nicklaus named him caddie
master at the exclusive Loxahatchee Club he built in Jupiter, Fla.
When a visitor would ask about his involvement with Nicklaus at the
Masters, Peterson would say, ``We have five green jackets.'' . . .
Jerry McGee, a Senior Tour player who won four times on the PGA
Tour, underwent cancer surgery on his neck and tongue Thursday. He
is expected to undergo 5-6 weeks of chemotherapy and will be out of
action for a minimum of three months . . . Duval was asked about
recent gallery problems, with fans becoming more vocal and using
cellular phones and cameras. ``You might hear a cell phone now and
again,'' he said. ``I haven't found a problem with it. I contend if
your head is where it should be, you are not going to hear the
cameras. The phones might be a little bit of a bigger problem. It
always seems they go off during someone's backswing. What are we
going to do? There are some people who feel they have to be in
touch. Doctors have to be reachable. I don't blame them.'' Duval
said he has been heckled only once. ``I had an instance in match
play when someone was loudly cheering for my ball to miss the hole
and go off the green,'' he said, ``but I haven't personally found
that to be a problem.'' At last year's US Open at San Francisco's
Olympic Club, Duval's playing partner, Colin Montgomerie, was
heckled. ``I thought it was out of line,'' said Duval. ``There was
nothing I could do about it. It was rude, but you need to move
beyond it and not let it bother you. You have still got to play.
It's still the US Open.'' . . . Golfweek recently released its list
of America's best classical courses and best modern courses
(constructed after 1960). The classical list includes The Country
Club at No. 20, No. 43 Taconic GC in Williamstown, Mass., No. 46
Salem CC, No. 44 The Kittansett Club, No. 53 Myopia Hunt Club, No.
62 Sankaty Head GC, No. 71 Newport CC, No. 76 Yale GC, No. 85
Oyster Harbors, No. 94 Country Club of Fairfield (Conn.), No. 95
Winchester CC, and No. 100 Essex County Club. The list of the best
modern courses includes No. 96 Crumpin-Fox Club in Bernardston,
Mass. . . . Amy Alcott, who won five major championships on the
LPGA Tour and has 29 victories overall, was inducted into the World
Golf Hall of Fame after standards were relaxed for LPGA players.
``Little did I know 35 years ago when I started with a sawed-off
club that this day would ever come,'' said Alcott. ``Today without
question is a dream come true for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
