<HEADLINE>
REICHEL MILE STONE GOAL LIFTS COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If a man reaches a milestone, he wants it to mean
something.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' Robert Reichel will not forget the 500th point of
his NHL career. His breakaway goal at 15:30 of the third period
proved to be the game winner as the Coyotes defeated the Calgary
Flames, 2-1, on Saturday night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel has scored six points in the four games _ and fourth
goal in four games _ he has played for Phoenix since being acquired
last Saturday from the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about 500,'' said Reichel. ``It's a nice mark
but it's more important to win this game. Calgary played very, very
hard. This game is almost like a playoff game, so it's very
important that we learn to win these types of games.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a quick outlet pass from Oleg Tverdovsky just before
crossing the red line and skated in free and clear to beat goalie
Ken Wregget and break up a stingy, tightly played game that didn't
figure to a high-scoring affair, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a look and saw him hanging back there and I hit him,''
said Tverdosky. ``The points haven't been coming to me too often
this season, so I'll take any kind I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin entered with a 10-1-3 career
record against the Flames and his opposite number, Wregget, was
merely on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Wregget was unbeaten in his past four games and had allowed just
four goals in his past three. He hadn't allowed more than two goals
in his last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a young team and they play with a lot of
enthusiasm,'' Coyotes wing Jeremy Roenick said. ``They play that
1-2-2 trap and it's almost impossible to play against. You have to
flip the puck in over them, or bounce if off the boards, and if you
happen to catch their defensemen playing shallow, beat them to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The system has enabled the Flames to post the NHL's second-best
record since the All-Star break. Saturday's loss was only their
sixth in their past 26 games.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick had a rather eventful second period.
</P>
<P>
   He ended a six-game goal scoring slump by finally cracking
Wregget at 3:05 of the second period to put Phoenix up 1-0, then
promptly played a role in allowing the Flames to knot the score on
Cory Stillman's power play goal at 16:05 of the period.
</P>
<P>
   After getting into a brief scuffle along the boards with Ed
Ward, the two went up ice in pursuit of the puck and left their
business undone, until Ward cracked the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk at
mid ice.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick went after Ward only to be intercepted by Calgary winger
Dave Roch e, who was pounced upon by Phoenix winger Stephen Leach.
When the ice chips had finally settled, Roenick drew two minutes
for interference and Roche and Leach each drew two for roughing,
leaving the Coyotes a man short.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick's goal came when he found himself all alone on Wregget
and deked right and and left, pulling Wregget out of position,
before sliding the puck past the goalie's stick side.
</P>
<P>
   The play was actually set up when Tkachuk broke in on Wregget
but lost control of the puck. He then followed it around the net
and passed to Tverdovsky, who threaded a pass that Roenick took off
Leach's stick and straight to Wregget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a good pass and I squeezed through an opening
and happened to find myself wide open,'' Roenick said.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman knotted the score 29 seconds later, knocking home a
quick shot from the side of the net. Calgary's Rene Corbet knocked
Phoenix defenseman Teppo Numminen off the puck right in front of
the Khabibulin and got it Jerome Iginla, who found the wide open
Stillman.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the first two meetings this season when the Coyotes
scored a combined five goals in the first period en route to a win
and a tie, Calgary pretty much controlled a scoreless, penalty
free-first period.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, sounds simplistic, unless you happen to be
Khabibulin or Wregget.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin had to turn away 12 shots, including stopping Valeri
Bure ``mano a mano'' at the 6:02 mark, while Wregget only had to
face nine shots. But two of those shots came at point blank range
from Greg Adams and Shane Doan, just after Rick Tocchet never
pulled the trigger on a 2-on-1 rush with Reichel and was forced to
bring the puck back from behind the net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
