<HEADLINE>
STARS FEELING STING OF CHAOTIC STRETCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Stars are either a tired, banged-up team
in dire need of rest, or they have picked a horrible time to lose
focus.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into today's 5:30 p.m. game with Nashville, Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock isn't about to accept either explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hard March. But we've never been an organization
to make excuses, and we're not about to start now,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We just have to fight through this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars closed the locker-room doors for 25 minutes after a
5-1 loss to the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim on Friday night. Both
Hitchcock and the players laid out a litany of problems that have
been creeping into the team's performance, including a lack of
aggressive forechecking, poor defensive zone coverage, poor puck
movement, lack of drive to the net in the offensive zone and
overall sloppiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time we should be getting our game back to our
level, not the opposite,'' defenseman and alternate captain Craig
Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had plenty of reasons for their poor outing. They were
playing their second consecutive game, their third road game in
four nights and their 10th game in the past 17 nights. The Ducks,
meanwhile, hadn't played since Sunday and haven't left the Los
Angeles area for the past 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also were without Jere Lehtinen (ankle), Richard
Matvichuk (knee), Shawn Chambers (hip flexor), Brian Skrudland
(torn rib cartilage), and they lost Jamie Langenbrunner in the
second period with an abdominal strain.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars (45-15-12) are on pace for their greatest season in
franchise history and are almost guaranteed the first overall seed
throughout the playoffs _ a clear time to coast, one would think.
Should glitches like this be expected in an 82-game season?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things we have to battle, but this isn't
just one game,'' Hitchcock said. ``We haven't been consistent over
the past eight or nine games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 3-3-2 in their past eight games and easily could
have lost a few more. They have scored 14 goals in that span, an
average of 1.75 goals per game. With 10 regular-season games
remaining, the Stars should be taking their game to the next level
and not struggling through their worst slump of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, it's been a struggle,'' center Mike Modano said.
``We've been getting by, but it takes a game like this to really
make you take notice. It's been building, we could all see it
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   With the heavy schedule, the Stars have been practicing
sporadically to preserve strength for games. But with their hardest
stretch of the schedule almost over _ they will have played 16
games, including 10 on the road in March, the Stars likely will
return to the practice ice more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting away from our game,'' captain Derian Hatcher
said. ``I think a couple of good practices and some rest would
help.'' SIM TO DEBUT
</P>
<P>
   Jon Sim, a 21-year-old Stars prospect, is expected to make his
NHL debut this afternoon _ and in style. With Lehtinen and
Langenbrunner, Sim has been selected to play left wing on a line
with Mike Modano and Brett Hull.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
