<HEADLINE>
DUVAL CAPTURES LEAD AT RUGGED SAWGRASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ PGA Tour officials like to refer to
The Players Championship as the circuit's unofficial ``fifth
major.''
</P>
<P>
   In the estimation of David Duval, the third-round leader at the
TPC at Sawgrass, the $5 million event incorporated aspects of three
major championships yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Players were subjected to greens as severe as Augusta National
Golf Club, home of the Masters Tournament. They endured U.S.
Open-quality roughs and battled breezes that would have been the
pride of any British Open links layout.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Duval, the tour's only two-time winner this season,
shot his worst score of the tournament (74) but still took control
of the leaderboard on a day when the average score was 76.2 at the
7,093-yard, par-72 layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got kicked around. This may have been the most
difficult scoring conditions I've ever seen in my career. It's
definitely in my top five,'' said Duval, who is at 4 under for the
tournament and is one of only six players remaining in red numbers
through 54 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Duval is being pursued by Phil Mickelson (3 under), Skip Kendall
(3 under) and a three-player group at 1 under that includes Colin
Montgomerie, Scott Hoch and Nick Price. Everyone else is at even
par or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie nodded at the brown-tinged greens and said he
understood why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was in trouble when I got to the first green and
looked down and saw my reflection,'' Montgomerie said. ``They're
awfully slick and shiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, one of only six players to break par in the third
round with a 71, said he purposely played his second shot at the
par-5 11th hole into a greenside bunker because he could not stop a
5-iron approach on the slick green of the downwind hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not complaining, but think about that for a second. That's
the type of shots we were faced with,'' Mickelson said. ``It was a
great mental challenge on every hole, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best at handling yesterday's mental challenge was
Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks, who was among the six players who
broke even-par 72 in yesterday's gusty conditions. Brooks improved
42 places on the leaderboard with a 71, leaving him at 3 over for
the tournament and in 25th place heading into today's final round.
</P>
<P>
   One day after surrendering seven strokes to par in his final
seven holes of the second round, Brooks closed with four back-nine
birdies to put himself in contention for his biggest payday of the
season. Brooks' best finish in 1999 was ninth at the Nissan Open,
which netted him $72,800. Brooks, the 1996 PGA champion, has not
earned $100,000 at any PGA Tour event since finishing seventh at
the 1997 TPC.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
