<HEADLINE>
SPRING'S GOOD, BAD FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Entering the final week of spring
training, an evaluation of the '99 Rangers is neither complicated
or out of character.
</P>
<P>
   Success depends upon what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoring runs,'' Rudy Jaramillo said yesterday. ``Get three or
four runs early, and then don't let up.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball multitudes will second his motion. It didn't take
five weeks in the Florida swamps to legitimize this popular theory
on the Rangers _ it's a team that will have to outscore it's own
pitching rotation.
</P>
<P>
   But as the hitting instructor, Jaramillo's words weren't meant
as a commentary on mound woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a commentary on what kind of batting order we have,''
noted Jaramillo. ``It's my way of putting pressure on myself.
Scoring runs is what we should do, not what we will have to do
because of this or that.''
</P>
<P>
   As springs go, this one has been on the cloudy and overcast side
for the Rangers, despite a month of almost solid sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   An evaluation of a club top-heavy in offense:
</P>
<P>
   Good _ Mark McLemore moving like three seasons ago on surgically
repaired (again) knees. If McLemore is as sound as he looks, the
defensive hole at second base is closed, plus the No. 2 spot in the
lineup is plugged.
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ A variety of injuries, lowlighted by John Wetteland's
ankle. The whole season rides on Wetteland being sound.
Bullpen-closer separates the Rangers from divisional foes Anaheim
and Seattle. A positive update is Wetteland threw from the mound
yesterday and again was without pain.
</P>
<P>
   Good _ Early in camp, manager Johnny Oates was on edge, snapping
at the media (which is not all bad), but his demeanor also raised
clubhouse eyebrows. Over the past three weeks, and particularly of
late, Oates has done a 180. He's become Mr. Cool Breeze. The Oates
of old was uptight and defensive. The current kind of Oates is a
much better manager.
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ Not one starting pitcher having an exceptional spring.
Even a good spring would be stretching it. ``It has at least been
consistent,'' said pitching coach Dick Bosman, attempting, I think,
to sound positive. Spring training often means zilch. In this case,
the Rangers hope so. But what does it say about Florida when the
team weakness has been a weakness?
</P>
<P>
   Good _ The emergence of third baseman Todd Zeile. ``I see one
big year coming for Zeile,'' said Jaramillo. ``That he's hitting
eighth for us says a lot about our lineup. I wouldn't hesitate to
say Johnny could hit him fifth if he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ Options on trading for a starting pitcher may not be as
numerous as first thought. The Rangers have not been impressed with
Kevin Appier's work this spring. There are rumors of a bone spur in
Kenny Rogers' elbow (although Rogers did have a good Friday outing
in Arizona, with Rangers' scouts watching.) Curt Schilling didn't
list the Rangers among four teams he'd consider if the Phillies
make a trade. The Twins are acting as if Brad Radke is untouchable;
then again, the season hasn't started for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Good _ For the moment, Rafael Palmeiro is storming back from two
knee scopes since February. ``Everything points to him being ready
for Opening Day,'' said Jaramillo, after watching Palmeiro
yesterday take batting practice. Rafael was more positive than
that. ``I will open in Arlington \RApril 5\S at first base, or at
the least, as the DH,'' he said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ Right-hander Esteban Loaiza trudges along, failing to
respond after being openly challenged by Oates, Bosman, etc. With
the best ``stuff'' on the staff, the Rangers hoped for a
breakthrough spring from Loaiza. Instead, he's the same puzzle that
Pittsburgh traded last summer. Remember, the Rangers gave up a nice
prospect, second baseman Warren Morris, in that Loaiza deal. Loaiza
won't be in the rotation and is also close to being bypassed for
long relief duty and shipped out of here.
</P>
<P>
   Good _ Rookie Ruben Mateo has had the kind of spring that almost
_ I said almost _ makes Doug Melvin happy the Roger Clemens trade
escaped the Rangers. Mateo will ``probably'' still open the season
as the Triple-A center fielder, although Oates said, ``I'm going to
keep him with us \Rthis week, including the Arlington exhibition
games\S. I just love to watch him play.'' Mateo's team-first style
and friendly smile are as impressive as his talent. This kid's
attitude is a carbon-copy of a young Sammy Sosa as a Rangers'
farmhand in the late '80s. The scary part is Mateo's talent is
better than Sosa's at the same stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ The Mike Simms injury, which may sideline him until
mid-summer, is bigger than the name Mike Simms implies for most
fans. ``As a part-time right-handed bat, Mike gave our lineup a
run-producing presence that kind of got lost behind all our other
names,'' said Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Good _ The regular season opens in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Bad _ Nothing. Not with Opening Day in Arlington just around the
corner.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
