r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     03-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN CAN THANK PROTEGE FOR THIS GIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Matt Kenseth is going to be big in racing
some day.
</P>
<P>
   He's going to graduate _ with honors _ from the NASCAR Busch
Grand National circuit. He's going to take the Winston Cup series
by storm. He's going to win a lot of prize money. He's going to
give a lot of news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   But not yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Not on a dank and drizzly day when Kenseth, just turned 27,
squandered a victory with the Coca-Cola 300 checkered flag only a
few laps away.
</P>
<P>
   Not yesterday, when Kenseth behaved like the teen-ager who
dented the family car then locked himself in his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have any comment,'' Kenseth finally told
reporters who waited for him in the rain for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk about it tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth is one of the lucky ones. He has a tomorrow in this
business.
</P>
<P>
   Today in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series Primestar 500, Kenseth
will be in the bullpen, waiting for the possible call to relieve
the injured Bobby Labonte. In coming weeks, owner Jack Roush has
arranged for Kenseth to drive in five Winston Cup races, as a
prelude to a possible rookie-of-the-year bid in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty big Matt Kenseth fan. I'm a pretty big supporter
of his,'' said driver Mark Martin, whose name will be on the new
Roush Racing team.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if you've read this before, but Martin won again at
Texas Motor Speedway yesterday. But this one was as much Kenseth's
doing as it was Martin's.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth was flying along with the greatest of ease. By Lap 7, he
was slingshooting past pole-sitter Dave Blaney and into the lead.
By Lap 95, he was breezing along at 181.702 miles per hour, the
fastest lap of the day. By Lap 140, Kenseth had led 127 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to catch him,'' Martin surmised.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was.''
</P>
<P>
   On the race's 140th lap, Kenseth pitted under a green flag. When
he emerged, he moved quickly to regain his lead until a collision
between Casey Atwood and Jeff Krogh sent debris flying in Turn 4.
The yellow flag promptly went up. But Kenseth, instead of trusting
his race car, accelerated to try to beat the leader, Jeff Green, to
the start/finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing Kenseth knew, he was on the infield grass, bouncing
and sliding sideways past the starting line _ looking a lot like
that Jeff Gordon Pepsi commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caution fell at the wrong time,'' said Robbie Reiser, the
owner and crew chief of Kenseth's No. 17 DeWalt Tools Chevy. ``Matt
was doing his best to get us back on the lead lap, and, well, we
just overdid it. It was just one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   A young driver, you could argue, makes mistakes like that. An
older driver _ a Mark Martin _ would have felt confident that his
car, easily the fastest on the track, would recoup the lost pit
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to get through, but he just didn't have enough
room,'' Reiser said. ``It's one of those deals. He's being hard on
himself. He feels terrible about it. He's thinking he's to blame
when he isn't; we're all in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   While Reiser talked with a small knot of media members, Kenseth
remained in his trailer behind closed doors. But Reiser wasn't
blaming his young driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about Matt Kenseth,'' Reiser said. ``He's a
great race driver. How can I not still be high on him? Matt is an
awesome car driver and an awesome person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be concerned if he ``wasn't'' upset right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a victory news conference, owner Roush and Martin
admitted that, yes, they have taken the Wisconsin native under
their wing. Last year, in his first full season on the Busch
circuit, Kenseth won three times and finished second in the points
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Roush said he plans to launch Mark Martin Racing and ``help Matt
and Robbie Reiser find their way into Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be big, they say. One day, Kenseth figures to be Roush's
lead driver. There will be races on Sundays, not rainy Saturdays.
And news conferences to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Matt's taking it on himself real hard,'' Roush
said. ``But we look forward to the year 2000 with Matt.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rain fell yesterday, though, Matt Kenseth was like the
pouting teen-ager, the one whose impatience had kissed a glorious
day away.
</P>
<P>
   He'll talk ``tomorrow,'' Kenseth said.
</P>
<P>
   They say he'll have many of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
