<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SPURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY SPURS ROLL OVER WEARY MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Last night was not a good time to be playing the
San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were in a rotten mood after the Toronto Raptors paid a
visit and defeated them on Friday night. The short-handed Mavericks
received the brunt of the Spurs' frustration as San Antonio turned
on the jets in the second half and rolled to an easy 99-77 victory
in front of a crowd of 25,921 at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured if anybody was going to sneak up on them, it would
be us,'' Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson said. ``But
\RToronto\S beat us to it, so we figured they would be mad as
hornets tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson figured right.
</P>
<P>
   Now three-fifths of the way through the season, the Mavericks
are 10-20 and didn't strike any fear in the Spurs after playing
impressively during the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In winning for the 13th time in their past 15 games, the Spurs
(19-10) displayed their superior power in the second half. Despite
playing their third game in three days, the Spurs outscored the
weary-looking Mavericks by 19 points in the final half after
leading by only 44-41 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said the main reason his team unraveled in the second
half was ``because they're a lot better than we are. We hung in
there for a long time, but then their strength, power and skill got
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks dressed only 10 players and played without their
most aggressive player, forward Gary Trent, who stayed in Dallas to
nurse a stomach virus. Nelson said he didn't know how much his team
missed Trent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't here,'' he said, ``so you deal without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent's absence enabled Samaki Walker to play 18 minutes, and he
responded with a season-high 16 points and six rebounds before
fouling out late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good out there,'' Walker said. ``But we just didn't
answer the call when they got up on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan rebounded from his worst scoring night ever against
Toronto to tally 21 points and grab 15 rebounds against the
Mavericks. By the end of the first quarter, the Spurs led 25-19 and
Duncan had already scored 10 points _ doubling his point total from
the Toronto game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept it three, four, five points most of the game,'' said
center Shawn Bradley, who had 15 points and 12 rebounds. ``But San
Antonio, being the good team that they are, when they got up by 10
points, rather than fold and let us believe that we can win and
sneak one late, they put us away.'' \Nsubheds:Notes Forward Gary
Trent's week-long stomach virus has finally cost him a game.
</P>
<P>
   Trent did not make the trip to San Antonio because of the
ailment. He became ill on March 19 in Detroit on the morning of the
Mavericks' game against the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just feels weak and sickly,'' Mavericks coach/general
manager Don Nelson said. ``He doesn't look sickly. He may have some
blood tests \Rtoday\S.''
\Nsubheds:BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   With his three blocks last night, Shawn Bradley has 102 blocks
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has eclipsed the 100-blocked shot barrier in all six of
his NBA seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson will give his players today off. The Mavericks, who
played games the last two nights, will play host to Seattle
tomorrow and play at Minnesota on Tuesday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
