u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKO-MINORLEAGUENOTEBO     03-28 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-MINOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEIGHTS FOR OLD EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Even in the days when Boston College wasn't skating to
Hockey East titles and NCAA Tournament berths, the Heights was
turning out future pros by the bunches.
</P>
<P>
   Several have gone on to starry NHL careers, and more than a few
others are scattered throughout the minor leagues. Two former
Eagles have found fame, if not necessarily fortune, in the
International Hockey League. However, their first names and alma
mater seem to be the only other things that Dave Hymovitz and David
Littman have in common.
</P>
<P>
   One scores goals in bunches, the other prevents goals. One has
been out of BC for three years, the other is in his 10th pro
season. One plays in the Midwest, the other in Florida. One is
still waiting for his first call from the NHL, the other has paid a
few quick visits to the world's best league. One likes to light up
the scoreboard, the other wouldn't be averse to seeing his name in
lights someday.
</P>
<P>
   Hymovitz, a left wing, is enjoying a career year with
Indianapolis; his 41 goals rank second in the IHL and are only 10
fewer than he had scored in his two previous years as a pro. With
11 games left, Hymovitz has an outside chance at 50.
</P>
<P>
   Skating most of the season on an all-New England line with
former Boston University star Bob Lachance and South Boston's Brian
Noonan before Noonan was signed two weeks ago by the Phoenix
Coyotes, Hymovitz, a Randolph native, has left his struggling
numbers from last season (11-15_26) far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Hymovitz scored 39 goals with Columbus in the East Coast Hockey
League as a rookie, earning a shot with Indianapolis at the end of
the 1996-97 season. Originally drafted by Chicago in the ninth
round out of Thayer Academy in 1992 before spending four years at
BC, Hymovitz is a free agent in the NHL's eyes, under contract only
to his independent IHL club.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade in pro hockey, Littman is the definition of
journeyman, but the trip the Cranston, R.I., native has taken has
been anything but mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo made Littman the 211th overall pick in the 1987 draft,
and he got into one NHL game a season from 1991-93 with Buffalo and
Tampa Bay. Since then, he has played in Rochester, Phoenix,
Atlanta, Fredericton, Providence, Richmond, Los Angeles, and San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Littman's career appeared finished after he was released
following the 1996-97 season, but Orlando needed a goalie and
signed Littman out of a Los Angeles beer league early the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   He finished ninth in the league in goals against average (2.66)
and, living up to his reputation as a big-game goalie, backstopped
the Solar Bears to the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   His 20 wins are third in the IHL this year, and he has appeared
in a league-high 51 games.
</P>
<P>
   With his time in hockey dwindling, another world is beginning to
open up for Littman. Along with two teammates, one of which is St.
Anselm's Hubie McDonough, Littman appeared in TV ads that won
awards from the Orlando Advertising Federation and have been
nominated for district and national honors.
</P>
<P>
   Littman lived in LA the summer after playing for its IHL
franchise in 1995-96, and spent time as a stuntman and working on
Hollywood sets. For a ``Seinfeld'' and movie devotee, how perfect
would a post-hockey Hollywood career be?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hockey News has published its annual ``Future Watch'' issue,
a gold mine of information that offers a comprehensive assessment
of the prospects who have already been drafted. The highest-rated
American Hockey League player, at No. 5, is Saint John goalie
Jean-Sebastien Giguere, who has been up with parent club Calgary.
Former BC center Marty Reasoner, who has spent most of the season
in Worcester, is tied for 35th. No current Hockey East players were
among the top 50 . . . Speaking of scouting, Patrik Stefan, a
projected top choice in this June's draft, certainly knows how to
draw a crowd. Some 43 NHL scouts recently gathered to watch Long
Beach's 18-year-old center play an IHL game in Kalamazoo, Mich.
Tampa Bay, which certainly needs help, sent six scouts; some 20
teams were represented . . . With most college teams done for the
year, the annual spring signing flurry has begun. Defenseman Dean
Stork left the University of Massachusetts a year early to sign
with Portland (AHL); he's still enrolled in classes while playing
weekend games with the Pirates. Any chance for independent study
credits? Also, Merrimack's Kris Porter has joined Worcester . . .
Lowell (AHL) has called up former UMass forward Blair Manning from
Louisiana (ECHL).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A team playing on home ice holds a three-goal lead with less
than five minutes remaining. Game over, right? No, the game was
just beginning for Saint John, which scored five times in a span of
4:10 to beat Hartford two weeks ago. With the WolfPack ahead, 5-2,
Martin St. Louis instigated the comeback by scoring with 4:21 to
go. The Flames netted four more goals _ Vermont alum St. Louis
assisting on two to complete a 4-point game _ and Saint John had an
improbable victory . . . Tough break for Bobby Sheehan, who was
forced to retire from Charlotte (ECHL) after suffering his second
concussion in three months. The rookie defenseman from Medford, who
played at Northeastern, has had six concussions in six years . . .
The Calder Cup and a display on the history of the AHL playoffs is
visiting all 19 league cities prior to the playoffs in mid-April.
The tour is due to hit Providence Sunday, New Haven Wednesday, and
Lowell Friday . . . After six seasons, the Portland Pirates have
etched some memorable accomplishments _ a Calder Cup their first
season, a final appearance in another _ so the team has begun a
Hall of Fame. Fans are invited to vote for the three initial
inductees (from 10 nominees) either at games or at
www.portlandpirates.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Success on the ice hasn't been reflected at the box office, so
Lowell will take the unusual step (for a first-place team) of
lowering ticket prices. With the team averaging only 3,294 fans,
next to last in the AHL, the cost of attending a Lock Monsters game
next year will range from $9-$15, down from $11-$22 . . . Make sure
to find a copy of last week's Sports Illustrated and read the
feature on Jesse Boulerice and Andrew Long, who were involved in a
grotesque stick-swinging incident last season in junior hockey.
Boulerice, playing again after a year's suspension, and Long have
spent time in the AHL and ECHL this season but have yet to face
each other . . . Logo of the Week: Pick your own. Hockey fans long
ago discovered the Internet and its multitude of resources. League
and team home pages, statistics, even chat rooms offer a wealth of
information. Along comes www.hockeydb.com, which offers not only
statistics for NHL and minor league teams but also a page on which
the logo of your favorite team _ active or defunct _ appears with
the click of a mouse. So log on and go logo lookin'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
