<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-28 1883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BOTTOM LINE: NOTHING DOING 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stand Pat behind the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Stand pat in the front office.
</P>
<P>
   And so we saw it again last week, the Bruins' modus operandi
running right to form as the '90s come to a close. The trade
deadline found Boston's NHL entry comfortable and satisfied with
its eighth-place standing in the Eastern Conference, showing no
urge whatsoever to upgrade the lineup, add to the foundation of
talent, as the playoffs approach.
</P>
<P>
   This is no surprise. It's the same tack the front office took
last summer when Mssrs. Harry Sinden and Mike O'Connell opted not
to sign free agents or make trades, content to hand the whole show
back to Pat Burns and ostensibly tell the coach, ``Make a little
more out of the same ol', same ol'.'' They expected Burns to wring
more out of the existing cast and start blending in some of the
kids from Providence.
</P>
<P>
   We know how that went. Some of the returnees got better
(witness: Joe Thornton, Byron Dafoe). Some got worse (witness:
Sergei Samsonov, Dave Ellett, Don Sweeney). A couple of the Baby
B's wannabes even showed a little something (witness: Cameron Mann,
Mattias Timander). By and large, however, Burns has been loathe to
thin the stock with AHL blood, and the Boston roster we now see is
ostensibly the same lot _ a little better here, a little worse
there _ that was bounced in the opening round of last year's
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it makes perfect sense not to tamper with the core of
youth. One only has to look at the implode-while-we-rebuild Celtics
to realize that, at some point, management has to identify its core
players and stick with them. Constantly changing the parts in hopes
of trading up is a strategy doomed for failure. It's never a team.
It's just a bunch of guys in a holding room, wearing the uniform of
the day, waiting to be handed a ticket out of town.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins needed to fill out around their youth with some
veteran help. That was true last summer. That was true last week.
It's all the more vivid when the coach, the guy who ultimately
decides who plays and who doesn't, makes it clear through act and
word that he isn't going to start slapping Shawn Bates, Randy
Robitaille, Andre Savage, Terry Virtue, and the rest of the best in
Providence into the Boston lineup come crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   Burns will go with what he knows, take his best shot with those
he feels are proven NHL commodities. Ellett is one of those guys.
That's the same Ellett placed on waivers just before the trade
deadline. That's the same Ellett Burns brought to the Hub when he
was hired as the new coach in the spring of '97.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's what's happening: The front office is telling Burns
to play the kids and he's saying the kids aren't ready; in turn the
front office takes Ellett, a coach favorite and a guy he counts as
one of those to be relied upon, and offers him around the league
for freebies. One side is saying the kid(s) can't play. The other
side is saying the old guy is too slow, overpaid, and can't play.
Hmm. Now there's an afternoon in Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are equally obstinate. That's the fun in watching
this unfold. Burns is all about winning, in the way he best knows
how. Sinden and O'Connell are all about business, and they keep the
Vault brimming with bucks by assembling a team and a coaching staff
that do just enough to keep one of the most loyal fan bases in all
professional sport hungry for more. If Pavlov had run out of dogs,
he could have substituted either Bruins or Red Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' decision not to beef up the lineup at the trade
deadline will be deadly. There were players available at cheap
prices: Derek Plante, Joe Juneau, Sergei Nemchinov, Wendel Clark.
None of them carried a price past this season. Each could have
added support for the playoffs, filled the jobs that the Baby B's
weren't able to fill last year or this year. An injury or two _ an
absolute guarantee in the postseason _ will leave the Bruins
wishing they had paid more attention last week when there was help
to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind, too, that ultimately Burns will have no choice but
to go with the kids, be it the next few weeks or be it next autumn.
The front office non-moves in the past nine months have made that
abundantly clear. Putting Ellett on waivers said it even more
profoundly. Trades? Improvements? Free-agent upgrades? Forget it,
coach. Those days are done. Grab a gallon of Clearasil if you have
to, get a primer on Generation X and, you know, like, go to work.
Cool.
</P>
<P>
   What if Burns won't do the job as deemed by the front office?
Then the next kid in town will be Peter Laviolette, the Providence
coach. Last week proved Causeway Street is all about control, cash,
and kids.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unless someone really catches fire, no one in the NHL will score
50 goals this season. That hasn't happened since the Bruins' Phil
Esposito popped in a league-leading 43 in 1969-70 (a Cup season in
Boston). Remember, this will be the first year the league presents
the Rocket Richard award to the leading scorer. ``I don't think
they should give anyone the trophy if they don't score 50,'' kidded
Anaheim's Teemu Selanne. ``The goalies are too good _ we need
bigger nets.'' The Rocket was the first NHLer to collect 50 goals
in a season . . . Before the Canadiens sent him to the Sharks, the
Oilers toyed with the idea of bringing Vincent Damphousse back to
Edmonton, where he collected 89 points in '91-92. The rental fee
would have been some $500,000 over 26 days, a price general manager
Glen Sather knew was too steep for Oiler ownership. In case you
missed it, Damphousse popped in two goals in his Sharks debut . . .
Peter Zezel's season came to a bizarre end Tuesday when he refused
a trade from Vancouver to Anaheim _ where he was projected as
relief for center Steve Rucchin. Zezel refused to report to the
Ducks, because he doesn't want to spend time away from his
3-year-old niece, who is terminally ill. ``If I'm not with my
family, I'll regret it the rest of my life,'' said Zezel. The deal
was voided and the Canucks bought out the last month of Zezel's
contract, contributed an equal amount, and will use the total to
set up a charity in the child's name . . . Ex-Boston University
star Chris O'Sullivan, of the Dorchester O'Sullivans, was dished to
the Rangers. O'Sullivan's skills are smooth but he didn't have the
requisite crusty edge to suit Flames coach Brian Sutter. The
Blueshirts assigned O'Sullivan to Hartford (AHL) . . . Actress
Susan Sarandon, in an interview last Sunday with Barbara Walters,
when asked if she and companion Tim Robbins had it all: ``If the
Rangers were to win the Stanley Cup, then we'd have it all.'' . . .
The April 5 edition of ESPN The Magazine carries a revealing piece
on Toronto netminder Curtis Joseph. Born in 1967 _ three days
before the Leafs last won the Cup _ CuJo was adopted by a couple
who owned and operated the Martin Acres Home for Special Care in
Sharon, Ontario. He was one of four children who shared living
quarters with 20 mentally disabled adult males. CuJo: ``It was a
big house with lots of rooms. It was pretty lonely. When I was old
enough, I used to look forward to going to school. I guess some
good comes out of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa forward Bill Berg to the Ottawa Sun after the Bruins' 3-0
victory over the Senators last week: ``If that was a preview of the
first round, then we'd better realize we're going to be in for a
tough playoff series.'' . . . Word around the NHL is that up to a
dozen clubs have expressed interest in signing free agent Jason
Krog, the University of New Hampshire center considered by many to
be the favorite to win the Hobey Baker Award . . . Even the steady,
successful Stars did some late roster augmentation, adding alum
Benoit Hogue (from Tampa) and picking up the speedy Plante from
Buffalo for a second-rounder. Also added to the mix: Blake Sloan, a
feisty forward they signed out of the IHL (Houston) on March 10.
The trio gives Dallas the kind of depth head coach Ken Hitchcock
could have used last season to make a real run at the Red Wings . .
. The Kings did the expected and bought out Steve Duchesne's deal
for $4.25 million, then re-signed him for this year and shipped him
to the Flyers for Dave Babych. When the year ends, Duchesne will
have been paid $8 million for the year and will be an unrestricted
free agent again. ``A valuable lesson,'' said Kings GM Dave Taylor,
who seriously doubts that he'll go shopping again in the overpriced
free-agent market . . . Cramer Productions in Norwood again is
staging an NHL playoff fantasy draft to benefit the Foundation of
Fighting Blindness. Interested would-be GMs can call:
1-800-683-5555 to book an April 20 reservation . . . The Bruins
recently lost one of their most royal rooters with the passing of
Gloucester's Peggy Marshall, a season ticket-holder for the past 20
years. Marshall sat in the first row near the Zamboni entrance,
alongside pals Marje Bishop and Gary Levin, and made sure that
everyone _ refs included _ went by the rulebook . . . In his
appreciative remarks upon welcoming Nemchinov to New Jersey, Devils
coach Robbie Ftorek reminded one and all that the skilled Russian
played on the Olympic team between Alex Mogilny and Pavel Bure.
Right line, wrong church. The three once rode together, but in the
World Championships. The point is still valid: Nemchinov, virtually
lost on Long Island, can be a real asset even at age 35 . . .
Zigmund Palffy, regarding the Islanders' plight, in comments to
Newsday: ``I thought we were going to build a good team here.'' . .
. The Flyers last week added _ hold on to your double-runners _ a
skating coach, ex-Canadian speedskater David Roy. Now that's
cutting-edge stuff . . . The Red Wings took Bill Ranford (one win,
$3 million this year) off the Lightning's hands on trade day,
easing about $500,000 off the Bolts' payroll this year. If the Red
Wings don't want Ranford next year _ and he doesn't get grabbed by
Atlanta in the expansion _ the Bolts will have to pick up a portion
of his 1999-2000 salary . . . When the Leafs acquired Yanic
Perreault from LA at the trade deadline, it meant Kevyn Adams,
another onetime Bruins first-rounder, had to head back to the
minors (St. John's) . . . The Capitals trimmed back payroll
significantly with an 11th-hour salary dump (including Juneau to
the Sabres), but they'd still like to unload Dmitri Mironov and
Michal Pivonka . . . Just like the Bruins, the Capitals are going
to reconfigure their ticket-price structure, perhaps dropping some
season-ticket prices at MCI Center by as much as 50 percent . . .
Don't look for Juneau to sign in Buffalo over the summer. An
unrestricted free agent, he's on record as wanting to sign with
Ottawa, but someone will pay him upwards of $3 million a year, and
that won't be the fiscally sensible Senators . . . The Islanders'
Craig Janney recently required hospitalization to thin out a blood
clot in one of his legs, ending his season. No truth to the rumors
that doctors found traces of Esa Tikkanen's bite marks on Janney's
heels and elbows, left over from the '88 and '90 Cup finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
