<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS STUN JAZZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It was the best of teams, it was the worst of teams.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the neck you'd expect to find in the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the night when the junkyard dogs - riding that bad
attitude after weeks of teasing -- finally caught the neighborhood
hooligans on the wrong side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Utah Jazz -- checking in as the NBA's best team,
relative to post-season pedigree - having their egos spanked
Saturday by the Clippers, 103-77, in front of 14,293 fans who
should save those ticket stubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a superb game of basketball for 48 minutes,'' said
Clipper coach Chris Ford, whose team recently has been good for
about 36.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night when Utah's Karl Malone, who usually receives
more calls than A-list telethons, was granted two technical fouls
and subsequently ordered to leave the premises. Malone, whose Hall
of Fame elbows became familiar with the chin of Clipper forward
Maurice Taylor, was booted at 9:44 of the third quarter after
clipping Taylor on a rebound skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really pissed me off,'' the young Clipper said. ``I told
him to quit whining about the calls, too. I know we go back there
(Utah) one more time, but I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who has made a habit of avoiding rebounds (he somehow
finished with zero), decided he wouldn't avoid this confrontation.
While teammates held him back, the second-year ex-Michigan star
clobbered Malone with more harsh language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to look up to him, sort of,'' Taylor said of power
forward role model Malone. ``From now on, he's just another another
(compound expletive) on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches from both teams left their benches to restore order.
Utah coach Jerry Sloan talked his way into a technical of his own.
</P>
<P>
   When the chitchat ended, the Clippers held a 59-36 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the real turning point was the opening tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (3-24), who keep threatening to commit basketball,
smothered the defending Western Conference champions from jump
street. The ringleader was rookie center Michael Olowokandi, who
defied the doomsday prophecy of Clipper draft critics by scoring
nine points and tracking down nine rebounds in the opening quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 15 points and 13 rebounds. Rookie forward
Tyrone Nesby and shooting guard Eric Piatkowski were in cahoots
with Olowokandi, the former scoring 16 points and snagging seven
rebounds, while the latter scored a game-high 18 points. Lamond
Murray added 15 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Malone missed six of his seven field-goal attempts, finishing
with seven points and ending his consecutive double-figure-scoring
streak at 575 games. Jacque Vaughn, Jeff Hornacek and Todd Fuller
led Utah (21-7) in scoring with ... 10 points apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers had a 52-32 edge at intermission, and increased the
lead to 79-54 through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   When did Ford feel comfy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never, really,'' said Ford, a student of recent history.
``It's just nice to see the guys rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter was a vintage edition of garbage time, with
the Clippers - in a casting change - refusing to hang from the back
of the truck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
