<HEADER>
A7050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLELEAFS     03-28 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLELEAFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET POINT OF TRIP TO TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ For better than 52 minutes, the Bruins had control.
For better than 52 minutes, the Bruins had it won.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was: Regulation lasts 60 minutes. In those
final minutes of the third period, the Bruins surrendered a 2-0
lead, giving up goals at 12:42 and 19:01, and were forced to settle
for a 2-2 tie with the high-flying Maple Leafs Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at
the Air Canada Centre.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were just 7 minutes 18 seconds from a clean getaway
after playing a nearly flawless first two-plus periods. The Bruins
had received a boost in the afternoon when the Rangers lost to
Philadelphia and had an opportunity to do themselves a bigger
service by winning. However, they ran out of gas, playing their
fifth game in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give the puck to the best offensive team in the NHL,
sooner or later, they're going to give it back to you (in the form
of a goal),'' said coach Pat Burns. ``We gave them the puck for one
goal . . . but it was a big point for us. We had a lot of good
chances to win the game and (goalie Curtis Joseph) was on top of
his game. He made some tremendous saves to keep them in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be satisfied with the point, we've got to be
disappointed with the point we lost, but I'm satisfied with the
point we got.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10 games remaining, Boston has a six-point lead over the
idle Florida Panthers and seven-point advantage over the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins finished the season series with the Leafs at 3-1-1,
the only loss coming in their final appearance at Maple Leaf
Gardens Jan. 9 with Ray Bourque sidelined by an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Boston increased its unbeaten streak to six games
(3-0-3). The club is 5-1-3 in its last nine.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bourque who put the Bruins ahead, 1-0, with a power-play
goal at 8:11 of the first period. Bourque scored from the point,
giving him 10 goals for the season, eight of which have come with
the man advantage. The score tied Bourque with fading Carolina
Hurricane Paul Coffey for most career goals by a defenseman (385).
In 45 games this season, Coffey has just two goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs thought they had tied the game at 2:38 of the
second. Right wing Mike Johnson, who was skating right to left
behind the Boston net, dished the puck to center Steve Sullivan.
Sullivan skated out from behind the cage and fired a wraparound
past Byron Dafoe at the left post. But the video replay showed that
left wing Derek King was in the crease and the goal was disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four minutes later, the Bruins made it a two-goal lead
on Joe Thornton's 13th of the season. As a penalty to Fredrik Modin
for interfering with Dafoe was expiring, Thornton blasted a shot
from long range that sailed past Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Boston could have had more. Anson Carter rattled a shot off the
post in the waning seconds of the period with the Bruins on a power
play that carried over into the third.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout much of the contest, the Bruins handcuffed the Leafs
offensively, holding the home team to a measly two shots in the
second.
</P>
<P>
   Burns asked his players at the morning skate which was the
highest-scoring team in the league. ``They all knew the answer,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs went into Saturday &UR;  &LR; night with 229 goals,
significantly more than any team in the Eastern Conference. Until
the third period, the Bruins played an ugly road game, clogging the
middle of the ice, trapping like crazy, and stifling any
run-and-gun ambitions the Maple Leafs had.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the polite fans screamed, ``Boring, boring,'' but
it was a style that played right into Boston's hands.
</P>
<P>
   That changed dramatically in the third. The Maple Leafs pulled
to within a goal at 12:42, a result of one of the few Bruins
mistakes. Don Sweeney was stripped of the puck and right wing
Sergei Berezin ended up flipping the puck at the net from high
between the circles, beating Dafoe to the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs came to life after the goal, putting their first real
heat on the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   They then cashed in another chance, tying the game with 58.7
seconds remaining in regulation. Not long after Landon Wilson had a
great opportunity denied by Joseph, defenseman Daniil Markov took a
centering pass from Sullivan with Joseph pulled for an extra
attacker and beat Dafoe from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played a lot of games in the last while,'' said Burns,
``but I thought we handled it pretty good. You can't give the puck
to the best offensive team in the league and not expect them to
score.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
