r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-SQUEEZE-2takes-     03-28 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SQUEEZE-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT VIDEO STORES FEEL SQUEEZED BY BIG-CHAIN RENTAL BARNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Call it the Monster that Ate Mom and Pop, as in
mom-and-pop video stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having the hardest time of my life,'' said Mark Tusher,
owner of three Alamo Video stores in Simi Valley northwest of Los
Angeles. ``Even strong independents like myself are suffering
everywhere. We've just been ravaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The devourers are the nation's two major videocassette rental
chains, Blockbuster and Hollywood Video, with much more than 5,000
outlets. Now dubbed ``Hollybuster'' in the trade press, the giants
have rolled across the land thanks to a new strategy dubbed ``copy
depth,'' in which they buy enormous quantities of new titles at
reduced rates and guarantee they'll be in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster, which will be spun off from Viacom Inc. this year,
has become particularly aggressive, both at building up its copy
depth and at building its stores. It had already planned to add
1,000 stores to its U.S. empire of more than 4,000 outlets and then
recently announced plans for 500 ``fill-in'' stores this year. In
other words, ``Big Blue'' will be everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been impressed. Viacom stock, which had been
dragged down by Blockbuster in the mid-'90s, has tripled in value
in two years; Hollywood Entertainment, parent of Hollywood Video,
is up 50percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The losers are the independents, which comprise two-thirds of
the nation's 27,000 video rental outlets. Once a staple of strip
malls everywhere, smaller video mom-and-pop outlets are vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independents are not doing very well because the big
stores are driving them out of business,'' said Richard Leyner, a
broker with Capital Commercial. ``We see vacancies from video
stores even though the overall commercial vacancy rate is very
low.''
</P>
<P>
   The Video Software Dealers Association believes nationwide store
count could drop by 10 percent this year; Ron Berger, chief
executive officer of wholesale specialist Rentrak, estimates 400 to
500 indie outlets are closing per month with about a third of those
replaced by major chain outlets; and Blockbuster has been shopping
a plan for indies to convert stores to Blockbuster outlets.
</P>
<P>
   It's an amazing turnaround for Blockbuster, which was on the
verge of collapse two years ago before dropping an ill-fated
diversification strategy and focusing on a ``Go Home Happy''
campaign that promised that new titles would be in stock. Analysts
now believe Blockbuster has the potential to control half the
nation's rental market, estimated at $8 billion to $10 billion
annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've been dedicated to doing is satisfying the consumer
for the past year and a half,'' said Blockbuster spokeswoman Karen
Raskopf, noting that walk-out rates _ customers leaving without
making a purchase _ had been as high as 20 percent previously.
``They told us loud and clear in focus groups that they wanted new
product guaranteed in stock and priced competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Roffman, an investor with a large position in Blockbuster
parent Viacom, predicted many indies will disappear, much like Meg
Ryan's bookstore closed after Tom Hanks opened a megastore nearby
in the movie ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in an age of massive consolidation of every
industry from bookstores to breweries,'' said Roffman, principal of
Roffman Miller Associates in Philadelphia. ``Blockbuster is
succeeding because it finally addressed the major customer concern
of not being able to get the tape you wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, a VSDA board member, said indies are doomed because they
can't match the marketing ability of the majors. In addition, and
probably more importantly, the independent video retailers aren't
large enough to participate in most revenue-sharing deals, under
which studios sell tapes to stores for $5 or less in exchange for a
revenue split.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blockbuster and Hollywood have the marketing strengths and ad
budgets and physical presence, if you will, to have copy depth,''
Berger said. ``They have the ability to simply outspend rivals and
create a far bigger presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Local indies believe ``Hollybuster'' is targeting them for
extinction. ``You're seeing nice stores with loyal clienteles close
down simply because Blockbuster wants market share,'' Tusher
asserted. ``No one is making any money right now because
Blockbuster is buying 10 times more copies than they need.''
</P>
<P>
   All this comes at a time the video industry remains one of the
great success stories of the last 20 years, generating $20 billion
this year from sales and rentals just in the United States. The
soaring popularity of the DVD format will probably add years of
robust life to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But with so much at stake and so many players, it's no surprise
that there's plenty of turmoil:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Independent Video Retailers Group has been threatening to
sue Blockbuster and major studios over unfair pricing and
revenue-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rentrak, which supplies more than 10,000 stores, and 20th
Century Fox have sued Hollywood Video's parent over underreporting
sales figures; Hollywood claims Rentrak misinformed Fox.
</P>
<P>
   _ A video store owner in Carmel filed an antitrust suit against
Blockbuster over a deal it signed giving the chain exclusive rights
to 45 movies from Showtime, Trimark and October Films; the New
England Buying Group called for a boycott of Trimark and October
titles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Revenue-sharing and the growing complexity of the video
business is forcing major supermarkets to abandon rentals.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   _ Distributors are complaining that indies are forming informal
buying groups to maximize buying power.
</P>
<P>
   _ VSDA President Jeff Eves resigned in January amid criticism
that he favored the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Indie retailers are not shy about placing the blame. ``I
personally feel that what Blockbuster is doing is predatory
pricing,'' said Alan Kirk, owner of Video Super Shop in Ventura,
northwest of Los Angeles. ``If I want to do revenue-sharing, I
can't get the same terms because I have to go through a distributor
like Rentrak rather than deal directly with the studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster's Raskopf denied the predatory pricing allegation,
adding, ``Our goal is most assuredly not to drive prices down; it
is to make sure we're priced competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Salzer, owner of Salzer's Videos in Ventura, and a VSDA
board member, said the studios are also to blame. Indies must set
up a special buying program for every movie, and stores are often
required to purchase far more tapes than they need, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of messages that we no longer matter in
the scheme of things,'' said Salzer, who opened his store more than
a decade ago. ``It's an unlevel field for indies to play on.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Salzer acknowledged, Blockbuster and Hollywood
have changed the behavior of the customer by stressing the
availability of new titles and then flooding the walls with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be the customers needed to be somewhat
unsatisfied,'' he said. ``It's always worked this way _ you build
up the desire for new product and offer plenty of other things, so
customers aren't conditioned to go after the latest and the
greatest. Now, Blockbuster and Hollywood are conditioning them to
look for nothing but new titles like `Rush Hour,' `There's
Something About Mary,' `The Truman Show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk agrees. ``The customer used to say, `I'll rent something
else,' but the customer has been trained to feel that they'll get
their first choice,'' he said. ``So I've spent a tremendous amount
of money, about three times as much as I normally would have, on
new titles. You have to adjust _ if that's what they want, you have
to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   And staying alive requires more than spending more, Kirk noted.
``I've got my boxing gloves on every day,'' he said, contending
that his store has better service and a better feel for the needs
of customers, in addition to supporting local community
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people that if the indies go out of business, the
consumers lose because then the corporate stores have total control
over pricing,'' Kirk said. ``When competition is dead and gone,
it's dangerous for consumers as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
