<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH ELBOW ROOM FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ There are 11 players still on the Red Sox
roster who will not be there on Easter, when general manager Dan
Duquette must submit his Opening Day list of 25 players to the
American League office.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Tim Harikkala doesn't look that far ahead. He takes a
far more pragmatic view of his tenuous status in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week you get big-league meal money is a bonus,'' he said
Saturday after pitching three scoreless innings in the Red Sox'
4-4, 10-inning tie with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   With Bret Saberhagen needing a couple of extra days after
developing a knot at the bottom of his right shoulder, Jimy
Williams needed another starter Saturday. How did he settle on
Harikkala?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like this,'' Williams said, taking off his cap and pretending
to reach in and draw out a name.
</P>
<P>
   Williams could afford to be casual about such matters because
his five-man rotation is set. The decisions must still be made in
the bullpen, where Harikkala is one of seven pitchers _ and a long
shot candidate at that _ for one, and possibly two, jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Four spots in the bullpen are assured: closer Tom Gordon, setup
men Jim Corsi and Derek Lowe, and lefthanded specialist Mark
Guthrie. John Wasdin, even though he has allowed 18 hits and 7
earned runs in just 12 1/3 innings (including tape-measure home
runs to Cecil Fielder and Marty Cordova in the last week), has the
inside track for the long-relief position.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave one position open. The favorites for that job
are Kip Gross, the returning Japanese import who has a big-league
deal with the club and has said he'll go back to Japan before he
goes to the minors; and Brad Clontz, who appeared in 140 games in
two seasons with the Braves as a setup man and says he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Rheal Cormier, who worked two snappy scoreless
innings Saturday, also would loom as a candidate, except the Sox
seem to feel that Cormier, on his second go-round with Boston with
a major elbow surgery in between, needs to build up more arm
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Harikkala, a 27-year-old righthander who five years ago was
named the Mariners' Minor League Pitcher of the Year but hasn't
sniffed the big leagues since 1996, is here as a nonroster invitee.
This is the deepest he's ever stuck with a big-league club in camp,
but he's a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start thinking about (the cutdown date), you'd drive
yourself nuts,'' he said. ``You just do the best you can, and let
the results speak for themselves. Hopefully, you make it tough for
them to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Clontz, who did not pitch Saturday, has a save and a win in his
last two appearances. The submarining righthander, who appeared in
two World Series for the Braves but was back in the minors in '97
and played with both the Dodgers and Mets last season before
undergoing elbow surgery, also is a nonroster invitee here. But he
has far more big-league experience than Harikkala, and is
well-known by Williams, who was a coach with the Braves when Clontz
was thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm healthy, pitching without pain, for the first
time since the middle of '96,'' said the shaven-headed Clontz, a
Virginia native who played college ball at Virginia Tech and
thought that the discomfort he began to feel with the Braves was
just something he had to pitch through.
</P>
<P>
   Clontz said that last September, David Altchek, the Mets' team
doctor who performed Saberhagen's shoulder surgery, took out two
bone spurs and five ``large-sized'' chips from his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I've got a new attitude,'' Clontz said. ``Before, it hurt
me to throw my slider, so I stopped throwing it. Now, my slider is
a lot sharper, and I can snap it off. I don't have to baby my
elbow. Everything is free and loose.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clontz, who will be 28 next month, is anything like the
pitcher who used to set up for Mark Wohlers of the Braves, he will
represent a significant upgrade for the bullpen. His slider, coming
out of his near-underhanded motion, is a very difficult pitch for
righthanded hitters to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason I came here is because I thought I'd have an
opportunity to fit in, to reestablish myself,'' Clontz said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he hasn't made any decisions yet, and may defer
them until next weekend, when the Sox play their last two
exhibitions in Denver against the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll keep an open mind,'' he said. ``For some of these kids,
even though it's just spring training, these games are like playoff
games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
