<SLUG> BC-LAUGH-INDEX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHUCKLE COST UP, INDEX SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We're paying bigger fees for smaller tee-hees,
according to the 1999 Cost of Laughing Index.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, the index of 17 comical indicators
rose 3 percent, reflecting a gain in the minimum fee for sitcom
writing and a jump in the fee for a singing chicken telegram.
However, the price of a dozen rubber chickens has fallen (from $66
to $60), partially offsetting the other increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 3 percent increase is no laughing matter,'' said author and
humor consultant Malcolm Kushner, who has been publishing the index
on or around April Fool's Day since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The index consists of 17 indicators, including admission prices
to 10 comedy clubs across the country, Mad magazine's newsstand
price ($2.50) and a dozen Groucho glasses ($15). The only other
indicator to fall was admission to Atlanta's Punchline club, down
to $14 from $15.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner, the author of ``Successful Presentations for Dummies,''
was enthused about taking advantage of the decline in
rubber-chicken prices as a way to shore up Social Security. ``Now
the government can afford to put a rubber chicken in every pot,''
he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner's full-time job is running a Santa Cruz-based consulting
business under which he gives speeches to corporations and
associations. But rather than offering instruction in workplace
joke-telling, he advises audiences to be careful in using humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep it clean and don't be mean,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
