<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN LESS EFFECTIVE VS. MOORE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Ricky Moore had the basic high school
BMOC scorer's resume: 21 points a game his senior year at Westside
High in Augusta, Ga., with a high of 37.
</P>
<P>
   But ego reduction is a fact of life for all but the very chosen
few in college basketball. In the fall, All-State quarterbacks are
turned into cornerbacks, and most of them are not very happy about
it when the idea is first presented to them. So, too, in
basketball, are offensive stars required to make very serious
physical and mental adjustments, some more than others. Ricky
Moore's came when Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun told him he could
forget about shooting it 12 or 15 times a game. The mentor had
something else in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed to find a place,'' explained Calhoun after a 64-58
victory over Ohio State sent his team into Monday night's national
championship game at Tropicana Field against Duke. ``We sold him on
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   On an evening when slender, glider-supreme Richard ``Rip''
Hamilton sliced through the Buckeye defense for 24 points and when
lovable point guard Khalid El-Amin submitted one of his Picassos
with 18 points, 6 assists, and a number of momentum-busting plays,
Moore, son of an Augusta National caddie, may have stood taller
than any other Husky. Moore's job was to make sure that Scoonie
Penn would not enjoy his trip to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The Penn line pretty much says it all. Ohio State's floor leader
was held to 11 points on 3-for-13 shooting to go with a manageable
four assists. He seldomly was allowed to penetrate into the lane.
Coming off a truly spectacular South regional in which he not only
had taken Ohio State to the Final Four but also had elevated his
status in the eyes of the pro scouts, Scoonie was very, very
mortal. He was just another 5 foot 9 inch guy.
</P>
<P>
   And he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Moore was tremendous,'' saluted Penn. ``He may not have
scored 24 points, but he was the MVP in this game tonight. When he
took me out of the game, it affected the way our offense was run.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing overtly cerebral about the Calhoun approach to
the Scoonie Penn problem. He simply said to Moore, ``You've got the
little guy,'' and then watched his senior human postage stamp affix
himself to the oft-frustrated Ohio State point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has seen it all before. He has put Moore on every
quality guard unfortunate enough to be on the Connecticut schedule,
and he really had no reason to expect the results to be any
different, NCAA national semifinal game or no NCAA national
semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scoonie Penn is going to make money playing
professional basketball,'' said Calhoun. ``But this year we've seen
Mateen Cleaves (Michigan State) and Arthur Lee (Stanford) and
everyone in the Big East, and Moore has continually done what he
did today. Basically, what we did was cut the head off the body. We
watched Ohio State on tape and as Scoonie Penn goes, so goes Ohio
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn and St. John's would each second that motion. Scoonie
abused them for 48 points, 12 assists, and even 11 rebounds last
week in Knoxville. Aside from a pair of open first-half threes and
one patented, snake-like slither to the hoop in the second half,
Penn's personal offense was kept under control by the 6-2 Moore.
And at no time did Scoonie penetrate into the lane for a dish-off
to, say Michael Redd, the Ohio State scoring machine. The head
Calhoun was alluding to was lying on the Tropicana Field floor
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to take the drive away,'' said Moore, who, in
fact, took the drive away.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a solo effort, but these things never are. Very few
modern teams play strict, straight-up, 100 percent, man-to-man
defense. Individuals are instructed to be aware of what's going on
around them. They are expected to double-team a roving opponent
when necessary, and in so doing they might run the risk of having
their own man break free for a score.
</P>
<P>
   Moore had no such responsibility in this game. Calhoun was
confident enough in the ability of the other UConn men to contain
the Ohio State threats _ Redd, specifically _ so that Moore could
concentrate on his one job, to stop Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other team helps out on Michael Redd,'' sighed Penn.
``Not UConn. Ricky Moore stayed with me all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien knew where the game was decided.
``Ricky Moore deserves an awful lot of credit,'' he said. ``He made
Scoonie work for the entire 40 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Guarding Penn wasn't all Moore did during his productive 37
minutes of work. He also found time to lead the Huskies with eight
rebounds. His 6 points on 1-for-7 shooting were almost immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   Moore is matter-of-fact about the whole thing. ``I'm still a
good offensive player, as well as a good defensive player,'' he
maintains. ``It doesn't matter to me. I knew I could stop people. I
just want to win games. I took on that role when he asked. I had no
problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He will always know that his efforts have been appreciated by
his coach. ``I've had a lot of good defensive players,'' Calhoun
declared. ``Ricky Moore is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have taken the best to stop Scoonie Penn, because he was
the hottest guard in America. You'd have to think that Jim Calhoun
will always have a soft spot in his heart for Augusta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
