<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-OHIOSTATE-BO     03-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-OHIO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE DEVILS MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ OK, so this had nothing to do with any
confounding losing streak Boston Coll . . . er, Ohio State
basketball coach Jim O'Brien had in his previous 18 head-to-head
matchups against Jim Calhoun and his Connecticut Huskies. UConn's
decisive 64-58 victory over the Eag . . . er, Buckeyes in the first
game of Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's national semifinal doubleheader before
41,340 at Tropicana Field had little to do with O'Brien's ancient
history against his former Big East rival.
</P>
<P>
   It's more to do with the fact that Calhoun's team, once again,
proved to be the better of the two on the court. It had more to do
with the defensive straitjacket Ricky Moore threw on BC's . . . er,
Ohio State's Scoonie Penn, limiting the Buckeye catalyst to 11
points on 3-for-13 shooting. It had more to do with the effort of
Richard Hamilton, who eclipsed the 2,000-point mark for his career
with a game-high 24 points on 10-for-17 shooting, as well as an
Ohio State team that missed 40 more shots than it made (23) and
committed 11 turnovers that led to 21 easy transition points for
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, no matter how much had changed for O'Brien, and the
members of his staff he imported from Chestnut Hill to Columbus,
since the last time he coached against UConn, one thing remained
painfully unchanged: His record against Calhoun. Eighteen times the
same scenario has played itself out _ like Bill Murray's wake-up
scene in ``Groundhog Day'' _ with Calhoun walking to midcourt to
extend a conciliatory hand to a bitterly disappointed O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th time around proved no different for the two men, with
two notable exceptions: the Final Four setting and the high stakes
of a possible national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a better team today and we had better players, and
that's why we won,'' explained Calhoun, who now has guided his team
(33-2) to unprecedented heights with a berth in Monday night's
title game. ``We had Ricky Moore on our side to stop Scoonie, who's
a great, great player.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our life has gone back and forth, (O'Brien) gets as much
out of his basketball team than anyone I know. They're a Final Four
team, sure. But they've faced a lot of tough teams and they're here
and that's a tremendous credit to him and, as I said to him, I
don't know of anybody who's more efficient at coaching than Jimmy
O'Brien. I mean they get everything done and they get all their
players involved.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the Buckeyes share O'Brien's stigma of losing to UConn,
but on much grander scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team,'' O'Brien said when asked if anything
about UConn had changed since he last faced them. ``They're one of
the better teams in the country. They played like it tonight. They
played every bit to the level that we anticipated they would
play.''
</P>
<P>
   So what did he say to Calhoun at the end, when both coaches met
at midcourt?
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' O'Brien said, ``And good luck on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien was hoping to hear those same words from Calhoun, and by
halftime, it appeared as though he would. The Buckeyes rallied from
a 32-23 deficit in the first half by going on a 10-0 run to take a
33-32 lead on an offensive putback by Michael Redd, who led Ohio
State (27-9) with 15 points on 7-for-18 shooting. But as they've
done all season, Hamilton and Khalid El-Amin, the chunky sparkplug
of a guard who chipped in 18 points, rose up and scored huge
baskets that gave UConn a 36-33 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Singleton, who led the Buckeyes with 9 first-half points,
pulled Ohio State within 1, 36-35, at halftime when he nailed a
jumper and then combined with Ken Johnson, who swatted Ed Saunders
underneath, on a pair of huge blocked shots. Singleton stuffed a
Hamilton attempt on the ensuing inbounds play, inciting a shoving
match that only seemed to fire up the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think definitely in the first half we really had them on the
ropes,'' El-Amin said. ``At the same time, we got kind of relaxed
on offense and we tried to beat our men one-on-one. That caused
them to get a couple of turnovers and score easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes erased a 51-41 deficit to pull within 57-54 on
Redd's fast-break basket, but with 2:50 remaining, the Huskies put
the game out of reach in an amazing sequence when Jake Voskuhl
mishandled a backcourt pass, almost passing it to himself, before
El-Amin alertly called timeout. Then, before he fouled out with
1:24 to go, Voskuhl saved a loose ball and fed it to Hamilton for
an absolute dagger of a jumper that lifted UConn to a 61-55 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly believe we have a better game in us,'' Calhoun said.
``We played well together defensively, but I wasn't happy about our
offense (26 of 55 shooting). I'm happy to be here. I'm tremendously
happy to be going to Monday night's game. But I think we have a
better basketball game in us and I hope that we have that on Monday
night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
