<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHIGANSTAT     03-28 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-MICHIGAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE DEVILS MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Finesse didn't work, not that Michigan
State was much for that anyway. Speed didn't work either. Duke had
too much of that going into the game.
</P>
<P>
   So Michigan State tried something that any Big Ten Conference
fan would appreciate. It went into its football mode. If coach Tom
Izzo's Spartans couldn't beat the Blue Devils in a conventional
way, maybe beating the Devil out of them would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   For a few minutes in the second half it almost did, but in the
end Duke turned into, well, Duke, a team that has now won 37 of 38
games, has not lost since a last-second loss to Cincinnati the day
after Thanksgiving, and is one victory away from entering the NCAA
record books as one of the greatest teams of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was played out at Tropicana Field Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in
front of a sellout crowd of 41,340 as Duke fought off an aggressive
Michigan State team, hanging on for a 68-62 victory and a spot in
Monday night's national championship game against UConn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously ecstatic about winning,'' said Duke coach Mike
Krzyzewski. ``The type of game and the type of team we played
against makes it even more worthwhile. I mean it really was as
fulfulling a win that we had all year because they're so good.
Points were so hard to come by.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first 20 minutes, Duke seemed to have things under
control. Led by center and Player of the Year Elton Brand, the
Devils forged a 32-20 lead. Brand, who had 18 points and 15
rebounds (including 13 boards in the first half), simply muscled
his way underneath, calling for the ball after he cleared out any
Michigan State defenders foolish enough to try and get in his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I could score most of the time and get fouled, find an
open man,''said Brand. ``I was really demanding the ball a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   For a school with the rich football tradition of Michigan State,
that was just not acceptable. Izzo, a big football fan himself,
gave his players some simple advice: If you want to win this game,
you needed to show some of the aggressiveness that Brand was
showing.
</P>
<P>
   If Duke has a weakness _ which no one outside of Cincinnati has
really come close to finding _ it might be this. They don't know
how to play football on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   So for 10 glorious minutes in the second half, bodies started to
fly as the Spartans went through drills that their football
counterparts would have appreciated in spring practice, which is
currently underway back in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, trying to keep in the spirit of the evening, shoved back,
but he also picked up his third and fourth foul of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was 51-48 with 9:32 left and some Dukies in the
building with a sense of history surely remembered the last time
Blue Devils played a game in this building: last year's South
Regional final against Kentucky, in which the Devils had a 17-point
lead near the nine-minute mark and found a way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. At least not against Michigan State. The Devils
already knew they could beat the Spartans, having taken a 17-2 lead
in the first five minutes of a Great Eight meeting in Chicago in
December and coasted to a 73-67 victory.
</P>
<P>
   This time there was no coasting. Michigan State (33-5) came out
of the locker room in the second half with an attitude and a plan.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half of a half, it all seemed to work. Michigan
State's All-American point guard Mateen Cleaves put in a couple of
3-point shots, super-sub Morris Peterson (15 points, 8 rebounds)
got some buckets, and the Spartans were back in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively speaking, of course. With Brand sitting for a spell,
the Blue Devils went to their next set of weapons, which this time
happened to be guard William Avery (14 points) and Chris Carrawell
(13). And, of course, Trajan Langdon, who made a 21-foot, 3-point
bomb from the left side that doubled the Dukies' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Elton out of the game, we knew we had to step it up as a
team,'' said Langdon.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Michigan State had no response. Or not enough of one
to create even a hint of uncertainty. The Spartans' strategy turned
into fouling and hoping for Duke misses, which was a reasonable
assumption since the Devils made only 14 of 27 free throws. But in
the final two minutes, the Devils made just enough to keep the
Spartans at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got it done for 40 minutes,'' said Izzo. ``We only got it
done for 25 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   For Duke, 40 more minutes of getting it done will mean a
national championship and a dream end to a dream season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
