<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NOR     03-28 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMMENSEN WON'T YIELD TO NORTHERN MICH. 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-NORTHERN MICHIGAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Northern Michigan coach Rick Comley worried
about Boston College's fast starts. He worried about the Eagles'
big guns on offense.
</P>
<P>
   He worried less about goalie Scott Clemmensen.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the BC guns _ Jeff Farkas and Brian Gionta, got second
period power-play goals and because of Clemmensen and a tight
defense overall, that's all the Eagles needed.
</P>
<P>
   BC shut down Northern Michigan, 2-1, in a first-round NCAA West
Regional game Saturday &UR;  &LR; night to lift its record to 26-11-4. And
more importantly, the Eagles earned a spot opposite top-seeded
North Dakota in Sunday's final with a berth in the Final Four in
Anaheim _ and a matchup with Maine _ at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen gave up a goal to Fred Mattersdorfer 5:38 into the
game. And that was it. He finished with 26 saves and finished off
the Wildcats' season at 22-15-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played better than I thought he'd play, in all honesty,''
Comley said. ``I thought their strength was up front. On tape, when
New Hampshire came back on them last week in the Hockey East
championship game I thought he was vulnerable. At times maybe he
didn't look great stopping it, but he kept it out of the net.
That's all he has to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He kept it out of the net after the Mattersdorfer goal while
Northern took the play to the Eagles in the first period. Caught a
break when Brad Frattaroli clanged one off the crossbar midway
through the period. He kept it out to keep the Wildcats off the
board through six power plays while BC was scoring twice on its own
six chances. And kept it out down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He kept it out well enough that BC coach Jerry York and forward
Blake Bellefeuille, who set up both BC goals, called it his best
game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quick and he played his angles well,'' said York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clem played great tonight,'' Bellefeuille said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen mostly left it for others to assess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed they were throwing it to the net and everyone kind
of crashed down,'' Clemmensen said. ``The second period we were
kind of running around and they really came at the net pretty hard.
I think it was one of my better games this year. I've been feeling
real good. Hopefully tomorrow night I have an even better game.''
</P>
<P>
   He may need one.
</P>
<P>
   York has watched North Dakota on tape and planned to see a
little more Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as good as advertised,'' he said. ``They're extremely
quick. It will be a completely different type of game. Northern
Michigan is more defensive. North Dakota wants to get to seven real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota, the 1997 national champion, is 32-5-2. The
Fighting Sioux lost to Denver, 3-1, in the WCHA finals last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After spotting Northern Michigan the first-period lead, BC came
back in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had done little with their first two power plays.
They scored 16 seconds into their third.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas took a pass from Bellefeuille and went to the net. He was
stopped by Wildcat goalie Dan Ragusett once and then put in his own
rebound for 1-1 at 5:01.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, Northern Michigan was already shorthanded
when Tyler Barbanoff was sent off for cross-checking.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats killed off 25 seconds of a BC five-on-three. But BC
still had a man advantage when Bellefeuille fired the puck from the
side boards and Gionta deflected it past Ragusett.
</P>
<P>
   BC had its work cut out protecting the lead in the third period.
The Eagles had to kill two penalties in the first half of the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen made a series of tough saves, including one glove
save on Barabanoff. In the last minute, Clemmensen held his ground
when J.P. Vigier came from behind the net and tried to tuck the
puck in.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmensen, a sophomore, backboned BC's run to the national
championship game last year. This year, he started all but one of
the Eagle games and is now 25-11-4.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, he and the Eagles put the team's seven-game win
streak on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really pleased,'' York said. ``We have a team that can
score a lot of goals. We're very talented and quick. But we
stressed right from the start of the year that to be successful on
a national level we've got to be able to play these low-scoring
games.''
</P>
<P>
   For a night, at least, they did. Much to Comley's dismay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
