<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-MAINE-CLARKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE OVERPOWERS CLARKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The University of Maine hockey team is on the
Avenue to Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears earned a spot in next week's Frozen Four by
dispatching ECAC regular-season and postseason champion Clarkson,
7-2, at the Centrum Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in the second round of the NCAA
East Regional before a record crowd of 12,517.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the attack was Hobey Baker finalist Steve
Kariya, who was Bunker Hill Monument tall as he registered three
goals and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There something in me that says I'm not satisfied,'' said
Kariya. ``There's something bigger left. Certainly it's gratifying
and we're excited to go to the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine is back in the big time under coach Shawn Walsh, who said
all week, ``We came here not just to win a game. We came here to
win a trip to California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we did it,'' Walsh said Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. ``Credit the
players. They wanted this so bad they could taste it and now
they'll go to the next level. A level they richly deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh had been indicating that his team was on the verge of
peaking and was he ever right.
</P>
<P>
   His Black Bears (29-6-4) were 2-3 in the last five games before
coming here. There were two losses at New Hampshire; two wins over
UMass-Amherst in the Hockey East playoffs, and a 3-2 overtime loss
to Boston College in the Hockey East championship game.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears were impressive Friday night in a 4-2 victory
over Ohio State and continued to look great in all facets of their
game Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been playing well all along,'' said Walsh. ``There
never was any reason to panic. Poise is necessary for success at
this stage of the season and we have showed poise.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I almost second-guessed myself. I wanted to peak at this
tournament so we paid a price against New Hampshire and Boston
College. We changed our power play, which basically was to put Cory
Larose on the point, and that worked. Our power play picked an
appropriate time to get warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine was 3 of 5 with an extra man and Clarkson was 0 for 5.
</P>
<P>
   Said Larose, ``We've been focusing a lot on team speed. That's
been our game plan all week.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya was fantastic. He's an athlete who could dance in a phone
booth like Gene Kelly while wearing his skates. He's an MVP's MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Said Walsh, ``That was an unbelievable performance by an
unbelievable player.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again team defense and firepower were keys to the Maine
victory starting with junior goalie Alfie Michaud who made 20
saves. Kariya's center Larose had 3 points and defenseman David
Cullen had 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal as seniors was to get Maine to be one of the
powerhouses in the country,'' said Cullen.
</P>
<P>
   Maine started the scoring at 9:32 of the first when Marcus
Gustafsson scored from point-blank range after he was set up by
Kariya and Cullen.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson tied it at 11:05 when David Evans took a pass from
behind the Maine cage from Erik Cole and scored his fifth goal into
the right side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson's Aaron Gates was caught hooking at 14:55. Costly.
Maine went up, 2-1, at 16:23 on the power play when Kariya scored
his 25th goal.
</P>
<P>
   A Maine goal by Cullen at 18:14 was replayed by officials and
was allowed because it went into the net after glancing off the
skate of a Clarkson defender.
</P>
<P>
   Another Clarkson penalty was costly as the Black Bears scored
their second power play at 4:55 of the second period when Kariya
potted his 26th goal.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkson was awarded a penalty shot and Evans made it 4-2 at
16:52 when he potted a 10-footer after a neat deke.
</P>
<P>
   Maine made it 5-2 at 0:37 of the third period when Larose scored
on an 18-foot backhander. Maine scored its third power-play goal
when Niko Dimitrakos of Somerville scored from 20 feet out at
12:21. Clarkson pulled goalie Shawn Grant and moments later Kariya
scored his third goal at 15:25.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh praised his assistants, saying, ``Gene Riley and Nate
Leaman convinced me to go with the high breakout to get it out of
the zone and they convinced me to shadow Erik Cole, who is as good
a player as any player we've seen all year.''
</P>
<P>
   To his seniors Walsh said, ``Good things happen to good people.
These are good people. No matter how we played tonight they'll be
successful. And all five will graduate on time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
