<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NEWHAMPSHIRE-MICH     03-28 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNH ELIMINATES MICHIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
 HAMPSHIRE-MICHIGAN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ University of New Hampshire freshman winger
Darren Haydar, frustrated on at least three occasions in the early
going by Michigan goalie Josh Blackburn, saved his best for last in
the NCAA East Regional Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at the Centrum.
</P>
<P>
   Haydar was in the right place 3:16 into the first overtime,
taking a feed from behind the net from center Jason Krog and
beating Blackburn to the short side, giving top-seed UNH a 2-1
victory over the defending national champs before a record crowd of
12,517 and a trip to the Frozen Four in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   It was deja vu for the Wildcats, who defeated Boston University
in overtime a year ago in Albany to advance to the semifinals at
the FleetCenter, where they were dispatched handily by Michigan,
4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's reign ended when Krog swept behind the Michigan net,
stripped the puck from defenseman Dave Huntziger, and found Haydar
alone at the post where he had Blackburn (22 saves) at his mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Krog behind the net and strip the D,'' said Haydar.
(Mike) Souza was yelling for the puck in the center and (Krog)
threw it into the middle. I cut in, and it hit Blackburn in the
pads and went in.''
</P>
<P>
   UNH outskated Michigan for long stretches and outshot the
Wolverines, 34-21. The Central Collegiate Hockey Association
champions (25-11-6) not only saw their their six-game winning
streak snapped, but also their quest to become the first team in 27
years to win back-to-back national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pressured the puck all night and didn't give up many
opportunities,'' said UNH coach Dick Umile, whose team improved its
record to 30-6-3, including a 9-1-2 streak over its last 12 games.
``I'm looking forward to going out west. This is a special group
and this is a team with a legitimate chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   With its come-from-behind, 5-3 victory over Denver here on
Friday, Michigan boosted its NCAA Tournament winning streak to five
games. The sixth wasn't to be, but Michigan made it interesting,
tying the game with 10 minutes to play on a Bobby Hayes wrister
that broke between the pads of UNH goalie Ty Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes had won the faceoff from Krog, something that the center
had on his mind as overtime loomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely felt like I owed the team,'' said Krog. ``I felt
like the season was on the line. I wanted to leave everything on
the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Souza, from Wakefield, gave UNH the early lead, finishing off a
two-on-one with Haydar with just 9.2 seconds remaining in the
opening period. Blackburn kept the game close after that, but
Michigan coach Red Berenson had a feeling that Friday's tough game
with Denver was working to UNH's advantage since the Wildcats were
rested and waiting with a bye in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night's game took its toll,'' said Berenson, ``and it
showed early and as the game wore on. Tonight, I don't think we had
enough left over.''
</P>
<P>
   UNH held an 8-1 shot advantage at the halfway point of the
opening period. Shot No. 8 was Haydar's foiled breakaway attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Haydar's frustration mounted with 7:41 to go in the period when
he was alone at the crease for a one-timer that was again foiled by
Blackburn.
</P>
<P>
   But UNH persevered, got the late first period strike, then kept
pouring it on, except for a stretch late in the second period when
Michigan mounted its only sustained pressure of the game.
</P>
<P>
   UNH, after killing off an early penalty, was in control for most
of the second period. Haydar made a nice move, but his wraparound
shot went through the crease. UNH's Jason Shipulski then tested
Blackburn with a 25-footer that the goalie tipped over the crossbar
with his glove. Midway through the period, Blackburn was quick to
deflect Matt Dzieduszycki's wrister.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan put some late pressure on Conklin with its best chance,
a Dale Rominski second rebound attempt that resulted in a pile of
bodies at the crease, but no goal.
</P>
<P>
   UNH, which was outshot in the second, 11-8, took its one-goal
lead into the final period, then lost it, then won in dramatic and
familiar fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sweet last year in Albany,'' said Krog, ``but this is
the present. It feels awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
