<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKW-HARVARD-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD WOMEN SHOW FINAL FLOURISH 
</HEADLINE>
 HAMPSHIRE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Exactly 10 years ago, in these same Twin Cities,
the Harvard men's hockey team won its first NCAA title in an
overtime thriller. Happy anniversary gentlemen, and move over while
you're at it: the Harvard women made more history when they won
their first national championship Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, 6-5, against the
University of New Hampshire in _ that's right _ an overtime
thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard (33-1) extended its winning streak to 30 games by
defeating the defending national champions in the second annual
American Women's College Hockey Alliance Division 1 National
Championship, before 2,507 in Mariucci Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be better,'' said an elated A.J. Mleczko, the
senior captain who had left school for two years to train for the
gold medal-winning 1998 US Olympic team. ``When I decided to come
back, I never dreamed we'd have a season like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner came 8:01 into the extra period when Jen Botterill
took a pass from Mleczko to score her 37th goal of the year. It was
Botterill's eighth point of the tournament, and she was named its
Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Mleczko's overtime assist was her first point of the game,
leaving her 2 shy of the NCAA mark of 116 set by Tony Hrkac for the
University of North Dakota in 1986-87.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I made it a point that counted,'' beamed Mleczko as
her teammates celebrated behind her on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The win came in front of backup goaltender Alison Kuusisto, who
was needed after a collision in Friday's semifinal win over Brown
left starter Crystal Springer with a broken collarbone, the same
one she injured in January that kept her out of action for six
weeks. In that span, the freshman Kuusisto went 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew not having (Springer) wasn't going to make a big
difference,'' said UNH coach Karen Kay, whose own netminder, Alicia
Roberts, kept the Wildcats in the game by saving 48 of 54 shots.
</P>
<P>
   With UNH silencing Harvard's deadly first line for much of the
game, sophomore center Angie Francisco _ like Kuusisto, a Duluth,
Minn., native with supporters in the crowd _ also came up huge.
Francisco's hat trick included two goals midway through the third
period that gave Harvard a 5-3 lead with less than seven minutes
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this game won at six minutes, and we let them crawl
back in because we were a little bit lazy, looking for a little
more offense before taking care of our own end,'' said Harvard
coach Katey Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard held the lead for just 90 seconds before UNH junior
center Carisa Zaban punched one in from the top of the crease at
14:41 to cut the gap to 5-4, followed at 17:22 by a turnaround
no-looker from junior right wing Samantha Holmes off a rebound to
even it at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone thought we were done when it was 5-3,'' said
Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Not anyone who saw last week's ECAC final, in which UNH also
came back from a two-goal deficit to take the Crimson into
overtime, only to lose 5-4. Saturday night was UNH's fourth loss of
the season to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the third period we went into the locker room and
regrouped,'' said Botterill of her team's shakier-than-usual play
for much of the game. ``We went out on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just knew what we had to do,'' agreed Francisco. ``We were
calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Crimson pandemonium that broke out after Botterill's
overtime score.
</P>
</TEXT>
