<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of  &UR; Monday &LR; ,  &UR; March 29, 1999 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (moving in `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Dateline to be determined) _ Lede-all. By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING (Washington) _ Developments on
atrocities in Kosovo, described by officials as ``wholesale ethnic
cleansing'' and the worst humanitarian tragedy in Europe since
World War II. By the time NATO gets around to stopping the ethnic
cleansing, will Kosovo be empty, with Milosevic having achieved his
goal? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ What the president did and said
Sunday. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE (Washington) _ On the rescue of the pilot of
the downed stealth F-117, the mood of fear and then exaltation at
the White House and Pentagon, and an explainer on the
search-and-rescue teams. By Eric Schmitt and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Washington) _ President Clinton says Slobodan
Milosevic started the wars in Croatia, Bosnia and now Kosovo, and
the British defense secretary describes him as a ``serial ethnic
cleanser.'' So why hasn't Milosevic been indicted by the war crimes
tribunal? And why hasn't Radovan Karadzic been arrested? It would
require a change in policy and a more aggressive policy by the U.S.
By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline to be determined) _ Developments on
the ground. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Serbia) _ The atmosphere in the
Serbian capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Anti-NATO protesters in a stolen police
car fire machine guns at the American Embassy in Moscow in broad
daylight. They also tried to fire a couple of grenades, but the
launchers failed. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUDAPEST (Budapest, Hungary) _ Warning that NATO's
bombing of Yugoslavia had severely damaged Russia's relationship
with the United States, a Russian delegation met here Sunday with
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke before attempting to travel by
road to neighboring Yugoslavia to present a peace plan to President
Slobodan Milosevic. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-F117-BASE (New Mexico) _ At the base from where the
stealth F-117 fly. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA (Berlin) _ How the current ``ethnic cleansing''
campaign in Kosovo compares with what happened in the early part of
the war in Bosnia. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Albania) _ On the flow of refugees entering from
Kosovo. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB-TV (Undated) _ How Serb television portrays the
news. By Anthony Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EMAIL (Undated) _ The first war where e-mail is a vital
tool for families to keep in touch. By Neil MacFarquhhar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ABORTION (Moscow) _ Russia's abortion rate dropped with
its birth rate. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CAPETOWN-WAR (Capetown, South Africa) _ Cape Town is in a
three-way war between criminal gangs, the police and a Muslim
anti-crime group calling itself People Against Gangsterism and
Drugs. Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SHEEP-SACRIFICE (Cairo) _ At the start the Eid al-Adha, the
feast of sacrifice, one of the most important festivals on the
Islamic calendar, it's a bad time to be a sheep. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-AFRICA (Dateline to be determined) _ The first lady
travels Africa like a candidate, drawing small crowds but making
big promises. By James Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-INTERNET-VIRUS (San Francisco) _ Developments in the
search for the culprit who wrote a computer virus that has computer
administrators at corporations around the globe bracing for trouble
when millions of infected computers go back on line Monday morning.
By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   HEMP-FARMERS (Bismarck, N.D.) _ Like so many American farmers
who are getting poor prices for traditional crops, Dennis Carlson,
who grows wheat in Bismarck, N.D., is scratching for alternatives.
In North Dakota that includes hemp, a plant harvested in other
countries for its fibers, seeds and oil that is banned in the
United States because it is a genetic relative of marijuana. But
American farmers, in struggling to survive, are colliding with the
war on drugs. The prohibition of hemp, whose psychoactive kick is
negligible, illustrates how deeply fear of illegal drugs has
imbedded itself in the fabric of American life. By Christopher
Wren.
</P>
<P>
   UNLICENSED-HEALTH-CARE (Tustin, Calif.) _ Unlicensed health care
providers _ including clinics that operate out of the back rooms of
other businesses _ are common among the immigrant communities of
Southern California _ Hispanic, Asian, even Russian. One case has
focused attention on the issue _ the death of a two-month-old girl
who received an injection of penicillin at one of these clinics in
the back of a gift shop. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER (Chicago) _ It's a sad Sunday at Broadway
United Methodist Church, where Rev. Gregory Dell leads services two
days after he was found guilty of violating church law by
conducting a same-sex union. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITALS-RESIDENTS (New York) _ Two years ago, dozens of
teaching hospitals across New York State embraced an unusual pilot
program to ease the nationwide glut of physicians. The federal
government would pay bonuses to the hospitals if they trained fewer
doctors, just as it once paid corn farmers not to grow corn. But
half those hospitals have now dropped out of the plan, after
finding that they cannot function without the low-cost labor
provided by doctors in training, known as residents. By Lisa W.
Foderaro.
</P>
<P>
   ACID-RAIN (Waynesboro, Va.) _ The St. Marys River cascades like
liquid crystal down the Blue Ridge Mountains into the Shenandoah
Valley near here. But appearances deceive: The river is dying.
Decades of acid rain have killed off species of fish, insects and
vegetation in its five-mile stretch, scientists say. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-VOYAGE (Undated) _ Until recently, it was assumed that
the vast majority of the passengers on the St. Louis, the infamous
``Voyage of the Damned,'' had perished. But the assumption was
wrong, and for two years, researchers at the U.S. Holocaust
Memorial Museum have been trying to flesh out the stories of the
survivors. Now, as the 60th anniversary of the voyage approaches
and the museum mounts a special exhibit, researchers are close to
tracing what happened to every passenger. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ As both sides forge proposals
for talks in hopes of settling the Microsoft antitrust case,
computer makers are letting the Justice Department and state
attorneys general know just what their bottom line is _ liberation
from what they perceive as a form of feudalism in which they play
the serfs. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-CHARITY (Undated) _ Special Report: As Americans become
increasingly comfortable shopping online, it is a pitch few can
resist: Buy an Elmo toy or a Stephen King novel through our Web
sites and part of the purchase price will go to the charity of your
choice. But once you buy Elmo online, it is impossible to know if
the few dollars you thought were speeding their way to a good cause
will ever end up in the charity's hands. By Reed Abelson. With art.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
