<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, March
29:
</P>
<P>
   PHILOSOPHY-PRISON _ During an unusual course in philosophy and
literature that Earl Shorris was teaching specifically for the poor
and homeless, a student who had a history of violent behavior
telephoned Shorris. The student had become so angry at a colleague,
he reported, that he wanted ``to smack her up against the wall.''
Shorris feared the worst. Was this a call from jail? No, because
instead of striking outward, the student had reflected inward and
asked himself, ``What would Socrates do?'' The Connections column.
By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-TV-MAKING _ The making of ABC's six-part historical
series, ``The Century.'' By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   CENTURY-TV-REVIEW _ Caryn James reviews ``The Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ORPHEUS-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ The premiere of ``Drifting
Center (Samsara II),'' by Han Yong, a 41-year old Chinese composer,
by the Orpheus Chamber Orchestra. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   AILEY-DANCE-REVIEW (New York) _ Jennifer Dunning reviews the
Alvin Ailey Repertory Ensemble at Aaron Davis Hall.
</P>
<P>
   RIDE-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ Ben Brantley reviews Lisa
Kron's ``2.5 Minute Ride'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ROUNDABOUT-THEATER (New York) _ It's moving time again at the
Roundabout Theater Company. (Is that why they call it the
Roundabout?) By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   FROST-BOOK-REVIEW _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews ``Robert
Frost: A Life,'' by Jay Parini (Holt).
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
