<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-TV-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CENTURY': DON'T EXPECT TO SEE EVERYTHING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not as if the year 2000 comes with Big Ideas already
attached; it's a number, not a philosophy. No wonder we're facing a
glut of retrospectives that seem driven as much by public relations
as public sentiment: millennial fever as a commercial ploy or a
knee-jerk response to some imagined obligation.
</P>
<P>
   So the Whitney Museum of American Art presents an exhibition
(coming next month) called ``The American Century: Art and
Culture,'' not to be confused with Harold Evans' best-selling book
called, simply, ``The American Century,'' in a pattern bound to go
on well into 2001. It's as if publishers and producers everywhere
were thinking, ``It's the end of the century, got to do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Does all this backward gazing satisfy a genuine longing for
closure? Or do the retrospectives feed an imagined appetite, with
the whole country gazing at the emperor's new clothes and
pretending to see the meaning of the last hundred years?
</P>
<P>
   One hint at the obligatory impulse behind it all is evident in
the way even a real issue, like the Y2K bug, is surrounded by
hollow apocalyptic warnings. Another clue comes with ABC News'
hugely ambitious, sometimes glorious and often disappointingly
pedestrian series, ``The Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the series creates a landmark of its own, its safe,
made-by-committee feel means that viewers should approach this epic
with diminished expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations are justifiably high because the series' very
existence is iconoclastic and daring. For a network to devote 12
hours of prime time to a documentary from the news division is
unheard of today. The series' scope and resources promise something
brash and inventive, something that reinvents the form or at least
brings it new energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Century'' has great intelligence behind it, but less
originality. If you stumbled across it while flipping channels, you
might think, except for the reassuring presence of Peter Jennings
as host and narrator, that it was one more PBS documentary, with
its historical film and too many talking heads from academia.
</P>
<P>
   The series is spread over six nonconsecutive nights, each with
two separate but linked stories. The episode on World War I is
paired with one on the war in Vietnam, both suggesting the
consequences of trying to reshape other people's countries.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Memphis provides a slighter connection between an
episode on the rise of Elvis Presley, with all he meant for pop
culture, and the sanitation workers' strike in 1968 that drew
Martin Luther King Jr. to the city where he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   This shrewdly selective focus is one way in which the series
differs from the best-selling companion book by Jennings and Todd
Brewster. (The History Channel's 15{-hour sister series, which
begins on April 12, is more plodding than ABC's. Superficially, it
resembles the book more in its chronological approach and reliance
on eyewitness testimony from ordinary people.)
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on storytelling makes each episode of the ABC
series a mini-drama. But hour by hour, the quality veers from
absorbing and illuminating to eye-glazingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The best and worst are on view Monday night, in a triumphant
episode on Charles Lindbergh's solo flight across the Atlantic in
1927 and a tired one about the NASA flights to the moon and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lindbergh's career may seem familiar, most people know
the barest outline. ``The Century'' creates a euphoric sense of
immediacy, of living in the moment when Lindbergh's success was
still an open question. (The full saga has been told with a fresh
vision in the recent biography by A. Scott Berg, who appears as one
of Monday night's more articulate commentators.)
</P>
<P>
   The storytelling here offers a swift, rich sense of context,
including the fact that Lindbergh's heroic flight was spurred by a
contest promising $25,000 to the first team to fly between New York
and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lindbergh, six men had died trying to make that flight.
The series' wealth of rare images includes film of one of those
earlier planes crashing and bursting into flames. Such images are
the most powerful elements in the series, which itself is strong
evidence that this is the century of pictures, both still and
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh is seen first as a meek young man from St. Louis,
overwhelmed by the raucous crowds of New York City. His plane was
called the Spirit of St. Louis at the suggestion of the hometown
businessmen who had backed him financially. ``They were, after all,
interested in publicity,'' Jennings says, in one of astute comments
dropped in. By not leaning too hard on such observations, the
narrative maintains its buoyant energy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-TV-REVIEW-2TA     03-28 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-TV-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: buoyant energy.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But ``The Century'' takes a sudden nose dive in Monday night's
second hour, which begins with President John F. Kennedy's promise
to send an American to the moon. It features familiar NASA stories,
with equally familiar pictures and talking heads. If there is a way
to make this tale seem newly told, the series has not found it.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday brings a gripping episode, ``The Great War.'' Its film
may be the most astonishing and its historical perspective the most
trenchant in the entire series. (The last two installments were not
available in advance.) It begins on Christmas Eve 1914 with the
cease-fire between British and German soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, the old black-and-white film makes the past live
vividly on screen. When Jennings says, ``In 1914 war was seen as an
exhilarating experience,'' the remark is backed up by scenes of
troops heading onto ships, and by interviews with survivors. The
reality of war is then depicted with horrifying clarity, in film of
German soldiers teeming out of foxholes after inadequate English
shellings, and of a man whose nose had been blown off being fitted
with a masklike contraption to give him a false one.
</P>
<P>
   And here the historical analysis of the disastrous World War I
peace plan touches the present. As the victors carved up and
reconfigured the area that now includes Bosnia and Kosovo, they
disregarded the ethnic grudges that, as one historian puts it,
``would haunt the rest of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the series' uneven course, the episode on Vietnam is
pedantic for too long before its drama emerges. In recent
interviews with people who were there and in startling film, it
presents Americans and South Vietnamese crowding on Marine
helicopters to evacuate Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   But even dramatic pictures aren't enough to save the ``two
cautionary tales,'' as Jennings calls them, about the rise of
Hitler and the making of the atomic bomb. Scenes of scientists
constructing a test bomb are amazing to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But these episodes offer abrupt, startling visions embedded in
stories that never catch fire. Similarly, your reaction to the
Elvis episode may depend on whether you've ever seen the film of
his early television appearances; they immediately reveal what a
break he was with the past, but they have been shown often before.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most obligatory retrospectives can emerge with popular
appeal, of course. ``The Century'' book remains on the best-seller
list months after clever marketing helped make it one of the
Christmas season's hottest presents. Feeding the last hundred years
back to us in easy bite-size morsels, ``The Century'' on television
may have been reaching for the widest possible audience. Given the
series' high ambitions, it's hard not to see the results as a lost
opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
