<SLUG> BC-1920S-FOSTER-BIO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOSTER FILE 
WITH CENTURY OF SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1879: Sept. 17: Born Andrew Foster in Calvert, Texas
</P>
<P>
   1897: Began baseball career pitching for the Waco Yellowjackets.
</P>
<P>
   1902: Recruited by white businessman Frank Leland to play for
the Chicago Union Giants. Left team soon after to join Cuban
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   1903: Led the Cuban Giants to the ``colored world
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   1904: Signed with the Philadelphia Giants, leading them to the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   1905: Had best season of his career, going 51-4 for the
Philadelphia Giants. Picks up nickname ``the Colored Rube'' after
defeating the Philadelphia Athletics and future Hall of Famer Rube
Waddell in an exhibition. Soon, it was shortened to Rube.
</P>
<P>
   1907: Re-signed with Frank Leland to pitch and manage the
Chicago Giants.
</P>
<P>
   1910: Signed with John Schorling, a white tavern owner and
son-in-law of Chicago White Sox owner Charles Comiskey. Under the
agreement, the Foster's club was renamed the Chicago American
Giants. A dynasty was formed. The Giants won the ``colored
championship'' every year but one from 1910 to 1922.
</P>
<P>
   1917: Records are incomplete, but it is believed he pitched his
last game.
</P>
<P>
   1920: Foster organizes the Negro National League, consisting of
eight teams. He is elected the league's president and is given a
five percent cut of the gate receipts from each game.
</P>
<P>
   1925: While asleep in an Indianapolis hotel room, a gas pipe
ruptured in his room, with the fumes nearly killing him.
</P>
<P>
   1926: Admitted to a mental hospital in Kankakee, Ill., after
stabbing a friend with an ice pick.
</P>
<P>
   1930: Dies of a heart attack on Dec. 9 in the mental hospital.
</P>
<P>
   1981: Voted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, N.Y. \Nname:_ Kevin Lyons
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
