<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1920S-MYTH-MAKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CENTURY OF SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 
THE MYTH MAKERS: Sportswriters in the '20s helped turn athletes
into legends (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Andy Friedlander 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one Saturday afternoon in 1924, Illinois halfback Red Grange
and the All-America backfield of Notre Dame made history.
</P>
<P>
   But it took Grantland Rice to make them part of history.
</P>
<P>
   The record books have noted that on Oct. 18, 1924, Notre Dame's
backfield of Harry Stuhldreher, Don Miller, ``Sleepy Jim'' Crowley
and Elmer Layden slashed through Army's rugged defense on the way
to a 13-7 victory in a battle of unbeatens. And that on the same
day, Grange scored five touchdowns and threw for another as the
Illini shocked No. 1 Michigan, 39-14.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Rice, the most respected sports journalist of his
time, who turned those exploits _ and the men who performed them _
into legends.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was not the only writer who sought to create characters of
mythic proportion. It was standard practice in the 1920s to build
up athletes with dramatic and often flowery prose (sometimes with a
bit of poetry mixed in), while ignoring their foibles.
</P>
<P>
   The stories rarely contained quotes from the participants.
Writers felt they were much more qualified to explain what happened
than the players or the coaches and laced their stories with grand
metaphors that made even routine games seem like epic battles.
</P>
<P>
   Never was that better illustrated than in October 1924. The
morning after Notre Dame outlasted Army at the Polo Grounds,
readers of the ``New York Herald Tribune'' and the more than 100
newspapers nationwide that carried Rice's column picked up their
sports pages and read the most famous and widely quoted lead in the
history of sportswriting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Outlined against a blue-gray October sky, the Four Horsemen
rode again. In dramatic lore they are known as Famine, Pestilence,
Destruction and Death. These are only aliases. Their real names are
Stuhldreher, Miller, Crowley and Layden. They formed the crest of
the South Bend cyclone before which another fighting Army football
team was swept over the precipice at the Polo Grounds yesterday as
55,000 spectators peered down on the bewildering panorama spread on
the green plain below.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon reading those lines, a Notre Dame publicity man came up
with the idea of a photo with the players on horseback. They would
forever be known as The Four Horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Rice turned his attention to Grange, the toast
of the football world for his elusive running style. Rice likened
him to a specter, fading out of sight at the last moment and
leaving defenders grabbing at air. To emphasize the analogy, Rice,
who had several volumes of his poetry published, broke into verse:
``''A streak of fire, a breath of flame
</P>
<P>
   Eluding all who reach and clutch
</P>
<P>
   A gray ghost thrown into the game
</P>
<P>
   That rival hands may never touch'' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the Galloping Ghost was born.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's ability to make a sporting event seem bigger than life
fit perfectly with the 1920s, a decade Rice dubbed The Golden Age
of Sports _ yet another label that endures. The '20s were all about
excess, be it Babe Ruth's prodigious home runs or Bobby Jones' 13
major golf championships in eight years or the 14 seconds it took
the referee to count to nine in the Jack Dempsey-Gene Tunney
rematch. And the sporting press of the day fed that monster,
because that's what the public wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The writers were more than happy to deliver, and in so doing
became celebrities themselves. Some had a head start _ famed
Western gunfighter Bat Masterson was already nationally known
before he began writing a sports column for the ``New York Morning
Telegraph'' (he died at his typewriter in 1921) _ but most, like
Rice, made their names with their words.
</P>
<P>
   The best of them gathered at nearly every big event, such as the
World Series or a heavyweight title fight or a big college football
game. Among them were Damon Runyon, called ``the best reporter in
the world'' by his boss, ``New York American'' publisher William
Randolph Hearst; Heywood Broun of the ``New York World'', who also
made a name for himself as a war correspondent and a union
crusader; young ``Daily News'' sports editor Paul Gallico, whose
first-person account of a sparring session with Dempsey put him on
the map and who would later become the bestselling author of ``The
Snow Goose'' and ``The Poseidon Adventure''; and Ring Lardner of
the ``Chicago Tribune'' and the Bell syndicate, whose cynicism set
him apart in an era of hero-building.
</P>
<P>
   Later, that group would be joined by Shirley Povich, who in 1926
was named sports editor of the then-struggling ``Washington Post''
at age 21 and became an institution almost immediately. And at the
major golf events, they could be sure to run into O.B. Keeler of
the ``Atlanta Journal'', who faithfully chronicled the astounding
achievements of Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these men helped make heroes out of athletes. Some,
like Ruth, whom Gallico called ``a swashbuckler built on gigantic
and heroic lines,'' needed little help in that regard, but got it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Lardner was the exception. He delighted in tearing down the
pompous, and his skepticism served him well in 1919, when he and
Hugh Fullerton of the ``Chicago Examiner'' were credited with being
the first to realize the White Sox had thrown the World Series.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 1606EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
