<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1920S-FORT-WORTH-CATS     03-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1920S-FORT-WORTH-CATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL IN BLACK AND WHITE: JAKE ATZ AND THE CATS 
WITH CENTURY OF SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Rusty Hall 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manager Jake Atz and the Fort Worth Panthers boarded a train in
Little Rock, Ark., after winning the first Dixie Series in 1920.
They went to sleep expecting to awake the next morning as the train
pulled into the Fort Worth depot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they were on the outskirts of Little Rock when they
woke up.
</P>
<P>
   The train's engine trouble delayed the Panthers' arrival home by
12 hours, but it didn't dim the excitement of the fans. Atz and his
players were loaded into cars that evening for a parade up Main
Street to the Metropolitan Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Roman warrior could have rightfully claimed greater
recognition than was accorded the Panthers,'' wrote
``Star-Telegram'' columnist Billy Bee. ``They rode in automobiles
instead of chariots. Small boys excitedly followed them and
thousands of grownups lined the sidewalks.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Babe Ruth's exploits were helping make baseball
the national pastime, the Panthers were on their way to capturing
the hearts of Fort Worth sports fans by winning six consecutive
Texas League pennants and five Dixie Series titles, the greatest
dynasty in league history.
</P>
<P>
   They were an easy team to like. What the players didn't have in
talent, they made up for with a competitive fire that reflected
their manager, who overcame a lack of speed and power to play parts
of four major-league seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Born John Jacob Zimmerman, Atz legally changed his name in 1900
after he was last in a minor-league club's payline and watched the
money run out. He might have lasted longer in the big leagues if a
fastball from Hall of Famer Walter Johnson had not slammed into his
hip in 1913 and left him with a permanent limp.
</P>
<P>
   Atz came to Fort Worth in 1914 as a player-manager for the
Panthers. In 1918, the team was purchased by a group headed by
local businessman W.K. Stripling and former minor-league third
baseman Paul LaGrave, who made Atz the full-time skipper.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, LaGrave had assembled a talented group of
players, giving Atz the tools he needed to put the Panthers on a
winning track.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to talent, fans were attracted to the Panthers
because the majority of the players stayed with the team throughout
its championship run, said Bobby Bragan, a Panthers player and
manager in the '40s and '50s and a baseball historian.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't the change you see today,'' Bragan said. ``They
might sell one or two players to the major leagues each year, but
fans were able to become familiar with the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Panthers were a team as entertaining off the field as
it was on. Atz once said his team ``could drink any brewery dry at
night and beat any baseball team the next afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Atz's Cats were the toast of the town. The team was alternately
referred to as the Cats, the story goes, because newspaper headline
writers could fit ``Cats'' instead of ``Panthers'' more easily into
large type.
</P>
<P>
   After the Panthers clinched the 1920 Texas League pennant by
defeating Wichita Falls, a night of celebration ensued. According
to the ``Star-Telegram'', fans rousted first baseman Clarence ``Big
Boy'' Kraft from bed and took him downtown, where, during the
course of the celebration, he was stripped of his clothes, ``except
for his unmentionables'' and made to walk back through the main
streets of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't holler,'' Atz advised afterward. ``Suppose they hadn't
left you that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Panthers wrapped up the 1920 pennant in the Class B
Texas League, the fans were given an additional reason to
celebrate. LaGrave convinced the Class A Southern Association
champion Arkansas Travelers to play the Panthers in a best-of-seven
series, which came to be known as the Dixie Series.
</P>
<P>
   A near-riot broke out as fans packed Worth Cigar Store in a rush
to purchase tickets, which cost $1 for bleacher seats, $1.50 for
grandstand general admission and $2 for reserve seats. Scalpers
were said to be getting $5 a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The seven games of the first Dixie Series drew 36,835 fans and
generated $50,000 in ticket sales, assuring the future of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   During the six years of the Panthers' pennant-winning streak,
they continued to draw huge crowds at Panther Park, west of North
Main between North Sixth Street and North Seventh Street. Sellouts
of up to 8,000 for regular-season games were common. Playoff games
attracted up to 10,000 fans when extra seating was added along the
foul lines.
</P>
<P>
   Large crowds weren't restricted to the ballpark, either.
Thousands of fans who didn't make the trip to distant playoff games
packed downtown streets to watch a giant scoreboard. Play-by-play
was transmitted back to Fort Worth by wire and announced to the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In 1922, WBAP broadcast the first baseball game in the South
during a five-game series between the Panthers and Wichita Falls on
Aug. 30. The game was transmitted by telegraph from Panther Park
downtown to a studio where the broadcast was made. The response was
so overwhelming that the station sent Harold Hough to the park on
Sept. 1 for the first live broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   By 1926, the Panthers' success led to the construction of a new
Panther Park, just east of the old site, near the Trinity River.
Despite the new surroundings, the Panthers began to lose more and
more players to retirement or higher leagues. Archrival Dallas
ended the Panthers' reign.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers remained competitive for the remainder of the
decade, but it wasn't until 1930 that Fort Worth was treated to
another Texas League pennant and a trip to the Dixie Series. But by
that time, Atz was no longer managing.
</P>
<P>
   Also missing was LaGrave, who became ill in 1928 and died in
1929. Panther Park was renamed LaGrave Field in his honor.
Stripling and the LaGrave estate sold the team to Ted Robinson in
1929. Atz returned briefly to manage the team in 1933, but he was
replaced before the 1934 season. He went on to manage in the Texas
League at Dallas, Shreveport, Tulsa and Galveston, as well as in
other leagues. He died in 1945 in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The fans' enthusiasm generated by the success of Atz's Cats
continued long after the steak ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was great enthusiasm from the fans when I came here,''
said Bragan, who joined the Panthers in 1948. ``I think a lot of
that can be traced back to Jake Atz and those six championships.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 1606EST &QL; 
