<SLUG> BC-1920S-WHAT'S-NEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW IN THE 1920S 
WITH CENTURY OF SPORTS PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FIRSTS
</P>
<P>
   First state football championship: On Jan. 8, 1921, Cleburne and
Houston Heights battled to a 0-0 deadlock in what was the first
official state football championship staged by the Interscholastic
League, the forerunner to the University Interscholastic League.
The game was played in the rain and ankle-deep mud at Clark Field
in Austin; the field had recently been plowed for sodding. Teams
were invited to the 1920 state playoffs based on records submitted
by 198 schools to the Bureau of Football Results, and then the
playoffs ensued.
</P>
<P>
   First SWC broadcast: On Nov. 25, the Texas-Texas A&AMP;M game was
broadcast by WTAW to College Station. The legend of the
Longhorns-Aggies rivalry took hold in this game before a crowd
estimated at 20,000 in Austin. UT won, 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   First true pro basketball team: The Original Celtics, who were
paid a salary to keep the players from bouncing to different teams,
were formed in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   First woman to swim the Channel: Five men had swum the English
Channel before New Yorker Gertrude Ederle, 19, crossed the 21 miles
covered in grease to fight the cold and broke the existing male
record by more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Best game: On Oct. 10, 1926, in the seventh inning of the
seventh game of the World Series, Grover Cleveland Alexander of the
St. Louis Cardinals struck out the New York Yankees' Tony Lazzeri
with two outs and the bases loaded. Alexander had pitched a
complete game the day before and was said to be nursing a hangover,
thinking he would not be used. But Cardinals player-manager Rogers
Hornsby summoned Old Pete in relief, and Alexander preserved the
Cardinals' 3-2 as St. Louis won the World Series.
WHAT'S NEW
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Age of Sports made for enduring innovations and
phrases that entered America's consciousness forever, some based on
fact, others intertwined with fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Athlete's foot: The first mention was believed to have been made
in ``Literary Digest'' in 1928. Ringworm of the foot became
associated with athletes; in the 1920s, locker rooms with showers
provided an ideal condition for lurking fungi.
</P>
<P>
   Cagers: Beginning in the late 1890s, most professional
basketball games were played inside a wire cage that encircled the
court, keeping the ball in play and unruly fans away from the
action (hence the nickname ``cagers'' for basketball players). But
in 1925, the American Basketball League, in an attempt to create a
more open game, became the first pro league of the century to
eliminate the cage. By 1929, cages were all but extinct. The ABL
also banned the double dribble, which was at the time a legal and
popular technique for advancing the ball among Eastern pro players.
</P>
<P>
   Globetrotters: Abe Saperstein, a former Chicago social worker,
founded the Harlem Globetrotters in 1927. He formed the Savoy Big
Five in '26, but when the Savoy ballroom in Chicago, the team's
home, was converted into a roller skating rink, Saperstein took the
team on the road. He chose the team's name to let the public know
the players were blacked and they traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Lively Ball: Babe Ruth's quantum leap in home runs from 29 in
1919 to 54 in 1920 is often attributed to a ``lively'' ball. Yet,
there is no evidence of a dramatic change in the ball in 1920. A
bigger change: the spitball and discoloration of the ball was
banned in February 1920. Ruth's breakthrough might have come in
1919, but he was still splitting time between the outfield and
pitching, and he appeared in only 130 games.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 16, 1920, Cleveland's Ray Chapman was killed by a pitch
from Yankees right-hander Carl Mays. The tragedy accelerated
reform. Instead of using only three or four balls per game, which
led to the balls becoming misshapen and dark, new baseballs were
fed continuously into a game. The National League reported it used
27,924 baseballs in the 1920 season, an increase of more than
10,000 over 1919. And owners, happy with larger crowds which led to
greater profits, weren't about to stop the batting onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Count: Sept. 22, 1927, seventh round, Soldier Field,
Chicago. Before a crowd of 104,000 that included 10 governors,
several U.S. senators and a radio audience of 60 million,
challenger Jack Dempsey knocked champion Gene Tunney to the canvas.
Dempsey goes to his corner five feet away rather than the
``farthest neutral corner'' as mandated by Illinois rules and as
agreed upon before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   The referee moved Dempsey to the proper corner and didn't pick
up the count until the timekeeper was at 5. At the referee's count
of 4, 9 by the timekeeper, Tunney raises his eyes and looks at the
referee. Could he have gotten up? At the ref's count of 9 (14 after
the timekeeper started the count)), Tunney was up. He danced away
from Dempsey the rest of the round, then dominated the rest of the
fight to retain his crown. Tunney insisted he could have gotten up
after the referee's count of two.
</P>
<P>
   Ice princess: In the 1928 Winter Olympics, Sonja Henie was the
first figure skater to be costumed in skirts that are short instead
of ankle-length, putting fashion into sport.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3, No. 4: On Jan. 22, 1929, the Yankees announced that all
players would have numbers on their backs, thereby becoming the
first baseball team to start continuous use of numbers. The system
was based on the batting order; Babe Ruth was 3, Lou Gehrig was 4.
By 1933, all big-league players wore uniform numbers.
</P>
<P>
   One leg at a time: Francis Schmidt became football coach at TCU
in 1929, and he is said to have popularized the saying that an
opponent's players, no matter how good, ``put their pants on just
like you do, one leg at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelfth Man: On Jan. 2, 1922, Southwest Conference champion
Texas A&AMP;M played in the Dixie Classic against Centre College at
Fair Park Stadium in Dallas. E. King Gill had been on the football
team, but had switched to basketball. He was in street clothes at
the Classic and was asked to help as a spotter in the press box for
a sports writer. Near the end of the first half, Gill was called
down to the Aggies bench, and was told because of injuries he might
have to play. He and one of the injured players went under the
stands and switched outfits. Gill never played, but he stood by,
ready. This is why A&AMP;M students stand during games.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Pipp: On June 2, 1925, Yankees first baseman Wally Pipp
supposedly begged out of the lineup because he had a headache. Lou
Gehrig, who had pinch-hit the day before, took Pipp's place. Gehrig
didn't come out of the lineup until his consecutive game streak
reached 2,130. Baseball players even today deride any regular
asking out of the lineup as ``Wally Pipp.''
</P>
<P>
   Win one for The Gipper: ``Some time, Rock, when the team's up
against it, when things are wrong and the breaks are beating the
boys, tell them to go in there with all they've got and win just
one for the Gipper. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Against Army on Nov. 28, 1928, Notre Dame coach Knute Rockne
ignited his injury-riddled team with what he said were the dying
words of George Gipp, the Irish All-American who died after
contracting strep throat late in the 1920 season. Notre Dame
defeated unbeaten and heavily favored Army, 12-6, at Yankee
Stadium. As Jack Chevigny, later head coach in the mid-1930s at the
University of Texas, scores the Irish's first touchdown, he shouts,
``That's one for the Gipper.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, contends author Murray Sperber in ``Shake Down the
Thunder: The Creation of Notre Dame Football'': No one ever
referred to Gipp in his life as the Gipper, and Rockne had last
visited him weeks before his death. What is indisputable is that
Rockne's team played inspired football that day.
</P>
<P>
   How good was George Gipp? Superior to Jim Thorpe or Red Grange,
Rockne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
