<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSE OFFSTAGE FOR THE ROUNDABOUT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's moving time again at the Roundabout Theater Co.
(Is that why they call it the Roundabout?)
</P>
<P>
   In its 34-year history, the Off Broadway and Broadway hit
factory that has grown into the nation's second largest nonprofit
theater after Lincoln Center's has moved from a Chelsea supermarket
basement to a Chelsea movie house, to the Fashion Institute of
Technology in the garment center to the former Tammany Hall on
Union Square to the Criterion Center on Broadway and 45th Street,
where it has been since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the Criterion's owner, Charles B. Moss Jr., reclaiming
the space amid a Times Square rebuilding boom, the Roundabout is
packing its bags once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be out in two weeks,'' said Todd Haimes, the
company's artistic director, as growing piles of cartons choked the
corridors. The offices for the staff of 100 will move into new
quarters at 231 West 39th Street next month, but the current plays
at the 499-seat main theater and the 399-seat Laura Pels Theater,
``The Lion in Winter'' and ``The Mineola Twins,'' will run until
May 30. The entire building must be vacated by June 10, Haimes
said, adding that a legal agreement with Moss prevented him from
saying more. The Roundabout's more far-flung productions,
``Cabaret'' at Studio 54, and ``Ashes to Ashes'' at the Gramercy
Theater on East 23d Street in Manhattan, are not affected.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new home, the 750-seat Selwyn Theater on West 42d
Street, is undergoing a $17 million renovation to be completed
around January. In the meantime, the Roundabout is to present a new
play, ``Hurrah at Last'' by Richard Greenberg, at the Gramercy. The
move from the Criterion forced postponement of another production,
``Sweet Bird of Youth'' in June. The 40,000 subscribers were
offered tickets to a non-Roundabout production, ``Death of a
Salesman,'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a familiar roller coaster ride for the Roundabout,
which barely had time to bask in the success of the Tony-award
winning ``Cabaret,'' ``A View From the Bridge'' and other Broadway
hits last season when a scaffold collapse on West 43rd Street
closed the Kit Kat Club, home of ``Cabaret,'' and briefly darkened
other productions. The accident cost the Roundabout $1.3 million in
lost ticket sales. Haimes said he did not know whether this can be
recouped by insurance. Renovating Studio 54 cost $1.7 million, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In September the Canadian-based producing behemoth Livent Inc.
named Haimes artistic director. Livent subsequently went into
bankruptcy and its partners, Garth H. Drabinsky and Myron I.
Gottlieb, were charged with fraud. With prospective buyers coming
forward to take over Livent, Haimes' prospects are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   So, he said the other day in the emptying Criterion offices,
there was only one thing to do: hold a party. On June 6 the doors
will be opened for the last time for a super cast party for all
actors who performed at the Criterion, with a guest list that
ranges from F. Murray Abraham to Helen Mirren to Eli Wallach, among
a host of other marquee names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
