<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN29-COX     03-28 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women should have greater role in setting public policy
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lydia Jankovic, a lawyer from Yugoslavia, now an
Atlanta resident, has a suggestion U.S. policymakers should take to
heart if we ever get back to the negotiating table on the Kosovo
crisis. She says a woman from the region should be in the
negotiations. These women don't want war, she told Atlanta Journal
reporter Virginia Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovic's comments caused me to stand back and think about the
silliness of the issues American women sometimes rally around:
create women's offices of this and that; demand that women get
equal tee times on the golf course; pass laws to confirm that women
can nurse their babies in public. (The Georgia General Assembly
just passed such a thing.)
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Jankovic's observation about her war-torn country
is the real reason why having more equal numbers of women in
national and international decision-making is necessary. Women, by
biology and life experience, whether they are mothers or not, are
nurturers more than are most men. They weigh the human costs and
benefits of domestic and foreign policy more heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that the singular female to rise to power in Serbia,
Biljana Plavsic, who became president of the Serb-controlled half
of Bosnia, broke with Radovan Karadzic over his refusal to go along
with the Dayton peace accords. Plavsic had served in the Karadzic
regime and was initially thought to be as bent on ethnic cleansing
as he. But at some point, she decided she could no longer stomach
his inhumanity.
</P>
<P>
   As Jankovic put it, ``The women are tired of war.'' Think about
it. Why are the women _ be they Serb or Albanian, Christian or
Muslim _ tired of war more than the men? Because eking out food,
shelter, clothing and some semblance of security for helpless
children falls on them. And it's harder in many ways than toting a
gun. That doesn't mean they're ``softer.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Madeleine Albright, America's first female
secretary of state, to recommend war is aimed at preventing further
ethnic killing and at halting genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Without trivializing the current international conflict, women
political leaders at the national and state levels need to focus on
long-term issues and stop using up so much energy on the symbolic.
While women leaders push for female health initiatives (such as
24-hour stays after mastectomies) on a micro level, the macro issue
is insistence on quality care even if it cuts into private profits.
That issue is part of an even greater reform need: campaign
finance, the mostly male-dominated money contributions to
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Women don't need more women's offices and programs. In Georgia
and other states, women need places on transportation, banking,
environment, utility and consumer boards and authorities. They need
to chair them. Georgia's new governor should appoint many women,
not just a few tokens, to the new 15-member Georgia Regional
Transportation Authority
</P>
<P>
   A few women who arrive at powerful posts mimic the good-ol'-boy
tactics. Georgia school Superintendent Linda Schrenko paid a former
Braves pitcher $25,000 this year to lobby for more education money.
She said it was the only way to get through to an all-male power
structure in the Legislature. Fortunately, other Georgia women
leaders, like Cathy Cox, the new secretary of state, found
mustering the facts and making sound arguments worked.
</P>
<P>
   Women's studies programs at various colleges should stop staging
one-time seminars and start forming state or regional policy
institutes to collect data and to analyze women's public policy
needs _ and more significantly, how to strengthen women's public
policy roles.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is on the editorial board of The Atlanta Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
