<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: FOR NEW YORK'S SILICON ALLEY, A TIME TO SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LISA NAPOLI and SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Out of symbolic modesty _ or maybe impatience _
Candice Carpenter took the subway rather than a limousine back to
her office from the Wall Street headquarters of Goldman Sachs
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   She was returning after watching the stock of Ivillage, the
Internet company she co-founded, open for trading the day after its
initial public offering, quadrupling its initial price of $24
before closing at $80.125.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that got me excited,'' Ms. Carpenter said of coming
back to Ivillage's offices at 170 Fifth Ave., ``was walking the
halls and seeing the kids so delirious that their hard work had
paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next few months there are likely to be a lot of
delirious executives and employees as more than a dozen of New
York's Internet companies try to go public. The Mining Co., for
example, another prominent member of the group, saw its stock more
than double after shares began trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The offerings, of course, will create a windfall payoff for the
work put into these companies, with their young programmers and
producers holding options worth _ on paper _ tens of thousands, or
even hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the company founders who really have the right to be
delirious. Ms. Carpenter and Scott Kurnit, chief executive of The
Mining Co., each now have paper wealth of more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Along with financial rewards, the successful public offerings
come as more than a little vindication for Silicon Alley, the
collection of entrepreneurs trying to make a go of Internet
businesses in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They have had to fight harder for respect and for financing than
their Silicon Valley rivals on the other side of the continent. The
technology mainstream considered the New York companies too lavish
in their spending, too focused on content by writers and designers
_ and simply too far from Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind all that. The success of Ivillage's offering
indicates that there are no hard feelings now between Silicon Alley
and the great wired masses of Internet stock buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, most New York Internet companies going public
are online extensions of the city's traditional industries. There
are media companies like Ivillage, which provides women's services;
Mining, an Internet directory that relies on human guides, not
machines; and Star Media, an online service for Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   There are offshoots of Wall Street, including Wit Capital, an
online investment bank, and Multex, which distributes
brokerage-firm research. The advertising business is represented by
Razorfish, an interactive agency, and Media Metrix, a company that
measures the audience size of World Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in other New York industries, like publishing and
fashion, are spinning out online divisions. These include
Barnesandnoble.com from Barnes &AMP; Noble, the bookseller, and Iturf,
an offshoot of Delia's, a maker of clothing for teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has become the center of the Internet content
business,'' said Fred Wilson, a principal with Flatiron Partners, a
venture capital unit of Chase Manhattan. ``People said that all the
technology plays and all the infrastructure plays have been done.
Now it's time for what you can build on top of the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some companies going public here would be just as
natural in Silicon Valley, including Juno, an e-mail service
financed in part by News Corp., and Mapquest, which makes
electronic maps.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing to base in New York was ``a real gamble,'' said Kevin
O'Connor, chief executive of Doubleclick, an online advertising
network that went public in February 1998 and has a value of $3.2
billion, the most of any Silicon Alley company. After starting his
business in Atlanta in 1996, he considered moving to California,
but chose New York because ``we're a tech company and a media
company, but mostly a media company.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, as technology stocks plummeted and investors
shunned public offerings, many Silicon Alley companies feared they
would never achieve their goals of going public. But the dark days
lasted only a few weeks, and two small New York Internet companies,
Earthweb and Theglobe.com, went public in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than validation for Silicon Alley, the herd of public
offerings could simply mean that investors are so addicted to
Internet stocks that they will buy anything, even something as
improbable as a technology company based in New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Indeed, the Ivillage offering went forward, at twice the
projected price, mere days after the company's former chief
financial officer accused Ms. Carpenter of overly aggressive
accounting. Ivillage says it stands by its financial reports, which
were audited by PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivillage is a lesson that the companies with the highest
profile in the media earn the highest valuations, even in the face
of accounting questions,'' said Alec Ellison, a managing director
of Broadview, a New Jersey investment bank. ``In the absence of any
rational metric with which to value a company, investors are
betting on the future, and that means image and brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are quick to caution that for any investor with a time
horizon longer than the life of a fruit fly, nearly all of these
companies are highly speculative. Even the biggest and most
established, like Ivillage, are swimming in red ink with no clear
way to profits in sight. Some other companies are so small and
unproved that in earlier days they would have hardly qualified for
a bank loan, never mind a stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Whether good for investors or not, the money flow benefits the
New York economy as some entrepreneurs apply profits from these
offerings to start new companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wealth is the next-generation seed capital that will be
reinvested in startups and will help strengthen the whole ecosystem
of new media in New York,'' said Brian Horey, a partner at
Lawrence, Smith &AMP; Horey, a venture capital firm, and a founder of
the New York New Media Association. ``Over the last 30 years, this
has turned Silicon Valley into an enormous economic flywheel.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of those at Ivillage, though, the talk is less of
pushing that flywheel than of pumping money into the local economy
in different ways: buying an apartment, taking a vacation, paying
for a nice wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first meeting where we talked about the
options, and they told us they might be worth a thousand dollars
some day if the company grew,'' said Kate Hanley, a producer at
Ivillage since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like, `Yeah, but we want a raise.' A lot of us had no
idea what an IPO was. Now, I've learned what a limit order is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
