<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPARATE TIMES TEST DESPOT'S SURVIVAL SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICK MONTGOMERY AND SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... hearts in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Since then he has fed the flames of nationalist jealousy and
fear, but not with the sort of expansionist goals or rhetoric that,
say, engulfed Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not talking about someone who has an ideology of
conquest. At best you're talking about someone whose ideology is
the expression of the deepest paranoia of Serbia,'' Remington said.
``In this case, there was a lot of historical reality behind those
fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when faced with choosing between Serb nationalism and his
personal base of power, Milosevic has consistently accounted for
his interests first.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ideology is anything that's going to keep him in power,''
said Mark Ellis, the director of the American Bar Association's
Central and East European Initiative. ``He has a remarkable ability
to shift depending on what the perception of the day is.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a key player in the 1995 Dayton peace accords _ seen by
some Serbs as an abandonment of nationalist interests in Bosnia.
And he has also been accused of abandoning Serbs in Croatia and
eastern Slovenia, the former Yugoslav provinces that declared their
independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has seen his popularity dwindle in recent years as the
effects of international sanctions have worn on. Accusations that
he had rigged elections prompted mass demonstrations in 1997. The
protests were fueled by independent news media and manned by
university students.
</P>
<P>
   He has since wiped out all but the state-controlled newspapers,
television and radio. The university system, meantime, has seen
academic freedom disappear and the faculty ranks filled with
political appointments.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic survives the present crisis, his presidency will
end in 2001. But his reign will not, Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will have gained so much influence over the various spheres
of government so that even after the presidency, he'll be in
control,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   And who, if anyone, controls Milosevic?
</P>
<P>
   Many critics point to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Mirjana Markovic. She is a lifelong Marxist _ ``The
Red Witch,'' as her many detractors in Yugoslavia tag her. The
sociology professor and magazine columnist is thought to have
orchestrated her husband's rise to power. She remains Milosevic's
one true confidante.
</P>
<P>
   ``She holds the handlebars, and Slobo pumps the pedals,'' said
former Yugoslav army chief of staff Gen. Stevan Mirkovic in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Her magazine columns blend musings about fashions and the
weather with cryptic comments on regional politics. If she chides a
Serbian politician or a Belgrade businessman one month, the target
of her ridicule often will be searching for work the next. So
prescient are her writings that Yugoslav readers have dubbed her
column ``The Horoscope.''
</P>
<P>
   Markovic's political agenda can be traced to her childhood. Her
mother, a communist guerrilla during World War II, reportedly was
captured and executed by German Nazis when Mirjana Markovic was 1
year old. According to a 1997 feature in the Chicago Tribune, the
first lady of Yugoslavia now wears a gardenia in her hair because
her mother wore one in the only picture that Markovic saw of her.
</P>
<P>
   Young Markovic was raised by an affluent family with close ties
to Josip Broz Tito, the charismatic leader of communist Yugoslavia.
She met her future husband when both were schoolchildren in the
town of Pozarevac. Milosevic soon became active in student politics
and was named to the League of Communists of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Today the ruling couple, ``Slobo and Mira,'' have a grown son
and daughter who contradict Milosevic's old-world dogma.
</P>
<P>
   The son, Marko, owns a disco and races cars; he's wrecked 19 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to have a girl, music, a car and a gun,'' he once told
an interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   His sister, Marija, once ran a rock radio station in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   For years the family's flashy lifestyle triggered jokes and
editorial cartoons across the region. But the ridicule has quieted
in recent months as Milosevic has kicked out journalists, driven
thousands of Kosovars from their homes and ordered soldiers to hunt
down rebels.
</P>
<P>
   From here, public opinion in Yugoslavia could go any direction,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO can exact enough casualties in the Serbian
heartland,'' said Bassuener of the Balkan Action Council, ``it
could bring Milosevic down. But it's going to require some internal
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his army gets to thinking, `We're going to get annihilated
here,' I could see someone going in there and dragging Slobo from
his palace. Serbia does have a history of killing its leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that same history augurs in Milosevic's favor. It
is a history that Milosevic now seems willing to embrace at all
costs _ a history of unforgotten suffering and almost
self-destructive defiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People there may oppose Milosevic on a lot of things, but not
on the issue of Kosovo,'' said Ellis of the American Bar
Association's Central and East European Initiative. ``They're not
going to abandon him as long he represents that cause.''
</P>
</TEXT>
