<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINES-SPINOFFS-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING MAGAZINES ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your newsstand is overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   It's stacked to the rafters with People, Teen People and People
en Espanol. There's Country Living and Country Living Country
Gardener and Country Living Healthy Living.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Traditional Home and Traditional Home Decorator
Showhouse and Traditional Home Renovation Style.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, publishers have come to see the spinoff
as the future of magazines. Spinoffs are new magazines that take
the title of the original publication and, by adding a subtitle
like ``For women,'' ``Finance'' or ``Gardener,'' attempt to attract
new readership and provide a new marketplace for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly endless iterations are only accelerating. This
week, Sports Illustrated for Women, the brainchild of Time Warner's
Sports Illustrated publishing staff, will join its firstborn
sibling, Sports Illustrated for Kids, on the newsstand. And they,
in turn, will be joined at the same time by the National Geographic
Society's National Geographic Adventure, the offspring of National
Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   Even Conde Nast, previously reluctant to risk diluting any of
its brand names, has thrown its hat into the ring. The unit of
Advance Publications announced last week that in partnership with
Ideas Publishing Group, a Miami company, it would publish Vogue en
Espanol.
</P>
<P>
   The pace is picking up faster than you can say ``Sports
Illustrated for Teen People en Espanol.'' And with the barrage of
new entries, the problems with spinoffs are beginning to show
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism from the advertising industry toward magazines deemed
to be stretching the brand name can result in a disappointing
number of ad pages. Cost-conscious publishers tend to load up _ and
annoy _ primary editorial staffs with the responsibilities of
producing a second, or even third, magazine. Consumers and
newsstand dealers get confused if logos are not different enough.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, they just plain fail, even with the power of a
great brand _ like Meredith Corp.'s Better Homes and Gardens or
even The Christian Science Monitor _ behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The Magazine Publishers of America keeps no records of how many
magazines a year are spinoffs, but Dr. Samir Husni, a professor of
journalism at the University of Mississippi who tracks magazine
startups, estimated that 20 percent of new magazines in 1998 were
spun off existing publications, compared with just 5 percent five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a magazine market of falling newsstand sales _ two-thirds of
all magazines reported declining newsstand sales in the second half
of 1998, according to Capell's Circulation Report _ one of the
primary advantages of a spinoff is that it appears to be risk-free;
a publisher can say it is merely testing an offspring publication
as a one-shot or a special-interest publication.
</P>
<P>
   If readers respond to the newsstand product, the publishers will
spin off the title officially _ as Rodale Press did with
Prevention's Guide to Men's Health, a one-shot magazine that became
the robustly successful Men's Health _ and announce a victory. If
the magazine does not find a sustainable market, the publisher can
explain it away as a special-interest publication that it does not
intend to revive, and still pocket the one-time revenue.
</P>
<P>
   On the marketing level, spinning off a new title takes advantage
of a company's existing brand. On an economic level, the cost is
usually minimal around start-up time because one editorial staff is
doing the work of two magazines.
</P>
<P>
   And from the psychological-developmental level, publishers see
spinoffs as incubators for future readers. The president of Hearst
Magazines, Cathleen Black, sees a junior version of Cosmopolitan _
aimed at girls, due on newsstands this fall _ as a way ``to
graduate them up to the big sister publication when they're
older.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Wall, the publisher of Newsweek magazine, said that Teen
Newsweek _ which will be sent to schools and subscribers in
September _ is a way to ``build a media habit among young readers.
'' Earlier this month, The New York Times and Scholastic Inc.
announced that they would publish a news magazine for teen-agers,
to be called The New York Times Upfront.
</P>
<P>
   And on a practical level, slipping a spinoff onto the newsstands
is easier than sneaking into a multiplex matinee on Sunday.
Magazine publishers do not have to approach and sell newsstand
distributors on the new concept or negotiate new contracts for the
newsstand space, said Daniel Capell, an authority on magazine
circulation and the editor of Capell's Circulation Report.
</P>
<P>
   But the editor in chief of American Express Publishing's Travel
&AMP; Leisure, Nancy Novgorod, pointed out that sometimes newsstand
dealers get confused about which title is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big concern,'' she said, adding that she recently saw
that a newsstand dealer in Dulles Airport in Washington had
confused her magazines, and only displayed copies of Travel &AMP;
Leisure Golf, not Travel &AMP; Leisure.
</P>
<P>
   And she said that the company was bound by postal restrictions
not to make the cover of Travel &AMP; Leisure Family markedly different
from Travel &AMP; Leisure, so that it could avoid extra fees that would
be charged if it were a separate magazine. ``And when that magazine
goes on the newsstand, people get confused,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all spinoffs survive. Times Mirror Magazines spun Popular
Science magazine off into Popular Science for Kids in 1995, which
lasted for five issues; The Christian Science Monitor introduced
World Monitor magazine, which folded after three years when the
company decided to invest in other areas of the media, despite
reaching a monthly circulation of 300,000 readers. Better Homes and
Gardens Home Garden magazine, a 1995 spinoff of Better Homes and
Gardens, hung around for eight issues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And the theoretical convenience of spinning off can be eclipsed
by practical matters like financing, staffing, advertising and
plain old editorial hey-that-was-my-idea-first adversity.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Outside Magazine, the owner Larry Burke _ the
chief executive of Mariah Media Inc. _ chose to spin off Women
Outside when he saw that according to Mediamark Research Inc., a
company that charts reader demographics, Outside was attracting
large numbers of women readers who would pick up the magazine after
their male friends or spouses had already read it.
</P>
<P>
   But in his enthusiasm, Burke overloaded his existing staff with
work on developing last year's test issue of Women Outside. One
result was that the added stress contributed in part to six staff
members quitting the company, said former staff members and Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly saw some sacrifices being made,'' said Burke,
referring to the burdens placed on his Outside staff while they
were finishing the test issue of Women Outside. ``But with
additional competitive magazines coming into the marketplace, I
thought it would be best to hire an additional team promptly.''
(The first issue of Women Outside will appear on newsstands on June
1, with a new, separate staff.)
</P>
<P>
   At Time Inc., a different problem has arisen, one of a spinoff
first enthusiastically embraced and then abandoned temporarily in
the corporate maze. Last fall, Lisa Gabor, then an editor at In
Style magazine, wrote a proposal suggesting a magazine (the working
title: Biz Style) that would be spun off In Style, the monthly
celebrity bible. Norman Pearlstine, the editor in chief of Time
Inc., thought the idea was terrific, and so did the editors of In
Style.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of the top editors of In Style,'' Pearlstine said.
``She had the idea of doing something that was more connected to
business and by extension to men.''
</P>
<P>
   But the editors of In Style, who are already developing a bridal
spinoff and whose readership is predominantly women, asked Ms.
Gabor to take her idea to a group more accommodating to the male
market. Ms. Gabor and her idea then moved to the Business
Information Group _ the group that includes Fortune, Money and
probably the least style-conscious of the Time Inc. magazines,
Mutual Funds magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Because Fortune already produces a special issue based on a
similar notion called Business Life every fall, Ms. Gabor found
herself competing against an existing part-time title, which
Fortune staff members felt already covered ``men and their toys and
moguls on ranches,'' in the words of one staff member. Pearlstine
said the magazine was being developed and may appear as a
stand-alone, with no other magazine's imprimatur on it.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the advertising possibilities for a magazine
like Biz Style are appealing; the Fortune Business Life special
issue attracts new advertisers to Fortune each year, said Fortune's
publisher, Jolene Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, advertisers are attracted to spinoff families because
they get discounted prices for buying packages of advertising in
several related magazines at once. But on the down side, the
advertising industry is wary of publishers overly stretching their
brand names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very adamant when I'm in the room with magazine publishers
who want to extend their brand to women,'' said Alan Jurmain, the
media director at Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS. ``I have a hard time
believing that women need their own magazine to talk to them about
stocks splitting or sports.'' Jurmain said that Sports Illustrated
for Women ``is an uphill trek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're assuming that the brand is that elastic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The People division at Time Inc. has proved that, at least for
now, its brand name is supple and elastic. Teen People, introduced
in February 1998, with a 500,000 rate base _ the circulation
guaranteed to advertisers _ now has a circulation of 1,279,000,
with a guaranteed rate base of 1.2 million. Ad pages have doubled
in the first year, to 92.5 in this year's April issue from 45 pages
in last April's issue, said a Teen People spokeswoman. (The
magazine is not yet monitored by the Publishers Information Group,
which charts advertising revenue.)
</P>
<P>
   In Style's ad pages have quadrupled _ to 1,939 in 1998 from 510
in 1995 _ since it was introduced, and circulation has doubled, to
more than 1.2 million in 1998 from 668,000 in 1995, according to
the Audit Bureau of Circulation. At the same time, some of their
success can be attributed to the continued growth of People, which
saw its ad revenue rise to $626.5 million in 1998 from $437.6
million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Moore, president of the People division at Time Inc. _ the
group that includes People, In Style, Teen People and People en
Espanol _ is a cheerleader for the roomy People brand and sees
endless possibilities. She said a title like Teen People en Espanol
for Girls was not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a need for it in the market, we'll publish it,''
Ms. Moore said, and added: ``Some people look at the newsstand and
see it as crowded. I look at it and see wide open spaces waiting to
be filled with more offspring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
