<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MS-KERVORKIAN-2NDTAKE     03-28 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MS-KERVORKIAN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MS PATIENT CHOSE SUICIDE; ONE WANTS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... when modern medicine doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way. When Patricia Smith was
diagnosed with MS in 1987, she was worried but hopeful. Many people
with the disease, she was told, don't become severely disabled.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993 the multiple sclerosis forced her to cut back and
retire from nursing. She took a desk job, but she stopped working
altogether in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was bedridden,'' David Smith said. ``She lost the ability
to swallow, she was losing her vision, she had tremors, she
couldn't control her bowels. We were led to believe she'd die in
December of '96.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Patricia Smith began communicating with Kevorkian
while her husband was at work. She didn't tell him until Kevorkian
reviewed her medical records and accepted her as a patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of discussions, my wife and I,'' David Smith
recalled. To cover his wife's medical expenses, he was working two
part-time jobs in addition to his job at the Jackson County
Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of ramifications, religiouswise,'' he said.
``You can't talk about it all the time. You have to continue with
the daily basics. In the end, it was what my wife wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   David Smith would not reveal how his wife contacted Kevorkian.
He described the process as a ``network you go through. There's a
coordinated effort among several players. You don't just make a
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith stayed in touch with Kevorkian for months. He
counseled her. He told her to make peace with her family and God.
Once she had done that, she was to contact him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to accept her decision a couple of weeks before we went
to see Kevorkian,'' David Smith said. ``We spent many hours
talking, planning. Things like, `How are you going to raise our
daughter?' When I made my peace with her, I made peace with
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the call came.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may think you have two more weeks, and then the phone
rings and you have to go now,'' Smith said. ``My wife spent hours
and hours on the phone the day before we left, but you can't tell
everybody. Some people, if they find out, they'll do anything to
stop you from doing it. Less than 10 family members knew about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only David Smith and his father-in-law, James Poland,
accompanied Patricia Smith on the trip to Michigan. A larger group,
they feared, would attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is undignified,'' David Smith said. ``Hurry and
scurry, hotel reservations, saying your goodbyes. Even a guy on
death row knows when he's going to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should not have to go to Michigan. You should be able to
do it at home or in a local hospital. She had to say goodbye to our
daughter at the door on the way out. You can imagine what that was
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian doesn't charge his patients, Smith said. The family
had to pay for their trip to Michigan, but Kevorkian took care of
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Smith would not say where Kevorkian met them. He spent several
hours with the family and asked Patricia if she wanted to go home
and die naturally. She said no. He gave a detailed explanation of
what he was going to do. Then, as David Smith watched, Kevorkian
stuck a tube in her arm and videotaped the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock,'' he said. ``I remember some things. Just
seeing her limp was real difficult. I miss my wife dearly. I regret
that she is not here, but that is my only regret.''
</P>
<P>
   David Smith went to a Pontiac restaurant and waited for
Kevorkian while he took the body to the emergency room of a Pontiac
hospital, where Patricia Smith was pronounced dead at 11:55 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   When Kevorkian met him at the restaurant, ``people treated him
like a celebrity,'' Smith said. ``He acted as if almost nothing
happened. I had never talked to him until that day. He was calm,
very reassuring. I haven't talked to him since.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Regina Merrick watched her husband gather
the children for a swing dance class. A spelling textbook lay open
beside her. The front door closed behind them, and she sat alone in
the living room beside a machine she uses to exercise her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In your dreams, you still walk,'' she said. ``In your dreams,
you always walk. I long to do that again. I long to hold little
children. I long to sit in my husband's lap. I long for life not to
be so complicated. It's lonely. People who meet you assume you were
always like you are now.''
</P>
<P>
   She hesitated, staring out the window as her husband backed
their van onto the street. Her thoughts returned to Patricia Smith:
</P>
<P>
   ``It must have been something for her. I couldn't know her
pain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
