<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-COLUMN-2NDTAKE     03-28 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORYTELLER TRACED KANSAN'S LIFE OF ACHIEVEMENT, FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... Meade, KS 67864.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't all Kobs wrote. There were stories about his
Grandpa Butler; the hard cases that once inhabited Englewood, Kan.;
and how getting roads built was no easier in 1920 than it is today.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, after his retirement Kobs wrote constantly. Plus he
became a calligrapher of sorts, learning how to make the graceful,
fluid lines that go back to medieval times. He wrote wonderful
little poems, took hours copying them onto fine paper, framed them,
then sent them to friends and loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs would tell people there was no way he was going to
vegetate. No matter what his age.
</P>
<P>
   Then a year ago Kobs, age 85, stopped writing. He had a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are holes in my memory,'' he said with candor.
``Everything's been crowded back in me. Oh, I can remember a piece
here, a piece there. But I can't tie it together anymore. Not so
that I can write it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobs' wife, Ethel, says he has improved. She couldn't say if
he'll ever write again. The calligraphy definitely has become a
thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, instead of sorrow, Kobs evokes empathy. He had reached a
certain age, and the body that had served him well since William
Howard Taft was president had developed a glitch. As he said, ``You
don't see many cars my age on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has his book on George B. Allen, the mysterious old man
dressed to the nines that Eddy saw all those years ago seated
stiffly in a racing sulky pulled by a Percheron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after I finished the book I had two calls, one from
California, one from Washington state,'' Kobs said. ``They were
grandchildren of George B. Allen. They said I'd gotten the story
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nice. I was happy about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
