<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-INSPECTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGE MAKEOVER: THE POSTAL SERVICE GOES HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service knew it had an image problem.
</P>
<P>
   As Postal Service officials saw it, when most Americans thought
about the Postal Service they either pictured the character of
Newman on ``Seinfeld'' driving empty bottles to Michigan in a mail
truck in search of deposit money, or else a headline about a postal
worker getting a gun and shooting people.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Postal Service hired Warren Weideman. An
advertising executive who had spent much of his career in ``product
placement'' _ making deals with advertisers to put their products
in scenes in Hollywood movies _ Weideman had an idea about how to
counter the Postal Service's deeply ingrained negative image.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to make movies about the exciting adventures of postal
workers, and he wanted the Postal Service to back them with a
national marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As to the obvious question: What exciting adventures of postal
workers? Weideman had a surprising answer: ``The most elite law
enforcement agency in the country, one nobody really knows about,
is the Postal Inspection Service. I made a deal with the Post
Office for rights to their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The result: ``The Inspectors,'' a movie, starring the
Oscar-winner Louis Gossett Jr., which played on Showtime last
September, scoring the best ratings for any original film in that
channel's history. Weideman and the Postal Service have recently
contracted with Showtime for four more movies based on the
adventures of postal inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the culmination of Weideman's seven-year quest to
reshape the negative image of postal workers. ``It reached a point
where some guy would shoot up a K-Mart,'' he said, ``and people
would say, `He went postal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Weideman said there is a trove of true stories about postal
inspectors, who investigate letter bombs and all manner of mail
fraud. He learned that the service was Efrem Zimbalist Jr.'s first
choice for a television series in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and the producer Quinn Martin approached the Post Office,
looking to do a show about postal inspectors,'' Weideman said. ``I
saw the letter they wrote. But postal inspectors liked to be known
as the `silent service' back then. They turned them down. So
Zimbalist went across the street to the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Even armed with his action-packed postal inspector tales,
Weideman found pitching a movie about them a hard sell. ``Most
producers' eyes would glaze over as soon as I said the words, `post
office,' '' he said. Finally, he said, he approached Showtime from
a different angle. He said he asked what the channel thought ``of
posters for Showtime in 40,000 post offices.''
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service did even more than that. It issued 5,000
commemorative envelopes and sold them for $20 each; it put notices
about the film all over the Postal Service Web site; it put
Gossett's voice on a recording played while customers are on hold
on the phone line inside many post offices, urging them to tune
into the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service did not invest in the movie itself, Weideman
said, but it put millions of dollars in advertising and marketing
behind the project to insure its success.
</P>
<P>
   Having had the success, Weideman is convinced he has stumbled
into a new business opportunity _ which is really a very old one
for television. He calls it the ``sponsored program.'' Weideman
defined it as ``finding the right property that you can associate
with a sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   That could mean movies or programs that connect tangentially to
a product and that will encourage the makers of the product to
promote the entertainment productions, Weideman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
