<HEADER>
A7178 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TWOTAKE     03-28 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-COLUMN-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORYTELLER TRACED KANSAN'S LIFE OF ACHIEVEMENT, FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEADE, Kan. _ The memory Eddy Kobs has of George B. Allen comes
from his youth _ seeing an impeccably dressed old man driving a
racing sulky pulled by a magnificent Percheron horse.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs, working in the fields of his family's farm, was
transfixed. Could that be (BEGIN ITALICS)the(END ITALICS) George B.
Allen, one of the earliest settlers of Meade County, large
landowner, breeder of champion racing and draft horses, autocrat of
a showplace home and farm, lawyer and sartorial dandy?
</P>
<P>
   And more, a business failure, abused husband, cuckold, derelict
father and, finally, murderer and convict.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs, then in his mid-teens, couldn't know. In those days and in
this place, George Allen's rise and fall was only whispered about.
Kobs went back to work and filed the recollection away. Soon
afterward, in 1930, Allen died.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, that picture of George B. Allen stuck with Kobs. And why
not? After all, Kobs had become a farmer, a man who spent lonely
hours in the fields. He had to have something to occupy his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs was also a storyteller. Never a gossip, though _ Kobs was a
stickler for facts. He'd track them down, verify, then fold them
into his stories.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs' son, Bill, can remember the late 1930s and early 1940s:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just something he did. Back then we had one of those
6-volt battery radios, but it usually didn't work. But we didn't
care about Jack Benny or Fred Allen. We had Dad, who'd tell stories
sitting around the dinner table or afterward out on the porch. It
was just in his nature.''
</P>
<P>
   There were all sorts of stories. How Kobs was born in 1912,
survived the 1918 influenza pandemic, and reached his majority when
this part of southwest Kansas was blowing away in what appeared to
be black smoke but which really was the land turned to dust.
</P>
<P>
   Or how the Kobses came out of Lafayette County, Mo. Or, on his
mother's side, how Grandpa Hank Butler had been a cowboy on the
Texas trails, found the short-grass country here to his liking and
settled down.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs had a way of spinning a tale. He threw in the minutiae _
the sound of the ceaseless wind, how men used to roll their
cigarettes just so, and how the October calf weaning always brought
an odd hopefulness to farmers and ranchers in spite of the looming
winter.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was always the George B. Allen story.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs farmed here for 60 years, raising hay, alfalfa and cattle.
He started with horses and mules, ended up with big tractors.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, when Kobs retired a few years ago in his late
70s, he started putting down all those old stories, first on a
notepad, then banging away at an old typewriter, and finally at a
word processor. Modernity never intimidated Kobs.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't care a whit about fiction or rose-colored
reminiscences. He liked true stories with a beginning, middle and
end.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things he did was start researching the George
B. Allen story, reading old newspapers, combing through court
records, visiting with old-timers. What emerged was a dandy.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, Kobs discovered, had come here from central Kansas in
1878, acquired several thousand acres for a song and became an
early promoter of the Angus cattle breed. He married a fine woman,
had children, and was on his way to becoming one of those
quintessential pioneer Kansas farmer//ranchers, a patriarch whose
core investment in land would withstand the vicissitudes of the
southwest Kansas agricultural economy and, even a century later,
make their heirs well-to-do men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Except Allen wanted something more than the 90-hour weeks most
Kansans knew. He decided to become a lawyer. Rather than overalls,
he wanted fine clothes. His real passion was harness racing.
</P>
<P>
   So he started reading law; sold off his land and cattle, except
for 160 acres for a horse-breeding and training operation; and
spent thousands on a Spanish-style home and barns. There was even a
racetrack on what he named the Lucern Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Allen bet he could finance his operation through the sale of
Standardbred buggy horses and Percheron draft horses, animals every
farmer needed to get to and from home and plow their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Allen bet wrong. With the new century came automobiles and
tractors. The Lucern Ranch was a loser from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs, in his research, also found personal problems. Allen's
first wife died soon after childbirth. Her death was followed by
Allen's 9-year-old son and his aged father. Allen then married a
woman who from 1902 to 1911, voluminous court papers showed,
regularly beat up Allen and had ``intimate associations with house
guests.'' The couple was divorced in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Allen's 15-year-old daughter became
involved, also intimately, with a saddle tramp named Tucker. Allen
shot young Tucker dead near Crooked Creek. He was arrested, tried,
convicted and sentenced to 10 years at Lansing, to the delight of a
crowd of a foot-stomping and hissing women who daily packed the
Meade County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Allen was released after four years and returned here to live
out his life quietly. He was a ruined man.
</P>
<P>
   Kobs, after all the old stories and his painstaking digging,
wrote a detailed book about Allen and his travails, with Meade
County as background. Called /{Wind Over Crooked Creek/}, it's
available ($20 postpaid) by writing to Box 191, Meade, KS 67864.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
