<HEADER>
A7180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNALISTS-KILLED-AR     03-28 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALISTS-KILLED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER JOURNALISTS DIE IN LATIN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica _ As dictatorships disappear from the map
of Latin America, leaving Cuba as a holdout, violence against
reporters has dropped correspondingly, to 23 journalists killed
last year from 41 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as democratic institutions have taken root in
Latin America's big cities, violence against reporters has shifted
to the region's redoubt of authoritarianism, the rural areas,
according to advocates for press freedom gathered here for a
meeting of the Inter American Press Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is far more dangerous to be a reporter in a small town _
you are far more vulnerable,'' said Robert J. Cox, chairman of the
association's press freedom committee. The shift comes as reporters
in Latin America's interior increasingly try to follow the
independent reporting of their big-city colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   In Colombia, which in the last decade has recorded the highest
number of killings of journalists in the Americas, eight of the 12
reporters killed in 1998 were from small cities or rural areas,
according to the press association.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these terrorist acts come after reporters in these
little cities denounce political and administrative corruption,''
said Enrique Santos Calderon, an editor of Bogota's largest daily,
El Tiempo, and the press association's Colombian representative for
15 years. ``The new agents of violence are guerrillas and
paramilitaries. Journalists who live in zones of guerrilla or
paramilitary infiltration are completely intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern was noted in a report just issued by the
Committee to Protect Journalists, based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the journalists killed in 1998 were small-town or
rural-based reporters who appear to have been targeted by corrupt
local officials,'' said the Latin America section of the
committee's 1998 annual report. ``The public outcry over the murder
of prominent journalists has made it safer for those working for
major publications. But substantial risks remain for reporters who
work for less visible outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, how do you extend this protection to rural
areas?'' Joel Simon, the committee's Americas coordinator, asked
here.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, press defenders are adopting tactics familiar to a
big-city police chief. A rapid-reaction team of investigative
reporters is being formed to respond immediately to every report of
a murdered journalist in the Americas. To reduce impunity for these
crimes, the team will travel to crime scenes, interview police
officers and prosecutors, and conduct regular, follow-up visits,
the Inter American Press Association said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will immediately go to the country, talk to the police
chief, and then follow up one month later,'' said Alberto Ibarguen,
publisher of The Miami Herald and director of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, to help focus attention on the problem, press
defense groups are expanding into interior regions of Latin
America, setting up e-mail networks and spreading information on
press rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every newsroom in the smallest newspaper in Latin America now
has e-mail communication,'' said Simon. ``Sometimes, I have gotten
information from rural Brazil, before the newspapers in Rio or Sao
Paulo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With the spread of democracy in Latin America, repressive action
against reporters has largely shifted from government to
individuals or unofficial groups, the major exception being Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of this year, Cuban police agents have detained
and interrogated independent reporters on 25 occasions, a sharp
increase, according to the press association. Currently, six Cuban
reporters are in jail. Two more, Jose Edel Garcia Diaz and Jesus
Diaz Loyola, were last seen in Havana on Feb. 25 and are listed in
the report as ``disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Press advocates attribute this to government nervousness about
the worsening economy and President Fidel Castro's discomfort with
a new breed of independent reporters who are supplying reports to
news organizations outside Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10-year period that ended in November, the press
association said, Cuba recorded the highest number of local
journalists forced into exile, 21, and the highest number of
foreign journalists barred entry, 105. In the category of
expulsions of foreign journalists, Cuba was second, with 17, after
Panama with 18.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Committee to Protect Journalists, put Castro as
the only national leader in the Americas on its list of ``Enemies
of the press: the 10 worst offenders of 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite implicit promises to Pope John Paul II that there
would be greater room for freedom of expression, Castro continues
his control over all media outlets and his harsh treatment of
independent journalists, who are routinely detained, arrested, and
beaten, or forced into exile,'' wrote Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Noting a new press law intended to intimidate independent Cuban
journalists, he added, ``A serious deterioration of press freedom
in Cuba has taken place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
