<HEADER>
A7181 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MS-KERVORKIAN-TWOTAKE     03-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MS-KERVORKIAN-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MS PATIENT CHOSE SUICIDE; ONE WANTS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Regina Merrick never knew Patricia Smith, but
their paths seemed destined to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Like Merrick, Smith was a nurse, a mother and an active member
of the Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   She also had the same debilitating form of multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 22, 1996, Smith, of Lee's Summit, decided to end her
pain with the aid of suicide doctor Jack Kevorkian. She was 40
years old and left behind a husband and their 17-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Her death haunted Merrick, now 45, who read newspaper articles
and watched television reports about Smith's suicide in Pontiac,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to contact Smith's family. She talked to counselors at
the Multiple Sclerosis Society. She hoped to run into Smith's
friends or family.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as Kevorkian went on trial and was convicted of
second-degree murder, Merrick's thoughts turned to Smith again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know what went through her mind,'' Merrick
recalled from her Kansas City, Mo. home. ``My MS was at the same
stage as hers was two years ago. Finally, I had to leave it alone.
It's worth it for me to live.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   When it was clear Smith's condition would continue to decline,
she decided to see Kevorkian, said her husband, David Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was strong-willed, determined,'' he said. ``She was
extroverted, compassionate and the most unselfish person I know.
She was a fighter, but even a fighter has to stop after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrick was diagnosed with MS in 1979. Her doctors expected her
to live a mostly normal life. They said she could have a family. An
avid skier and cyclist, she carried on with a slight limp. She had
six children and taught them at home.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1991 she started walking ``as if I was drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later she couldn't walk at all.
</P>
<P>
   The chronic-progressive multiple sclerosis that is gradually
breaking down Merrick's body is the most debilitating form of the
disease. It is the same strain of MS that tormented Patricia Smith.
It affects 15 percent of all MS patients, according to the
Mid-America chapter of the National Multiple Sclerosis Society.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick has limited use of her arms but can get around in a
battery-powered wheelchair. Smith, on the other hand, was
bedridden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very thought-provoking,'' Merrick said of Smith's
suicide. ``If assisted suicide gets legalized, for someone like me,
who is no longer a contributing member of society _ I mean, it
costs for me to stick around _ then what's going to happen to me?
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband dresses me. All my personal care has to be managed
by someone. It is so devastating when you can't handle that
anymore. You don't know what will happen. The last three or four
years have been much more difficult. When I could no longer do
anything, it took a little reckoning.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrick and her family live on the campus of Midwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary, where her husband, Bruce, teaches. Members of
the seminary's Faculty Wives Club assist the family. Once a month
they prepare an assortment of stews, lasagna and casseroles. The
meals are labeled and stored in the freezer for future use.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick sees her doctor at least once a month. She has
prescriptions for anti-depressants, and has urinary tract
infections and a host of other physical ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the frame on her wheelchair broke. Although the chair
carries a warranty, the manufacturer is charging $600 for labor.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration is just one of many for the Merricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a struggle, especially if I have morning classes,'' Bruce
Merrick said. ``I've got to get me up and her up, and if I don't,
there's stress. You have to look at the reality of the
deterioration. She's losing ground day by day, changing day by
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Five months before her death, Patricia Smith could no longer
accept the deterioration of her body. She had tried everything: bee
venom therapy 20 to 30 times a day, a quack doctor in Florida who
promised a cure, and New Age healing that called for suspending
metal balls around the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inclination is to hang on,'' David Smith said. ``You
really grasp for just about anything when modern medicine doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
