<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7182 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILOSEVIC-PROFILE-TWO     03-28 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILOSEVIC-PROFILE-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPARATE TIMES TEST DESPOT'S SURVIVAL SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RICK MONTGOMERY AND SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic wears fine suits and puffs
pricey Cuban cigars in a region where only half the people hold
steady jobs. He seldom smiles and rarely speaks in public. And, if
recent opinion polls mean anything, popularity eludes him, even in
his own country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slobo,'' the enigma. The opportunist. Serb protector,
political schemer, wily survivor. ``The Butcher of the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   The old labels to describe Milosevic provide convenient
shorthand for Americans who, until last week, had mostly ignored
this latest international villain.
</P>
<P>
   Like other despots, he is said to ``thrive on chaos,'' although
he lacks the bluster of Saddam Hussein or the fevered charisma of
Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   He has long denied supporting a policy of ethnic cleansing. He
has never been indicted for genocide. But the United States
contends his hands are stained by the blood of hundreds of
thousands of Bosnians, and now thousands of ethnic Albanians. In
those same hands rests the fate of a torn and troubled Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He creates disorder and manages to convince people only he can
resolve it,'' wrote biographer Slavoljub Djukic. ``He is both the
pyromaniac and the fireman.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO last week launched its first offensive on a sovereign state
after Milosevic refused to accept peace terms that would have
restored some self-rule to the southern province of Kosovo, where
90 percent of the population is ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say NATO allies hope the bombing of Yugoslavia, where
Milosevic's support has long been eroding, will spur his war-weary
people to finally bring down the 57-year-old Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility, however, is that the U.S.-sponsored air
attacks will lend credence to an anti-West resentment that prevails
across much of Yugoslavia, largely through news media controlled by
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone knows how to calculate securing the first
possibility'' _ an overthrow of Milosevic _ ``and not getting the
second'' _ strengthening his position, said Kurt Bassuener of the
Washington-based Balkan Action Council, which opposes Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   A banker-turned-communist bureaucrat who then turned Serbian
nationalist, Milosevic rose to prominence in 1987, when he
back-stabbed some of his communist allies and staged a coup to
become Serbian Communist Party president. Two years later, as
communism collapsed across Europe, he waved the banner of Serb
nationalism to prevail in Yugoslavia's first democratic elections
since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The new president of Serbia used his power to abolish the
autonomy of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   When Milosevic's second term expired in 1997 _ amid economic
instability and street protests over his policies _ he tapped
friendly factions in the Parliament to become president of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Milosevic's approval ratings there have
rarely climbed above 30 percent. His country's economy once was as
advanced and vibrant as any in eastern Europe. But in the past
decade it has staggered backward, hampered by international
sanctions, to the brink of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, experts say, Milosevic has managed to maintain
power by controlling ruthless police and military forces, by
fanning Serbian fears of victimization, and by pointing to Kosovo
as the rightful domain of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's always believed his own nationalistic rhetoric is
debatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slobodan Milosevic certainly did capitalize on the nationalist
card in terms of his rise to power in Serbia,'' said Robin
Remington, a University of Missouri-Columbia political scientist
who has studied Yugoslavia and has done research there. ``He
started out as a perfectly faithful communist.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is the son of a Serbian Orthodox priest and a
schoolteacher. His father shot himself in 1962; his mother hanged
herself in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Milosevic, a Communist Party bureaucrat, seemed an
unlikely ringleader for Serb nationalism. Observers often cite his
visit to Kosovo that year as the moment that transformed him into a
champion of Serb interests throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   History made Kosovo the perfect stage. It was there on June 15,
1389, on the ``field of the blackbirds'' that Serb forces fell to
the Turks of the Ottoman Empire. As the sun set, Serbian King Lazar
was beheaded and his people were cast into 500 years of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, during his 1987 visit, represented the federal
government in talks with the Albanian Kosovars. Local Serbs
demonstrated outside his meeting, yelling, ``Save us, save us,'' as
police pushed them back.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic emerged and commanded, ``No one shall beat the
people.'' He had their hearts in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ...
</P>
</TEXT>
