<HEADER>
A7183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      03-28 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS ITEMS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer Users Prepare For Spread of E-Mail Virus
</P>
<P>
   With tens of thousands of computers already thought to be
infected, corporations and network security professionals said that
they were bracing for the continued spread of the ``Melissa''
computer virus this week.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which is carried by e-mail, appears to be one of the
fastest replicating viruses ever detected because it automatically
tries to mail itself from each recipient's machine to 50 other
e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Products Put in Shows by Computer
</P>
<P>
   Another frontier in the commercialization of culture was crossed
earlier this month when computer-generated images of four products
appeared briefly in scenes on the UPN series ``Seven Days.'' The
images were inserted into the episode after it was completed by the
producer through a process that seeks to create images
indistinguishable from actual objects.
</P>
<P>
   Reshaping Image of Post Office
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to reshape the image of postal workers, an advertising
executive hired by the Postal Service came up with an idea for a
movie about the Postal Inspection Service. The result was ``The
Inspectors,'' starring the Oscar-winner Louis Gossett Jr., which
played on Showtime last September. Four more movies based on the
postal inspectors are planned for Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Devices to Store TV Shows Digitally
</P>
<P>
   Two Silicon Valley makers of digital VCRs plan to introduce
services that enable TV viewers to filter, store and retrieve
programs as digitized video.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox to Buy French Company
</P>
<P>
   Xerox announced that it was buying SET Electronique, a French
company that makes continuous-feed printers that can produce 500
pages a minute and can accept data that are compatible with
printers made by IBM and Oce. With SET, Xerox can take on those two
giants in the market for printers that accept data from desktop
computers and turn large rolls of paper into sheets like bills and
monthly statements.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America Safer for Reporters
</P>
<P>
   Violence against reporters in Latin America has declined, to 23
journalists killed last year from 41 in 1989, and appears to have
shifted from big cities to rural areas, according to advocates for
press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO bombers pummel Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic
has shut down virtually all the independent newspapers and
silencing the nation's most prominent independent radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Counting on a Volume Business
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of companies are trying to capitalize on the promise
of conducting commerce and serving customers on the Internet. But
many Internet-only businesses are built on the strategy that
whatever millions of dollars they lose today, they will later make
up in volume. A growing number of industry watchers and executives
have begun to question how a volume-driven Internet can survive,
let alone grow, when its native businesses cannot turn a profit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
