<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REPORTER GETS A JUMP ON HIS BEAT 
A MAGAZINE CHECKS UP ON ITS INVESTIGATORS 
AT KNIGHT RIDDER, THE CHIEF BELIES TIGHTFISTED IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Mass.)  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much is a good Rolodex worth?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of J.D. LaRock, the recently hired education
reporter for the all-news cable channel NY1, it did not hurt that
he spent the last 18 months as a press officer for the New York
City Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   LaRock, 25, was hired by the cable news channel earlier this
month over several other candidates, most of them seasoned
reporters. NY1 said it chose LaRock even though he did not have any
prior journalism experience because of his familiarity with the
city's notoriously Byzantine school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted someone who could walk right in,'' said Steve
Paulus, the station's general manager. ``We feel like reporting
techniques are something we can teach him.''
</P>
<P>
   But some in the news business wondered whether LaRock would pull
his punches. ``I would say it raises serious conflict of interest
issues,'' said Sandy Padwe, an associate dean at the Columbia
School of Journalism. ``How do you stay fair when you have to
report on the same venue you just came from?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of LaRock's new colleagues found it unnerving two weeks ago
when he showed up at a board news conference as a reporter, his
hair newly blown out for broadcast consumption. Only days earlier,
LaRock had been taking questions from the same journalists, and
some worried that his insider status would give him an unfair edge.
</P>
<P>
   His former employers, however, said they did not find his new
career troubling. ``We certainly have no problem with it here,''
said Chiara Coletti, a spokeswoman for the chancellor. ``There's so
much jumping back and forth these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Although officials with the city's Conflict of Interest Board
had no comment on LaRock's case, the board's deputy counsel, Wayne
Hawley, explained that unless former public employees use
confidential information for private advantage, the city charter
does not bar them from using their expertise in a new position.
``You don't have to get a lobotomy when you leave government,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As an alumni of the city's public school system _ and the son of
two current Board of Education employees _ LaRock says he is
well-suited for his new profession. ``I don't see my old job and
new job as adversarial,'' he said. ``A press officer is ultimately
responsible to the public and the press serves the same master.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides,'' he added, ``I was never privy to a lot of
sensitive information.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW JACOBS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Magazine Checks Up on Its Investigators &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may not be in a magazine publisher's best interest to anger a
man with close ties to Salvatore Gravano, the mob hit man who
worked for John Gotti. But John F. Kennedy Jr., the publisher and
editor in chief of George, and Richard Blow, its executive editor,
have certainly annoyed Peter Maas, the author of ``Underboss: Sammy
the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the Mafia'' by holding up an
article for more than eight months.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the magazine's editors, Maas and Mike
Barnicle, the columnist who resigned from The Boston Globe last
summer amid charges of sloppy journalism, wrote an article for
George a year ago titled ``The Brothers Bulger.''
</P>
<P>
   Maas and Barnicle filed the article _ which appeared this month
and focused on William M. Bulger, the president of the University
of Massachusetts, and his brother, the reputed Boston mobster James
J. (Whitey) Bulger _ in early June 1998. Then, in late June, the
scandal erupted around Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were raving about the piece,'' Maas said. ``Then Mike got
into trouble, and they really panicked. So they held it until this
month, eight months later.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Blow, the Barnicle scandal led the magazine to
believe that ``it was worthwhile to take as much time as necessary
to make sure that everything in the article checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, he said, ``Mike Barnicle's ethical problems presented
an easy avenue of critique for anyone who didn't like the story.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added that additional fact-checking and legal supervision
were necessary because ``both Peter Maas and Mike Barnicle are
journalists who have been involved in journalistic controversies.''
(Blow was referring to a lawsuit against Maas in 1997 that accused
him of wrongly sharing profits from ``Underboss'' with Gravano.)
</P>
<P>
   Maas said that he was not aware that any extensive fact-checking
had taken place. Barnicle did not return telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The two, meanwhile, have put George behind them. This month,
Barnicle begins contributing to The Daily News as a Sunday
columnist. And they sold the rights to the George article to Robert
Redford's entertainment company, Wildwood Enterprises. Redford,
Maas said, is interested in playing one of the Bulger brothers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ALEX KUCZYNSKI &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Knight Ridder, The Chief Belies Tightfisted Image &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to being tight with company money, few newspaper
executives can match P. Anthony Ridder, the chief executive of
Knight Ridder, the country's second-largest newspaper chain. For
his relentless cost-cutting, he is known as ``Darth Ridder,'' a
nickname he has joked about while demanding 20 percent profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   But no expense was spared last year when Ridder moved the
company's headquarters to San Jose, Calif., from Miami, the
company's proxy statement showed.
</P>
<P>
   The company paid moving expenses for about 40 of its 150
headquarters staff. The 40 also got bonuses to compensate for the
higher price of housing in Silicon Valley, a deal that two
compensation consultants who work for companies and corporate
boards say was appropriate for lower-level workers, but not for
Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   Ridder received a $300,000 ``relocation bonus'' for moving to
San Jose, where he had lived for most of his adult life before a
promotion brought him to Miami in 1986. He also got $274,163 to pay
income taxes on the bonus, plus ``incidental relocation expense
allowances of $25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Less senior employees got a year's salary with a minimum of
$70,000, plus taxes, and part of the incidentals money.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ann Schlatter, a Knight Ridder spokeswoman, said the bonuses
``were paid so people would make the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jean Connors, senior vice president for human resources,
said relocation consultants estimated that housing would cost 2.5
times as much in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation consultants said Ridder should not have taken
the housing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Foley, a compensation lawyer in White Plains, N.Y., called
the payments ``an extra helping'' at a table where Ridder is
telling everyone under him not to take too much because money is
tight. ``It looks like a $600,000 handout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Johnson, an executive compensation consultant in New York,
said: ``It's a high price and terrible optics. This is a national
corporation with national-level pay for senior executives, so the
higher housing price argument doesn't hold. And if it's on top of
actual moving expenses, then it is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to moving expenses and the relocation bonus, Ridder
was paid $810,000 in salary last year. He also received a $415,242
bonus and 80,000 stock options that the company's board valued at
$926,400 on the day they were granted. He made $2.1 million
exercising options and holds options worth about $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Connors agreed that Ridder was paid on a national scale, but
she said that he was included in the relocation bonus ``because we
didn't want to discriminate against Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
