<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTURY-TV-MAKING-830     03-28 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTURY-TV-MAKING-830&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRICKY PATH FOR AN AMBITIOUS SERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CENTURY-TV-REVIEW, CENTURY-TV-LIST) 
(rk) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After what only seems like 100 years of journalistic labors,
ABC's 12-hour documentary project ``The Century'' will finally
begin broadcasting Monday night after one of the longest, most
expensive and most convoluted odysseys of any single project in
television history.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1990, when ABC was a part of Capital Cities Inc.,
and ended with ABC owned by the Walt Disney Co. It went from a $10
million budget in the early stages to about $25 million in the end.
</P>
<P>
   It went through at least three different narrative approaches,
three executive producers and various attempts to kill it, and it
was entirely reimagined starting last August after David Westin
took over as ABC News president and hired Shelby Coffey as his top
deputy. All the people interviewed about their memories of World
War I have died.
</P>
<P>
   The project hits the air with the unexpected momentum provided
by the success of the best-selling book ``The Century''
(Doubleday), by Peter Jennings and Todd Brewster, which grew out of
the research for the project. And Jennings, the series' anchor,
says television viewers are interested in what is on the screen,
not what it took to get it there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name me a news organization that doesn't have some degree of
turmoil on a major project,'' he said. ``What people care about in
The New York Times is what gets in the paper. It's the same with
us. There are people out there who think their job is to set the
bar for us, but the bar for me is set by the audience, and I think
there is a real hunger out there from everyone I encounter to
relive and experience and learn from what's gone on over the last
100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the project will indeed rise or fall on what viewers see
on their screens, it has also been a cautionary saga about the
difficulties of doing ambitious projects amid the shifting winds of
changing corporate ownership, programming and news trends and cable
competition in television.
</P>
<P>
   And its debut Monday night, in an inauspicious time slot against
the NCAA basketball championship game, is a far cry from the
grandiose hopes with which the project began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Century,'' which will be broadcast Monday night and five
other nights through April 10, is the result of a prodigious
journalistic effort. Reporters interviewed more than 500 witnesses
to the century's most important events, studied more than 3,000
hours of news film and ended up with a project that will include
the book, the ABC News documentary, a 15{-hour documentary that
will be shown on the History Channel, a Web site at thecentury.com
and efforts at spreading the research to teachers and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way the project lurched along like television's
version of the 30 Years' War. Early plans envisioned partners like
the United Nations and Russian and British broadcasting and a
26-hour extravaganza marketed like the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The partnerships fell through, and the research moved along with
either corporate hostility or indifference for years. The original
producer, Lionel Chapman, helped dig up rare film and began with a
chronological approach. Amid waning corporate support, he was
removed as head of the project and relegated to the less
prestigious cable project. He died of a heart attack five months
later, in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced by Av Westin, a producer with a long history at
CBS and ABC. Westin retooled the entire project, replacing the
chronological approach with a thematic one, basing each episode on
a theme like war or technology or American music. Then, with only
eight months to go before the first broadcast, he, too, was
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems you have on television _ you may have it
in print as well _ is you don't really focus until you get close to
deadline, which is where I came in,'' said David Westin, who is no
relation to Av Westin. ``The thematic idea sounded good on paper,
but it was hard to do without being somewhat dry and abstract and a
little bit like a textbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Yellin, a longtime collaborator with Jennings on
investigative and documentary projects, was brought in, and the
focus changed once more. Covering the whole century was never an
option.
</P>
<P>
   But after a meeting in August with Yellin, David Westin, Coffey
and Phyllis McGrady, executive producer of special programming, and
with the concurrence of Jennings, who was on vacation at the time,
the approach shifted toward a more story-based narrative. The goal
became telling evocative stories that together illuminated many of
the important themes of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between storytelling and an essay about a
theme,'' Yellin said. ``We think the first is much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Elvis segment is not just about Elvis. It's about
producing change in popular culture, the youth revolution, how
culture is spread around the world. It's a story about profound
social change, but if you began with the idea of doing a story on
profound social change, it wouldn't work. Tell a good story and it
will.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Monday night's program is called ``Heaven and Earth'' and
includes Charles Lindbergh's flight across the Atlantic and the
exploration of space leading to Neil Armstrong's first step on the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   The second, ``Ultimate Power,'' includes the rise and fall of
Hitler and the race to build an atomic bomb. The third, ``No Man's
Land,'' focuses on World War I and Vietnam. Other topics include
Martin Luther King Jr. and civil rights; the Depression and the New
Deal; the Cold War and the myth-making powers of Hollywood; the
Iran hostage crisis and the role of television, and a final program
of analysis and perspective.
</P>
<P>
   With its scale, the project will no doubt be critiqued on
various levels. It is, for example, the century through very much
an American lens, omitting topics as profound as the end of
colonialism in Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings and Yellin said that given the program's audience, the
role played by the United States and the scope of the project from
the World Wars in Europe to Vietnam to the crisis in Iran, the
American perspective was unavoidable and the project was far more
than just America's experience.
</P>
<P>
   And David Westin and Yellin agreed that the project could have
used a few more months to fully realize the new approach. But
Yellin said that the shifts in regimes did not have a huge impact
on the project. What did change from 1990, he said, was the
development of a whole new cable universe with avenues like the
History Channel able to present history and documentaries on a
scale that had never been done before.
</P>
<P>
   That evolution, the proliferation of news magazine programs and
the range of alternatives to the networks made an approach that
might have made sense in 1990 inadequate in 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar is just so much higher,'' Yellin said. ``You can't do
a pretty good job and think that's OK. So this has been an odyssey,
but I think it would be a mistake to focus too much on the odyssey.
There were many opportunities for ABC to have walked away from
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the end it wasn't cynical or mercenary or ratings
factors that kept it alive, but a sense of obligation in the best
sense. Since I've been involved, there's been no desire to see this
be anything other than the best it can be. We want to be judged on
the results we put on the air, and we feel we've given it our best
shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
