<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BUDAPEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS MEET WITH HOLBROOKE BEFORE HEADING TO YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BOSNIA,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA) 
(nk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ Warning that NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia
had severely damaged Russia's relationship with the United States,
a Russian delegation met here Sunday with the U.S. special envoy,
Richard Holbrooke, before attempting to travel by road to
neighboring Yugoslavia to present a peace plan to President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Three prominent liberal politicians from Moscow, who said that
their mission had been approved by Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
said their primary goal was to stop NATO air attacks against
Yugoslavia. They also said the Clinton administration made a
serious miscalculation by expecting that bombs would bring
Milosevic to the negotiating table over Kosovo and by failing to
understand how the bombing would inflame anti-American feelings in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the continuation of the fighting and bombing in
Yugoslavia is extremely dangerous for the world. If the situation
continues in the direction it is going now, we are confronted with
a serious danger of the Cold War re-emerging,'' said Yegor Gaidar,
a member of the delegation and acting prime minister in 1992 after
he helped launch the shock therapy reforms of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gaidar and other members of the delegation said that they had
several specific peace proposals to present to Milosevic, but that
they would not disclose them until after they met with the Yugoslav
leader.
</P>
<P>
   However, Milosevic's response to previous mediation efforts
suggested that the Russians' chances for affecting the course of
the war were slim.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Milosevic met with a Ukrainian delegation led by
Foreign Minister Boris Barasyuk, which, like the Russians, had
traveled to Belgrade in an effort to mediate an end to the
conflict. There was no indication that they had met with any
success.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, an official at the Yugoslav foreign ministry said
efforts were being made to set up a meeting for the Russians, but
had no other details. The Russian group was reported to have
reached the Yugoslav capital this evening.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting here with the Russians, Holbrooke, who is in
Budapest on private business, said that while he wished the peace
delegation well, he wanted to make clear that the Moscow group
would not be carrying a message from the United States to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reviewed the American position,'' said Holbrooke, who
failed last week in talks with Milosevic aimed at persuading him to
accept a plan for peace in Kosovo. ``There is no change in that
position in the sense there is a clear disagreement between the
Russian government and NATO, but that does not mean we cannot still
continue close contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Western diplomat said after the meeting that the
Russian delegation was extremely unlikely to make any headway with
Milosevic and that its presence in Belgrade would have no effect on
NATO's bombing campaign. But the diplomat said that the mission
represents ``a genuine desire'' on the part of Western-minded
reformers in Russia to limit, and, if possible, reverse a marked
deterioration in American-Russian relations since the bombing began
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of some NATO governments Sunday suggested that the
Russian government itself could be useful in negotiating with
Milosevic to stop armed attacks by Serbian forces in Kosovo against
ethnic Albanians and bring an end to the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac has urged Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov to go to Belgrade to ask Milosevic to end the
crisis, French officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit called on Yeltsin to help
find a political solution to the conflict. ``I think an
intervention by Mr. Yeltsin to persuade Serbia to a more reasonable
position would be most useful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch Foreign Minister Jozias van Aartsen also said that the
Russians have a key role to play in resolving the conflict over
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here, Boris Nemtsov, a former Russian deputy
prime minister, said that the bombing of Serbia was an ``enormous
miscalculation'' that has infuriated an overwhelming majority of
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov said the bombing, if it continues, could provoke a
powerful anti-American political movement that would severely
weaken the influence of pro-Western reformers in Russia. He made
his remarks before hearing word of shots being fired Sunday in
Moscow at the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Milosevic,'' said Nemtsov. ``I know that bombing is not
going to make him change his mind. It has made him a hero to the
Serbian people. The United States made a big mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
