<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON or TUZLA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ A day
after a NATO stealth fighter is lost over Yugoslavia, undeterred
allied forces step up the air strikes campaign in ``Phase Two.''
Meanwhile, reports of Serb atrocities against ethnic Albanians
continue and tensions heighten along Yugoslavia's borders.
(Shepard-Holmes, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   WITH:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA _ TUZLA, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Five days of NATO
air strikes have begun to take their toll on the border between the
former Yugoslavia and the current Yugoslavia, particualrly the U.N.
peacekeeping force here. Tensions are mounting in the wake of the
shoot down of the twin MiGs, buzzing of twin Serb helicopters and
daily air raid sirens. Moreover, the local Serb community is liking
the U.S.-led peacekeepers even less than ususal. Developing.
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AID _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ When humanitarian aid groups
pulled out of Kosovo last Wednesday, they distributed enough food
and water to support the distressed people there _ which then
numbered more than 500,000 _ for about a week. That means these
folks will run out of food by midweek. The situation may actually
be worse because the distribution centers where they left the food
are probably being overwhelmed by freshly displaced people. There
are talks of humanitarian air lifts to drop food but no one
believes that's a reasonable solution. Meanwhile, sources in the
provincial capital of Pristina report and confirm the chaos there.
(Roughton, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC _ An in-depth profile of Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic, president of Yugoslvia. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
