A7207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      03-28 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: INTERACTIVE TV; RAIN-FOREST PLANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week a tiny New York company received a huge patent that it
says covers many aspects of pay-per-view television as well as the
integration of Internet content into television programming.
</P>
<P>
   This patent, the seventh so far issued to Personalized Media
Communications LLC, is unusual for its heft as well as its breadth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely broad,'' said Mark Lemley, a University of
Texas law professor specializing in intellectual property. ``It
covers the basic sort of Web TV applications. But it might cover,
even more broadly, customized interactive information.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company contends that its patents cover the practice
of directing any type of television advertising or content to
specific households or demographic areas.
</P>
<P>
   Several patent experts speculated that last week's patent might
well set a record for the number of references it contains to
``prior art'' _ the way the Patent Office refers to previous
inventions related to the one described in a particular patent.
</P>
<P>
   Many software patents have been criticized for containing few,
if any, references to related inventions. Patents with a paucity of
prior art are considered more susceptible to lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Personalized Media's patent, though, contains more than a
thousand such citations.
</P>
<P>
   The patent is also unusual because its lineage dates to the
paleolithic era of the Internet and interactive television, to a
patent applied for in 1981 by John C. Harvey, a former investment
banker who has been building a patent portfolio since the late
1970s in the area of interactive television.
</P>
<P>
   And this latest patent is likely to be just one of many progeny
to spring from that original 1981 ancestor. Tom Scott, the
company's patent lawyer, said he submitted more than 300 new patent
applications _ all linked to the original 1981 patent _ in June
1995, a day before a new law went into effect changing the way the
term of a patent is figured.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of that law was to thwart ``submarine'' patents
_ that is, patents that applicants manage to keep submerged at the
Patent Office by delaying their issuance until a technology became
widely used enough for the patent holder to reap substantial
royalties from companies that had in the interim brought related
products to market.
</P>
<P>
   Inventors could do this without being penalized, because patents
were valid for 17 years from the date of issuance. The new law,
while extending a patent's coverage to 20 years, calculates the
term of patents applied for after June 1995 from the date of
application. Thus, an invention that takes 18 years to win a patent
will have it for a mere two years.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``submarine patent'' has often been associated with
Jerome Lemelson, an inventor who patented prolifically. He
successfully sued automobile manufacturers and others during the
1980s and 1990s by wielding patents whose original application
dated back to the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said it would be unfair to compare Harvey to Lemelson.
Lemley, on the other hand, called the similarities striking _ and
troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This original patent was split and refiled an extremely large
number of times,'' he said. ``That's precisely the sort of thing
that Lemelson did. I don't want to make the statement that he's
deliberately doing this to subvert the industry,'' he said of
Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``But regardless of the intent,'' he added, ``the effect on the
industry is the same _ he has taken an industry by surprise. A
fairly robust industry grew up in this technology during the time
after which this was filed. All the companies who developed this in
good faith in the interim could in theory be infringing the
patent.''
</P>
<P>
   Personalized Media said it would seek licensing agreements from
companies using technologies described in its patents.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary legal skirmish with a number of large companies
_ including DirecTV, a unit of General Motors Corp.'s Hughes
Electronics subsidiary, and Thomson Consumer Electronics, the U.S.
arm of Thomson Multimedia in France _ the federal U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals recently ruled that a claim in Personalized
Media's sixth patent was invalid.
</P>
<P>
   While this was only one claim of many in the patent, it could
foreshadow troubles for Personalized Media, said Walter Hanchuk, a
lawyer with Morgan &AMP; Finnegan, a firm whose clients include some of
the defendant companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court found only one claim invalid, but this could
nevertheless have a serious impact on the validity'' of subsequent
patents issued to Personalized Media, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and James W. Cuddihy most recently received patent
5,887,243, which was assigned to Personalized Media.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon Tribes Seek Patent Revocation
</P>
<P>
   A group representing Amazonian tribes said it would file a
request with the Patent and Trademark office on Tuesday to revoke a
patent issued in 1986 for a rain-forest plant that shamans use in
religious ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition for Amazonian Peoples and Their Environment
contends that the patented version of the plant _ Banisteriopsis
caapi _ grows naturally throughout the Amazon and is not a new
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the World Wide Web at www.uspto.gov or
may be ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the
Patent and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
