</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-SACRIFICE-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE SHEEP ARE PLENTIFUL AND HAVE REASON TO BE NERVOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ It was a bad time to be a sheep here. All last
week, it seemed, they were everywhere you looked _ being herded
down crowded streets, peering from taxi windows, even munching
clover on urban balconies. But this was no sheep's holiday. They
were on their way to the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the start the Id al-Adha, the feast of sacrifice,
one of the most important festivals on the Islamic calendar. The
holiday is better known as the Id al-Lahma, or the feast of meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Id is our best season,'' said Mohammed Mustafa, a
27-year-old butcher and a beneficiary of the ritual that calls for
Muslims in this crowded capital, and all around the world, to pay
tribute to the occasion by killing a sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any sheep will do. The ritual prescribes that it be a
male, at least a year old and in good health, with intact teeth and
horns. And so, inevitably, prices soar, and anxiety soars _
something like what happens with roses in the United States around
Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To our clients, I know it doesn't sound fair, but we don't
have a choice,'' said Mustafa, who butchered as many as 30 sheep a
day all week, for what here is the not inconsiderable sum of $150
for a suitable 100-pound specimen. A customer buys it live, brings
it to the butcher, and receives it back in parts.
</P>
<P>
   To save money, and to track down tasty candidates, many Cairo
residents head out of town themselves, picking out a lamb in a
rural village and then driving it home themselves _ making for what
sometimes can be an extraordinary clash between the old and the
modern.
</P>
<P>
   Often the sheep rides in the back seat, along with the children,
or in the back of a truck, with crates of vegetables. And at home
Cairo, a city of more than 14 million people with the greatest
population density in the world, people stick to traditional ways.
They fatten the lamb at home, on a roof or balcony, or even in a
bathroom, until the day when its end must come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember when I was a teen-ager and we had two lambs
in the basement, where I was feeding them myself,'' said Said
Abdullah, a driver who lives in Saidda Zainab, a lower-middle-class
section of Cairo. ``When they were supposed to be slaughtered, I
cried and said no, but dad told me to stop, since I should not try
to be more merciful to animals than God himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the Id al-Adha is linked to the climax of the
Muslim hajj, the annual pilgrimage to the holy city of Mecca,
birthplace of the prophet Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of the ritual of sacrifice lies in a story from the
Koran, in which Ibrahim is ordered by God to sacrifice Ismael, his
only son, in Mecca, but is relieved of that burden at the last
moment, when God sends a lamb instead. In the Judeo-Christian
tradition, Abraham and Isaac play out this drama, in Jerusalem,
where the Dome of the Rock now stands.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Mohammed Taha Abu al-Farh, a scholar Al Azhar University,
said that even today, ``All Muslims around the world should
sacrifice a sheep if they can afford it, and Egyptian Muslims, like
their brothers around the world, keep to this practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in Mecca, among the pilgrims, is the practice mandatory.
There, some 2 million sheep were slaughtered early on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But all Muslims who can afford it are encouraged to carry out
the practice, and so countless sheep met their end, as the gesture
on Mount Arafat was echoed, in a sign of absolute obedience to God.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The practice follows prescribed rituals. The sacrifice, usually
of a sheep but sometimes of a cow, must be carried out in a precise
way _ by a trained butcher, who binds the legs, wields a knife with
a quick, single slash, and says the words ``Allahu Akbar,'' or
``God is good.'' The owner of the animal must be present, as a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   And the product of the slaughter is distributed according to a
strict prescription _ a third for the family that made the
sacrifice, another third as gifts to relatives and neighbors, and
the last third for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of that sharing is to leave many people who cannot
otherwise afford meat suddenly awash in it, and that sets in motion
days of gorging, with meat is eaten at nearly every meal _
beginning with the first breakfast, of fatta, a mix of boiled lamb,
bread, rice and soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot resist eating,'' said Manal Salaheddin, 29, an
electrical engineer who lives in the wealthy Cairo neighborhood of
Heliopolis and who said she treasures also the ``spirit of giving''
at the heart of the holiday. But also, and inevitably, it is a
holiday of blood _ and, sometimes, of comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   These days, many people do not take part in the sacrifice
itself. Instead, for the last several days, they have been buying
up their meat at busy butcher shops, after the killing has been
carried out at government slaughterhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Many others, though, adhere rigorously to tradition, and long
ago made an appointment with one of the many butchers who, early
Saturday morning, put an end to much of the baaing that has blended
with the noise of traffic on Cairo streets. Some insist that the
sacrifice be carried out at home _ a catalyst for the kinds of
stories that are the stuff of Egyptian family lore.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salaheddin, the electrical engineer, recalled that when she
was an adolescent, her father brought a lamb to their apartment
building. First, she remembered, the lamb tried to ram its
reflection in a mirror in the lobby _ causing $350 in damage, many
times the lamb's worth. Then ``it jumped from the 22nd floor
balcony,'' and that was the end of that experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then,'' she said, ``we have always kept the lambs either
in a private garage or at the butcher's himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
