<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACEDONIA-725(2TAKES)     03-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACEDONIA-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO WAR PUTS HEAVY STRAIN ON MACEDONIA'S STABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TETOVO, Macedonia _ As a mullah sang out the call to prayer at a
mosque next to the post office, local volunteers Sunday distributed
sheep, ritually slaughtered for the Muslim holiday that began
Saturday, to Albanian refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A few streets away, one of the leaders of the Albanian
nationalist movement in Macedonia warned that religion should be
kept out of the edgy politics of his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two problems,'' said Arben Xhafari, leader of the
Democratic Party of Albania. ``The effort to marginalize Albanians
in this society is one. The more inherent problem is the
Islamization of Albanian culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Tetovo, a small, bustling Macedonian city, is something of an
anomaly: the majority of its 300,000 residents are ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian Slavs, who are the dominant ethic group in this
former republic of Yugoslavia, are in a minority here. Tetovo is,
in a way, the capital of the Albanian nationalist movement.
Especially now, when the war in Kosovo is putting heavy strains on
the country's fragile stability, Albanian leaders here are
struggling to keep up their battle for equal rights, without
sliding into the ethnic and sectarian divisions that have brutally
torn apart other former Yugoslav republics.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia is now the only former Yugoslav republic that has
peacefully retained an ethnically mixed society. The war in Kosovo,
waged at Macedonia's borders, is harshly testing the country's
ability to keep itself intact.
</P>
<P>
   It is a country with all the ingredients for a Bosnian-style
debacle _ poverty, political instability and fierce ethnic and
religious rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   But what is working in its favor is an ambition to move toward a
Western-style democracy and, most important, a widely shared dread
of ending up like its wartorn neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all recognize how important it is to keep Macedonia stable
in the middle of a very rough neighborhood,'' a senior Western
diplomat said, noting that the crisis mentality here is very real.
``But Macedonians have always understood the first rule for a small
country in the Balkans: Keep your head down and survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has not exactly done that. It took a risk by allowing
10,000 NATO troops to be deployed along its borders as the vanguard
of the NATO force that would have kept the peace in Kosovo if
Yugoslavia had accepted a settlement for Kosovo autonomy. But
negotiations fell apart, and NATO began bombing Belgrade and its
strategic points in Kosovo. Now Macedonia is hoping that those NATO
troops will protect them from attack from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the government of Macedonia, which is in the
``Partnership for Peace,'' the cooperative arrangement that NATO
extended to former Soviet bloc nations, asked urgently to be
admitted into NATO. ``We have given NATO everything they asked
for,'' a Macedonian official told Reuters. ``And we need guarantees
on their part.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO is unlikely to take such a step any time soon, but the
request was a sign of just how exposed and vulnerable Macedonia
feels.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a riot on Thursday outside the U.S. Embassy led by
Serbian sympathizers in Macedonia, Pavle Trajanov, the country's
interior minister, warned of ``attempts by terrorism to deteriorate
the stability of our institutions and the state and to involve
Macedonia in the so-called Kosovo scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia's eagerness to align itself with the West and to
protect itself from Serbian reprisals is putting strains on its
coalition government, which is made up of a Macedonian Slav party;
the Democratic Alternative, a pro-Serbian group, and Xhafari's
Democratic Party of Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians in Macedonia unequivocally support NATO's
action to protect ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Other ethnic groups, even while fearing that Serbia, the major
entity in Yugoslavia, could threaten their country's sovereignty,
express far less enthusiasm about the presence of NATO troops. The
differences are expressed not just by political leaders, but also
by ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here think Clinton is garbage,'' Slobodan Atanasovski,
a Macedonian Slav who owns a small shop in a Slavic neighborhood of
Tetovo, said sourly. ``We want to be part of Europe, but that
doesn't mean we want to be invaded by American troops.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The yearning to join the West, however, can be seen on the
city's streets. Tetovo, a rundown city of Soviet-style high-rises
and rickety slums, also has a new shopping center and on main
corners, large, colored recycling bins. It was the first city in
Macedonia to introduce the notion of recycling plastic, glass and
tin.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Kosovo refugees have found shelter in the private
homes of relatives or friends here. There is little evident
resentment of their presence by other ethnic groups, who live in
different neighborhoods and are only distantly aware of the new
arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the crisis in Kosovo has heightened existing
Macedonian tensions over national identity and civil rights. Since
1994, Tetovo has had its own university, a cluster of shabby cement
apartment houses converted into classrooms and dormitories, where
6,000 students and 300 faculty members conduct classes in Albanian.
The university is not accredited by the Macedonian government, and
it relies on donations from Albanians in the city, some of whom are
quite prosperous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of Macedonia doesn't want us to be educated,''
complained the university's rector, Fadil Sulejmani. ``They think
that by keeping Albanians as ditch diggers and street cleaners,
they can keep us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Xhafari agrees, arguing that the only way to avoid a radical
Islamic movement in Macedonia is to build up secular Albanian
institutions, such as schools and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our global project is to cooperate with the West,'' he said.
He expressed mistrust of his estwhile allies in government, whom he
described as sympathizing with Serbia, but he also acknowledged
that they shared the same long-term goals. ``Spiritually they are
with the East, but their self-interest lies in the West,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Religion, which was never deeply tied to national identity in
Macedonia's history, has not yet surfaced as a major dividing line,
either in Kosovo, or in Macedonia. Ethnic Albanians in both places
did not convert to Islam until the 16th and 17th centuries, and the
religion is observed lightly.
</P>
<P>
   For now at least, Islam is not a rallying cry for the fighters
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the separatist rebels who have many
Catholics in their ranks and whose leaders recognize the strategic
importance of allying their movement with the West.
</P>
<P>
   For similar reasons, Islam has not been exploited by Albanian
nationalists in Macedonia. And that has helped keep the country
from falling apart. On Friday, only a few men showed up for
afternoon prayer at Tetovo's unusual painted mosque _ a colorful,
richly frescoed testament to how Macedonia mingled Christian art to
islamic tradition imported under the Ottomon empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people do not come here so often,'' Avdi Mustafa, the
mosque's aging caretaker, said a bit sadly. ``They are more
interested in schools and universities than the mosque.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
