<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE CURTAILS INDEPENDENT PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, MACEDONIA) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As NATO bombers pummel Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic
pummels the country's independent press.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to tighten an official near-monopoly on what Serbs are
told about the war, Milosevic responded to the bombing by shutting
down virtually all the independent newspapers and silencing the
nation's most prominent independent radio station, B-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hearing that all the independent media are shut down,''
Ann Cooper, executive director of the Committee to Protect
Journalists, said Friday. She added that the last Albanian-language
paper was closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based group has become a clearinghouse for
information about abuses of journalists around the world. On
Thursday, it issued its annual report, Attacks on the Press in
1998. An encyclopedic, 390-page study that runs from Afghanistan to
Zimbabwe, this book reported that around the world last year 24
journalists were killed, 118 were imprisoned and 500 were attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The section on Yugoslavia devoted 10 pages to a campaign of
attacks and censorship of journalists. But attacks on news
organizations intensified so sharply this month that the committee
released an update on Thursday, the day the book was released.
</P>
<P>
   By March 22, all of the Albanian-language press in Kosovo had
closed because of heavy fines imposed in mid-March. The fines
averaged $85,000 for each newspaper, part of almost $1 million in
fines that have been levied on independent newspapers and reporters
since a new press law went into effect in October.
</P>
<P>
   The book reports that on Sept. 30, Voijislav Seselj, Serbia's
deputy prime minister, described independent journalists as a
``fifth column.
</P>
<P>
   Vesna Radavojevac, a Serbian political reporter for the
independent Belgrade daily, Glas Javnosti, was caught by the
outbreak of the air war while visiting New York. ``I am very scared
that the journalists from the independent media will be the first
victims, she said on Friday. ``It is a great opportunity for
Milosevic to get rid of the opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
