 CULTURE NOTES: RUSSIAN GRAPHIC ARTS; NEIL SIMON PLAY IN LONDON;
BENEFIT FOR HARLEM SCHOOL; ANOTHER AWARD FOR JUDI DENCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian posters, illustrated books, journals, sheet music,
popular prints and other printed matter, as well as costume and
stage designs, form a comprehensive new exhibition at the Jane
Vorhees Zimmerli Art Museum at Rutgers University in New Brunswick,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from the National Library of Russia and the Research
Museum of the Russian Academy of Fine Arts, both in St. Petersburg,
and from collections in the United States, ``Defining Russian
Graphic Arts: From Diaghilev to Stalin, 1898-1934,'' continues
through June 30. Information: (732) 932-7237.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-Towners
</P>
<P>
   It is debut time for a couple of actors whose names happen to be
Richard Dreyfuss and Marsha Mason. They will give their first
London performance beginning Tuesday, when they open at the Theater
Royal Haymarket in the West End premiere of ``The Prisoner of
Second Avenue,'' Neil Simon's comedy about an unemployed
middle-class New York advertising executive, his wife and their
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play opened in New York in November of 1971,'' Simon said
recently. ``I could have written it about the New York of 1999.
With giant mergers of corporations, thousands of employees have
lost their jobs. Paper-thin walls of apartment houses bring every
sound of your neighbors into your bedroom. Nervous breakdowns must
have been around since the Renaissance. The more we change, the
more we stay the same.'' Information: 011-44-171-930-8800.
</P>
<P>
   High Hopes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The comedian Robert Klein will serve as host Monday
night when the singers Denyce Graves, David Garrison and David A.
Dorsey perform at the Merkin Concert Hall in ``Music and Friends,
an Intimate Concert to Benefit the Harlem School of the Arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Also performing will be students from the school, founded 35
years ago for aspiring artists from minority groups. Proceeds will
match a $70,000 grant from the Hayden Foundation for a scholarship
program in the arts for students ages 11 to 15. Information: (212)
926-4100, extension 306.
</P>
<P>
   A Player's Life
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dame Judi Dench's busy calendar is getting fuller.
Besides March 21 (accept Academy Award for best supporting actress)
and April 3 (open at the Barrymore Theater in David Hare's ``Amy's
View''), there is May 17 (accept the Shakespeare Guild's Gielgud
Award for Excellence in Dramatic Arts at the Barrymore).
</P>
<P>
   With Robert MacNeil as host, the presentation by last year's
recipient, Zoe Caldwell, also celebrates the 435th birthday of
Shakespeare, and the 95th birthday of John Gielgud. Information:
(212) 685-1095.
</P>
