<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING YOUR NOODLE ABOUT Y2K BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Tampopo'' is a favorite cult film in our house, mainly because
it's about food.
</P>
<P>
   The film focuses upon a truck driver who wages an endless search
across Japan for the perfect bowl of noodle soup.
</P>
<P>
   I have finally diagnosed his problem: The film's hero was
searching the wrong country.
</P>
<P>
   The people seeking solutions to the Y2K ``crisis'' are making
the same error. The solution doesn't lie in Redmond, Wash., or in
California's Silicon Valley. What we have to do is move the
headquarters for Microsoft and other major computer companies to
Luoyang or Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
   OK, American computers develop a nervous headache when they
contemplate the arrival of Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There is no crisis in China, where the people are living in the
Lunar Year 4697. On the Tibetan Buddhist calendar, it is Earth-Hare
Year 2126. The Tibetan monks disposed of Y2K 126 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   My moment of enlightenment concerning noodle soup and computer
clocks dawned a few moments after I added a dollop of hot chili
sauce to my $5.50 chopsticks banquet at Pho So 1 in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the truck driver in ``Tampopo,'' two brothers-in-law _ Fred
Bell and Jack Hall _ embarked upon a quest to find the perfect bowl
of the Vietnamese soup known as pho.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of pho parlors, and noodle-soup aficionados, in
the Seattle area these days. Bell and Hall whispered the news to
me. Pho So 1 serves the best pho. Who knows? It may be the best in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The secret lies in the broth, which is best made with beefy soup
bones and a hunk of rump roast simmered for a few hours with
peppercorns, cinnamon stick, cloves, coriander seeds and a couple
of spoonfuls of Asian fish sauce.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to eat my noodle soup at Pho So 1. At home I might stir
up a similar Thai dish you could call:
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Street Soup
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cups diced, red potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef broth
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sirloin steak, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh ginger, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   5 cups Thai seasoned broth
</P>
<P>
   Pour 3 tablespoons of oil into a skillet, then add potatoes and
cook over medium heat 4 or 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. Stir
in the chili powder and the cup of beef broth. Cover and simmer
until potatoes are tender and broth has been absorbed. Remove
potatoes to a warm bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remainder of the oil to the skillet. Toss in the beef
strips, garlic and ginger and stir-cook just until the beef no
longer looks raw. Add the cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the potatoes and beef mixture among four large bowls. Add
hot Thai broth and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Broth
</P>
<P>
   5 cups beef broth
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup diced green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   1 stick cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan heat together the broth, onion, cardamom, cinnamon
and cumin. When the broth is steaming add cayenne pepper a bit at a
time to achieve the desired level of hellfire. You can also add a
dash of Sriracha hot chili sauce, which occupies a place of honor
at most Thai or Vietnamese tables. Remove the cinnamon stick before
pouring the broth over the beef and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Here is another terrific noodle dish:
</P>
<P>
   Thai Thighs and Noodles
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces dried rice noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red curry paste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless, skinless chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Thai fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped peanuts
</P>
<P>
   3 green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   Cook or soak the noodles according to package directions. Or you
can follow these general rules: If you are using vermicelli, you
usually need only to soak the noodles in hot water until they are
pliable. Rice sticks, on the other hand, should be cooked in
boiling water 2 minutes or until they reach the stage of al dente
spaghetti. When done, toss with { tablespoon of oil to prevent
sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the chicken thighs into thin strips.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining tablespoon of oil in a skillet or wok. Add
the curry paste (I used Thai Accents brand) and stir-cook 1 minute.
Add half the chicken strips and stir-fry 2 minutes. Remove, add the
rest of the chicken and cook another 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Return all the chicken to the pan and add the fish sauce and
lime juice. Bring to a boil and simmer 1 minute. Add the bean
sprouts and noodles and toss well. Add the garlic and green onions
and cook 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Plunk the contents of the pan onto a warm platter and sprinkle
with peanuts and cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
