<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPETOWN-WAR-950(2TAK     03-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPETOWN-WAR-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPE TOWN VIGILANTES LOSING PULL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ The police intelligence document that
Superintendent Wicus Holtzhausen plucks from his briefcase is a
warning that he is on a hit list.
</P>
<P>
   He was, it says, among those branded ``political criminals'' who
``should be eliminated'' whose names were read out recently at the
mosque where the Muslim group called People Against Gangsterism and
Drugs, was formed.
</P>
<P>
   It is no idle threat. Already this year, two senior officers
investigating the group, known by its acronym, PAGAD, have been
gunned down from passing cars, one fatally.
</P>
<P>
   Holtzhausen, spokesman for the continuing investigation, has
been assigned bodyguards, but they are not always around. Police
headquarters here was bombed Jan. 28. PAGAD is suspected, but
denies it. In this police office building _ thanks to bravado,
tight budgets and puzzling management decisions that characterize
the force _ nobody bothers to stop visitors wandering the halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't walk into my office to get me,'' Holtzhausen
insisted. ``They definitely don't have the heart for that. They're
not suicide-bomber types.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would, though,'' he added, grinning to break the
tension of discussing the chances of his own assassination. ``I'm
ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Town, which once had a crime rate far lower than
Johannesburg's, is now a city in a three-way war between the
vigilantes of PAGAD, drug gangs that have become powerful over the
last five years, and police. Last year, there were 529 drive-by
shootings and 79 pipe bombings in the Western Cape province, which
includes the city, the vast mixed-race Cape Flats neighborhoods
east of it, and many quiet beach and farming towns.
</P>
<P>
   Many of South Africa's 500,000 Muslims live in the Cape Flats,
most descended from Malay slaves imported by the Dutch East India
company in the 17th and 18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   PAGAD is suspected of killing more than 25 drug dealers and a
police captain, Bennie Lategan, in addition to wounding a police
superintendent, Schalk Visagie. And it is suspected of bombing,
along with the police headquarters, several smaller station houses,
a synagogue and a Planet Hollywood restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant attack was in August, just after the United
States fired cruise missiles into Afghanistan and the Sudan in
retaliation for the bombings of two American embassies. But no one
has been convicted, so the authorities are careful not to accuse
the group publicly.
</P>
<P>
   PAGAD's representatives deny the accusations but hedge as they
do. Abieda Roberts and Ebrahim Francis, who are on its governing
committee, were asked in a joint interview if PAGAD had shot
officers and bombed stations. Both answered in virtually the same
words, ``No _ as far as we're concerned.'' Mrs. Roberts added
quickly, ``It's never been PAGAD policy to attack police stations
and policemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if police were right in saying that PAGAD's armed wing,
the G-Force, is never directly ordered to kill but interprets the
lists of enemies read out at the mosque as targets, they answered:
``We can't speak on behalf of the G-Force. We can't tell you how
they interpret it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't policy to kill,'' Mrs. Roberts added. ``But if people
decide to go out there and kill, it doesn't mean the leadership is
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when PAGAD first appeared in the crime-ridden
Cape Flats, it had a Wyatt Earp status. It could rally 5,000 people
at midnight to march from one drug dealer's house to another,
following a masked leader called the emir who would be flanked by
masked guards.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers were given an ultimatum: Confess at the Gatesville
mosque and quit the trade _ or die. Sometimes warnings were
spray-painted on their walls; sometimes gasoline bombs were thrown
against them.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, in a moment caught by a television crew and
broadcast around the world, a gang leader named Rashaad Staggie,
who was shoving through a crowd around his house, was beaten, shot
dead and set on fire. His twin brother, Rashied, who took over the
leadership of the gang, was wounded late this month in a drive-by
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Many citizens said they were sad that it took vigilantes to
clean up the area, but they agreed with PAGAD that police were at
best inept and at worst in the pay of the dealers who ran the Hard
Livings, the Americans, the Sexy Boys and other gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, a PAGAD march on a warm Sunday is lucky to get
500 people. A recent one drew only 80.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that misdirected violence has shriveled public
respect. The Planet Hollywood bomb _ which Mrs. Roberts
specifically denied was PAGAD's work, but which the group is still
suspected of carrying out _ blew off the leg of an 8-year-old
British girl. A drive-by shooting apparently aimed at a greengrocer
believed to sell drugs killed his 4-year-old daughter, whose
angelic face was on front pages the next day. Another baby was
killed when the wrong house was firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   A second reason for PAGAD's falling popularity is that it now
openly rejects the government. Crime analysts, police and local
journalists say it was taken over in 1997 by Qibla, an older
Islamic fundamentalist group. But PAGAD's leaders say they do not
endorse an Islamic revolution here _ a quixotic idea anyway,
considering fewer than 2 percent of South African residents are
Muslim. ``We're not stupid,'' Mrs. Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Francis added: ``We object to facets of the constitution.
Like abortion, like no death penalty, like this distorted sense of
human rights that lets gangsters walk free. We want a moral basis
to society.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The two contended that ``police intimidation,'' not their own
loss of touch with the people, has caused PAGAD's rallies to
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   But the rallies have also become dangerous. One on Jan. 8
protesting a visit by British Prime Minister Tony Blair turned into
a shootout inside clouds of tear gas. Police contended that PAGAD
was handing out guns, so officers opened fire with rubber bullets;
PAGAD said that some used live ammunition. One PAGAD member was
killed and other demonstrators were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Although police informants clearly attend rallies and mosque
meetings, the G-Force itself resists infiltration. Peter Gastrow,
an analyst at the Institute for Security Studies, a local research
group, said that it consisted of cells of a few men whose names
were known only to one another and who got their targets not
through a chain of command but from the lists read out at the
mosque.
</P>
<P>
   But it is possible that the police have finally made a dent in
the group. On Jan. 27, extra officers and soldiers began pouring
into Cape Town for a police drive against terrorism called
Operation Good Hope. The bomb at police headquarters, at Caledon
Square, went off the next day, as the operation's leaders were
meeting nearby. The bomb injured 11 pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, police have arrested what they think are two
G-Force cells. First, they stopped six men in a car at midnight and
found guns and a videotape showing police stations. Two days later,
five more men, also armed, were arrested driving down from
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say that one member of the second group is an
informant for South Africa's National Intelligence Agency and that
they believe the five planned to blow up Parliament as President
Nelson Mandela addressed it. The intelligence agency says that Cape
Town Muslim militants are being trained in the Middle East by
Hezbollah, or Party of God, the Lebanese guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
   Little evidence backing these claims has been released so far,
and police and intelligence agents are feuding over how the
information got out.
</P>
<P>
   But, as one local journalist who used to cover PAGAD put it,
``It's been dead quiet since they busted those two groups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HOOPER-ART-NYT     03-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HOOPER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FOREIGN SERVICE CAREERIST TURNED IMPASSIONED GADFLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, MACEDONIA) 
(lh) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first NATO missiles and bombs were only a few
hours from striking Yugoslavia when James Hooper, once the State
Department's senior dissenter on Balkan policy, sipped his coffee a
few blocks from the White House and talked of ground troops likely
to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now are going to have to consider a NATO protection force
on the ground to go in on very short notice if the blood-letting
escalates suddenly,'' said Hooper, characteristically speaking the
politically unspeakable on the Balkans without apology.
</P>
<P>
   It has been two years since Hooper, the very model of an earnest
Foreign Service careerist, quit the government in frustration after
26 years of toiling at diplomacy. He joined a handful of pioneer
State Department dissenters who left across two administrations
protesting Balkan policy.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the easiest of choices. ``I had wanted to be in the
foreign service since I was a teen-ager and read `The Ugly
American,''' Hooper said of the novel about intrigues and
frustrations of laboring abroad. ``It got me mad and interested in
foreign affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he plays the role of articulate, impassioned gadfly as
director of the Balkan Action Council, one of this city's countless
independent pressure groups that nip at the heels of government.
``It's as if there's a destiny,'' he said of his sudden decision to
retire from the Foreign Service to promote his views from without,
not within. ``I wanted to follow my dream, and now here's the
Kosovo issue front and center.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooper, who was once the State Department's deputy director of
Eastern Europe in charge of the Balkans, can sympathize with the
American public in its bewilderment over the region. ``To be
honest, I didn't know a damn thing about it,'' he said, referring
to his taking on the Balkans portfolio a decade ago after years of
specializing in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   He soon came to conclude that Serbian ultranationalism was a
threat to European order and to American leadership rooted dearly
in the Allies' anti-fascist victory in World War II. In the midst
of the modern Balkan violence, Hooper's father, a World War II
veteran, told his son he had finished that war in Czechoslovakia
yet only lately has understood what was at stake. The son tries to
stay mindful of his father's lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has to be prepared to use force abroad to
protect democratic values and our interests,'' said Hooper,
describing himself as a Truman Democrat. ``I think we're still
living off the patrimony of the policies of the Truman
administration,'' he said of such bulwark measures as the Berlin
airlift and NATO itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truman's the politician I admire most,'' he said, finding
President Clinton lacking the statesman's instinct of Truman. ``You
get that for being willing to step out into the dark to take risks,
to take responsibility for policies when you don't know the
outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Studying the confrontation as an expert amid the American home
front's considerable confusion, Hooper discusses the complex
problem in terms of two dominant personalities, Milosevic and
Clinton. He finds the authoritarian Serb leader cunningly using
force to test the American leader, a poll-driven consensus
politician who turned late _ not too late, Hooper hopes _ to
forceful intervention and to an overdue lesson for the public about
the global leadership at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the president has to restrain himself from stopping the
NATO attacks too early,'' said Hooper, who was dubious about
Clinton's latest burst of tough talk about Milosevic until the
first NATO missiles actually struck Yugoslavia. ``To pause would be
projected as weakness toward Milosevic,'' he warned, estimating
that if Clinton stays resolved and commits ground troops, if
necessary, the Kosovo outcome could prove as successful as the
earlier Bosnian intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper has a bachelor's degree from the School of International
Service at American University and a masters in Middle Eastern
Studies from Columbia University. His reading ranges from George
Kennan, the former Moscow ambassador and master Sovietologist, to
purely escapist books on mountain climbing. ``You've got to get
away from all this in order to survive,'' he says of his
preoccupation with the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 52, Hooper, a native of Grand Rapids, Mich.,
misses the friends and economic security of the Foreign Service,
but not at all the careerist pressures that can make change from
within a difficult task at any of this city's institutions of
power. Asked about role models, he talks simply of his mother's
lesson in persistence in gaining a college degree late in life when
she was going blind. He talks of steady guidance from his wife and
two grown children. ``It seems to me the fun in life is to try and
get as far as you can by being yourself and sticking to your
principles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always conscious that we were bureaucrats back in
Washington trying to change the policy,'' he said of his State
Department days in wrestling with the Balkans. ``I would drive home
every night and the greatest threat I faced was the traffic, while
there were people out there who were doing the real fighting and
dying,'' he said as he tracked the NATO bombs and missiles finally
falling on the forces of Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
