<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-VIRUS-550&AMP;AD     03-28 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-VIRUS-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRUS MAY INFECT MORE COMPUTER SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ With tens of thousands of computers already
thought to be infected, corporations and network security
professionals said Sunday that they were bracing for the continued
spread of the ``Melissa'' computer virus with the beginning of the
workweek on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, computer security firms said they had received
an unusually large number of calls for assistance from companies
infected on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa, which is carried by e-mail, appears to be one of the
fastest replicating viruses ever detected because it automatically
tries to mail itself from each recipient's machine to 50 other
e-mail addresses, computer security experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This message may be sitting in a lot of mail boxes dormant,''
said Jeff Carpenter, the incident response team leader from the
Computer Emergency Response Team, or CERT, a Department of
Defense-financed computer security hotline. ``When people go to
work and open it up, a large number of organizations could be
negatively effected.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said CERT had received 50 to 60 calls on Friday and
Saturday from organizations, ``most of whose mail servers were
incapacitated'' by an overwhelming volume of mail.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it appears that the biggest threat from the virus is
that it overwhelms networks because it reproduces so rapidly, but
it is not thought to otherwise attack the machines it infects.
Also, the infection appears to go dormant after once using a
recipient's computer as a platform to resend itself.
</P>
<P>
   As the virus continued to spread over the weekend, a debate
emerged as to whether it was intended as a malicious attack or was
actually an Internet marketing ploy that spun out of control. The
e-mail message that carries the virus includes an attachment that
lists several dozen Web sites with adult content.
</P>
<P>
   Computer security experts speculated that the virus program
might have been written as an effort to promote the pornographic
sites by automatically spreading them across the Internet in a way
that made each message appear to have come from an acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, said Eugene H. Spafford, director of the Center
of Education and Research in Information Insurance and Security at
Purdue University, Melissa could be a malignant form of ``spam,''
as unsolicited advertising by e-mail is known,
</P>
<P>
   When a user opens the list.doc file attached to the e-mail, it
executes a Microsoft Word macro, a sort of rudimentary program,
which searches the recipient's hard drive for an address list
produced by one of two Microsoft e-mail programs _ Outlook or
Outlook Express.
</P>
<P>
   It then copies the message to the first 50 names in the address
book, giving it the appearance of having been sent by a friend,
colleague or other acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person may have an economic incentive,'' Spafford said of
the virus' creator. ``He may be trying to propagate his list far
and wide.''
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, the program is actually intended to wreak
havoc with Internet mail servers, Spafford and other security
experts said it could have been much worse. The virus could have
been written _ and could yet be modified _ to carry a far more
dangerous payload, like a program that deletes data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entirely possible that within hours to months, we will
see something worse'' Spafford said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Network security experts continued over the weekend to search
for the origin of Melissa. One lead that several said they were
exploring involved a posting made to a sex-related Internet
discussion group early Friday morning, just before the virus
started spreading.
</P>
<P>
   The posting included the same list of pornography sites carried
by the virus.
</P>
<P>
   In at least one other instance, in December 1997, a person using
the same e-mail address posted lists of adult Web sites and
passwords that also contained viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The virus hit Friday afternoon, and this message was posted at
7 a.m.,'' said Richard M. Smith, president of Phar Lap Software,
Inc. in Cambridge, Mass. ``One could assume that this message was
the first time the virus existed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Word macros are probably more powerful than they ought to be,
but you do get something for that power,'' said Eric Allman,
co-founder of Sendmail, the Emeryville, Calif., software company
that makes the Internet's most popular post-office program for
routing e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Since the virus appears to affect only computers that are loaded
with both Word and either Outlook or Outlook Express, it appears
designed to take advantage of three of the most popular programs on
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts said that computers loaded with Word and one of
the two Microsoft e-mail programs are vulnerable even if the
default e-mail program on the computer is a competing product like
the Netscape Communications Corp.'s Navigator mail or Qualcomm's
Eudora.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Allman said, consumers need to be more aware what
information they are accepting on their hard drives and other
storage devices when they download an e-mail attachment. A setting
within Microsoft Word cautions users when they are about to open an
unknown document that contains a macro and asks if they would like
to continue.
</P>
<P>
   One lasting impact from the attack of the virus is that it
appears to alter the user's settings within Word so that the
program no longer warns users if they are about to open a file with
an unknown macro, Spafford said. The virus ``turns the protections
down on the machine to the lowest setting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Users can tell if they have been infected by the virus by
checking the Windows registry, which is a database that contains a
list of programs downloaded onto the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the corporations infected by the virus on Friday were
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., Lucent and the Intel Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
