<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-0329     03-28 1538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-0329 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILOSEVIC: FROM AMBITIOUS APPARATCHIK TO STEELY DICTATOR
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON On a muggy June day in 1989, near a railroad junction
a half hour's drive from the Kosovo capital of Pristina, nearly one
million Serbs gathered in a broad mountain-rimmed meadow called the
Field of Blackbirds.
</P>
<P>
   There, 600 years before, Turkish invaders routed Serbs in a
battle that forever changed the face of the Balkans, opening
Europe's southern underbelly to the voracious appetite of the
Ottoman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only Serbs who died on that field. Hungarians stood
with them, as did Poles and Albanians. They were part of an
international force of Christians, answering chiefly to Rome,
mustered to counter the growing reach of Islamic Turks.
</P>
<P>
   The horde that assembled ten years ago, however, came not to
praise the notion of ethnic diversity, but rather to bury it.
Presiding over the wake was an ambitious middle-aged Communist
Party apparatchik named Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Descending upon the masses by helicopter, like a rock star or
some lesser god, Milosevic held out a vision of redemption and
deliverance to those willing to believe that ethnicity was destiny,
particularly for Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo heroism does not allow us to forget that at one
time we were brave and dignified,'' Milosevic admonished the crowd.
``Six centuries later, we are again engaged in battles and
quarrels. They are not armed battles, though such things should not
be excluded yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The world took little notice of this barbed expression of Serb
nationalism. It's paying more attention now.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Balkans historian Janusz Bugajski, ``was the
beginning of the end for Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, Milosevic, a tightly wound man with a fondness
for expensive French cognac and double-breasted suits, was elected
president of Serbia, buoyed by the violent waves of
ultranationalism he helped to foment.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since then, with his influential Marxist wife
Mirjana Markovic at his side, Milosevic has led those same forces
on a bloody Balkan rampage that has left a quarter of a million
civilians dead along a swath extending from Slovenia through
Croatia, to Bosnia and the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as U.S. and allied warplanes rip daily into the military
and economic underpinnings of his authoritarian regime, Milosevic,
57, is counting on his gifts for using the power of symbols and the
utility of myth to seize political victory from the jaws of a
battlefield defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic, if he knows he's going to lose the military war,
wants to win the propaganda war,'' said Bugajski, director of East
European studies at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies, a Washington think tank. ``He wants to go down in history
as the savior of the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a sobering conclusion for U.S. policymakers. It suggests
that the Serb leader has every historical, political and personal
incentive for hunkering down to absorb a protracted campaign of air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   If his Serb forebears could attain martyrdom at the hands of
Turks with long knives, after all, Milosevic hopes to gain the
modern political equivalent, standing no less brave and dignified
against an onslaught of NATO cruise missiles and smart bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The historical template was a defeat, and it was bravely down
to the last man being willing to absorb that defeat rather than
accept compromise,'' said Jerrold Post, director of political
psychology at George Washington University. ``While it may be 600
years ago, it's like today to them. The past is present, and the
heart does not tell time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a culture that looks largely to its legends and tortured
history as the balm for a national psyche traumatized by a century
of turmoil, Milosevic may be the perfect tyrant.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the dawn of World War II to parents who would both
later, and separately, commit suicide, Milosevic seems to have
turned a personal persecution complex into something of a national
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs are the victims of the latest holocaust in this
century,'' Milosevic told the Washington Post in a December
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``My duty is to protect the interests of my people and my
country,'' Milosevic said. ``If anyone has a problem with that, I
can only tell you that I am proud of my role in defending and
protecting the interests of my country, and my people.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics, though, Milosevic is a politically astute psychopath
leading a morally addled nation on a doomed mission to roll back
the tide of history with the blood of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In an Oval Office address to the nation last week, President
Clinton described Milesevic as a dictator ``who has done nothing
since the Cold War ended but start new wars and pour gasoline on
the flames of ethnic and religious division.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks were aimed at explaining why he ordered U.S.
pilots to attack Serb troops who reportedly have killed more than
3,000 ethnic Albanians and run another half million more from their
homes during a year of repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, in his December interview, offers a reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Albanian narco-mafia gives money to foreign journalists
and politicians for the media war against us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire Western story of the Yugoslav crisis if false,''
Milosevic railed. ``This is the failure of journalism, moral
failure of journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic brooks no such shortcomings in his own country, where
the state-run media still dominates and journalists for independent
papers and radio stations are subject to fines, imprisonment or
worse for unflattering portrayals of his motives and moves.
</P>
<P>
   To those controls he combines an aggressive state security
apparatus to lock down political opposition and suppress dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is,'' said Bugajski, ''the last dictator in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April, 1941, Belgrade fell to Nazi occupation after days of
bombing by Hitler's Luftwaffe. Four months later, Milosevic was
born in the provincial town of Pozarevac, east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a theology professor, and his mother, a
schoolteacher, would later divorce. As a young adult, Milosevic
endured the suicide of his father and, years after that, his
mother, who was suffering from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   An economics graduate from Belgrade University, Milosevic scaled
a slippery career pole dominated by Communist Party machinations,
before turning his ambitions toward government.
</P>
<P>
   A quick study in politics and finance, Milosevic became one of
the youngest executives ever at Technogas, the state-owned company
that managed the country's natural gas purchases from the Soviet
Union. He quickly rose to become general director and five years
later he became president of the United Bank of Belgrade. He was 37
years old.
</P>
<P>
   To the Soviet contacts he'd developed in the gas business,
Milosevic added a Rolodex of banking sources from the West,
including many in the United States, which he visited as head of
the Belgrade bank.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he went into politics full time in 1984, heading the
communist party's Belgrade chapter, Milosevic seemed well equipped
to help a country struggling to negotiate the collapse of Soviet
influence and the coming primacy of Western capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   He soon turned his talents, though, toward other ends,
harnessing his personal ambitions to the powerful engine of Serb
nationalism, the enduring source of his authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind this facade of Serbian nationalism, this is not a man
with deeply held beliefs,'' said Post, who has studied Milosevic
extensively. ``His major goal is maximizing his own power and
surviving in power, and certainly not his dedication to the Serb
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is married to Mirjana Markovic, a Belgrade University
professor of Marxist sociology.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Marija, runs a radio and television station in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Son Marko is a flamboyant child of privilege. In a state
impoverished by years of war, Marko flits about in flashy sports
cars and runs a Belgrade disco. On Saturday, as troops under his
father's command pressed their campaign of terror just south of
Belgrade, Marko reportedly signed a multmillion-dollar contract to
build an amusement park called ``Bambiland'' in his father's
hometown of Pozarevac.
</P>
<P>
   In a trend surely disturbing to U.S. policymakers, Milosevic has
seen his opposition wither in the days since NATO launched its
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is more popular today than he's been since 1989,
when he first rose,'' said former U.S. envoy to Bosnia, Bill
Stuebner. ``Just as we would do, everybody's rallying around the
flag.''
</P>
<P>
   To anyone trying to read the mind of Milosevic, that would
suggest that he's not about to capitulate to continued NATO
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   With no sign that Milosevic might run up the white flag,
Stuebner, a Balkans specialist at the U.S. Institute of Peace, a
Washington think tank, posits a haunting question: ``Are we going
to keep it going until he dies of old age?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
