<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, March 29, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
late-night supervisor is Josephine Schmidt; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Washington) Despite bad weather, allied planes
started attacking Yugoslav troops Sunday night as NATO officials
repeatedly accused Serb forces of large-scale atrocities against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. Even as the United States and Great
Britain committed additional aircraft to the allied force, NATO's
secretary general, Javier Solana, said their mission was shifting
from neutralizing air defenses to ``stop the humanitarian
catastrophe which is taking place on the ground.'' By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING (Washington) _ Developments on
atrocities in Kosovo, described by officials as ``wholesale ethnic
cleansing'' and the worst humanitarian tragedy in Europe since
World War II. By the time NATO gets around to stopping the ethnic
cleansing, will Kosovo be empty, with Milosevic having achieved his
goal? By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana, Albania) _ Their Kosovo villages in
flames behind them, tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians are being
hounded by Serb forces into Albania in long lines of battered cars,
tractors and on foot, threatening to overwhelm the scant resources
of this desperately poor country and the hasty efforts of Western
aid workers. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Defiant as ever and
proud of his nation's resistance to NATO's air attacks, Slobodan
Milosevic staged an eerie celebration Sunday _ a rock concert in
the center of Belgrade to mark the 10th anniversary of the
death-filled days when he stripped autonomy from Kosovo. By Steve
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE (Washington) _ Shortly after 2:45 p.m.
Saturday, a secret search-and-rescue team based with American
forces in Bosnia received an urgent phone call: An F-117 stealth
fighter, the premier attack plane in America's arsenal, was down in
Yugoslavia. The fate of the pilot was unknown. Within minutes, a
recovery mission was underway, tapping the talents of an elite,
highly trained special operations unit poised to pluck downed
pilots from storming seas or enemy-infested territory. By Eric
Schmitt and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ What the president did and said
Sunday. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Washington) _ President Clinton says Slobodan
Milosevic started the wars in Croatia, Bosnia and now Kosovo, and
the British defense secretary describes him as a ``serial ethnic
cleanser.'' So why hasn't Milosevic been indicted by the war crimes
tribunal? And why hasn't Radovan Karadzic been arrested? It would
require a change in policy and a more aggressive policy by the U.S.
By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline to be determined) _ Developments on
the ground. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Anti-NATO protesters in a stolen police
car fire machine guns at the American Embassy in Moscow in broad
daylight. They also tried to fire a couple of grenades, but the
launchers failed. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUDAPEST (Budapest, Hungary) _ Warning that NATO's
bombing of Yugoslavia had severely damaged Russia's relationship
with the United States, a Russian delegation met here Sunday with
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke before attempting to travel by
road to neighboring Yugoslavia to present a peace plan to President
Slobodan Milosevic. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-F117-BASE (Dateline TK) _ At the base from where the
stealth F-117 fly. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA (Berlin) _ How the current ``ethnic cleansing''
campaign in Kosovo compares with what happened in the early part of
the war in Bosnia. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERB-TV (Undated) _ How Serb television portrays the
news. By Anthony Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EMAIL (Undated) _ The first war where e-mail is a vital
tool for families to keep in touch. By Neil MacFarquhhar.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HOOPER (Washington) _ The first NATO missiles and bombs
were only a few hours from striking Yugoslavia when James Hooper,
once the State Department's senior dissenter on Balkan policy,
sipped his coffee a few blocks from the White House and talked of
ground troops likely to follow. It has been two years since Hooper,
the very model of an earnest Foreign Service careerist, quit the
government in frustration after 26 years of toiling at diplomacy.
He joined a handful of pioneer State Department dissenters who left
across two administrations protesting Balkan policy. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MEDIA (Undated) _ As NATO bombers pummel Yugoslavia,
President Slobodan Milosevic pummels the country's independent
press. Seeking to tighten an official near-monopoly on what Serbs
are told about the war, Milosevic responded to the bombing by
shutting down virtually all the independent newspapers and
silencing the nation's most prominent independent radio station,
B-92. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA (Tetovo) _ Macedonia is now the only former Yugoslav
republic that has peacefully retained an ethnically-mixed society.
The war in Kosovo, waged at Macedonia's borders, is harshly testing
the country's ability to keep itself intact. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
