<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-605&AMP;ADD     03-28 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. EMBASSY IN MOSCOW IS SCENE OF GUN BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A masked gunman tried to fire a grenade launcher at the
U.S. Embassy on Sunday, igniting a gun battle that left the
building pockmarked with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   While the embassy has been the scene of angry protests over NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia in recent days, the motive for
Sunday's attack was not clear. The gunman and at least one
accomplice escaped without giving any indication of their purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-NATO protesters and Russian police officers clung to the
ground during the midafternoon shootout, which ended as the
attackers drove off in a white jeep.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle, which reportedly had been stolen from the police,
was later found riddled with bullets and abandoned in a nearby
courtyard. There were reports that three men had been detained for
questioning, but there was no indication that any of the attackers
had been captured.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations at the embassy took an ugly turn on Thursday
when beer-drinking toughs pelted the embassy with bottles and
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Many windows in the stately yellow and white structure, on
Moscow's main thoroughfare, were broken. Two Moscow policemen were
hit by flying bottles and hospitalized. But the police gave no
indication that they would take a tough stance against the
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Kommersant reported on Friday that most of the
several dozen demonstrators who were arrested soon reappeared at
the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's disorder, additional police officers were
stationed in front of the embassy and the protests became more
orderly. Still, the protesters were allowed to assemble near the
embassy, and their anti-American signs and catcalls were a staple
on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russian government's actions have been relatively
restrained _ it has even restated its support for the START-2
treaty _ official statements have been harsh. Igor Ivanov, Russia's
foreign minister, has gone so far as to suggest that NATO officials
be tried for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional tone of the debate has grown so heated that a
group of reform-minded former officials _ Yegor Gaidar, Boris
Fyodorov and Boris Nemtsov _ set off on a peace mission to
Belgrade. The trip appeared to be an effort by a group of generally
pro-Western Russians to protect their left flank. A rally on
Saturday in front of the embassy, which featured Communist leader
Gennady Zyuganov, was generally peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday also started as a relatively quiet day in Moscow, as the
city's residents took advantage of a rare sunny day to drive or
stroll along the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in an episode captured by Russia's NTV independent
television network, a white jeep suddenly stopped in front of the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Russian police were initially slow to respond, as a man wearing
a black mask and a camouflage uniform got out of the vehicle. He
raised a grenade launcher to his shoulder, aimed it at the embassy
and attempted to fire it, but failed.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian policeman told NTV that the gunman failed to cock the
weapon properly.
</P>
<P>
   After the police noticed the gunman, who was accompanied in the
jeep by at least one accomplice, several policemen opened fire.
Using a Kalashnikov automatic rifle, the gunmen fired back.
Witnesses later counted 11 bullet holes in the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The jeep drove away through the congested weekend traffic.
Witnesses said that the jeep was abandoned in a courtyard crowded
with children about a five-minute drive away. It had bullet holes
and, according to one account, traces of blood. The witnesses said
that the gunmen, still dressed in their masks and uniforms and
carrying their weapons, ran away.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inside the U.S. Embassy, Marine guards donned flak jackets,
helmets and guns. Officials and residents in the compound were
urged to stay inside and away from windows.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's attack recalled a 1995 episode in which a
rocket-propelled grenade was fired at the embassy across the same
thoroughfare, apparently in protest at NATO's bombing campaign
against the Bosnian Serbs. In that attack, the grenade struck the
embassy, destroying a copying machine but causing no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin's spokesman, Dmitry Yakushkin, said the Russian
president had ordered an investigation into Sunday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Yakushkin said the episode ``throws a shadow on Russia, which is
currently undertaking titanic efforts to solve the crisis around
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Interior Ministry said it would take steps to prevent
future attacks. It was likely that protesters would now be kept
farther from the building, but the ministry said it would not ban
demonstrations near the embassy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
