<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY MILOSEVIC HAS AVOIDED WAR CRIMES CHARGES _ SO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton in recent days has described
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia as the ``leader who
started the wars in Bosnia and Croatia,'' and a senior British
official accused him of being a ``serial ethnic cleanser.''
</P>
<P>
   But eight years after the outbreak of war in former Yugoslavia
brought fresh atrocities to Europe at the end of the 20th century,
Milosevic has not been indicted by the international war crimes
tribunal, not even secretly, according to U.S. and tribunal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. officials consider Milosevic largely responsible
for much of the warring that has ravaged the region, the Yugoslav
leader has avoided any legal accountability.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this, both U.S. and tribunal officials say, lie
with both the tribunal and with the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration made Milosevic a partner in
guaranteeing peace in Bosnia, and neither the court nor the United
States has considered the indictment of Milosevic a priority.
Consequently, they have not devoted the resources to gathering
evidence for an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said repeatedly that it has
cooperated fully with the International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia. But the tribunal does not have the expertise to
ask the right questions about intelligence information, and the
United States has not volunteered evidence that would help the
tribunal build a case against Milosevic as well as others, tribunal
and U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say that evidence that might be used to weigh an
indictment against Milosevic is to be found in the massive amounts
of intelligence that the United States gathered in the former
Yugoslavia, where just about every intelligence gathering asset has
been deployed, from sophisticated spy planes to telephone
intercepts and informants.
</P>
<P>
   But that intelligence has not been fully organized, analyzed and
presented to the tribunal, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an easy case to make,'' said Paul Williams, who was in
the State Department's legal office from 1991 to 1993 and is now
professor of international law at American University here. ``While
I was there, there was a flood of information coming in which
clearly established Milosevic's responsibility for war crimes in
Bosnia, and would have supported an indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration could hardly have taken the
initiative to build a case against Milosevic, one senior
administration official explained Sunday, after it adopted the
policy in late 1994 of working with the Serbian leader to bring
about an end to the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, the United States government, have been the largest source
of information for the tribunal, but we have never compiled
dossiers with the aim of indicting Milosevic, or any specific
individual,'' said this official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indictment of Milosevic would require a policy change by
the United States,'' he added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to officials familiar with discussions within the
administration, the prevailing argument against indicting Milosevic
has been that it is necessary to work with him in order to carry
out the Dayton accords, which established the armistice in Bosnia,
and to get a peace agreement in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it is for the tribunal to decide whether or not to
indict Milosevic, but it, too, has been reluctant to proceed
against the Serbian leader.
</P>
<P>
   It did not begin a concentrated effort to develop a case against
him until last October, according to tribunal officials. Resources
were limited, and they were devoted to developing easier cases
against lower-ranking military commanders and not wartime leaders,
several tribunal investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the tribunal's work was not a high priority with the
Clinton administration, officials said, with only junior level
officers at the State Department, Pentagon and CIA assigned to work
with it.
</P>
<P>
   The cooperation improved, but it never matched the public
position from the administration about its support for the
tribunal, said one official.
</P>
<P>
   Institutionally, there is resistance from government agencies
that have valuable information. The CIA worries about compromising
sources and methods of gathering its intelligence. The State
Department worries about protecting the confidentiality of the
diplomat's conversations and cables. At the Pentagon, the attitude
during the war in Bosnia was that there were no good guys, so it
has not devoted energy into digging up information about Serbian
war crimes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There was another way to proceed against Milosevic, and that
would have been to prosecute his subordinates and, as one U.S.
diplomat put it, ``squeeze'' them for information about their
commander.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely candidates for that role were Gen. Ratko Mladic,
who was the wartime commander of Serb forces in Bosnia, and Radovan
Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb political leader.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, who rose as proteges of Milosevic's, have been
indicted by the war crimes tribunal, for genocide and crimes
against humanity, but neither has been brought to the Hague,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Mladic has lived in Belgrade for the last three years, and the
Clinton administration chose not to pressure Milosevic to hand him
over to the tribunal, because Milosevic had become the
administration's partner in the search for peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic lives in the Serb-controlled area of Bosnia, and the
Pentagon has long opposed any operation to seize him, fearing that
some U.S. soldiers might die in the operation or be subject to
attacks afterwards. While others in the administration, notably
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Richard Holbrooke, the
negotiator on Bosnia, argued strenuously for the NATO force to
seize Karadzic, Clinton sided with the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   But one senior U.S. diplomat in the Balkans said that failing to
seize Karadzic was seen by Milosevic as another sign of the West's
lack of resolve, and gave him the sense that he could act with
impunity.
</P>
<P>
   With the bombing of Yugoslavia and the atrocities in Kosovo, the
administration's view of Milosevic has clearly changed, and some
officials say this could make his indictment more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he's indicted as a war criminal now remains to be
seen, but there are war crimes being committed on the ground right
now, and those individuals who are committing those atrocities are
going to be held accountable,'' Secretary of Defense William Cohen
said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' Cohen added, ``He's at
risk of being indicted as a war criminal at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department officials put it more bluntly: ``If we were
to turn to it now, we could have a lengthy, ringing indictment of
Milosevic in 24 hours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
