<SLUG> BC-CAR-BROTHERS-CUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE SETS OF BROTHERS ABOUND IN WINSTON CUP 
WITH CHART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Geoffrey and Brett Bodine have settled for
good will instead of bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, both successful Winston Cup drivers, grew up in
racing together, fell from grace with each other in an ugly public
feud, then repaired their wounds. All in a sport that has
flourished on generations of family ties and sibling rivalries
throughout its existence.
</P>
<P>
   The Bodine brothers, who also include Busch Grand National
driver Todd, were one of five sets of brothers to race in
yesterday's Primestar 500. Remarkably, brothers make up nearly 25
percent of the field in every Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it brothers? It's because of the exposure we were part
of as kids,'' said Brett Bodine, whose grandfather, then father,
operated a small-town track during racing's formative years in
upstate New York. ``I am thankful my family elected to go in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Winston Cup brother tandems include: Kenny and Rusty
Wallace; Corpus Christi natives Terry and Bobby Labonte; Jeff and
Ward Burton; and Darrell and Michael Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   The Bodines' luck at the Texas Motor Speedway yesterday did not
match that of the Labonte brothers. Dueling it out for much of the
race, Terry Labonte outran younger brother Bobby and Dale Jarrett
to win. Bobby finished third.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bodine crashed on lap 140 and did not finish; Brett
never contended and finished 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work together a little bit more than some guys,'' said
Terry Labonte, 42, who is seven years older than his brother Bobby.
``We actually get along, not like some other brothers in this
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Labonte's statement is more innuendo than fact, but it
reflects the rifts that can evolve when a sibling is also a
competitive opponent. Winston Cup racing demands success to retain
sponsorship and ultimately your livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Bodines infamously directed attention upon
themselves at the inaugural Brickyard 400. Late in the race,
Geoffrey passed Brett, who then nudged Geoffrey from behind and
sent him sailing out of Turn 4 and out of the race. Brett went on
to finish second.
</P>
<P>
   What occurred next set off a stinging war of words. On live
television, Geoffrey mentioned that he and his brother were not on
speaking terms and that it did not surprise him that Brett tried to
hit him. The explosive whirlwind that followed exposed a family
financial matter and a boiling sibling feud.
</P>
<P>
   News quickly spread that the Bodine brothers were enemies off
the track as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documented incident with Geoff and I, which at that time
was the biggest race in NASCAR history, was that we had on-track
problems. Unfortunately, that brought out some issues that were
private family problems. On my behalf, it was not a problem with
me. I have never taken off-track things on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at odds for some time. I'd say for more than year.''
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the uncompromising crossfire of the tabloid-style feud
was youngest brother Todd, a former Winston Cup driver who races
exclusively on the Busch circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's \Rracing\S is all we've ever done. It's all we've ever
known,'' Todd said. ``It was tough. I was in the middle and was
still friends with both; it was a strange position to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   While the pressures attached to racing can drive a wedge between
loved ones in the sport, it can also serve as a bridge to bring
brothers together.
</P>
<P>
   The Labonte and Waltrip brothers have fostered strong and
supportive relationships since both joined the Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm his biggest cheerleader,'' Michael, who finished 14th
yesterday, said of his older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip, 52, hardly knew his younger brother, now 35,
because of their age difference. In fact, the five sets of Winston
Cup brothers are separated by an average of 9.2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer now than we've ever been. We weren't close at all
when he started,'' said Darrell, who finished 25th yesterday. ``I
was in my prime at the time and trying to take care of my own
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bobby Labonte of brother Terry: ``We've always been close,
but I think \RNASCAR\S keeps us closer. A sad day for me will be
when Terry doesn't come to the racetrack, when he retires and I'm,
hopefully, still racing.''
Brother to brother Five sets of brothers race on the NASCAR Winston
Cup circuit, further extending NASCAR's claim of being a family
sport. A look at the brothers: Family/Brother, age/Car/Comment
Waltrip/Darrell, 52/No. 66 Big Kmart Ford/Three-time Winston Cup
champion / Michael, 35/No. 7 Philips Chevrolet/Winless in 400 Cup
starts
Wallace/Rusty, 42/No. 2 Miller Lite Ford/1989 Cup champion / Kenny,
35/No. 55 Square D Chevrolet/13 DNFs in 1998
Labonte/Terry, 42/No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet/Texan a two-time Cup
champ / Bobby, 34/No. 18 Interstate Batteries/Has emerged as a star
Burton/Ward, 37/No. 22 Caterpillar Pontiac/Hasn't won since 1995 /
Jeff, 31/No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford/Seven career victories
Bodine/Geoffrey, 49/No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet/Last victory in
1996 / Brett, 40/No. 11 Paychex Ford/No top-10 finishes in 1998
</P>
<P>
   Note: Mike Wallace races in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck series
and has Winston Cup experience. Todd Bodine is a regular on the
Busch Grand National circuit
nn
</P>
