<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, March 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The coastal storm which brought chilly, unsettled conditions to
the Northeast coast during the weekend will slowly move away
Monday. Clouds and patches of light rain will persist from Cape Cod
to the White Mountains. Most of Maine will be damp and cool.
Sunshine will return to the Middle Atlantic region and central
Appalachians with temperatures rising above seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Despite high pressure off the Southeast coast, clouds will
spread into the Carolinas from the lower Mississippi and Tennessee
Valleys. A large, but weakening jet stream disturbance over the
western Gulf of Mexico will produce more showers and thunderstorms
from the Texas coast to the Mississippi delta. A fast flow above
15,000 feet will carry the moisture toward the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Chillier air will rush into the Great Lakes behind a cold front.
Brisk winds from the northwest will gust over 35 miles an hour in
parts of Michigan. A few rain or snow showers are possible near
Lake Huron. High pressure building east from Nebraska will sponsor
sunny and pleasant weather across most of the plains.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds will persist in central and western Texas as winds
from the east direct gulf moisture toward the southern Rockies.
Patches of drizzle are likely on the higher ground, including
southeast New Mexico. Bright and mild weather will dominate the
central and eastern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain snow and coastal rain will be associated with a strong
cold front moving into the Northwest. Showers will reach into
northwest California, but most of the state will see sunshine and
temperatures will be more seasonable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Dry Spell Ends &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rains finally returned to south Texas this weekend. Through
late afternoon on Saturday, Corpus Christi had received only .85
inches of rain this year. Normally, this city should have had 4.46
inches after 86 days in the new year.
</P>
<P>
   A torrent came during Saturday evening with 2.07 inches falling
by daybreak Sunday. This shattered the previous record of 1.25
inches set 102 years prior. Suddenly, Corpus Christi went from a
serious drought to concern about flash flooding. The disturbance
which triggered the heavy rain will drift over the western Gulf of
Mexico perhaps bringing more rain on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
