<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7267 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSI     03-28 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFRONTING A REGIME `INTENT ON GENOCIDE'
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE,
KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA) 
(jw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The systematic ethnic-cleansing campaign against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo appeared aimed at emptying the province
of the majority of its people and was on the verge of creating the
worst humanitarian crisis in Europe since the end of World War II,
NATO and American officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, NATO officials suggested that the air assaults
against the ethnic Albanians might not be enough to stop Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic from achieving his goal as his army,
police, paramilitaries and armed civilians continued to sweep
across Kosovo in a rampage of mass executions, torching of villages
and the forced exit to neighboring countries of women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the brink of a major humanitarian disaster, the
likes of which we have not seen since the close of World War II,''
Jamie Shea, the spokesman for NATO in Brussels said Sunday morning.
The Yugoslav leader was trying to irreversibly clean Kosovo of its
ethnic Albanian inhabitants and, in the process, send them over the
borders to destabilize neighboring countries, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was in a ``race against time'' against Milosevic, Shea
added.
</P>
<P>
   Other NATO officials involved in military planning said Sunday
that constraints being imposed by NATO's civilian leaders were
limiting the air campaign hitting at the heart of Milosevic's war
machine. The NATO civilian leaders want to use ``gentleman's club
rules against a man who was practicing genocide,'' one NATO
military planner said.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian leaders had ruled out, for example, targeting the
Belgrade headquarters of Milosevic's military planners who were
orchestrating the highly organized ethnic-cleansing campaign in
Kosovo, the planner said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the prospect of Kosovo's being emptied of most of
the ethnic Albanians who make up more than 90 percent of the
province's nearly 2 million population, the NATO planner said,
``No-one can give guarantees that won't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A former U.S. Ambassador in the Balkans, Peter Galbraith, who
was the envoy in Croatia, said Sunday that the current air campaign
might eventually cripple Milosevic's ability to wage war but could
leave Kosovo ``an empty square.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is he's accelerated greatly and we don't have a
way to stop it,'' Galbraith said. ``This will not be a triumph if
we've destroyed their equipment but Kosovo is empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith said he believed that NATO ground troops might be the
only way to counter Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   To carry out his scorched-earth policy, NATO said Sunday,
Milosevic has been using volunteers of Zeljko Raznjatovic, known as
Arkan, whose paramilitary fighters, the Tigers, were among the most
brutal in the Bosnia war.
</P>
<P>
   There they drove around in jeeps, executed people with pistols
and rifles and then looted their houses. By throwing Arkan's men
into Kosovo, Milosevic was making the task of NATO much more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   NATO aircraft can eventually target the 300 or so tanks that the
Yugoslav Army is using in Kosovo but it will be almost impossible
to target Arkan's men, armed civilians or other paramilitaries, a
NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   In their public campaign to keep the support of the American
people behind the NATO air strikes, Clinton Administration
officials, including Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, talked on television Sunday
of Milosevic's stepped-up efforts at ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the lineup of American officials condemned Milosevic
as strongly as British Secretary of State for Defense George
Robertson, who spoke of the Yugoslav leader's ``murderous campaign
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said that reports from ethnic Albanian refugees who
had escaped over the borders were enough to ``convince us that we
are confronting a regime which is intent on genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters, Shea described the sweep of Milosevic's
``scorched earth policy'' against the ethnic Albanians as being
provincewide, with ``wholesales ethnic cleansing'' taking place in
five towns. He named the towns as Lekovac, Podujevo, Srbica,
Malisevo and Dakovica.
</P>
<P>
   As an illustration that Milosevic's operations were not only
confined to the central Drenica area, which is the heartland of the
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army, but encompassed the whole
province, NATO officials said that Serb forces were creating a
buffer zone about six miles wide along the Albanian border. This
was being accomplished by emptying and then burning villages along
that swath of territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, 50,000 people have been uprooted from
their homes, making a total of 500,000 ethnic Albanian refugees
since the conflict started 14 months ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The determination of Milosevic to get rid of the ethnic
Albanians was demonstrated by the actions of his border guards at
the crossing with Albania, Shea said. The nearly 10,000 refugees
who had trekked into Albania on Saturday and Sunday were stripped
of their identity documents and those with cars had their license
plates taken.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups said they were continuing to receive grave
accounts of executions of whole families and of the separation of
men from women. They stressed again Sunday that it was still very
hard to verify the accounts, including those that thousands of
ethnic Albanians were being used as human shields at Serb military
installations.
</P>
<P>
   More precise information was hard to come by, a NATO official
said, because of technical difficulties in launching the Predator,
a spy plane specially developed to track atrocities occurring on
the ground. The plane, an unmanned aircraft, is capable of
transmitting video quality material of activities on the ground as
they take place.
</P>
<P>
   The Predator will not be airborne over Kosovo for ``another day
or two,'' the NATO official said. Other imagery from satellites and
high flying unmanned aircraft was being used primarily for
targeting and bomb damage assessment.
</P>
<P>
   There were continued reports Sunday of forced expulsions by
police from the Kosovo town of Pec, with neighborhoods there still
burning. These people were heading by foot or car, with few
belongings, to Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the refugees arriving in Montenegro said Sunday that the
Serb police in Pec had spread the word that the remaining ethnic
Albanian population there would be forced on Monday to board buses,
which would take them to the Montenegro border.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said Sunday night that
15,000 ethnic Albanians had crossed into Albania in the last 24
hours and were being taken to the town of Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   There were no men in the group between the ages of 16 and 60,
and many young women were being kept behind in Kosovo, a spokesman
for the agency, Panos Moumtzis, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, Pristina, several residents calling relatives
abroad said that families were being expelled from their apartments
and collected in the city stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed clear that Milosevic was continuing to target the
ethnic Albanian intellectual elite. Alush Gashi, the dean of the
School of Medicine in Pristina was executed, according to Bajram
Gecaj, the head of the Kosovo Crisis Group in London.
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of Ibrahim Rugova, the pacifist leader of the
ethnic Albanians for the last decade and of Vetan Surroi, a
prominent newspaper publisher, remained unknown. They were presumed
to be hiding.
</P>
</TEXT>
