<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER     03-28 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYERS AND TEARS FOR PASTOR DISCIPLINED OVER GAY CEREMONY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Neb.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(jw) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The flock turned out Sunday to pray for its pastor,
the Rev. Greg Dell, who faces suspension for officiating at the
union of two gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your ministry brought me back to church,'' one woman said
during Palm Sunday services, her voice trembling, as parishioners
held hands and offered prayers. ``This is a church where I could be
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   During the services, Dell stood at an altar lighted by a single
flickering flame and made it clear that he would not abandon his
view that homosexuals, who constitute about 30 percent of his
congregation, deserve full rights and privileges in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not rest until God's family is affirmed in all its
diversity, in all its glory,'' he said. ``The church of Jesus
Christ will not be defeated.'' Someone in the pews shouted
``Amen.'' And then there was the sound of a muffled sob.
</P>
<P>
   ``God says don't forget who you are _ and whose you are,'' Dell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal parishioners of Dell, 53, turned out at the Broadway
United Methodist Church here Sunday to pray, to sing, to weep and
to raise Cain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not feeling very Methodist today,'' a middle-aged woman
said with a glower during a meeting with Dell after services this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to secede,'' said a man with a gray beard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Methodist church is telling us we're a leper colony,''
another man said angrily.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a jury of 13 Methodist ministers found Dell guilty by
a vote of 10-3 of disobeying the denomination's ``order and
discipline'' by performing a ceremony celebrating the union of two
men last year. He was suspended from his duties, effective in July.
</P>
<P>
   The jury said the suspension would be lifted if Dell signed a
pledge that he would never officiate at another such ceremony. But
he said signing such a document would run counter to his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the service, parishioners stood in a circle
around the altar, holding hands, and offered their prayers. Many of
them spoke of Dell's battle with church authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the ecclesiastical trial and of his suspension, Dell
prayed for strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear us, God, in the midst of our pain,'' he said. ``There are
going to be times when we feel lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The small brick church, situated in the heart of Chicago's gay
community on the north side of the city, was draped in a banner
fashioned by the pastor's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless Pastor Greg and Jade Dell,'' it read, referring to
the minister and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   People came here from churches throughout the Chicago area.
Supporters included at least one Methodist minister from another
church.
</P>
<P>
   On his way into the services this morning, Dell displayed a bit
of gallows humor. Noting that the pews were filled, he whispered,
``A trial really gets attendance up at church.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's conviction is the first under a 1996 United Methodist
Church rule forbidding ministers to conduct same-sex marriages. The
United Methodist Church, with 8.5 million members, is the nation's
second-largest Protestant denomination, after the Southern Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer session with his parishioners and
other supporters, Dell said he would consider leaving the United
Methodist Church for another denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, who has been a minister for nearly 30 years, receives a
yearly salary of $35,000 and a residence.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, in the only other trial to date held on the
issue, a Nebraska pastor, the Rev. Jimmy Creech, was narrowly
acquitted of disobeying church law after his lawyers argued that
the ban on officiating at gay unions was merely advisory and not
legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   The jury initially scheduled Dell's suspension to begin July 1.
But Jack Tuell, a retired bishop who acted as the judge in his
trial, agreed to delay the suspension until July 5, to allow Dell
to perform a wedding on July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the gay men at Broadway United Methodist Church said
Dell had helped them find the path back to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Samber, 48, who wore a dark business suit and a tie, said
most other churches make gay people feel unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to the innuendo, the smart remarks,'' he said,
``and it's obvious you're not part of the flock.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would probably not be attending church if it were not
for Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `We are not here to tolerate you _ we are here
to celebrate you,' '' Samber said. ``That's powerful stuff, you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Samber's partner, Darcell Windle, a retired banker, said Dell
helped people focus on the essential meaning of the gospels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed,'' said Windle, describing his feelings. ``Just
very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Heterosexual members of the church, meanwhile, said they could
not fathom why their pastor was being disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``God calls us to unity,'' said Dennis Stafford, 39, who works
in marketing for a blues nightclub. ``God's love is bigger than
race, gender or sexual preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after services ended, a parishioner called out in a
forceful but tremulous voice to Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took until my 20s before a minister could look me in the
eye without saying, `You're evil and you're going to hell.' '' the
parishioner, Arlie Sims, 37, said.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled at Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of you,'' he said, ``there are Methodist kids all over
the country _ kids who thought they were the only ones _ who now
know that they're OK and that God loves them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
