<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0329-C     03-28 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0329-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPORTS OF SERB ATROCITIES, REFUGEES SWELL AS NATO EXPANDS
BOMBING CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0329; KOSOVO-AID-0329; KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American and NATO officials, warning of genocidal
attacks against Kosovo Albanians, ordered up more air firepower
Sunday and took sharper aim at Serbian tanks and troops reportedly
waging a bloody campaign of terror that has displaced more than
500,000 ethnic Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the brink of a major humanitarian disaster in
Kosovo, the likes of which have not been seen in Europe since the
closing stages of World War II,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said
Sunday in Brussels as allied warplanes began a new phase of
low-altitude raids against Serbian forces allegedly pursuing ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced that as many as a dozen more U.S. planes,
including long-range bombers, would be added to the nearly 200
warships already participating in ``Operation: Allied Force,'' the
NATO bombing campaign to force Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to sign a peace deal ending ethnic strife in the Serbian
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton, after consulting with his foreign policy
advisers and the leaders of Great Britain, France, Germany and
Italy on Sunday, urged NATO to ``persevere'' in stopping
Milosevic's ``campaign of inhumane violence'' against the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, while leaving the White House for the presidential
retreat at Camp David, bristled at a reporter's question of whether
the bombings he initiated against Yugoslavia were driving the
atrocities in Kosovo. ``Absolutely not,'' he snapped.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the flood of ethnic Kosovars streaming
across the border into Albania and Macedonia has increased
dramatically since the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia began last week.
They estimated that more than half a million have now been
displaced since fighting began 13 months ago between ethnic
liberation forces and Serbian troops and paramilitary gangs in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a systematic campaign against the Kosovo population at
large,'' Shea said of the refugees. ``We are seeing reports of
ethnic cleansing operations going on in a number of areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Even more alarming is that the majority of these
people are women and children. What has happened to the males
between the ages of 16 and 60?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confronting a regime that is intent on genocide,''
British Defense Minister George Robertson said in London.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth day of NATO bombing was accompanied by protests and
calls for a resumption of peace talks. In Moscow, anti-NATO
protesters scattered as police and gunmen exchanged shots in front
of the U.S. embassy after attackers tried to fire a grenade
launcher at the building.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, in his Palm Sunday address, said, ``It is
never too late to meet and negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   And three liberal politicians from Russia, a country that has a
long history of ties to Serbia and whose leaders have been
outspoken in their opposition to the NATO air strikes, arrived in
Budapest for talks with U.S. Balkan envoy Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation continues in the direction it is going now,
we are confronted with a serious danger of the Cold War
re-emerging,'' former Russian Prime Minister Yegor Gaidar said
after the meeting with Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, NATO intensified its air strikes on Serb targets
Sunday, despite the loss of a F-117A Nighthawk stealth fighter jet
near Belgrade, the capital of Yugoslavia, Saturday night. The
F-117A pilot was rescued and returned unharmed to Aviano Air Force
Base in Italy, the primary staging area for air strikes against
Yugoslavian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon declined to identify the pilot. But news
photographs of the plane wreck showed the name, Ken 'Wiz'' Dwelle,
on the cockpit. Phone calls to the home of a Ken Dwelle near
Holloman Air Force Base in New Mexico, home of the lone F-117A
fighter unit, were not returned Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   In a wheat field outside of Belgrade, where the F-117A went
down, hundreds of jubilant Serbs rummaged through the wreckage of
the stealth jet Sunday, celebrating what they said was a victory
over NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Belgrade, thousands of defiant Serbs attended an
anti-NATO outdoor rock concert despite air raid sirens warning of
impending missile attacks. One of the signs at the concert read,
``Clinton: Serbia is not Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend was the 10th anniversary of Milosevic stripping
Kosovo of much of its autonomy, a primary reason for the current
conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian radio reported the Yugoslav army shot down two NATO
aircraft over Kosovo on Sunday. But there was no independent
confirmation of the claim. Serbs have made a number of claims of
downing NATO planes since the alliance started its punitive air
strikes against Yugoslavia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With tens of thousands of ethnic Kosovars fleeing Serbian
forces, Albanian officials called on NATO Sunday to send in ground
forces to stop the reported atrocities. Refugees have told of
murders, door-to-door raids by Serb gangs, looting and burning.
</P>
<P>
   But Bratislava Morina, the Serb refugee commissioner, dismissed
such accusations as propaganda. ``There is no humanitarian
catastrophe in Kosovo whatsoever,'' she said on state-run Serbian
television.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, in an appearance
on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' program Sunday, spoke of a
``bloodbath'' in Kosovo, American and NATO officials continued to
emphasize they have no plans to deploy NATO soldiers on the ground
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that sending several hundred thousand
soldiers in to occupy Serbia for the next five or 10 years is the
right way to deal with this problem,'' U.S. National Security
Adviser Samuel E. ``Sandy'' Berger said on ABC's ``This Week''
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not considering at this moment sending forces on the
ground,'' NATO Secretary General Javari Solna echoed Sunday in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But key U.S. senators left the door open to such action if the
NATO air strikes fail to force Milosevic back to the peace table or
to stem the carnage in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must win this conflict with whatever it takes,'' Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., said on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, seemed to agree that ground troops might be necessary.
``I don't know . . . of any war . . . that's been won totally by
air power.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Pat Roberts, R-Kansas, a member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee, told CNN that ``there is not any support for
(sending U.S. combat troops) in the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
