<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES SHARP, CONTINUES TREND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Right-hander Ismael Valdes gave up two runs
in seven innings. The nerve of him.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's a little harsh. But it's symbolic of how well the
Dodgers' top three starters have pitched this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who also struck out six without allowing a walk in a 3-2
win against the Atlanta Braves on Sunday, staff ace Kevin Brown and
Chan Ho Park have each flourished this spring.
</P>
<P>
   It is spring training, but the numbers are still overwhelming.
The three are 7-1 with a 1.47 ERA. Opponents are batting .211
against them and they've struck out 49 in 611/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top three guys, I don't think you can throw the ball any
better in spring training,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``Rocket (Valdes) was outstanding. He made one bad pitch. After
that he was really sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   That one pitch was a towering 425-foot homer by Chipper Jones in
the first inning. After that, Valdes was sensational, as he's been
all spring. And as the Dodgers hope he'll be when the season
begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm further ahead this spring than other springs,''
Valdes said. ``This is my first spring training that I've been
pitching well. I feel more relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said he got into form earlier in the spring because he was
active in the offseason, pitching in the Asian Games. Ditto for
Valdes, who is 3-0 with a 1.37 ERA. He pitched in his native Mexico
during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen banter: Though no one is saying so, you can just about
scratch Chris Haney's name from contention for the left-hander's
job in the bullpen. Haney hasn't pitched since March 20 and he's
not scheduled to pitch in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Haney would have been utilized as a long man out of the bullpen,
but with right-hander Dave Mlicki relegated to the bullpen because
of the overloaded starting rotation, that role appears filled.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves lefties Greg Cadaret, Pedro Borbon, Onan Masaoka and
Jeff Williams fighting for one or two spots. Borbon could be in the
process of securing one of them _ he hasn't given up a hit in his
last seven innings _ but Johnson said a decision wouldn't be made
until the team traveled west.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some pretty good tests coming up,'' Johnson said.
``When we go and play Anaheim and the Yankees twice, you have to
have good left-handed pitchers to beat those clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Todd Hundley caught for the second time
in three days, going five innings and reporting no problems.
Johnson said he'll catch Hundley again Tuesday and Wednesday, his
first test in back-to-back games.... Right-hander Antonio Osuna
said he may make his spring debut Tuesday. He threw on the side
Sunday and reported that his elbow felt fine. He hoped to be ready
for the season opener, but said ``I think I'll start the season on
the disabled list.'' Osuna wants to be ready in two weeks....
Right-hander Mel Rojas threw 22/3 innings in an intrasquad game.
Johnson said he wanted Rojas to work on the side so he can get more
work. ``I wanted to stretch him out, to throw the ball down,''
Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
