<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING31-COX     03-28 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Varied systems offer measure of stability control
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is probably more diversity in the methods used to
accomplish stability control than in the two technological steps
that preceded it, anti-lock brakes and traction control. Last week
I discussed the innovations that led up to it. Here is how it works
in several vehicles:
</P>
<P>
   From hands-on driving experience, I can tell you that the
performance and personalities of these systems are as varied as the
brands that carry them.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac offers StabiliTrak, which is an extension of the basic
traction control system, but it also utilizes yaw sensors to
determine which of the front brakes should have pressure applied in
order to keep the vehicle going forward. It is a basic,
non-intrusive system.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz, on the other hand, has its Electronic Stability
Program. It can sense impending loss of control at both the front
or rear of the car and momentarily apply the brake on one wheel to
restore stability. That is something even a skilled driver cannot
do.
</P>
<P>
   I found ESP to be one of the most aggressive systems. The
further the driver is in over his or her head, the more control ESP
is going to take. In typical Mercedes-Benz style, the system is
going to do everything possible to keep you from hurting yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo offers the industry's first duplicated system on its new
S80 luxury sedan. It has two yaw sensor control systems so that in
the unlikely event one fails, there is a backup.
</P>
<P>
   On a snow- and ice-covered road, I reacted faster than the
Volvo's system. When it activated, the car provided an unexpected
response. Then again, I do not consider myself a typical driver.
For a mother tending to her toddler, a salesperson talking on a
cell phone or any driver who is the least bit distracted, the
system should provide exactly what is called for.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most transparent and most driver-friendly system I
have tested is in the new Porsche Carrera 4. As a
performance-oriented driver, I hardly welcomed the installation of
a stability control system on a car like a Porsche. The idea of
some computer telling a Porsche driver how far he or she could hang
the tail out was offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But after a test drive on an autocross in pouring rain, I
quickly determined that I loved it. Sure, I could get the car
around the course with the system off, but it was more work, less
fun and slower.
</P>
<P>
   The Porsche PSM system may be the best stability control system
in the industry for two reasons: You really don't know it's helping
you out, and it comes on acceptably late in the process, allowing a
driver to believe that she or he is still in control. The fun is
not gone.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your focus and needs, there is a wealth of
technological innovation available to make your driving experience
not only safer but even more pleasurable.
</P>
<P>
   However, as exciting as the new technologies are, none of them
gives license to drive with utter abandon. They cannot overcome
basic laws of physics. They are designed to help a driver who is
putting forth the best effort and using reasonable judgment from
becoming involved in a perilous situation.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp's column is written exclusively for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Write her in care of Wheels, The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
