<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-DRIVE31-COX     03-28 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BMW M Coupe speedy and sporty, but it's pricey
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best way to approach BMW's new M Coupe is with your eyes
shut and your bank account open.
</P>
<P>
   Get a salesperson or the owner of such a car to seat you behind
the compact leather-wrapped steering wheel of an M Coupe that's
pointed toward an open road or, better yet, a road course. It will
sell itself via its major attribute _ true sports-car performance _
before you realize the little speedster is plug-ugly.
</P>
<P>
   It's pricey, too. The upside is that the base price of $41,800
includes so many features that the only options are a power-tilt
moonroof for $300 and an in-dash CD player for $200.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid crowded malls and jammed-up traffic, though. The M Coupe
is so different from anything else BMW has built in recent years
and still so new that it's got an astronomical quotient for
inviting questions and thumbs-up gestures. It's not a car for those
times when you want to be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's a car built for comfort, speed and agility. It'll
sprint with a Corvette (zero to 60 mph in 5.1 seconds) and stop
like a Georgia snow shower (60 mph to zero in 121 feet). Its
handling abilities challenge those of sports cars costing twice as
much.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Z3 line of fun cars built at Spartanburg, S.C., the
M Coupe gets its drivetrain from the BMW 3-Series machines given
the ``M'' designation after being tweaked by the German automakers'
Motorsports division. That means a quick-revving 3.2-liter engine
that delivers 240 horsepower at 6,000 rpm _ it will pull to about
6,800 rpm _ and 236 pounds-feet of torque at a utilitarian 3,800
rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Given that kind of grunt, the M Coupe is seldom caught with its
acceleration ability on the flat side. The five-speed manual _ no
automatic is offered _ shifts satisfyingly. The clutch can be testy
on start-ups, but that shouldn't be an ongoing problem for drivers
drawn to this type of car.
</P>
<P>
   The interior can startle the senses, because the two-tone
leather is keyed to the exterior colors, which include the test M
Coupe's bright Evergreen, Imola Red, Estoril Blue and Kylami
Orange. The headroom is better (37.8 inches) than the height (50.4
inches) suggests, and the interior is nicely cozy for two
medium-size adults. Because the M Coupe doesn't haverear seats, it
does have 14 cubic feet of cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a lot of looking and/or miles to fault the interior
design, and even then about all there is to criticize are drink
holders located too far back between the seats to be convenient and
some gauges low on the center of the dash. Otherwise, it's a nicely
laid-out cockpit with most everything easily located and operated.
</P>
<P>
   The ride will seem harsh to anyone accustomed to luxury-car
softness because of the sports-tuned suspension, but the enjoyment
of driving and riding in the radical-look M Coupe offers a quick
cure for that _ and for the desire to find a two-seat coupe with
performance and luxury in equally high measures.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 BMW rear-drive M Coupe
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $42,670 (base: $41,800)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front and side air bags, anti-lock disc
brakes, switchable traction control system
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 3.2-liter six-cylinder engine with 24 valves (240
horsepower), five-speed manual transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: power tilt moonroof, $300
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 19 mpg premium unleaded city, 26 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
