<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC31-COX     03-28 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electrical system could be draining battery
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:This thing about batteries is as clear as mud, I mean red
Georgia clay! 12.66 volts? Amperes? Cranking amps? Reserve
capacity? This is what I understand.
</P>
<P>
   A 36-month battery lasts two years. A 48-month battery lasts two
years. A 52-month battery lasts two years. Just sell me a battery
that will last five years! This whole thing is driving me nuts!
</P>
<P>
   _Bill
</P>
<P>
   A:Even I can get three years out of a battery. I think you need
to get your vehicle's electrical system diagnosed by a professional
mechanic, using proper equipment and diagnostic technique, not the
quick tester used in auto parts stores. Your driving habits could
be the culprit, but I strongly believe the problem is in the
electrical system.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I am a master mechanic with over 24 years of automobile repair
experience and have worked in the same shop since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Your latest articles about electrical system problems struck a
slight nerve with me. You pretty much stated that mechanics just
``guess'' at what's wrong when the car/truck won't start. We never
guess at what's wrong with a starting/charging system, and I was
offended to be grouped with a bunch of hacks that ``claim'' to be
mechanics. Too many times I've had to correctly repair the results
of these wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   My diagnosis has often found the root of many electrical
problems completely overlooked by these guys. For instance, three
new batteries installed by a national chain didn't cure the problem
caused by a bad cable.
</P>
<P>
   We have a large clientele of loyal, long-time customers and to
this day, not one has cast a bad vote about the service or the
quality of the work we do. So, I would like to maybe help you
understand that there are some good shops our there. ... Please
don't group all of us, good and bad, together.
</P>
<P>
   _Charles Emmons
</P>
<P>
   A: I certainly never meant to imply that all mechanics are from
the same mold. If I believed that, I would have bailed out of the
automotive profession years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Your letter actually supports what I have been preaching for the
last four years. Unfortunately, many consumers continue to
patronize the shops that promise the most and often deliver the
least.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials depict independent shops as dark dens of iniquity
where grease monkeys hang out. These boogey-man scare tactics
reinforce the stigma that has been attached to our profession, thus
fueling the public's preconceived notion of what mechanics are.
Money-saving coupons lure motorists away from independent shops
that neither can afford to nor want to offer cut-rate/cut-corners
service.
</P>
<P>
   Professional, quality mechanics all over the country have
cleaned up the mechanical messes created by these shops. To
compound the problem, we live in a state that requires no
credentials or certification of mechanics. Virtually anyone can
purchase a business license and profess to fix cars.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I support organizations like the Automotive Service
Association of Georgia, Automotive Service Excellence certification
of mechanics and the Georgia Advanced Emission Repair mechanics
certification program is to offer the consumer some viable
alternatives. I'm not promising perfection, only some aspect of
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes about autos for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
