<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7286 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0329-1S     03-28 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0329-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: corrects byline to 'Holmes' from 'Shepard'
 &HT;    U.S. PEACEKEEPERS IN BOSNIA FEEL THE RISK OF THE AIR WAR NEXT
DOOR
 &HT;    600&AMP;add.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0329.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Bratunac is roughly
equidistant between Sarajevo and Belgrade and is on the Drina
River, on the border of Bosnia and the Serb republic.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATUNAC, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ The young Bosnian Serb in a black
leather jacket had a message Sunday for the U.S. army peacekeeping
patrol moving slowly in their armored Humvees through his village.
His obscene remark cannot be restated here, but the intent can:
Yankee go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a problem before the air strikes. But now
people are very angry and upset,'' said Protaic Vojim, another
resident of Bratunac, a Bosnian Serb border village.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO warplanes pounding Serbian targets in Yugoslavia
are having an unintended consequence in nearby Bosnia. The bombing
campaign is rattling the delicate peace here and making life harder
-- and riskier -- for the NATO peacekeeping contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Some 7,000 American infantry troops are stationed in Bosnia,
among 32,000 allied peacekeepers enforcing the 1995 Dayton Accords.
</P>
<P>
   Their position next door to Serbia already has made them targets
of reprisal by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and his Serb
forces. Two Yugoslav MiG-29 jet fighters were downed by U.S.
warplanes last Friday as the Serb jets strayed into Bosnian
airspace, presumably with the intent to attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that whatever happens in Kosovo stays across
the river and does not ruin what we've achieved in
Bosnia-Herzegovina,'' said Lt. Col. Rich Totleben(CQ) American
commander at Camp Dobol, home to armor and infantry units from Fort
Hood, near Austin, Texas. Camp Dobol is one of five American bases
in the Bosnia peacekeeping zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will always maintain our right to protect ourselves,
whether it is a man on the street with a club or a MiG-29,''
Totleben said.
</P>
<P>
   In this dangerous part of the world, both the club and the MiG
pose equally troubling threats.
</P>
<P>
   At the street level in Bosnia, the side effects of the air
campaign were on display Sunday in the American sector, where
routine American patrols face increasing animosity and verbal
threats from the ethnic Serbs living in their zone.
</P>
<P>
   Since the air war began Wednesday, U.S. troops have experienced
intensifying hostility from ethnic Serbs in Bosnia, angry that the
United States is leading an air campaign against Serbs in
Yugoslavia, who live across a border only within sight of the
American sector here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 'middle-finger' factor has definitely increased since the
Kosovo operation started,'' said Capt. Scott Smith, a company
commander in the 1st Cavalry Division, referring to the gestures
greeting American patrols in ethnic Serb enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he added, ``our presence here is provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. commanders acknowledge the irony that NATO air strikes in
one part of the Balkans could disturb the long-sought peace in
another -- the Bosnian accord reached and maintained at great U.S.
expense after a brutal civil war between Bosnians, Serbs, Croats
and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   American peacekeepers patrol about one-third of Bosnia, with
daily convoys by heavily armed infantry platoons riding Humvees
through the rich farmland and bomb-shattered wreckage of the
four-year ethnic war that ended in 1995. The intent is to
demonstrate their forceful presence as a reminder to the former
combatants in the multi-sided Bosnia conflict that renewed violence
is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. commanders insist that their peacekeeping role in Bosnia
has not changed amid the air war against Serbia and that allied
defenses are strong enough to protect American troops.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.S. forces in Bosnia went on a heightened state of
alert. Troops are now under orders to wear helmets and flak jackets
at all times, and to carry fully loaded M-16s while off the base.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-edge of Serbian nationalism remains in towns like
Bratunac, Zvornik and Srebrenica, where combat and instances of
``ethnic cleansing'' by Serb forces in the civil war drove out or
killed Muslims, Bosnians and ethnic Croats.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the service-age Serbian men who helped carry out the
mass killings during the war, we're probably looking into their
faces every day in Bratunac,'' said Sgt. Archie Haynes, on
peacekeeping patrol Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the anti-Americanism has not turned violent, except for
the occasional stone thrown at a U.S. convoy, as happened Sunday.
But with the air war continuing, U.S. commanders are fighting a
perception among Bosnian Serbs that the peacekeeping force will
join the air assault and start to wage war against the Serbs in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the American peacekeepers say, the provocations come
from a small and radical minority of Serbs in their Bosnian patrol
zone. But, they add, a minority can inflict political and physical
damage should their verbal abuse evolve into acts of retribution
for the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Last last week, American soldiers described as a ``mini-riot'' a
tense stand-off between U.S. peacekeepers and a Serb mob. It ended
without violence, but some worry that a breaking point could come,
and with it an unraveling peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need compromise and peace from the United States, not
war,'' said Pavlovic Milali, 34, a Bosnian Serb in Bratunac.
``Otherwise the revenge will come from the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
