<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN     03-28 0255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESS NASTY, MORE FILLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's tough deciding what you'd like your automatic
start-up page to pop up as when you launch into the Internet. So
try this one for a while _ KFWB sports reporter Joe McDonnell has
overhauled his web site (www.la-sports.com) with a nice, clean
presentation to replace his former Big Nasty home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing a place for McDonnell's daily rants, it
includes links to just about anywhere else you'll end up going _
local teams, national sports services, 34 newspapers and 29
columnists. There's also links to his own favorite sites, which of
course include his current employer (http://www.kfwb.com).
</P>
<P>
   There's also a quick scroll of the day's scores, a chat room and
an instant poll.
</P>
<P>
   That was simple. What else do you need?
</P>
<P>
   Read the lame explanation for how Duke University came up with
Blue Devils as its nickname on the school's official athletic site
(http://www.goduke.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup '99 site (http://wwc99.fifa.com) does a
nice job covering all the countries involved and spotlighting key
players. And, of course, providing local ticket info.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants are working on an idea that will allow
season-ticket holders to sell seats they can't use via the Internet
as late as game day, according to the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Which should soon introduce a new phrase: Cyberscalping. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
