<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN     03-28 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'75 WAS END OF LINE FOR WOODEN ERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (begin ital)(followed by the ranking of the
event from the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in
Los Angeles Sports History'' in parenthesis):(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   March 29, 1975: After UCLA's 75-74 overtime NCAA semifinal
victory over Louisville, coach John Wooden announces the final
against Kentucky will be his last game. ``We were getting ready to
celebrate when the man walked in and told us,'' said Bruins star
Marques Johnson. ``The room went quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   March 29, 1985: UCLA wins its first NIT championship with a
65-62 win over Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   March 29, 1933: At Wrigley Field in Los Angeles, local underdog
Jimmy McLarin knocks out world champion Young Corbett III for the
welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   March 30, 1974: In USC's first game at Dedeaux Field, Trojans
right-hander Russ McQueen throws a no-hitter against Cal in the
first game of a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   March 30, 1966: Dodgers pitcher Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale
end their dual month-long holdout, signing a contract for $130,000
and $105,000 respectively. Koufax won 26 games in '65; Drysdale won
23. Their contract still fell short of their goal: a three-year
deal for $1.05 million. Two weeks before ending the holdout, they
signed movie contracts to prove they were serious.
</P>
<P>
   March 31, 1975: The last of UCLA coach John Wooden's NCAA
championships comes in his final game when the Bruins beat Kentucky
92-85 in San Diego. Richard Washington scores 28 points and Dave
Meyers has 24. (begin ital)(4)(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   April 1, 1930: At Wrigley Field in L.A., Chicago Cubs catcher
Leo Hartnett catches a baseball dropped out of a Goodyear blimp 800
feet up. The force of the ball breaks his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   April 1, 1950: The Pacific Coast League's Hollywood Stars shock
local baseball fans by showing up to play their opener in shorts
and rayon shirts at Gilmore Field.
</P>
<P>
   April 1, 1963: The Dodgers sell future Hall of Famer Duke Snider
to the Mets so he can end his career in New York.
</P>
<P>
   April 1, 1984: Sophomore Cheryl Miller and the senior McGee
twins, Pam and Paula, lead the USC women's basketball team to its
second straight NCAA championship, a 72-61 win over Tennessee.
(begin ital)(78)(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1930: Officials at USC refuse to play a polo match
against UCLA. The reason: The Bruins have a woman, Barbara Rand, on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1974: The Dodgers pick up 17-year-old Pedro Guerrero
from the Cleveland Indians in a deal for pitcher Bruce Ellingsen.
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1986: USC basketball star Cheryl Miller wins her third
straight Naismith Award.
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1995: UCLA captures the NCAA basketball title with an
89-78 win over Arkansas in Seattle. Senior Ed O'Bannon leads the
way with 30 points. Freshman Toby Bailey adds 26 playing for
starting point guard Tyus Edney, who missed most of the game with a
sprained wrist.
</P>
<P>
   April 4, 1971: Wilt Chamberlain establishes a Lakers franchise
playoff record by grabbing 33 rebounds in a game against the
Chicago Bulls. Three days earlier, Chamberlain had 31 rebounds
against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Friday: Former Dodgers and Angels pitcher Don Sutton
(54) and former Dodgers outfielder and coach Reggie Smith (54).
Saturday: Former Dodgers outfielder Wally Moon (69) and Clippers
center Michael Olowokandi (24). Sunday: Former Angels infielder and
manager Jim Fregosi (57). &QL;
