<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7298 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     03-28 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S GREATEST CHARACTER? HOMER SIMPSON (D'OH!) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day after the debut of Matt Groening's new animated series,
``Futurama,'' is as good a time as any to say something about his
previous one:
</P>
<P>
   Homer Simpson is the greatest television character of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'oh!'' you say. Homer is an overweight, underachieving tub of
goo who keeps his family together (barely) more in spite of his
efforts than because of them. The man is no role model; instead, he
is a pathetic, self-centered cretin.
</P>
<P>
   Well yeah, exactly. Which makes him come off a lot more like a
regular guy than Dr. Cliff Huxtable ever did.
</P>
<P>
   So forget Lucy, no matter how much you love her. Felix and Oscar
are the odd men out. Seinfeld signed off two years too late, a
shell of his former Seinself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after 10 seasons, Homer keeps plugging away. He's as
hapless, hilarious and hopelessly romantic (in his own inimitable
way) as ever.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that Homer has his shortcomings. This is a man, after
all, who once gained 61 pounds so as to become morbidly obese,
thereby qualifying as disabled and allowed to work at home.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a man who, not wanting to go to church one Sunday,
established his own religion. (Waffles and professional football
were involved, as well as an unsuccessful effort to recruit Moe:
``Sorry, Homer. Once a snake-handler, always a snake-handler.'')
</P>
<P>
   And yes, this is a man who invented the Lazy Man Reclining
Toilet Chair.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just one side of Homer, the side his critics latch on
to. Sure, he did all those things. But as ever, there is more to
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Homer got fat, but he also saved Springfield from certain
nuclear disaster (``you turned a potential Chernobyl into a mere
Three Mile Island'') because of his hard-won girth.
</P>
<P>
   He had his new religion approved, more or less, by God himself.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lazy Man Reclining Toilet Chair . . . well, no one is
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we all have our own favorite TV character, and any
such claim unleashes a wave of nostalgia. That Matt Dillon, he
walked tall, some will say. He embodied all that's right about
'Merica. Little Joe Cartright was the soul of ``Bonanza'' and the
Old West, and a handsome devil, to boot. Hawkeye Pierce spoke for
all men everywhere in the late '70s and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Please. Go back and watch some reruns before you make your
arguments. ``Gunsmoke''was a fine show, but Marshal Dillon was a
cardboard caricature of the Old West sheriff. Little Joe was just
the first (though, admittedly, the least overdone) step in Michael
Landon's maudlin progression toward angel status, which he achieved
in ``Highway to Heaven.'' Like ``MASH,'' Hawkeye started out great;
by the time the show's run mercifully ended, he was an emasculated,
sanctimonious bag of politically correct wind.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Homer, despite the occasional stab at self-improvement,
doesn't change much.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes him all the more realistic. He remains true to
himself, even if that self is less than appealing. Let's face it,
the reason Homer is the best character television has yet produced
is because, no matter whether you want to admit it, he's the most
like us.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us hasn't failed our spouses, our kids, our employers
in some way, large or small? Who hasn't taken the selfish route?
Who hasn't bought a life-size dummy and thrown it over a deadly
waterfall in front of co-workers in a ruse to get the day off and
then spent it lying in a hammock?
</P>
<P>
   Wait, forget that last one. Anyway, sure, Homer's
characteristics and foibles are exaggerated, but that's TV. (See
``ER,'' `` The Brady Bunch'' and Berle, Milton, for further
examples.) And in the end, his love for his family always wins out.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say we should emulate a guy who offers to his
son ``three little sentences that will get you through life _ No.
1: Cover for me. No. 2: Oh, good idea, boss! No. 3: It was like
that when I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Just that we should enjoy him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
