<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNLICENSED-HEALTH-CAR     03-28 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNLICENSED-HEALTH-CARE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TUSTIN: their kids.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So they go to places like Los Hermanos.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Selene had been sick with a cold for about 48 hours. Her
parents treated her with over-the-counter medication, but the cold
seemed to be getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   The parents did not have health insurance but they made sure
that Selene and her 4-year-old brother had a regular doctor. But by
the time Selene's father got home from his construction job on Feb.
22 at 6 p.m., the doctor's office was closed.
</P>
<P>
   Then he remembered that a friend had told them about a gift shop
in Tustin, 20 minutes from their home in Anaheim, where they could
take Selene for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a cold.
</P>
<P>
   When the family arrived at the gift shop, Shanahan said, they
asked to see the doctor and were taken into the back room. A woman
examined the child and reported that she had a fever and needed an
injection. The woman said everything would be all right.
</P>
<P>
   The charge was $37.
</P>
<P>
   When the family returned home, they realized Selene was not
getting any better, and at 8 p.m. she ``was having something like a
seizure,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents scooped her up and ran to the emergency room at
Anaheim Memorial Medical Center, across the street from their home.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors tried to revive her, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said the father told investigators that he thought the
woman in the gift shop was a doctor. He also told them that if they
had taken Selene to the emergency room in the beginning they would
have run up an expensive bill.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a cold.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as the police shut down Los Hermanos and carted
away hundreds of packages of unlicensed medication from the back
room, Shanahan said, ``all we saw was women and young children with
running noses coming to the store to see the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan said that the shop opened in 1997 and was licensed to
sell toys, greeting cards and other similar items. But hundreds of
people also went there to buy unlicensed prescription medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was very busy,'' the lieutenant said. ``Some of the
employees we talked to said they were giving dozens of shots every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the raids since last June, the authorities in Los Angeles
County have targeted gift shops, grocery stores, garages and
private homes, where unlicensed medication was being sold and
unlicensed treatment, from dentistry to prenatal care to plastic
surgery, was being offered.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have confiscated more than $2 million in
unlicensed medications, much of it brought from Mexico and Central
America in a prescription drug pipeline that federal
law-enforcement agencies are investigating. Many of the seized
drugs are banned in the United States. Some of the drugs had
expired and some had been stuffed into the wrong packages.
</P>
<P>
   And many of the drugs seized can be sold legally only with a
doctor's prescription, like Viagra, Valium and penicillin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these places are better stocked than a chain drug
store,'' said Gregory Thompson, a pharmacist with the County
Department of Health Services, who goes on many of the raids to
identify unlicensed medications.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the more than 50 people arrested, including a Russian
immigrant and, the other day, three Chinese immigrants in a store
selling herbs in Chinatown, have been charged with misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a team of Los Angeles County public health officers
and deputy sheriffs raided a weary-looking house in the middle of a
weary-looking block in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They came out of the house with several large plastic bags
filled with unlicensed medications, including the same kinds of
vials of penicillin that Selene was said to have gotten her
injection from.
</P>
<P>
   They also came out with several thousand dollars in cash. The
house was apparently a makeshift pediatric clinic doing a brisk
business.
</P>
<P>
   The word on the street is that the back-room pharmacies are
cheaper than even the licensed health clinics set up for the poor.
That is not true, Ms. Hamai said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these businesses,'' she said, ``are raising their
prices sometimes up to five times the amount they would get from a
real clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Pontanillo, 49, used to buy his diabetes medicine from a
back-room pharmacy before he started seeing a doctor at a hospital
clinic. Still, Pontanillo swears that buying the medicine in the
back room was at least half as expensive as going to a regular
clinic. He collects cardboard for recycling and after 10 to 12
hours on the streets, he might take home $35.
</P>
<P>
   If he has to stop going to the hospital clinic, he said, he will
return to the back rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have no choice,'' Pontanillo said. ``I am a poor man
and this is an expensive disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Salinas, 34, buys medicine at a Santa Ana gift shop when
he feels he has to. He makes his living painting and cleaning
apartments, and for him, dimes are like dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pontanillo, he has no health insurance, but his four
children do. He bought some flu medicine from a back room for his
wife, and she got ``very sick and now only takes medicine with a
prescription,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a regular doctor once for a bad cough, he said, and
it cost him $120, which is almost half his weekly pay.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets sick, he prays the illness will go away. When he
gets really sick, he goes to the back room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not enough clinics for all the poor people,''
Salinas said. ``That is why we go to the gift shops.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
