u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERB-TV-490&AMP;AD     03-28 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERB-TV-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIA USES TV TO ATTACK NATO POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA) 
(lb) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Serbs watching government-controlled Serbian television, the
world of the Balkans is not complex and conflicted, but crystal
clear: NATO attacked Serbia because of a longstanding criminal
conspiracy by the West. Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo are terrorists.
And Serbia, above all, will fight to the last man.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing in doubt, as the somber-suited men and women of
the Serbian evening news say repeatedly, is the eventual
``international recognition of our just cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Such, at least, is the picture that emerges from a 29-minute
excerpt from Serbian television that was broadcast on March 25,
shortly after the start of the NATO air campaign, and repeated the
same evening on C-SPAN, the U.S. cable channel, with an English
translation.
</P>
<P>
   As in any conflict, historians will have to separate truth from
propaganda, but what is clear is how completely the Serbian
government has harnessed its television network as part of daily
political life and, now, in the cause of Serbian defense.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian television reporter interviews a Serbian general and
begins his questioning with a preface: ``What are your comments on
this somewhat unexpected situation where on one side we have this
huge military power that demonstrates some weaknesses and on the
other side the Yugoslav army who has shown excellent results in
defending their country?''
</P>
<P>
   The general nods and replies that more than 450 planes and 150
missiles have been launched ``against our small country'' in the
first hours of the NATO strike. ``That means they are truly afraid
of us or they are not able to plan and carry out an operation with
forces that are proportional to the enemy forces,'' the general
said. ``Or this means they are planning to carry out a barbaric
genocide against our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian reporters attempt to pre-empt criticism that some of
their film footage may be staged. In another part of the evening
news, the Serbian news anchor reports: ``Tony Blair, British prime
minister, urged British journalists and population not to trust the
TV footage from Yugoslavia showing civilian victims and damage.
This is a new invention of Tony Blair saying even TV footage is not
to be trusted, if it comes from Serbia. Tony Blair obviously wishes
to conceal from his voters the crimes to which he is an
accessory.''
</P>
<P>
   And Serbian journalists appear to be preparing Serbs for a NATO
invasion. ``Our sources report,'' the anchor said in the same
evening news broadcast, ``that in addition to 2,400 NATO soldiers
stationed in Macedonia, 1,800 U.S. soldiers have just arrived. NATO
plans to use these forces to provoke border incidents and stage an
alleged Yugoslav attack on Macedonia, which would be used as a
pretext for sending NATO ground forces into Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO, by contrast, says it has some 10,000 soldiers in Macedonia
_ most of them European _ who are there to enter Kosovo as
peacekeepers if fighting stops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, television has been on a war
footing since the late 1980s, when the Yugoslav state created by
Marshal Tito, who died in 1980, began to fall apart and the
interethnic rivalries he had suppressed were displayed openly on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Slobodan Milosevic's rise to power might be traced to
April 1987 when television cameras caught Milosevic, then an
unknown communist bureaucrat, telling a crowd of enraged Serbs in
Kosovo being pushed back by baton-wielding police, ''No one will
dare to beat you again.''
</P>
<P>
   By July 1990, when Serbian authorities took over the
Albanian-language radio and television stations in Pristina,
capital of Kosovo, ethnic Albanians could see a dangerous future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see it all on television,'' recalled Ismer Jeku, 38,
an ethnic Albanian lawyer in Pristina who moved to New York in 1993
and returned from a visit to Kosovo last month. ``In the early
1990s, Serbian officials started talking about how we must begin to
differentiate. It did not sound harsh, but what they meant was that
Serbs were good and Albanians were evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who could afford it, and even those who
couldn't, soon started buying _ as an alternative to state-run
television _ expensive satellite dishes costing $500 or more,
equivalent to three months' salary for a working-class Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of satellite dishes now in Kosovo, tuned to
television from Albania proper, but also to American, French,
German and Italian television channels, said an ethnic Albanian who
lives in New York and would give only his first name, Hysen, for
fear of reprisals against his parents and brother in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say that we could see much satellite TV now,''
he said. But electrical brownouts are common in Pristina, he said,
so there may not be enough electricity to run the additional
equipment, and only state-run Serbian television is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching Serbian TV, the Serbs are poisoned with chauvinism,''
Hysen said. ``It is a big, big poison.''
</P>
<P>
   Mentor Sejdiu, 32, a former ethnic Albanian doctor in Kosovo and
now an elevator service man in New York, said the Internet filled
some gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We follow Serbian television to see what the latest lies are
and we turn to the Internet to find the truth,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
