<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7304 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1000(     03-28 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BELGRADE, SUPPORT FOR MILOSEVIC MOUNTS AS ANTI-U.S. SENTIMENT
RISES  
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-CLINTON,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING, KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE,
KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST, KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Defiant as ever and proud of his nation's
resistance to NATO's air attacks, Slobodan Milosevic staged an
eerie celebration Sunday: a rock concert in the center of Belgrade
to show solidarity with the soldiers facing down the allied
assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the thousands of Serbs who attended were unaware that
Sunday was also the 10th anniversary of the day when Milosevic
stripped broad autonomy from Kosovo, just after his security forces
had killed some 30 ethnic Albanian protesters in Pristina, Kosovo's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Serbian security forces continued sweeping
through Kosovo, driving tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians into
panicked flight and provoking what NATO spokesman Jamie Shea called
``the worst humanitarian crisis in Europe since World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, given strict censorship rules and the patriotic
fever of wartime, few Serbs seemed to know much about the events in
Kosovo or Western reaction to them. They poured their scorn on the
Americans, rejoicing in what Serbian television persistently called
the shooting down of an F-117A stealth jet, and rallied around
their nation _ and, by extension, its leader, Milosevic _ in a way
not seen here in years.
</P>
<P>
   The rock concert organized to celebrate the holiday known as
``the day of Serbia's statehood'' bore an ironic resemblance to
similar concerts held by anti-Milosevic demonstrators during the
mass pro-democracy demonstrations of 1996-97 in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The same bands played Sunday to some of the same people, by
their own account symbolizing the unifying effect that airstrikes
have had on the general population. ``Forget who is supporting
whom, this is no time for divisions,'' said one of the lead singers
at the rally, Dejan Cukic.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the thousands at the afternoon rally _ named ``Songs
Keep Us Alive and United'' _ wore small placards on their chests
displaying a black target. One placard referred to the downing of
the stealth aircraft, and read: ``F117 A. Sorry, we didn't know
that you are invisible.'' Another redefined NATO as ``New American
Terrorist Organization,'' while others compared President Clinton
to Hitler, whose air force bombed Belgrade in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   During much of the rally, Belgrade was under an air raid alert.
The first bombs fell Sunday at about 4 a.m., and others followed at
8 a.m., with their detonations preceeding air raid sirens. Air raid
warnings continued to howl after dark. By nightfall, however, in
contrast to Friday and Saturday night, when the city was plunged
into darkness, most of Belgrade's street lights stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic held a meeting of his Cabinet and military leaders and
issued a statement praising the army and the citizenry. The two
were linked ``by strong unity, a high patriotic conscience and
determination to endure in the just struggle against the criminal
aggressors,'' the statement said. ``Our citizens are demonstrating
high personal responsibility and a high degree of mutual
solidarity.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no reference to increasingly blunt Western charges
that Milosevic's armed forces and police are engaged in widespread
atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western reporters with no access to Kosovo were largely reduced
to interviewing the ethnic Albanian refugees pouring across its
borders, a situation reminiscent of Cambodia in the mid-1970s, when
the victorious Khmer Rouge emptied the cities and reporters had to
piece together the scale of atrocities from the refugees who
straggled into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   On Serbian state television's evening news, the Serbian minister
for refugees, Bratislava Morina, whose late husband was a Kosovo
Albanian Communist, suggested that ethnic Albanians were fleeing
NATO bombs, not the Serb military. ``If NATO wants these people to
return to their homes, it should stop this aggression
immediately,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the official Tanjug news agency did announce that NATO
planes attacked before and after sunrise, targeting the air force
base in the Belgrade suburb of Batajnica for the fourth consecutive
day. Two explosions cracked windows at Belgrade's main civilian
airport, Surcin, 15 miles from the city center. Other missiles fell
near Cacak, site of a huge military factory in central Serbia,
Tanjug said. In Kosovo, four bombs hit an army barracks outside
Prizren, the agency said. There was no report of any casualties. To
date, the Yugoslav media has talked of dozens killed in the air
raids.
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, words of general patriotism came from noted
performers like Cukic and Momcilo Bagajic, known as Bajaga, who
said: ``We should defend ourselves.'' Bagajic is known not to be a
rabid nationalist, and he has played in other parts of the former
Yugoslavia, like Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a hugely popular and moving song about the Yugoslav
civil wars, largely initiated by Milosevic, that says: ``My friends
are pearls scattered all over the world.'' Ironically, the
government is now playing the song often on state television as a
backdrop to patriotic pictures of the Yugoslav armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the Children of Bad Musicians, a popular group,
told the crowd: ``I used to play sax, but since that sex maniac
plays it, I don't touch it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Olga, a 43-year-old economist wearing a fur vest and Italian
shoes, said she never went to the air-raid shelters because she
could not bring her English setter, Loli. She is no fan of
Milosevic, she said, but war is no time for divisions. ``I was in
all the demonstrations for democracy,'' she said, ``but now I have
to be in favor of defending my homeland.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Zoran Djindjic, the leader of the Democratic
Party and an organizer of the pro-democracy demonstrations, noted
the irony. ``The bombs have marginalized any dissenters here, and
there's little we democrats can do to affect the situation,'' he
said. ``The same is also true of those democrats and moderates
among the ethnic Albanians,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has spent more on one day's bombs than it ever spent
helping the democracy movement in Yugoslavia, Djindjic said
bitterly. ``Milosevic could be far more easily eliminated through
the development of democracy here than through air strikes,'' he
said. ``Every crisis strengthens him. The only players that matter
now are Milosevic, the Kosovo Liberation Army and the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of the air strikes are ``this radicalized and
pauperized Serbia and a destabilized Montenegro,'' whose
independence under President Milo Djukanovic Washington wanted to
encourage, Djindjic said. Yugoslavia consists of Serbia and
Montenegro, and Djukanovic is a former protege of Milosevic who in
the past year has turned against the Yugoslav president. ``Now
Djukanovic is compromised by the bombs, and there is more
anti-American feeling in the entire region,'' Djindjic said.
</P>
<P>
   There are Yugoslav military and police depots and headquarters
in Montenegro, and NATO has bombed them freely, despite a statement
by Djukanovic that Montenegro would stay neutral in any fight
between NATO and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic and Djukanovic are close, and Djukanovic told him the
day the bombing began that no one in the American government ever
telephoned to explain the situation or to warn him, Djindjic said.
``Ordinary people in Montenegro will now say that Djukanovic based
his entire policy on America, but we're getting bombed just as
badly as Milosevic,'' Djindjic said. ``This will make it much more
difficult for Montenegro to secede.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening news gave an interesting hint of a Russian
initiative to solve this crisis, announcing that Russian President
Boris Yeltsin and Milosevic had exchanged letters. But the Yugoslav
ambassador to Moscow, Milosevic's brother, Borislav, said he could
not confirm that the two presidents would meet, and there was no
indication that a Russian delegation which arrived Sunday and
includes former Prime Minister Yegor Gaidar would get anywhere with
its own peace initiative. France said it was pressing Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to seek a diplomatic solution. Russia is
a traditional backer of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Yugoslav government for the first time organized a
junket for some 70 foreign journalists here _ dominated by non-NATO
countries like Japan _ to the site where the F-117A crashed, in
Budjanovci, 30 miles northwest of Belgrade. Reporters, in two
buses, were only allowed to see the remains of a wing while local
villagers danced with evident joy at this small triumph of their
hugely outgunned military.
</P>
<P>
   A young boy wearing a knitted cap bearing the logo of the
Chicago Bulls stood on the U.S. Air Force star painted on the wing,
while the assembled cameramen scrambled for angles. The boy had a
toy pistol in one hand while he tried to make the Serb victory sign
with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The evening news said that, in addition to the wartime
censorship that now applies to media, new wartime banking rules had
been established to fund the military, and that profiteering would
be punished severely. On Sunday the newspaper Glas Javnosti printed
a story about the arrest of the first ``war profiteers'' in the
city of Nis: a man and his son who owned a gas station and had been
hoarding 3,171 liters of gasoline, 5,300 liters of diesel fuel and
1,000 liters of oil. Gasoline is nearly unavailable now except on
the black market, where the price has reached almost 10 German
marks a liter, many times its price a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the back page of the newspaper, however, there was a story
about the opening of the yearly automobile show at the Belgrade
Fair, featuring a photograph of the new Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, Dragoslav Rancic, a senior contributing editor
of the weekly magazine Nin, and his editor, Stevan Niksic, were
released from police custody. They were arrested early Saturday for
offending censorship regulations with an article about Milosevic's
negotiating style. Friends said they had not been beaten by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   No Belgrade newspaper published a word about their arrest, a
sharp contrast to the solidarity local journalists displayed when
Veran Matic, the chief editor of the banned radio station B-92, was
detained for eight hours last Wednesday. But Wednesday night, the
first NATO bombs fell on Belgrade, and, as one local journalist
said bitterly, ``media solidarity is evidently another casualty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
