</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE THOUSANDS, REFUGEES FLEE TO IMPOVERISHED ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Their Kosovo villages in flames behind them,
tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians are being hounded by Serb
forces into Albania by Serbian forces, threatening to overwhelm the
scant resources of this desperately poor country and the hasty
efforts of Western aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in long lines of battered cars, on tractors and on
foot, the refugees told harrowing tales of being wrenched out of
their homes by Serbian police and paramilitary units, sometimes
robbed and even stripped of their license plates before they
crossed the mountainous border.
</P>
<P>
   The head of a European observer mission said that at least
15,000 people had crossed into Albania by Sunday evening, and
arriving refugees spoke of a column stretching back more than 10
miles, with an estimated 150,000 to 200,000 on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Even as NATO stepped up its air raids against Yugoslavia, the
forced exodus here, and similar reports of columns of refugees
headed into other areas bordering the embattled, rebellious
province of Kosovo appear to show a deliberate effort by the Serbs
to apply the tactics of ``ethnic cleansing'' they had used in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scorched-earth policy,'' said a senior Western official
here. ``We're seeing the same thing as in Bosnia, a similar sort of
scenario. The refugees are on the road again.''
</P>
<P>
   A border crossing closed by the Serbs for the past 11 months on
a main highway through the mountains between Prizren in Kosovo and
Kukes in Albania was suddenly opened about 3 p.m. Saturday with
about 2,500 people crossing before it was shut down at 10 p.m.,
Western relief officials said. It reopened at 3 a.m. Sunday,
setting off a day of chaos with streams of refugees pouring into
Kukes, a town of some 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 5 o'clock, we couldn't count the refugees,'' said Andrea
Angeli of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
``It's really dramatic up there. They are coming in at a thousand
an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the arrivals was a van that pulled into Kukes about 11:30
a.m. and disgorged about 75 people, including small children and
babies, who had been packed inside for the six-hour drive from the
village of Korish, a photographer there said. The refugees told
harrowing stories of the places they had left.
</P>
<P>
   Isuf Morina, gray-haired and neatly dressed, described how
Serbian forces had selected about 200 men from his village of
Krushe and forced them to give the three-fingered Serbian salute
before mowing them down with automatic weapons. Nuhi Mazreku, a
46-year-old schoolteacher from Manisheva, said Serbs in his village
had methodically broken all the baby carriages they could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a pleasant story,'' said Eugene O'Sullivan, head of
the European security organization's observer mission in Kukes. ``A
lot of them got a knock on the door in the morning and were told to
leave. It depended on who was doing the ethnic cleansing. Some were
given an hour or so to get their things together. Others were not
so lucky. They were just told to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a final vetting at the border, where they were
taking necklaces and rings from the ladies, and stereos and the
better cars,'' he continued. ``There is a consistency going through
these stories that, while we can't independently confirm them, it
seems impossible to be made up.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan said the final step in the exodus of the ethnic
Albanians had been the confiscation by Serbs of their passports,
identity papers and even license plates, ``so these people no
longer exist as far as they are concerned.'' Accounts from refugees
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is particularly evil,'' O'Sullivan, who has
served with international agencies in Africa and Bosnia, said by
mobile phone late Sunday. ``It's very difficult to see how this can
be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   European observers near the border could see villages in flames,
including Orahovac, a major settlement in the agricultural region
northwest of Prizren, the area that appeared to be home to most of
the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The chief representative of the rebel Kosovars here _ Ilaz
Ramajli, with an office in the diplomatic quarter of this
ramshackle capital _ said he had reports of a column of refugees
some five miles long on the way to Montenegro from Pec. Montenegro
is the last state still allied with Serbia in what is left of the
former Yugoslavia, but has been showing increasing signs of
independence from Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other refugees have streamed into Macedonia _ also
once part of Yugoslavia _ causing increased tension there,
including violent demonstrations against the American embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the refugees were women, children and old people.
European officials said they did not know whether the men of
fighting age might have slipped into the forest, joined rebel bands
or, perhaps, met a fate that one described as ``somewhat worse than
that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once the last Stalinist bastion of the Eastern bloc under the
dictator Enver Hoxha, Albania of late has slid into anarchy and is
ill-equipped to help its fleeing ethnic brethren. What little order
there was dissolved a few years back in widespread anti-government
rioting over a failed nationwide investment scheme that saw most of
the army's weapons looted, up to and including tanks. Roads have
crumbled, gangsters are the major force in what there is of the
economy and, Western officials here say, there is virtually no
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The government held an emergency meeting Sunday of a special
committee headed by Deputy Prime Minister Ilir Meta to attempt to
cope with the refugee crisis. Some 100 buses, government officials
said, would be sent up the rough roads to Kukes to bring refugees
back to the capital in hopes local families would take them in. But
a main outcome of the meeting was a call for help from foreign aid
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani called Sunday for NATO to send
ground troops into Kosovo as the only way to stop what he called
``monstrous crimes ... ethnic cleansing and depopulation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramajli, the local representative of the ``Republic of Kosovo''
_ the independent state ethnic Albanians have proclaimed in their
embattled province _ made a similar appeal in a meeting this
evening with a group of American correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how difficult it is to take this decision, especially
for President Bill Clinton, but I think this is the right time for
the U.S. to intervene on the ground,'' Ramajli said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has insisted that no ground troops will be sent to
Kosovo and that air power alone will be used to accomplish NATO's
goals _ which, at this point, appear somewhat murky.
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell, some 8,000 people gathered in Skanderberg
Square _ dominated by a fierce statue of the 15th-century warrior
king who led a failed revolt against the Ottomans _ for a rally in
support of NATO and the Kosovars. It was a rare event in which the
American flag was waved rather than burned.
</P>
<P>
   At the offices of the U.N. High Commission for Refugees, the
main agency running relief efforts, Jim Worrall, the field
coordinator, struggled to pull together tents, mattresses, beds and
the trucks to deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infrastructure here is nonexistent. A large influx is
going to create problems,'' he said. ``We'll never get enough stuff
up there. It's a day up, a day to unload, a day back. I dispatched
trucks this morning. I don't know when I'll see them again.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties were compounded, he added, because just at the
time the aid agencies were meeting to evaluate this year's needs,
American envoy Richard Holbrooke appeared to have made a peace
agreement with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was hoping for a political settlement,'' he said,
referring to talks at Rambouillet, the French chateau. ``Holbrooke
and Milosevic signed and had a beer. Rambouillet was supposed to be
like Dayton. Then it was like will they or won't they?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
