<SLUG> BC-TEN-LIPTON-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS TAKES THE SIBLING SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Their father likened it to a bullfight,
this Lipton Championships finale between his teen-age prodigies
Venus and Serena Williams, the first sisters to lock horns in a
final since Maud Watson ambushed her older sister Lilian and
hoisted the trophy at Wimbledon in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, and a world away from the genteel brand of lawn
tennis demonstrated by the Watsons in their billowing white skirts,
the Williams sisters strode onto the stadium hard court Sunday
wearing skin-tight designer outfits and matching glares.
</P>
<P>
   Both had ample reason to feel bullish about the circumstances
that complicated their first final against each other. This was one
of those thorny situations where sibling empathy, they agreed, had
to take a back seat to sibling ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, 18, had her 1998 Lipton title to defend and a
2-0 record against her little sister to uphold, and Serena, 17, had
her tour-leading 16-match undefeated streak on the line, along with
an opportunity to break into the Top 10 if she broke through the
big-sister barrier and captured this title.
</P>
<P>
   Their 1-hour-58-minute slugfest was the debut of what promises
to be a lengthy sister-to-sister rivalry whenever there's a trophy
at stake, and in the end it was Venus who kept her errors to a
minimum and her composure to a maximum and prevailed, 6-1, 4-6,
6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena always comes back and defeats people, and I didn't want
to become another victim,'' Venus Williams said. ``But in the end,
we go home, we live life. You have to remind yourself that it's a
game, and there's only one winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a second-set spell in which she let her 16th-seeded
sibling strut her stuff from the baseline, the sixth-seeded Venus
Williams, helped by the reach from her spidery 6-foot-2-inch frame
and her 117-mile-an-hour serves, gained and maintained the upper
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every time Venus plays Serena, she tries to murder
Serena; I just waved the red cape and just let them go at it,''
said Richard Williams, who determined, when the two youngest of his
five daughters were mere kindergartners, that tennis was the
likeliest vehicle to transport them from their ghetto beginnings in
Compton, Calif., to the celebrity status and six-figure paydays
they are enjoying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, 2-for-2 in title defenses in 1999, after her repeat
victories here and at Oklahoma City, collected $265,000; the
runner-up, who reached three consecutive finals and collected the
first two titles of her career during this streak, earned $132,500.
</P>
<P>
   Although Richard Williams insists that he allows no trophies
across the threshold of the family's compound in Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., he said he would have to make an exception for the
two crystal bowls that signified his daughters' history-making
encounter Sunday afternoon on the stadium court he calls ``Venus'
house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This trophy will not go in the garage,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sisters denied that the confrontation, or future
confrontations, had the power to put a damper on their familial
bond. Adversaries at crunch time, they remain best friends the rest
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that family comes first, not a game that's going to
last 10 years at the most,'' Serena Williams said. ``Why would I
want that to come between someone who has always been around,
always been a very special friend for me? I couldn't imagine that,
and I don't think she could either.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the loser made it clear that she has no sibling
inferiority complex regarding her sister. ``I'm definitely looking
forward to another final with Venus,'' Serena said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always dreamed of seeing her on the other side of the net,
and now that my game is taken to a different level, it's going to
happen more,'' added Serena, whose back-to-back titles came at
events where Venus steered clear of the same singles draw.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, the day Serena won her first career title, in Paris,
Venus was busy defending her first career title, in Oklahoma. That
day marked another historic coup for the Williams sisters, who
became the first sisters to claim separate titles on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   In a different competitive format, Venus Williams, the more
aloof and regal of the sisters, might win the pageant while her
younger, chattier sister would be a shoo-in for Miss Congeniality.
But on the tennis court, they aren't just aiming to be No. 1 and
No. 2 in the world: they envision themselves as co-No. 1's.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf, whose last three losses have been wrought by one or
another Williams sister, said the duo are destined for great
things. ``Their athleticism is incredible, they're taking risks,
they don't really have a certain weakness, and they're tall and
big,'' Graf said.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's final, neither Williams sister played the furious
level of tennis that took them to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, bothered by a tired right knee, which has
absorbed the wear and tear of reaching three tournament finals
within a five-week span, made 66 unforced errors and dropped her
serve seven times.
</P>
<P>
   After working her way back into the third set, in which Venus
had taken a 3-1 lead, and knotting things up at 4-4 by breaking her
sister with a ruthless backhand pass, Serena, who moves to 11th in
the ranking, served up nothing but errors in the ninth game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a lot of errors, eight or nine, went for too much too
soon,'' she said. ``That was really out of control there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't the same Serena like the rest of my 16
matches,'' she said, referring to her winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Given the chance to serve for the match, Venus Williams made no
mistakes. She held at love, and calmly accepted victory when her
little sister, subordinated once again, rushed a forehand that
clipped the net and caromed wide. The sisters exchanged a high-five
at the net, and as they walked toward the umpire's chair, Venus
draped a comradely arm around her sister and gently patted her
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, I was making my shots, I didn't feel any
pressure,'' said Venus, who also got the better of her sister in
the mixed doubles final last year at the French Open. ``Serena is a
great player, she takes down players left and right, so to survive
such an onslaught is just great.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner will continue to be the loser's biggest fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I teach her everything I can,'' Venus Williams said, ``do
everything I can to make Serena the best player she can be, and
that I can be. I believe in my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
