<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `GO WILLIAMS' YELLED, AND BOTH OF THEM DID
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Just when tennis fans thought they had seen
everything, there were two sisters slugging away in the final of a
major tournament, while their father sat in the stands scribbling
words with a grease pencil on a hand-held message board, for all
the world to see.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, who claims he once consulted a psychiatrist,
or maybe it was two psychiatrists, to determine the proper way to
handle two sisters in the same profession, seemed oblivious to his
intrusion into the world of his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams and Serena Williams have long since learned to
block things out _ most everybody and everything around them.
Venus, as remote as that distant planet, said about her father's
message board: ``I couldn't see the sign. My eyes aren't that
good.'' And Serena insisted she did not give much thought to the
player on the other side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time two sisters had played each other in a
major final in 115 years, which, in its own quirky way, put this
Lipton Championships final in the same category as the Baltimore
Orioles visiting Havana, only 90 miles away, straight across the
sparkling water.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Venus Williams defeated Serena Williams, 6-1,
4-6, 6-4, and Richard Williams set a record by writing seven _
count' em, seven _ messages that he strenuously displayed for the
television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Williams Show,'' was his first message.
</P>
<P>
   He said the hand-held board had to do with helping children with
AIDS, or something to that effect, but then again, this is the same
man who said the other day that he was thinking of buying
Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, we should not scoff at Richard Williams, who a few
years ago professed to have a plan to make his daughters champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you so!'' his second sign said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters are both competitive, and they can hit the fuzz
right off the yellow balls, and they also seem to love each other
very much. The father used to have it both ways by saying Venus
came first but that Serena would be better. Some think he has some
master plan. Some think he simply likes to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the other day that the psychiatrists had told him
``that it wouldn't be good to enter Venus in this tournament and
Serena in this tournament because we wanted two girls to grow up
with a bunch of love for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``And that love needed to be cultivated and developed,
and it needed time to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Every family has assigned roles, which members cannot easily
relinquish. In the Williams family, Venus is the dreamy one and
Serena is the mean one. They were supposed to practice against each
other on Saturday at the family compound north of here, but they
claimed they were giggling so much that they got nothing
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's match, Venus blasted Serena in the first set, after
which Williams showed his third message: ``Go Serena Go!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Serena started to pound back, breaking Venus twice, and the
father held up his fourth sign: ``It Couldn't Have Happened to a
Better Family.'' With the younger daughter back in the match, the
father went for a walk for nine games, smoking a cigarette, trying
to beat down a vendor for a $3 pretzel at half price.
</P>
<P>
   Serena won the second set, and the sisters were on serve, when
Williams came back, his writer's block now over. His fifth sign
said, ``Hello to My Mother-in-Law, Ora Lee Price.''
</P>
<P>
   His sixth sign said, ``Hello to My Friends in Compton,'' a
reference to the old neighborhood back in Los Angeles, which he
rarely discusses these days, but Sunday he did refer to the drugs
and the gangs and an alleged $15 million community center he is
allegedly going to build. (Can't use allegedly too often in this
case.)
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Williams had been totally tasteful and low-key, but
now he got a trifle tacky, and held up a sign that said, ``The
Williams Family Loves Fox TV.'' That was just before Serena
faltered in the last two games, and Venus closed her out.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters did not show much emotion on the court, and
Venus did not do her normal victory dance, and the sisters did not
display much emotion afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't necessarily say that our relationship is going to be
affected by tennis,'' Serena said later. ``We have a strong
background. We're Jehovah's Witnesses; we really believe that
family comes first, not a game that's going to last 10 years at the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   The father and his daughters scoffed at the suggestion that
there was something scripted about the match. Venus said people
don't understand exactly how competitive Serena is, and Serena
showed just the slightest sizzle about losing to the same opponent
three straight times.
</P>
<P>
   And when they are both on the court, they cannot see their
father's message board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
