<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES-450&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES EXTRA INNINGS FOR ORIOLES TO TOP CUBANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ The team that compiled a losing record last year
despite having the highest payroll in baseball history nearly
topped itself Sunday. Embarrassing themselves but avoiding
humiliation, the Baltimore Orioles outlasted the Cuban national
team, 3-2, in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles rallied for the winning run after the Cubans played
the gracious host and removed Jose Contreras, who allowed two hits
and struck out 10 batters in eight innings of relief.
</P>
<P>
   No judgment can be made about the relative ability of the Cuban
team on one game; over a series of games, the strength and depth of
the Orioles would surely prevail.
</P>
<P>
   But this was an interesting development for the Cubans, who can
take some sort of bragging rights away from the game, the first for
a major league team in Cuba in 40 years, as they prepare for a
return match in Baltimore on May 3 and future games with other
major league teams.
</P>
<P>
   The most interested spectator in the crowd of about 50,000 at
Estadio Latinoamericano might have been Fidel Castro, who arrived
about half an hour before the game, visited both dugouts briefly,
then went to his seat and remained there for all 11 innings. He
left the stadium without offering his views of the game publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the commissioner of baseball, sat to Castro's left
and Peter Angelos, the Orioles' owner and the prime mover behind
this game, sat to his right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was delighted when the game was tied,'' Angelos said,
``because they were behind for over half the game. It didn't appear
that they were going to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Harold Baines lashed a two-out single up the middle in
the 11th, driving home Will Clark with the tie-breaking run, and
Jesse Garcia turned a diving stop of a grounder between first and
second into the game's final out with a runner at first, Castro's
mood changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a little disappointed,'' Angelos said,
``because it appeared there in the eighth and ninth inning that
they were going to prevail. But we got the breaks and we won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles won in spite of the long and sparkling relief effort
of Contreras, normally a starting pitcher, and the poor batting
performance of Albert Belle, the Orioles' often slugging right
fielder.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans loved Belle before the game when he hit one batting
practice home run after another, and they loved him even more
during the game when he made one out after another.
</P>
<P>
   Belle batted five times and did not get the ball out of the
infield, striking out twice, grounding out, grounding into a
forceout and grounding into a double play. He ended three innings
with a total of four runners on base. Contreras retired him three
times.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen him in other games before and knew something about
him so I was ready for him,'' Contreras, a 27-year-old
right-hander, said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban pitcher, in fact, seemed to have done a whole scouting
job on the Orioles himself. He said he had seen some of their
post-season games on television and videotape and was not just
guessing out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a strategy against their best batters,'' he said. ``My
strategy was to pitch against the weak points of each batter.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was nervous, Contreras said: ``I was a little
anxious and nervous because for 40 years no American (professional)
team had played in Cuba. As the game went on, I felt more
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Urquiola, the Cuban manager, or director, as he is
called here, brought Contreras into the game after Jose Ibar, the
starter, opened the third inning by hitting Brady Anderson with a
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning Ibar threw a pitch that Orioles catcher
Charles Johnson, who played here in the 1991 Pan-American Games,
slugged for a two-run home run, the only runs the Orioles scored
until the decisive 11th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Pedro Perez, the Cuban team's pitching coach,
sat in the dugout with Ibar, going over reports he had compiled on
some of the Baltimore batters from a videotape of a game the
Orioles played against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave him a short report on what we know, but we don't know
very much,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he hoped to have Ibar pitch five or six innings, but
Urquiola had seen enough one batter into the third. Urquiola
explained later that he removed Ibar because he was not very
effective and ``his speed was not good enough, not the one he
usually has.''
</P>
<P>
   The early pitching change turned out to be brilliant. But then
Urquiola had to go and spoil his day by removing Contreras after
the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras, who had missed two and a half months of the Cuban
season with a hand injury and had last pitched 15 days ago, said he
felt good enough to stay in the game. Spoken like a true major
leaguer. But, he added, it was the manager's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little tired; he had thrown a lot of pitches,''
Urquiola said.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff, the Orioles' left fielder, said Contreras was
effective because he mixed speeds on his pitches, was able to throw
his breaking ball over when he was behind in the count and did not
throw anything right down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick singled against Contreras in the fifth inning, then
was thrown out trying to steal as Clark struck out. Anderson rapped
a leadoff double to right field with no one out in the eighth, but
Contreras struck out Bordick, walked Clark intentionally and
induced Belle to ground into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   He walked three other batters. But after he put two batters on
base with walks in the fourth he struck out Jeff Reboulet for the
third out, and he struck out Anderson in the 10th after walking
Reboulet, who then became the third out when he tried to steal
second.
</P>
<P>
   As Contreras induced Johnson to ground out as the leadoff batter
in the 10th, Castro turned to Angelos and said something. Could the
Orioles' owner have been trying to make a deal for the pitcher?
</P>
<P>
   Angelos, when asked, laughed and said: ``That would have marred
the trip. Some people said the purpose of coming here was to spirit
away Cuban baseball players. That was not our purpose.'' He paused,
then added, ``Even if he had been offered, we would have turned it
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Lazo was the pitcher chosen to replace Contreras in the
11th. ``Lazo is very good at ending the game,'' Urquiola said. Not
this time.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba scored individual runs in the seventh inning against Scott
Erickson, the Orioles' starter, and in the eighth against Arthur
Rhodes and Mike Timlin, the Orioles' closer.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Miller, the Baltimore manager, said he never thought about
the possibility of losing the game. But he certainly played to win.
He had his first team in the starting lineup except for Cal Ripken
Jr., whose father died last week, and he made only one change other
than for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted to one other bit of strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I did today,'' he said, ``was bring in my closer
to face Linares. I know very little about the club except that he's
a great ballplayer and if we get him out, we have a good chance of
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Linares came to bat in the eighth with two out and Jose
Estrada at third base after a leadoff double. Rhodes had just
retired Yobal Duenas, who led the Cuban League with a .418 batting
average this season, for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Linares, a five-time Cuban batting champion and one of the
greatest Cuban players ever, foiled Miller's plan by stroking a
single to left field, tying the score.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th, however, Linares batted with runners at first and
second and two out, and Mike Fetters retired him on a pop-up to
shortstop. Then the Orioles scored in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes even the best player loses a game,'' Urquiola said.
``This is a great show and I feel satisfied with our role, although
I would have liked to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in losing, though, the Cubans won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
