<SLUG> BC-BBO-SELIG-CASTRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO PROVES A PERFECT HOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES, BBO-CUBA-DEFECTORS, BBO-CUBA-FANS) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ He wined and dined them, then he sat in the middle of
them at a baseball game Sunday. Fidel Castro was the perfect host.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fascinating experience,'' Commissioner Bud Selig said
Sunday. And that was before he sat next to the Cuban leader at the
game the Baltimore Orioles played against the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Castro hosted Selig, other baseball officials and assorted
owners and club officials at a four-hour dinner Saturday night. The
primary topic appeared to be baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about player development in the Dominican
Republic,'' said Sandy Alderson, an executive vice president of
Major League Baseball. ``He's very knowledgeable. He's very big on
details.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said that Castro, a pitcher in his youth, talked about
pitching and other aspects of baseball. ``He talked about his
career,'' Selig said, ``but in all honesty he didn't build himself
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Coleman, the National League president, said politics
were not discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Castro visited both dugouts before the game on Sunday. ``He told
me this was a great baseball town, '' Manager Ray Miller said. ``He
said not to worry, you're playing in front of the greatest fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
