<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-EARNHARDT-FIREMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT HONORS FALLEN FIREFIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GINGER D. RICHARDSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ As Dale Earnhardt raced around Texas Motor
Speedway in the Primestar 500 yesterday, he paid tribute to one of
three firefighters killed in an arson blaze last month.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And with each lap, 24-year-old Steven Sanders was reminded of
how much his brother loved NASCAR racing _ and Earnhardt, in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' brother, Garry, was killed Feb. 15 when the roof of the
Precious Faith Temple in Lake Worth collapsed on him and Fort Worth
firefighters Brian Collins and Phillip Dean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a huge fan,'' Sanders said of his younger brother, who
was a volunteer for the Sansom Park Fire Department. ``He used to
wear his Dale Earnhardt cap to the station every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the fire, we left it in his locker.''
</P>
<P>
   When speedway officials heard how much Garry Sanders liked
Earnhardt, they asked the driver if Steven might serve as an
honorary member of the pit row fire and rescue crew.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt said yes, and placed a decal on the passenger side
dash of his No. 3 GM Goodwrench Chevrolet that read ``In memory of
Garry Sanders,'' A similar decal, adorned with a red fire helmet,
was on the back of the car. Earnhardt finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, as he waited for the race to start, Sanders, also a
Sansom Park volunteer firefighter, said his brother would have
loved to have been at the Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he'd be so mad at me for being here,'' Sanders said. ``We
grew up watching this guy \REarnhardt\S, so I know he'd be honored
by all of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support our family has received has just been
overwhelming. This just adds to it; it's unreal.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
