<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOGUSBEANIES29-COX     03-28 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOGUSBEANIES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black market dolls not what they seem
 &HT;    By Henry Farber
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The August sun scorched the Atlanta shopping center's
pavement, and Gail Gross was feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-year-old mother of two carried a wad of $100 bills in her
purse, looking for a man she'd met only over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a fellow with a goatee waved from a Grand Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   She introduced herself. He seemed impatient, and stood
uncomfortably close as he showed her the goods on the floorboard of
his Jeep. ``He said he was afraid somebody was going to steal
them,'' she recalled later.
</P>
<P>
   Gross had never done this before. It felt uncomfortable, but she
went through with the deal. She doled out $1,475 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   And he handed her nine Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
   Or so she thought.
</P>
<P>
   This month, a judge declared the little dolls from last year's
deal to be bogus Beanies. Cuddly but counterfeit. Unfit to be Ty.
</P>
<P>
   Gross has been promised her money back from the seller, thanks
to her persistence in small-claims court _ and the fact that she
brought to the witness stand an expert in Beanie Baby counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after marketing wiz Ty Warner gave birth to the first
of his creations, Beanie Baby mania is still going strong _ so
strong that the marketplace is being flooded by knock-offs and
fakes. Gross and fellow collectors resent having to inspect their
pellet-filled playthings to make sure they're the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they have authentic-looking neck tags with the cutesy names
given each model, such as ``Bubbles'' and ``Coral'' and ``Ears.''
</P>
<P>
   But if they're not really made by Ty Inc., they're no more
valuable than, well, a bag of beans. The problem is such that
collectors can attend seminars on spotting counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   Victims say the problem has contributed to a softening of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   In the Neverland that is the Beanie Baby marketplace,
authenticity is everything. Not just any six-inch stuffed critter
will do.
</P>
<P>
   But let's back up a minute.
</P>
<P>
   How could there be a market for a few inches of cloth stuffed
with plastic? And why in the wide world of collectibles would
anybody pay $164 (Gross's average price that day) for one of them,
much less an armful?
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable thing is that Gross would have been getting a
good deal if the dolls had been real.
</P>
<P>
   The Beanie known as ``Britannia,'' a bear with a Union Jack on
his chest, was going for $400 last summer. In the parking lot last
year, Gross bought two at that price. ``Garcia,'' a tie-dyed bear
created in memory of the leader of the Grateful Dead, was selling
for $175, so she thought she was doing well when she paid $100.
</P>
<P>
   These are not store-shelf prices. Ty Inc. recommends a $5 price
tag for all Beanies. What jacks up the value is the secondary
market for pre-owned models. The company produces them in limited
editions (Ty's famous ``retirement'' system), and the intense
demand immediately makes them collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's human nature to want things that aren't readily
available,'' said Gina Greene, the self-trained Beanie detective
who testified in court that Gross's purchases were counterfeits.
``I've seen elderly people who spend their Social Security checks
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost three years, Gross bought almost every Beanie that
came out, usually paying $5 to $9 at stores. The most she has paid
for a used one was $325 for Lefty the Donkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've waited two hours in line to buy them,'' she said. But
what happened last summer almost burst her bubble.
</P>
<P>
   The day after her parking lot purchase, she took her new
additions to a weekly Beanie swap meet. Trained Beanie inspectors
there told her she'd been swindled.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell the difference, but a comparison showed that
the fake Britannia's nose stuck out too far. The eyes were a bit
big. The neck ribbon wasn't equally shiny on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   So she called back to complain to Greg Kozar, the man who'd
placed the classified ad before they met in the parking lot. His
response astounded her. He knew they were counterfeits.
</P>
<P>
   The next time she saw him, March 4, was in night court for
small-claims cases.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Richard Faber ruled that Kozar committed breach of
contract. Faber said he couldn't have ruled without Greene's expert
testimony as a Beanie detective. He doesn't know a Ty Beanie from a
teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order: Kozar must pay back $1,526, including
interest, and he gets his fake Beanies back.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Kozar has appealed to State Court, but said last
week he has ordered his lawyer to pay in full.
</P>
<P>
   Kozar, who describes himself as a free-lance salesman, was
contacted by phone page on a golf course. He denied trying to
deceive Gross, saying he told her stuffed animals were counterfeits
when she bought them. She knew she was getting a bargain and wanted
to resell them for a bundle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Absurd, Gross said. She didn't want to profit from her purchase.
She wanted to give them to her daughter for Christmas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   If she's in it for the money, why has she held onto 200 of them?
They nearly cover the wall in her 10-year-old daughter Shannan's
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Inc., a notoriously media-shy company, didn't respond to
inquiries about the counterfeiting problem. But collectors said the
company has little incentive to go after knock-offs. After all, Ty
profits only from new models. By the time bootleg producers make
copies, Ty already has ``retired'' the model, or stopped
production.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Faber's advice: ``If you're buying something that's not
valuable for its intrinsic value _ but is valuable as a collector's
item _ have an expert look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Beanie buyer, beware.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
