<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-VOSKUHL-HNS     03-28 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-VOSKUHL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Jake Voskuhl said he was determined to leave
the Lone Star State to go to college because Texas is football
country and he needed to go where basketball was king.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The decision to head north to Connecticut three years ago gave
Voskuhl almost all he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Almost, because he could have gone to the University of Texas
and gotten closer to the zenith of college basketball in his
freshman year, when the Longhorns advanced to the Sweet 16 of the
NCAA Tournament while his Huskies failed to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   The last two seasons, though, Voskuhl, who attended high school
at Strake Jesuit, has been getting closer to getting all he wants
in basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut might have been bumped from the Elite Eight by North
Carolina last season, but tonight when they take the court against
Duke, Voskuhl and his fellow Huskies can capture it all. They are
only 40 minutes of basketball away from being national champions.
</P>
<P>
   One slight problem: Duke is the overwhelming favorite to claim
the national title, and, worse yet, Voskuhl matches up with Elton
Brand, who has been capturing national player-of-the-year honors on
an almost-daily basis for the past couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl gets to live his lifelong dream, yet may suffer through
his worst nightmare at the same time. It is like hoping for rain
and then finding yourself in a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the matchup everyone's really been looking
forward to,'' Voskuhl said. ``This is the matchup the media and the
fans have wanted because we don't play each other during the year.
You guys wanted it; now you got it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Voskuhl really wanted it, he's got it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Brand, a 6-8, 260-pound sophomore who posts like a center,
rebounds like a power forward and runs the floor like a small
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl, on the other hand, is a plodding, workmanlike 6-11,
245-pound junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that with a player like him you can't really say
you're going to stop him and he's not going to do anything,''
Voskuhl said of Brand. ``You just have to try to contain him and
hope he doesn't really go off on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl stands to get a lot of help from teammates in an effort
to keep Brand from going off. According to Brand, he had better get
some help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the best thing to do would be to double-team
me,'' Brand said. ``When I see a man-to-man matchup, my eyes light
up. I feel I can either score, get fouled or find someone open. So
double-teaming me would be the best situation.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn coach Jim Calhoun was reluctant to reveal his defensive
game plan, but it will be no surprise if the Huskies send several
players at Brand to keep him in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thing is to get the ball down low to Elton, and I think
everybody knows that,'' Duke's Trajan Langdon said. ``So that is
where you have to start your defensive focus, but we have a lot of
weapons and double-teaming Elton opens up a lot of things for other
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody we have played came in thinking of stopping Elton,
but they leave Shane (Battier) open and he hits a couple of 3s, or
I'll hit one or two, and there goes that plan.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Calhoun will do the unthinkable and ask Voskuhl to
handle Brand straight up. Not likely. He says any team playing Duke
has to pick its poison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to make some decisions,'' Calhoun said. ``Are
we going to go big to double, who is it going to come from, and
where is it going to come from?''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl said he feels no added pressure in taking on a player
with Brand's credentials, but he knows the task will be a tough
one.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, the first thing Voskuhl will have to do is
avoid foul trouble, which has dogged him of late. He played only 19
minutes before fouling out against Ohio State in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Brand was in foul trouble in the Blue Devils' semifinal victory
over Michigan State as well, but in the four Tournament games prior
to the Final Four, Voskuhl had been whistled for 15 fouls to only
seven for Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl takes the lighter side in evaluating that difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's just getting calls and I'm not,'' he kidded. ``But
seriously, it's very important for me to be out there. I just have
to play smarter, really.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to play solid. I think he (Brand) has proven he
can score on anybody in the country. Just to foul him is maybe not
going to be the most intelligent thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl, who had only two points against Ohio State and has
scored nine points or fewer in 19 games, hopes to contribute on the
offensive end to combat Brand's production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to make players play both ends of the
court,'' Voskuhl said. ``If one guy all he has to do is play
offense and doesn't play very much defense _ not saying that he
doesn't _ it helps him out. It gives him more energy and gets his
team pumped up. He's kind of like the heart of their team, and when
he's playing really well, they're really on top of their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton Brand is Elton Brand; there's not a lot of players like
him. He does everything well.''
</P>
<P>
   Matchups like these are why he came to Connecticut, Voskuhl
says. It is part of his dream.
</P>
<P>
   How he fares against Brand may determine if the game becomes
part of a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks Duke is going to win,'' Voskuhl said. ``But
you can't count out the Huskies, that's all I know. I know my team;
I know everything we've been through. We get our opportunity
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, everyone dreams about something like this. You
always play something like this in your head, so now's your chance
to really do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
