<HEADER>
A7333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TPC29-COX     03-28 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TPC29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duval tops with TPC win
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ After a week when luck and looniless
ruled at the TPC of Sawgrass, in the end all made perfect sense.
The advance storyline became the story. All is right and logical
with David Duval's beautiful, bentgrass world.
</P>
<P>
   He's finally No. 1 without an argument. And, no, Duval doesn't
have a major championship yet, but now he's got the next best
thing. Something even better than his round of 59.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Duval, a Jacksonville native who camped at the
practice range bleachers at the TPC at Sawgrass since he was 12 and
collected caps scribbled with autographs, dreaming about someday
making a living inside the ropes, is running out of non-major
worlds to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech alumnus captured The Players Championship and
its $900,000 first prize Sunday, closing with a 2-over-par 73 for a
72-hole score of 3-under-par 285 that beat Scott Gump (71), who won
$540,000, by two strokes. Duval's third victory this year pushed
his earnings to $2,148,300. Not bad with the Masters still two
weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming to this for years,'' Duval said. ``And, to be
honest, I don't know if I have thought I was going to win here.
Obviously, I dreamt about it and thought about it, but I'm not
going to tell you I thought I was going to win this golf
tournament. I thought it would be a very, very difficult thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone wanted more to the scenario, David's father, Bob,
completed the historical day by capturing his first win at the
Senior PGA Tour's Emerald Coast Classic Sunday in Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as proud of me as I am of him,'' Dad Duval said in
Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   Countered David, ``I think I would win that award as who was
most proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price's 73 earned $340,000 for third at even-par 288. Fred
Couples, who after a Thursday 77 was just trying to get his aching
back through four rounds, shot a 68 _ the lowest round of the
weekend _ to tie for fourth ($220,000) with Hal Sutton (73).
</P>
<P>
   Grinning and atypically gleeful, Duval moved to No. 1 in the
rankings, passing Tiger Woods, who spent 41 weeks at the top. Had
Woods parred the 18th, instead of making bogey on a vicious slash
from the pine straw to the lake, he would have tied for sixth and
retained No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful week,'' Duval said. ``I'm very proud of
myself today how I played. . . .I'm kind of anxious to see tapes of
this. It really must have been brutal looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to rock-hard greens and nasty rough, conditions never
even approached the simple range, but Duval handled them better
than anyone else. So much for discussions about the identity of the
world's best player. Duval beat golf's strongest field _ 49 of the
top 50 players on the world rankings _ and won his 10th tournament
in the last 32 events. Nicklausian stuff, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Although the greens had been watered slightly and winds calmed
down somewhat Sunday, holding off a return to Saturday's silliness,
the final round still became a time to embrace pars and accept a
few bogeys. But while most everyone else in golf was made to look
foolish by Sawgrass' harsh set-pup, Duval kept his game together.
Even after bogeys at 14 and 15 sliced his lead over Gump to one
shot, Duval said he never questioned that he would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned at all,'' he said. ``I knew other people
were going to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Sawgrass' scary island 17th would ultimately
determine whether a guy with the same name as the county where he
gets his mail (Duval) would prevail, or the fellow they call
``Forrest'' would soil the final chapter. As it evolved, Gump's
8-iron at the 17th hit back-middle of the green and scooted off the
back into the water for an eventual double-bogey 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 137 to carry,'' Gump said. ``I would have had to step on
a 9-iron. I just choked down on (the 8-iron), really smoothed it.
Unfortunately, as soon as I hit it, I pretty much knew it was in
the water. I was trying to hit a little cut, and I killed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero, however, would make no such gaffe at the 17. Duval's
pitching wedge came to rest six feet from the cup. He sank the putt
for a birdie to return to 3-under. Equally valuable was Duval's
fluffy wedge from behind the green at the 18th to a foot to save
par, but the 17th could have ruined everything in a few seconds.
Remembering how he once saw Nick Price just walk up boldly and
strike the same shot to win in 1993, Duval put the image to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best shot I've ever seen played,'' Duval said. ``He
walked up there, grabbed his club, stood over the ball and hit it.
He never gave himself enough time to think about anything other
than hitting it up there close. That's all I tried to do was grab
the club and hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
