<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 BASKETBALL COLUMN: DUKE HAS BECOME A TEAM YOU CAN ROOT FOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Who would have guessed at the beginning
of the decade that by the end of it Duke, an elite private
university in North Carolina, would have a basketball team that
could be heralded as The People's Team? Just goes to show how time
can alter images and perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Duke began the decade by playing for the national championship
in April 1990. This was the time when the great yoke around coach
Mike Krzyzewski's neck was that he had been to the Final Four three
times without winning the title. And that night, Nevada-Las Vegas
defeated Duke by 30 points, the widest margin of any National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament championship game.
</P>
<P>
   I felt bad for the Duke players who had to suffer through a loss
like that, and I even empathized with Krzyzewski. But there was
also satisfaction that UNLV had played flawlessly, with speed and
intelligence, counteracting a contrived media representation that
put Duke as the force of light and UNLV as the force of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carrawell was 13 years old at the time. He watched the
UNLV-Duke game at home in north St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1990, I was happy they lost,'' he said. ``I hated Duke as
well. What you hated was that they were that good. You wondered how
they beat all those good teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they did was study. How could they have high GPAs and
still win?''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later Carrawell is a junior and a key part of a team
that may be one of best in college basketball history, one that
will play Connecticut Monday night for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was a little surprised they recruited a guy like me
who comes from a different background,'' Carrawell said. ``But I
jumped at the opportunity. Coach K went out and recruited me, he
came to my house, came to the inner city. He could relate.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's aura wasn't merely a matter of class, but also of
attitude. Shane Battier, Duke's sophomore forward, attended prep
school in Michigan. He didn't like Duke, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like everyone else in the country,'' Battier said. ``I
thought they were a country-club team, with stuck-up players who
thought they were too big for their britches.''
</P>
<P>
   What turned Battier around was not a recruiting visit but a
frailty. When Krzyzewski had back surgery and sat out for most of
the 1994-95 season _ Duke had a losing record that season _ Battier
looked at Duke and Krzyzewski differently. ``I guess I realized
that he was human, like you or I,'' Battier said. He took his
visit, met the coach, ``saw his passion and intensity to be the
best'' and he met some of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were cocky because they were good,'' Battier said, ``not
good because they were cocky.''
</P>
<P>
   This team doesn't have that air, but it has that edge. ``This
team doesn't have the brash arrogance of the early 1990s team,''
Battier said. ``We just have confidence every time we walk out on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the teams in the nation, Connecticut was the only one
that entered the tournament with a chance for an upset. And make no
mistake about it, a UConn victory would be an upset. Both teams
have deep benches, skilled players. Both teams wear blue.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Duke won with finesse. Pricked you with little pins
and made opponents die a hundred deaths. This 37-1 team has the
weight of an anvil and the power of a sledgehammer. This accounts
for the grass-roots popularity of the team, the presence of
Carrawell, William Avery and Elton Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski adjusts. The formula he used at the beginning of the
decade has been modified to fit trends and times. You can't win a
national championship sitting in an ivory tower; you can't win one
sitting in prison, either. There is a wide middle ground, and it
was crucial for Duke to find the Carrawells and Averys.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe a player has a tattoo, wears an earring and a cap
turned backward and talks with an edge. Walks with a swagger. All
that has nothing to do with character, with right and wrong or work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun called Krzyzewski the perfect
coach for the '90s; Krzyzewski said that he has simply adjusted.
Maybe the year off had something to do with it, maybe it was the
thought of his program slipping. Who knows? It could have been that
30-point loss in 1990. Whatever the catalyst for change, Duke is
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand things better now,'' Krzyzewski said, ``having
gone through a bunch of things.''
</P>
<P>
   As the decade comes to an end, UNLV has virtually slipped from
the national scene. Its coach at the time, Jerry Tarkanian, now at
Fresno State, is still like the bandit running from the posse; in
the last two seasons, players in his program have been tainted with
allegations of point shaving.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's foundation has never wavered, it has merely expanded.
``The fans are not fans of winning,'' Krzyzewski said, ``they're
fans of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   As Carrawell left the arena Sunday, he thought about the arc of
feelings that had him hating Duke in 1990 and loving it in 1999. He
grew up surrounded by underprivilege; now, in a classic exchange of
talent for exposure, he is surrounded by privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Duke; I didn't think I would,'' he said. ``When I go
home and come back, it's like getting away. Not that I don't love
where I come from. I just like Duke a little bit better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
