<HEADER>
A7339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-TEXAS29-CO     03-28 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-TEXAS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Terry Labonte homes in for win in Texas
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Terry Labonte couldn't have said it better
himself: Don't mess with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the native son from Corpus Christi, won the Primestar
500 with more than a little encouragement from many of the 200,000
fans at Texas Motor Speedway, including the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped by to see the Labonte boys this morning and I told
them good luck,'' Gov. George W. Bush said. ``They said they didn't
need any more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Labonte passed Dale Jarrett with 11 laps remaining
in the 334-lap race and won it under caution when Jimmy Spencer's
car hit the frontstretch wall on lap 330. The scene, Labonte said,
was ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the crowd and they were all standing up cheering (during
the final caution laps),'' Labonte said. ``All the other drivers
pulled up beside me and congratulated me. That's a good feeling.
When you don't win a lot of races like some of these other guys do,
guys will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Labonte's first victory since last fall at Richmond, 26
races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the biggest race I've ever won,'' he said. He
was at the track's groundbreaking four years ago; now he knows what
victory lane looks like.
</P>
<P>
   He got a chance to experience it by pushing his No. 5 Chevrolet
past Jarrett's No. 88 Ford late in the race, by being in front when
Spencer's crash brought out the eighth caution of the day, and by
avoiding the tire troubles that accounted for five cars going into
various walls.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was running in the top four most of the day but mounted
his big charge after Jarrett had led from laps 285-322.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get by him on the outside over there in (turn)
2,'' Labonte said of an earlier attempt to take the lead. ``I
really wasn't up to his door. I was up to his quarter-panel and I
was hoping his spotter was going to say 'There's somebody on your
outside.' I could tell he didn't see me, so I had to get out of the
gas there and try again.''
</P>
<P>
   He got the break he needed on lap 323, when Jarrett was slowed
by the lapped cars of Robert Pressley and Kenny Irwin. ``I was
wearing his tires out, I wasn't wearing (Jarrett) out,'' Labonte
said. ``The groove had come in pretty good. I was surprised to get
a run off turn four and get by him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that maybe if I could use up enough race track I
could keep Terry behind me,'' Jarrett said, ``but the lapped cars
were wanting to stay on the lead lap, I guess. As I caught one of
them in three and four, my car pushed up as I tried to get back in
the throttle and that hurt me then. Terry just got up high and got
a run to the outside and there was nothing I could do after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The tires may have as much to do with the outcome of the race as
lapped traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Contenders Jeff Gordon, Mike Skinner and Mark Martin lost
control and went into the wall, separately, apparently because of
tire trouble. Gordon ended up 43rd with bruised ribs, Skinner was
42nd and broke a shoulder. Martin, who wrecked while leading on lap
217, had his car patched up and back on the track, finishing 34th.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, which supplies the tires, blamed the track conditions
and the absence of a happy hour practice session Saturday for the
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``(This is) basically a brand new track compared to last year,''
said Phil Holmer, Goodyear's marketing manager for stock car
racing. ``Teams didn't have the critical Saturday afternoon hour
practice due to rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
