<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MIKE-SKINNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD BREAKS AT TMS CONTINUE FOR SKINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD TIJERINA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Two races at Texas Motor Speedway, two
crashes into unforgiving walls and two broken bones. Mike Skinner
must be feeling a bit snake-bitten.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who only two weeks ago was leading the NASCAR Winston
Cup points standings, continued his drop yesterday. He dropped from
fifth to ninth in the points race for the Winston Cup championship
after crashing into the Turn 1 wall on the 124th lap of the
Primestar 500 at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   All Skinner wanted was to somehow drive his battered No. 31
Lowe's Chevrolet back onto the track. But his crew could not repair
the damage, which was extensive to the front and right side of the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner never saw his car being repaired because doctors were
working on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It was an all-too-familiar sight, seeing Skinner crash into a
wall at TMS and emerge with a broken bone and a shattered car. He
bowed out of last year's race here in similar fashion, making him
one hard-luck driver, at least in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a motorcycle rider: I'm learning how to crash,'' said
Skinner, who suffered a hairline fracture in his right shoulder
blade.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the culprit was Skinner's right front tire. It blew
out, causing him to crash into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fluttered a little bit,'' Skinner said. ``I don't know what
the deal is, but I'll be all right. It's a good thing we have a
week off. We healed up before and we'll heal up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, Skinner was on top of the NASCAR world.
After two fourth-place finishes and two sixths in his first four
races, Skinner was the points leader entering last week's TranSouth
Financial 400 in Darlington, S.C. But his 32nd-place finish there
dropped him to fifth place, going into the Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, he finished 42nd. He has a week off to think about
his downward slide in the standings and to figure out what may be
wrong with his car.
</P>
<P>
   When he crashed, he was flirting with a top-10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no warning, no nothing,'' Skinner said. ``The car
was running great and then, all of a sudden, we were into the wall.
... The sad part is that I have experience with this. I think we
had a top-five car today.''
</P>
<P>
   The tire woes left crew chief Larry McReynolds, well, tired.
Skinner told his crew to attempt to fix the car's damage, but it
was too severe to get back into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've got now is a bunch of junk,'' McReynolds said.
``Just when you start thinking your tire problems are behind you,
they come back to get you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew \RJeff\S Gordon had problems earlier, and we agreed
that with this track being green, `Let's just see what we had
because the car was a little tight at the start.' But the wear
looked good and the pressure buildup wasn't that bad, and those are
all the things you look for when you blow a tire.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
