<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINALS-ADVANCE29-     03-28 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALS-ADVANCE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Place in history at stake for Duke
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ It's one thing to be playing for a
national championship. It's another to be playing for your place in
history. That's what Duke (37-1) will have on the line tonight when
it meets Connecticut (33-2) in the title game of the NCAA
Tournament at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   The adjectives to describe this Duke team have long ago been
exhausted. The Blue Devils have a 32-game winning streak, their
only loss coming to Cincinnati on Nov. 28. Only five times in 38
games has Duke failed to win by a double-digit margin.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a six-point victory against Michigan State (68-62) in
Saturday's semifinals, the Blue Devils have won their past 14 games
by an average of 26.9 points.
</P>
<P>
   If Duke wins tonight, it would set an NCAA record for most
victories in a season. Only two other teams _ Duke's team of 1986
(37-3) and UNLV in 1987 (37-2) _ have matched this team's current
win total.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Duke is the best team in the
country. No question at all,'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun said. ``They
could be one of the best teams of all-time.''
</P>
<P>
   But without a national championship to cap a truly remarkable
and dominating season, Duke could be relegated to the list of great
teams that came up short of college basketball's ultimate goal.
Among them are Houston in 1983 (31-3), Georgetown in 1985 (35-3),
UNLV in 1991 (34-1) and Kansas of 1997 (34-2). Fair or not, Duke
will go to the top of that list should it lose tonight to the
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Krzyzewski says he's not concerned about this Duke
team's place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, we have had a truly wonderful season,
one that none of us will never forget,'' said Krzyzewski, who will
be going for this third national championship. ``This has been a
wonderful team.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn, however, IS concerned about its place in history. The
Huskies, in their first national championship game ever, are the
only team other than Duke to be ranked No. 1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the opportunity of a lifetime,'' said UConn guard Richard
Hamilton. ``All season we've watched them (Duke) and wondered what
it would be like to play them. Now we get that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of playing Duke is not only overcoming its talent,
which is considerable, but also not being intimidated by its legacy
of success in this tournament. The Blue Devils are playing in their
eighth national championship game since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no fear factor in this game, said the Connecticut
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't fear anybody,'' said UConn guard Khalid El-Amin. ``We
have to guard them but they have to guard us, too. We've got some
things we can bring to the table. We feel we're very capable of
beating Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most memorable games in the NCAA Tournament are
those where teams like N.C. State (1983 over Houston) and Villanova
(1985 over Georgetown) earned a place in history as giant-killers.
UConn would dearly love to join that list. The Huskies, however,
would not consider beating Duke an upset of historical proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 33-2 so we've had a reasonably good season ourselves,''
said Calhoun, tounge in cheek. ``Duke's great but it all comes down
to 40 minutes of basketball_not what people think could or would or
should happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you want in life is an opportunity. And now we have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
