<HEADER>
A7351 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BOHLS-COLUMN29-CO     03-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BOHLS-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobby Labonte shows he's a tough racer
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bobby Labonte didn't understand what all the
fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the press, race officials and the thundering
throng of 220,000 spectators at the Texas Motor Speedway were
astonished that the Corpus Christi native even drove in the
Primestar 500 Winston Cup race. This stocky, no-nonsense Texan
thought nothing of the fact that he also remained in his bright
lime-green Interstate Batteries Pontiac for all 334 laps,
challenged for the lead all day and finished third to his
victorious brother, Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Bobby was concerned, he just went for a Sunday drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why'd you come to work today?'' he said, reversing a
reporter's question about his stamina. ``You wanted to, right? So
did I.''
</P>
<P>
   It needs to be pointed out that of the 43 drivers in this third
annual Texas event, Bobby Labonte was the only one who almost
literally had to be strapped in his car with a specially designed
brace. That's because he was also the only one who had broken his
right shoulder clavicle nine days earlier in a practice session at
Darlington Raceway in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the 34-year-old Labonte raced in that TranSouth 500
in Darlington as well, just two days after suffering the injury in
a practice session when he rammed into a wall. So you just knew
he'd be embarrassed to sit out a race in his home state after a
whole week of rest.
</P>
<P>
   To get credit for Winston Cup points, he had to start last
week's race before giving way to relief driver Matt Kenseth. But he
remained in the Joe Gibbs-owned car for 43 laps _ until the second
caution flag _because a pit stop when racing was first delayed
after lap four would have cost him a lap. Besides, Labonte wanted
to stick it out long enough to earn the five extra points for
leading a lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the toughest guy out here,'' said Butch Hylton, Labonte's
car chief. ``He has unbelievable grit and determination.''
</P>
<P>
   What else would you expect from a gung-ho character who loves
Mel Gibson movies and races a Primestar 500-record 144 mph in
vehicles that are real lethal weapons? How many folks could just
sit in traffic for 3 1/2 hours, drive 500 miles and tolerate the
kind of shooting pain Labonte felt, much less try to negotiate a
super-fast racetrack with a narrow straightaway and tough turns _
all with 42 buddies playing bumper cars behind you? How many people
could sway in a hammock that long?
</P>
<P>
   Labonte spent all week at the Carolina Panthers offices, getting
massage therapy from trainer Al Shuford, who fitted him with a
donut-shaped brace that the driver referred to as a ``big ol'
coconut shell.'' Crew chief Jimmy Makar readjusted Labonte's seat,
adjusted the support system on the right side of the car and gave
him some Alieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``All his life he's endured a lot of pain,'' Makar said. ``His
90 percent is as much as a lot of other guys' 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty laps into Sunday's race, Labonte instructed his crew to
have Kenseth dressed and ready. But as his car held up and points
rival Jeff Gordon left the race after an early crash, the
adrenaline kicked in. Not even a sore neck the final 100 laps was
going to keep Labonte from finishing.
</P>
<P>
   He's accustomed to pain. Breaking a shoulder at Darlington
wasn't even virgin territory for Labonte; he cracked his other
shoulder blade in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, the one-time Super Bowl-winning coach of the Washington
Redskins, did not minimize his driver's incredibly high pain
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I appreciate it more because I know what it's
like,'' Gibbs said. ``Bobby fed off his brother, but it was a gutsy
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   With his third-place finish, Labonte picked up his fourth
top-five finish of the season; he trails Winston Cups points leader
Jeff Burton by only two points. Not surprisingly, only three
drivers had run every lap of the first two Texas events, and the
same three _ Sunday's runner-up Dale Jarrett and the Labontes _
completed all 334 circles again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good run for Bobby,'' brother Terry said admiringly.
``He's awful tough. I've done that before, too ... but not one week
after I broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   After post-race interviews, Bobby Labonte zipped to a nearby
private airport to fly home to Trinity, N.C., where he's lived
since his sophomore year in high school. As his spokesman, Jimmy
White, said, ``A good race-car is the best medicine. But he was
whooped.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Labonte was asked just what he planned to do for two
weeks, since NASCAR does not race on Easter, he sized up the
questioner with a straight face and a crooked shoulder and said,
``Probably go skiing or snowmobiling.''
</P>
<P>
   We think he was kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
