<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CUBA29-COX     03-28 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cuba thrills to U.S. baseball
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ At 1:03 p.m. Cuba time Sunday, almost 50,000 Havana
baseball fans heard the strains of a song few of them had heard
before: The Star-Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:08, after 11 innings, Baltimore Orioles first baseman Will
Clark made the final out. Behind him, high in the right field
grandstand, a huge sign encourages fans: Support The Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But politics took a back seat to baseball Sunday. Clark made the
out, and the Orioles walked off the field 3-2 winners. Final stats:
Baltimore three runs, six hits, no errors; Cuba two runs, 10 hits,
no errors.
</P>
<P>
   No U.S. professional baseball team has played in Cuba since
March 1959, when Sandy Koufax pitched five innings for the Los
Angeles Dodgers against the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   That was then, when Fidel Castro had recently brought his
revolution out of the hills and his rebels brought their guns to
the games, when Ernest Hemingway was still throwing down daiquiris
at La Floridita Restaurant in Old Havana and the roulette wheels
still spun and George Raft was starting to think maybe Cuba wasn't
the best place to invest his money.
</P>
<P>
   And now is now. George Hamilton, in Cuba on a humanitarian
visit, closed the bar at La Floridita Saturday night. Woody
Harrelson, here for the ``people-to-people'' exchange between Cuban
and U.S. artists and musicians, dined that night at La Bodeguita,
another Hemingway haunt. Jimmy Buffett has been singing around
Havana all week. U.S rock-and-rollers have been jamming with Cuban
bands for five days. Something is happening here, but they don't
know what it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, baseball was happening. The Cuban All Stars are players
in the 16-team Cuban National League, a state-run enterprise where
players are paid around $400 a year and discouraged from leaving
the country. The season is three months long, about 90 games per
team. If socialized baseball holds a benefit for Cuban fans, it's
the price of admission to the ballpark _ five cents in U.S. money.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans love baseball. Any level place is a potential playing
field. Dusty parks host pick-up games until night falls. Streets
are stickball emporiums, pretty safe for the kids because there are
not a lot of cars in Havana and many are up on blocks.
</P>
<P>
   They play finesse baseball in Cuba _ smaller players than in the
United States, small strike zones, precision base running, defense.
Defense is very important in Cuban baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban National Team third baseman, Luis Ulacia, has an arm like
a rocket launcher. In an earlier era, Washington would have wrapped
a blockade around the island until the Cubans did something about
Ulacia's arm.
</P>
<P>
   Foul balls hit into the stands are rare. Saturday, during five
innings of championship play between Santiago and the Industriales
of Havana, not a single foul ball left the playing field. Maybe the
batters pick their opportunities with care. Maybe, like all
commodities in Cuba, baseballs are precious. The Orioles fouled
more pitches into the stands by the third inning Sunday than the
Cuban teams had in the previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   But the ball that left the park and counted for something was
former Marlins catcher Charles Johnson's second inning home run, a
390-foot shot that landed 12 rows up in left-center field _ under
another sign extolling the virtues of the revolution. That put the
Orioles up 2-0, and although the Cubans would send the game into
extra innings, both teams as well as the crowd settled into a
pleasant afternoon, free of tension on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Castro was there, in his usual seat just behind home plate. He
doffed his military cap for the U.S. national anthem but didn't put
his hat over his heart as many of the visiting Americans did with
their Panama hats and baseball caps. As the teams were introduced,
Castro joined with the fans in clapping twice after each name _
only twice, always twice. Scott Erikson, clap-clap, Brady Anderson
clap-clap, the whole park applauding as one. No single player is
accorded more than his two claps.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Americans, including more than 100 members of the
media, took in the game. More than 100 schoolchildren from the
Baltimore area were there, baseball players all of them, in Cuba as
part of the ``people-to-people'' exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Their parents crowded the sole souvenir shop in the stadium,
where plastic chessmen, dominoes, sandals and game programs were
being sold by three old women from behind a frosted glass
partition. Baseballs sold out early. By the fifth inning the
shelves at the shop _ not well stocked to start with _ were as bare
as a Moscow butcher shop.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson was there. ``I loved baseball as a kid,'' the actor
said. ``Today is a great day for the game. The weather, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   A visiting U.S. stage technician said it was all sort of like
ping-pong diplomacy in China during the early '70s. Then he thought
for a moment and said, ``But they got Tiananmen Square in 1989.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubans in attendance were there by invitation of the government
only. There were no nickel seats to be had. Col. Carlos Danil of
the Cuban Ministry of the Interior, sitting with other officials in
the third-base box seats, explained that some system had to be put
in place to assure order at the entrance gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``And please say this,'' the colonel asked. ``It has been 40
years, yes, since our peoples have played baseball together, but
our peoples have always been friends. We must be friends in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the colonel snapped to attention as the Cuban national
anthem was played, a marching song of the old socialist and now
mostly extinct sort that paid homage to tractors and plows.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd was there for baseball, not music. Music they
would find after the game, when American and Cuban musicians
performed at the Karl Marx Theater. They cheered as their team took
the field. Castro raised a fist in salute.
</P>
<P>
   When Brady Anderson led off the game for the Orioles and lifted
the first pitch into shallow right field _ an easy out _ the fans
made the place shake. But C.J.'s home run quieted the partisans for
the rest of the day. When it was over, Castro congratulated his
players _ they are government workers after all _ and left the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was not the only hero from South Florida. Murray Cook,
former manager at West Palm Beach's Municipal Stadium, was the man
who brought Havana's field up to major league standards. In 1996,
Cook started his own company, which manages the field at Roger Dean
Stadium. Major League Baseball asked him to ready the Havana grass
and infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down here last week, and all they had at the stadium
was a lawn mower and one infield rake,'' said Cook. ``No batting
practice cage, the outfield in rough shape. It looks good today.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of Havana does not look great. It's like the picture of
Dorian Gray, locked away in its Caribbean closet for 40 years,
untouched by developers, old but forever beautiful. But it's slowly
falling down. Streets are lined with rubble fallen from facades not
only untouched by developers for 40 years but untouched by
repairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Havana looks like it did when I came here as a teenager in the
'50s,'' said George Hamilton. ``But then you look again, and it's
sad. The city needs help, the people. In time, maybe there will be
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Cubans at the next table nod in agreement, but they
believe the walls have ears and won't comment on political changes.
It's not time yet, even if the Orioles and Jimmy Buffett are in
town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
