<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7354 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-TEXAS-TIRES-TEX     03-28 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-TEXAS-TIRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRE WOES PUT A HOLE IN DAY FOR THREE TOP DRIVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEN HAYWARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mark Martin was the first driver to turn a
lap at Texas Motor Speedway. And those laps helped develop a
Goodyear tire for use in the Winston Cup series at the 1.5-mile
superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's Primestar 500, however, Martin was one of the
drivers that had trouble with their tires during the race. In the
216th lap, Martin hit the wall in Turn 1 when he was running in the
top five. He said after the wreck that his right front tire went
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one of those ol' racetracks that's mean on
tires,'' Martin said shortly after he climbed out of his wrecked
car. ``I've been involved with Goodyear on developing a tire,
testing the original tire for the original track. This place is
just a tough nut.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martin was not alone in his problems with the right front
tires. Both Jeff Gordon and Mike Skinner lost right front tires and
both hit the outside retaining wall, causing the point standings to
fluctuate and raising some concerns. Gordon crew chief Ray Evernham
said he thinks Gordon's tire had a cut, while Skinner's blew out.
</P>
<P>
   There was some talk in the garage area that some teams were
running as much as 4 pounds below Goodyear's recommended tire
pressure during the race.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin's crew chief, Jimmy Fennig, said that too much
camber, or wheel alignment, in the setup of the car is what caused
Martin's problem. Saturday's rain prevented the Cup cars from the
late Happy Hour practice to work on the setups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we had too much camber in the front of the car because
without Happy Hour we could not see how much camber we had,'' said
Fennig after Martin finished 32nd and fell to sixth place in the
point standings. ``We were wearing the inside of the tire out more.
We just got to do the job of setting the front end, so we don't
lose the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Childress, Skinner's team owner, said they were
conservative with their air pressure and knew the 1.5-mile
superspeedway can wear out tires. Dale Earnhardt, who drives
Childress' other car, finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this track is a little tough on tires, and we were
very careful of what we were doing,'' Childress said. ``We weren't
very aggressive at all. \RThe tire\S just blew, and Skinner went
straight into the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Holmer, Goodyear's marketing manager for stock-car racing,
said that, as the race progressed, things began to return to normal
for the tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams didn't have the critical Saturday-afternoon hour
practice due to rain,'' Holmer said in a statement. ``Teams were
going on the best information they had for race setups. After
engineers re-verified the minimum tire-pressure recommendations
with the teams during the race, the last half of the race went in a
normal fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's tire problem came 36 laps after NASCAR threw a
mandatory caution flag to have Goodyear engineers check tire wear.
The decision to have the mandatory stop was because Saturday's
Happy Hour was rained out.
</P>
<P>
   Holmer said the tires are being sent to the tire company's
technical center in Akron, Ohio, for testing.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams that finished the race did not have trouble with
their tires, but there was concern when three of the top-five
drivers in the point standings left the race because of right-front
tire trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were telling me they were OK, and they know not to tell
me that unless it's the truth,'' second-place finisher Dale Jarrett
said. ``We weren't as low on air pressure as some of those guys
were. We knew that created a problem for a few people anyway, so we
were giving up a little bit on the longer runs by not starting out
with air pressure as low in the right front tire. That's gonna
create a problem sooner or later if you continue to do that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
