<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE DEAL CLOSE, AIDE IS OFF TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky,
flew to Beijing on Sunday after U.S. negotiators told her they were
close to a deal under which Washington could support China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barshefsky is expected to meet the Chinese prime minister,
Zhu Rongji, in Beijing on Tuesday. Next week, Zhu is to begin a
lengthy trip to the United States, and Washington is trying to make
a complex trade deal _ in which China would sweep away obstacles
that have long frustrated American businesses _ the centerpiece of
his visit. China has sought entry into the trade group for more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barshefsky said she did not expect to complete a deal during
her visit. But Washington is seeking concessions from China in a
wide range of areas, and she hopes to negotiate the most
politically sensitive problems directly with Zhu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-USAF-425&AMP;ADD-N     03-28 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-USAF-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LEADER WHO DRAWS ON LESSONS FROM HIS FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SERB-TV, KOSOVO-EMAIL) 
(lh) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gen. Michael Edward Ryan, chief of staff of the
U.S. Air Force, is adamant that he is no ``wild-eyed advocate for
air power solving every military problem.'' He freely admits that
he does not know whether the current air war over Yugoslavia will
put an end to President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign of terror
against the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can do it without ground troops,'' he said
in an interview Sunday in his sunlit Pentagon office.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Air Force commander in charge of the two-week-long
air campaign over Bosnia in 1995 that led to the Bosnia peace
accords in Dayton, Ohio, Ryan is certain of the value of an early
air campaign for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We waited for years in Bosnia, through years of atrocities,''
he said. ``I didn't think the nation could turn its back on the
atrocities in Kosovo now, particularly in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   The general is the only Air Force chief of staff to have
followed in the his father's footsteps. Gen. John D. Ryan held the
same position from 1969 to 1973. ``This is my dad's old office,''
said the 58-year-old current occupant. ``I'm even living in his old
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection goes deeper. Michael Ryan graduated from the U.S.
Air Force Academy in 1965 with his older brother, John D. Ryan, Jr.
They went on to serve in the same squadron during the Vietnam War.
They broke the rules and flew their 100th combat mission together
over Vietnam. John even married a woman he met when she was the
maid-of-honor at Michael's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1970, John died in a still unexplained air crash out of
Hamilton Air Base in California. ``He and I were really close,''
said Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   His rise in the ranks was also tied to his sense of
accountability. When the military plane carrying Commerce Secretary
Ron Brown crashed in Croatia in 1996, Ryan reprimanded 16 Air Force
officers, including two generals, ending the careers of several of
them. One year later, the Air Force chief of staff quit in protest
after Secretary of Defense William Cohen disciplined an Air Force
general over the terrorist attack of a U.S. military barracks in
Saudi Arabia. Ryan was appointed to the job.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he is drawing on lessons from Vietnam or
Bosnia in the current air campaign, Ryan quickly points out that in
today's military it is the theater commander for the region _ in
this case Gen. Wesley Clark _ who calls the shots. ``What we do is
organize, train and equip the personnel and advise,'' said Ryan.
``Then the operations are run out of the theater, and what we do
here is a lot of pacing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When he was commander of NATO's allied air forces in southern
Europe, Ryan was there, shaping the air war against the Bosnian
Serbs. That air war was a success in part, he said, because the
NATO air force was working with ground troops _ the armies of the
Bosnian Muslims and the Croatians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the major difference between that campaign and today,''
he said. ``There was a real threat on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Today there are no ground forces in Kosovo to take advantage of
the air campaign. The Kosovo Liberation Army, the ethnic Albanian
rebel group there, is barely an army, Ryan said, and ``essentially
can't go up against'' Yugoslavia's professional, disciplined force,
which has sufficient tanks and weaponry to destroy the fledgling
Albanian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. George Joulwan, the former supreme allied commander in
Europe, said he actively lobbied the administration to promote Ryan
to chief of staff because he had worked within NATO and become
accustomed to ``having to keep the alliance together.``
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can appreciate what a challenge it is to work with all
of those countries, to mount an intense bombing campaign and still
limit any damage beyond military targets,'' said Joulwan. ``Mike
did a super job of it.``
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was also the commander who oversaw the rescue of Scott
O'Grady, the Air Force captain whose F-16 was shot down over Bosnia
in 1995. That led to improvements by Ryan in the search-and-rescue
units that were used on Saturday to save a downed American pilot
who crashed in Yugoslavia. ``This last operation was done very,
very well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is also credited with improving intelligence gathering for
pilots before they take off on their combat missions, said Kenneth
Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the poster boy under Secretary William Perry for
improving the use of intelligence for war fighters,'' Bacon said.
``He set up intelligence centers where he brought together
everything we collect and then got it very quickly to the people
briefing the pilot just before the mission, updating the pilot in
the cockpit when necessary.``
</P>
<P>
   When asked where he was born, Ryan said, ``I'm from Air Force.''
He translated that, saying he was raised all over the country but
born in San Antonio, Texas, on Dec. 24, 1941. He and his wife,
Jane, are the parents of four grown children, two daughters and two
sons, none of whom has chosen a professional military career.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to prepare public sentiment in Europe and the United
States for uncertainties of the current air war is never far from
Ryan's thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be an easy operation, and it was a hard
choice for the administration,'' he said. ``Air power is what we
tried last in the Bosnian War but this time our NATO allies agreed
to try it first.``
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, among others, he abhors any attempts to assess
the Kosovo campaign. ``You can't be instantly gratified with only
five days of bombing,'' he said. ``It's got to take some time to
sink in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
