<HEADER>
A7361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-AVERY-NYT &LR;      03-28 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-AVERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERY WOULDN'T HEAR NO, EVEN FROM DUKE'S COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ When William Avery was a junior in high
school, Mike Krzyzewski told him the truth: No matter how wondrous
his basketball talent, he did not have the grades to get into Duke.
The young man walked out of the coach's office and told his mother,
Terry, that he had found the school for him.
</P>
<P>
   For his senior year, he transferred to a Virginia prep school,
Oak Hill Academy, and devoted more attention to developing
classroom acumen than a crisper crossover dribble. ``It was either
go to junior college and play basketball or learn to learn and go
to Duke,'' he said, matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   When he got to Durham as a freshman last season, Avery backslid
briefly and ran afoul of Krzyzewski's academic requirements, and
the coach left him home for the Blue Devils' opener at Army. Avery
got right with the academic program immediately and played the next
35 games in a 32-4 season.
</P>
<P>
   He never started, though he averaged 8.5 points, 2.5 assists and
19 minutes a game as a backup to a Krzyzewski favorite, Steve
Wojciechowski. So began the education of the latest in a long line
of classic hard-nosed, intelligent Duke point guards.
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday night, when the Blue Devils (37-1) face
Connecticut (33-2) in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
championship game, between the only two teams to hold the nation's
No. 1 ranking this season, Avery will be the most vital player for
either team on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski believes the Blue Devils are in good hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all our players who have had big years, William has had the
most important one,'' he said. ``He's a better player than he was a
month ago. He's getting better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Avery and Chris Carrawell have started every game for the
Blue Devils. Avery earned this distinction by responding the same
way he did after that first meeting with Krzyzewski. Avery blew up
old habits and replaced them with new, better ones and in doing so
became the undisputed floor leader of the team that has won 32
straight games.
</P>
<P>
   He is responsible for getting his friend and roommate Elton
Brand the ball down low, for hitting Trajan Langdon on the wing
after he pops from behind a pick, for triggering the Blue Devils'
man-to-man pressure as soon as the opposing guard crosses the
halfcourt line.
</P>
<P>
   He is responsible for everything but what he did best as a high
school standout in Augusta, Ga.: scoring points. That is why Brand,
a fellow sophomore, calls Avery the best student he has come across
in his short college career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has been easy for him,'' Brand said. ``He's had to
start over at everything. Last year, he'd come into the game and
look to score points. Now he knows that's not what we need from
him. It's been really something to watch him grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Avery has abandoned putting the ball in the basket. He
is the Blue Devils' third-leading scorer, averaging 15 points a
game with a 49.2 percent field goal average. He is also a deadly
3-point shooter, as Michigan State learned in the semifinals when
he sank a 23-footer to stretch the Blue Devils' lead to 57-50 in
the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But it is his team-leading 5.3 assists a game and quick hands on
defense that Duke will rely on against UConn. Krzyzewski calls the
Huskies the best offensive transition team in the country.
``William needs to be ready to cover all their perimeter players,''
said Krzyzewski, checking off Richard Hamilton, Khalid El-Amin and
Ricky Moore.
</P>
<P>
   When Avery squares up with Moore, a new chapter of a shared
history will play out. The two were teammates and state champions
at Westside High School in Augusta. Then Moore was a senior and
prolific scorer; now he is one of the most feared defenders in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In high school Avery was a budding shooter. Now he is an
important stopper on one of the best defensive teams in the nation.
In the course of this transformation, he has built himself into a
first-round National Basketball Association prospect, perhaps as
early as this spring. It is something he has thought about ever
since having the word ``Truth'' tattooed on his left biceps.
</P>
<P>
   But for now only the Huskies hold his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm interested in right now is running my team,'' he said.
``I'm important to what is going to happen. We've come a long way,
and now it's time to finish what we started. I need to make that
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
