<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST HOW PRINCELY IS DUKE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Let's say Duke wins tonight. Let's say
Duke wins big, 15 or 20 points, maybe 25. Will the Blue Devils
merit consideration as one of the greatest teams in NCAA history?
Or are they merely the best of a depleted field? They wouldn't have
beaten North Carolina three times by 55 points if Antawn Jamison
and Vince Carter had stayed in school.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Duke's credentials are worthy of the best ever. The
Blue Devils have seven McDonald's high school All-Americans, every
starter will be a lottery pick _ yes, even unheralded small forward
Chris Carrawell _ and a win tonight gives them 38 this season, an
NCAA record.
</P>
<P>
   They became the first team in Atlantic Coast Conference history
to go 16-0 and the first to have every starter named all-league.
(The ACC selects three five-man teams.)
</P>
<P>
   Their average scoring margin (25.4 points) is No. 8 in NCAA
history, less than a point behind UCLA's 1967 and 1968 teams.
</P>
<P>
   They have made 67 more free throws than their opponents have
attempted, which means they're brutally hard to guard, and
opponents have 217 more turnovers than assists, which means they
play hellacious defense.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, Duke is one of the most dominant teams ever. But
it's case for being one of the best seems thin.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination begins at home: This probably isn't coach
Mike Krzyzewski's best team. The 1986 gang won 37 before losing to
Louisville in the championship game, and the 1992 version, with
Christian Laettner, Bobby Hurley and Grant Hill, was one for the
ages _ the first post-Wooden team to win back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the '92 team was probably better than both '86 and
'99,'' said ESPN analyst Jay Bilas, Duke's starting center in 1986.
``Neither of those teams had anyone as versatile and clutch as
Laettner, who's probably the best player Duke has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one thing that's unique this year is the ACC's down. If
this team played the '92 schedule or the '86 schedule, it wouldn't
be 37-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils may not be the best team of the past three
years. Kentucky '96 was awesome. Its average victory margin in six
NCAA games was 21.5 _ Duke's is 25.4 through five games _ and it
had six first-round picks: Derek Anderson, Antoine Walker, Tony
Delk, Nazr Mohammed, Walter McCarthy and Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Match the Blue Devils against the best teams of all time (San
Francisco '56, UCLA '68, '69 and '72, and Indiana '76), and they
fall short on two counts. With a freshman, three sophomores, one
junior and one senior in the top rotation, they lack the experience
to compete with the greatest. And while 6-foot-8 sophomore Elton
Brand is the best big man in the nation today, he couldn't possibly
compete with Bill Russell, Lew Alcindor and Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from L.A. (Rolling Hills), I'm sensitive to the
comparisons with the Wooden teams,'' Bilas said. ``People say the
road was easier back then because you only played four tournament
games instead of six, but I doubt Alcindor and Walton would have
had much trouble with a No. 16 seed. UCLA pounded teams. Alcindor
was the greatest scorer of all time. I don't buy the comparison for
one second.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's straight from the mouth of a Dookie.
</P>
<P>
   It's official: Of the 13 Pac-10 referees who worked the first
weekend of the tournament, only four were deemed worthy of
advancing to the regional round: Bill Kennedy, Don McAlister,
Charlie Range and Dave Libbey, who called the Duke-Michigan State
game Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   (That's right UCLA fans, no Terry Christman.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Pac-10 wants better officials, it should find a better
coordinator of officials. Two of the best refs, Tom Harrington and
Mark Reischling, no longer work the league because of differences
with boss Booker Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: A name to consider as Pepperdine searches to
replace departed coach Lorenzo Romar: Santa Barbara's Bob Williams,
a former Pepperdine assistant who is well-respected in coaching
circles and did a great job this year with the Gauchos. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Former St. John's coach Fran Fraschilla may find his new gig at
New Mexico tougher than it looks. The lofty expectations aren't
commensurate with the in-state talent, and Albuquerque's a long way
from L.A. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Stanford will have a new offense next season in response to
better athletes and opponent scouting. Coach Mike Montgomery says
teams have figured out his system. I can think of one that hasn't.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   I had a dream Sunday night that San Diego State hired Steve
Fisher, the former Michigan coach. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Tonight probably is Brand's last game at Duke. A 6-foot-8,
260-pounder, Brand will be a top-five pick in the NBA draft with
Rhode Island's Lamar Odom, Maryland's Steve Francis, Miami-Ohio's
Wally Szczerbiak and UCLA's Baron Davis. Is this Duke sophomore
point guard William Avery's last game, as well? . . .
</P>
<P>
   In this space Saturday, I identified Brad Millard, St. Mary's
7-foot-3, 340-pound center, as Russ Millard, who played for Iowa
several years ago. Is delirium a defense for stupidity? . . .
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, Glendora native (and Stanford recruit)
Casey Jacobsen scored 23 points in the McDonald's All-American game
Wednesday. Odds are, he'll match that total a few times in Maples
Pavilion. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Looking for a player to watch tonight? Try Duke
freshman Corey Maggette, a prodigious talent who will thrive in the
speedy tempo just as Toby Bailey excelled for UCLA in 1995. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
