</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-F117-BASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 ON THE LOST STEALTH JET'S OWN GROUND, FIGHTING WORDS AND EMPATHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ETHNIC-CLEANSING,
KOSOVO-PILOT-RESCUE, KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL, KOSOVO-BUDAPEST,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-HOOPER, MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SERB-TV, KOSOVO-EMAIL, KOSOVO-USAF) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLOMAN AIR FORCE BASE, N.M. _ Half a world away from the site
in Yugoslavia where an American F-117 stealth bomber crashed, the
flier's home base commander defended the warplane Sunday as a
``premier weapon system,'' and vowed to send ``a couple dozen
more,'' if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not invulnerable, they are not invisible, they are
`low observable,''' the commander, Brig. Gen. William Lake, said at
a news conference held here against the backdrop of a desert mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Rain was not a factor in the crash, said the commander of a base
where pilots are accustomed to flying the cloudless blue skies of
southern New Mexico. Asked if the kind of older radar used by
Yugoslavia might have picked up the plane, he declined to answer.
Although he described the jet as a top-secret plane, he said that
NATO bombers have not returned to the site to destroy the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot received only minor cuts in the ejection, Lake said,
adding that on Saturday he gave the bad news first, then the good
news, to the pilot's wife here. He said he expected that the pilot,
whose name has not been released, would soon return to flying.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the base commander was the pivotal figure in
a drama that revealed how this small corner of America is
intimately tied to the war in faraway Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As about 75 officers and their spouses gathered for a farewell
dinner at the Officers Club, the traditional bantering atmosphere
had been replaced by tension, from watching Yugoslavian
television's images of the burning wreckage of the Holloman jet. At
the start of the dinner, Lake rose and briefed the somber gathering
with the latest Pentagon information.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later he stood up and said, ``We got him, it's
over, he's in good health, and on his way back'' to Aviano Air
Force base in Italy, Col. Eckhard Sowada, who commands a German air
force training unit here, recalled Sunday. ``Everybody in the hall
broke out in a cheer when he said that the pilot was successfully
taken out of Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is relieved he was saved, we are just just happy
that he was OK,'' said the wife of one stealth fighter pilot who
has not been sent on this mission. ``It's a small stealth
community; we all know everybody. It would have hit everybody
pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Several stealth pilots did not return telephone calls. But one
flyer in another group said of the loss of the war plane, ``No
matter what anybody says, when you lose an airplane, it gives you
pause.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the base, in this small city of 31,000 people, relief was
tempered by disappointment that a $43-million aircraft, marketed to
the public as a ``stealth'' would be the first NATO plane to crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of mind-boggling to have such modern technology and
to have something like this happen,'' said Rick Covarrubia, a
special education teacher. ``I feel disappointment in the aircraft
being such a wreck, the news showing it like it was made of
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   At a welding shop, Larry Berry, an Army veteran from Vietnam,
noted that this was the first stealth plane to go down in combat,
and said, ``So far they had been real lucky, kind of invincible.
It's a reality check when one gets blown out of the sky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
