</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-UCONN-745(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOP HEAVEN IS CROWDED, AND THE VIEW IS DIZZYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Duke has been in this position before,
sailing through March and landing safely on a Monday night with the
chance to be crowned the premier squad in college basketball.
Connecticut will walk into foreign territory, tiptoeing a bit as it
tries to defeat a team many experts consider impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   Only 40 minutes of basketball are left before one of those teams
finishes a six-month blitz through a hectic season as the best;
before Duke completes the decade with its third national
championship or UConn snares its first; before the climax of
another magnificent hoops display. It used to be strictly about
basketball. But now the Final Four is basketball immersed in four
days of hype, hoopla and hysteria. It is a spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Super Bowl now,'' said John Wooden, the
88-year-old former UCLA coach, who won 10 national championships in
12 years in calmer conditions.
</P>
<P>
   When Wooden won his last championship in 1975, 15,151 people
turned out to see UCLA's victory over Kentucky. A crowd of 41,430
crammed into Tropicana Field here on Saturday to watch the
semifinal games of the men's Final Four, and at least as many will
attend the championship game on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Some upper-level seats are so far from the court that tickets
should come with binoculars and miniature televisions. Still, the
fans flock to the games and even the practices. A throng of 27,662
watched four perfunctory workouts on Friday. Layup lines have never
been so fervently applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Why do they come? They are lured by a passion for basketball,
and for what they see as the purity of the college game, which
culminates in 19 maddening days in March.
</P>
<P>
   It is really the only time of the year when college basketball
dominates the sports world, no matter what fans in North Carolina
or Indiana think. Select the 64 best teams, toss them into a
tournament, and wonderful stories always evolve as the group is
whittled to one. All the National Collegiate Athletic Association
has to do is oversee the action, constantly refer to the players as
student-athletes, grin once a minute and listen to the cash
registers hum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love hoops, you come to these games,'' said Rich
Blaser, who traveled here from Manassas, Va., for his eighth Final
Four and who might have had a better view if he had stayed home.
``This is heaven for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is lucrative for the often-beleaguered NCAA, which has an
eight-year, $1.725 billion contract with CBS for the rights to
televise the tournament through 2002. The $226 million the NCAA
will receive from CBS this year represents about 80 percent of its
total revenue for the 1998-99 fiscal year. The NCAA will gross
another $18.2 million from ticket sales for the tournament, $3.7
million of that at the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite these tidy totals, and despite what Duke coach
Mike Krzyzewski called a ``kind of neat'' championship game, which
will match the only two schools to hold the No. 1 ranking this
season, the tournament cannot erase lingering problems.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has agreed to pay damages of $54.5 million to about
2,000 assistant coaches whose earnings were restricted. It has seen
its Proposition 16, which set minimum test scores for athletic
eligibility, ruled discriminatory. It is also being sued by an
athletic apparel company and two manufacturers of aluminum bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``As trying as these times are, I don't feel the NCAA is under
siege,'' said Cedric Dempsey, the association's president. ``The
NCAA is in the midst of change, and I see those changes as being
very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The men's basketball title game has certainly changed
immeasurably since Oregon defeated Ohio State, 46-33, before 5,500
fans in Evanston, Ill., in 1939. The NCAA lost $2,531 on that game.
It was the last time the NCAA lost money on a men's championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Now the spectacle, and the income from it, is gigantic. CBS
charges $700,000 for a 30-second commercial, and more than 1,000
news-media credentials were issued for the Final Four. But is
bigger necessarily better? Wooden, still spry as he sat 10 rows
from the court on Saturday, was not certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think television has been bad for collegiate basketball,''
he said. ``I think it's made showmen out of players, coaches and
officials, to a certain degree. But I never want that statement to
be used unless I also add that it's been the savior of
non-income-producing sports and women's sports. So there's two
sides to everything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson and Larry Bird helped elevate the championship
game to another level in 1979. Forget Michigan State and Indiana
State. It was Magic against Larry. The smooth point guard with all
the fancy moves and the electric smile against the savvy forward
with the sharp jumper and the vacuous expression.
</P>
<P>
   There was something magnetic about the two best players in the
country, one black and one white, meeting in the title game,
something that made even nonfans gravitate toward the game. With
Johnson scoring 24 points and Bird struggling to a 7-for-21 effort
from the field, Michigan State prevailed, 75-64.
</P>
<P>
   The game in Salt Lake City attracted 18 million television
viewers and the rating of 24.1 remains the highest for a
championship contest; last year's game between Kentucky and Utah
drew a 17.8 rating.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know why more than 40,000 fans will be at
Tropicana Field on Monday night, why one scalper was trying to
purchase a pair of courtside tickets for $3,500 to resell them for
$5,000, and why millions will watch on television, think Magic and
Larry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it started the explosion of college basketball,''
said Johnson, who watched Michigan State lose to Duke on Saturday
night. ``I think that it pushed college basketball to another
level. We know it changed things. It's still the highest-rated
game. That's the proof in the pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, Bird, who buried his face in a towel to
hide his tears after the defeat, was not as willing to dribble down
memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic's been promoting that because he won the game,'' Bird
said. ``If I had won the game, you would've never heard of it. So
I'm sick of it. I'm ready to move on with my life. It was 20 years
ago. I can't remember that far back.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the tournament has become such a money maker, do not
expect to see the Final Four held in anything but a dome. The
selection committee has picked the sites through 2007, and they are
all domes with a minimum seating capacity of 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is this game being played in a dome?'' Wooden asked on
Saturday. ``There's only one reason they're playing it here. It's
not so more people can fit. It's so more people can pay. That's the
reason. But money rules everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Final Four, it surely does. It was difficult to walk
around Tropicana Field without someone muttering, ``You selling
tickets?'' Even some coaches who met here for the National
Association of Basketball Coaches meeting sold their tickets, which
is a violation of NCAA rules and also against the law in Florida.
One assistant coach, who insisted on anonymity, said he scalped two
tickets for $1,250 because it was more than he earned in a week.
</P>
<P>
   High above the court, Blaser, the fan from Virginia, leaned
against a wall between Sections 313 and 315 and watched basketball.
Or tried to. It was impossible to see almost half of the court,
because a monstrous catwalk obstructed his view.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blaser, who paid $80 for tickets as one of 11,278 fans
who were fortunate enough to secure them through a lottery, was
content. But John Brzezinski of Chicago, who paid a broker $475 for
tickets, was perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry,'' he said. ``We knew we would be up high, but they
didn't say anything about this catwalk. You think twice about
coming again.''
</P>
<P>
   Brzezinski could vent, but there would always be someone else to
scoop up the ticket. Sandra Harrington of Columbia, S.C., called
her seat cruddy _ according to figures in a press guide, it was
about 230 feet from midcourt and 225 feet above the floor _ but
then added: ``I'd rather be here than in a sports bar. You're in
the dome. You're in the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere extended to something called Hoop City, at the
Tampa Convention Center, where fans could participate in basketball
drills, meet coaches and players and visit interactive exhibits.
Alicia Brown, 19, of Riverside, Calif., even won $1 million by
draining a 3-pointer there on Saturday. For those who could not get
tickets to the Final Four, there was a high school all-star game
and college slam-dunk and 3-point-shooting contests.
</P>
<P>
   So the season is down to one game. Shane Battier of Duke
admitted that the rims ``get tighter'' now, while his teammate
Trajan Langdon said he had dreamed about Monday night since he was
a kid in Alaska. E.J. Harrison, a reserve guard for UConn who made
the team as a walk-on, spoke like someone who did not want this
experience to end. He was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream,'' Harrison said. ``It's the Final Four, the
national championship. Everybody wants to play in this. Everybody
wants to see this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
