<SLUG> BC-SOC-USWOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN SHUT OUT MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ It took an entire match to wear down Mexican
goalkeeper Linnea Quinones, and by the time the United States was
finished with the former San Diego State standout, she was all
smiles despite the Americans' 3-0 victory at the Rose Bowl on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Foudy scored in the 38th minute to give the U.S. a 1-0
lead and Kristine Lilly scored two late goals to ice the victory in
a World Cup tune-up at the site of this summer's Women's World Cup
final on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Quinones, one of eight Californians on Mexico's roster, turned
away several U.S. shots, and at one time smothered America's
favorite striker, Mia Hamm, on a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a moral victory for the Mexicans. In three
matches against the U.S. previously, Mexico was beaten 9-0, 12-0
and 9-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone showed a lot of confidence today and a lot of
confidence in me,'' said Quinones, who faced 20 shots on goal. ``Of
course the U.S. is one of the top teams in the world. We knew it
would be a tough match, but everyone on this team really came
together and was out for one thing. We wanted to show that we
deserve to be in this World Cup and in the class of the elite teams
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinones talked about her encounter with Hamm, sounding more
like an admiring fan than Mexico's captain in the nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw her coming, thinking `this is Mia Hamm right in front of
you,' but I concentrated on the ball and didn't look up,'' she
said. ``I was lucky to get it so when I got up I had all these
feelings. It was pretty emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a huge edge in shots (42-1) and a thoroughly controlled
midfield, the U.S. led only 1-0 before Lilly's goals in the 85th
and 88th minutes. U.S. coach Tony DiCicco expected the Mexicans to
pack it in defensively and felt comfortable with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an excellent defensive effort by Mexico, they've come a
long way since we played them in September,'' DiCicco said. ``They
played with a lot of heart, but I was pleased with our team because
we kept attacking. At times we were left a little naked in the
back, but we worked hard to get behind the ball and we defended
well. The final result was a just result because the goals came
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, who came into the match with 103 career goals, needed only
three more to match the international world scoring record held by
Italy's Elisabetta Vignotto. She failed to score for the fifth
consecutive game, however, and joked with a reporter who suggested
she was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're obviously not my sports psychologist,'' she said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm explained that the U.S. team's layoff in the fall may have
affected her ability to return to normal form.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come to grips with your psychological dimension
and tell yourself it's going to take some time,'' Hamm said.
``That's where I am right now. I really have to concentrate on the
things I'm doing well. I'm hard enough on myself, and sure I would
have loved to score today, but it wasn't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I keep contributing to help this team win, that's
all I care about. Goals have never defined me as a player and I
don't think it ever will. What defines me is my impact on this team
even if it means sitting there (on the bench) with pom-poms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
