<HEADLINE>
GORDON STRIKES OUT FOR THE THIRD TIME AT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jeff Gordon's third stab at the Texas Motor
Speedway ended with a familiar message: Don't Mess With Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive year, Gordon failed to finish the
NASCAR Winston Cup race at Texas Motor Speedway. The three-time and
defending Cup champion ran up front until the right front tire on
his No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet went down and sent
Gordon hard into the Turn 4 wall after 68 laps during yesterday's
Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who had been in early contention, was rushed to the
infield care unit, where X-rays revealed no broken bones. Bruised
and frustrated, Gordon's team exited TMS long before Hendrick
Motorsports teammate Terry Labonte crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much the hardest I've ever hit a wall, that's for
sure. I hit \Rit\S a ton,'' said Gordon, who suffered his second
Did Not Finish in six races, matching his total DNFs for all of
last season. ``I'm not exactly sure what happened. Somehow the
right front tire went down, but we're not exactly sure why, yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Ray Evernham said the tire did not blow out. ``It
just went on the liner and didn't turn, so that tells me it's
possibly a cut. I wanted to see the tire, but it's so hard when the
tire is that destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's Coca-Cola 300 winner, Mark Martin, and Mike Skinner
both crashed yesterday from similarly blown or cut right front
tires. Skinner suffered a hairline fracture of the right shoulder
blade. Martin re-entered the race and completed 253 of the 334 laps
to finish 34th.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said he will be ready to run in the next Winston Cup
race, the Food City 500 in Bristol, Tenn., on April 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've ever seen him wreck that hard,''
Evernham said. ``If he said he'd be ready for Bristol we'll get him
ready somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   His wreck yesterday continued a run of tough luck in North
Texas. The wreck, which made Gordon the race's first casualty, was
his fourth crash in as many races at TMS, but the first that didn't
result from a crash already in progress in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon got caught up in his third consecutive TMS crash Saturday
during the Coca-Cola 300, a Busch Grand National race he said he
wanted to run to get more lap time and become better acquainted
with TMS' 1.5-mile quadoval. He finished 13th, making it the only
TMS race he has completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running pretty good \Ryesterday\S, but it looked like
his car was pushing a little,'' said Dale Jarrett, who trailed
Gordon at the time of the crash. ``It surprised me when I saw him
hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon placed 43rd for the first time in his career and finished
last for only the second time, the first coming on March 9, 1997,
at the Atlanta Motor Speedway when he finished 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, whose finished earned $60,000 yesterday, fell from
second to fourth in the Winston Cup points standings with 790, 119
points behind leader Jeff Burton, who finished seventh yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next couple of days I'll be pretty stiff,'' Gordon said,
``but I believe I'll be all right and we'll be ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
