</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-FANS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS IN CUBA WALKING TALL DESPITE LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES, BBO-CUBA-DEFECTORS, BBO-SELIG-CASTRO 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr. WITH MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ It was a sunny event laced with nationalism and
patriotic feeling, but in the end, the game played here Sunday
between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban national team was about
baseball, and the 50,000 Cubans who attended walked out with their
heads high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a magnificent game,'' Sergio Girat, a 34-year-old
hospital worker, said after the 11-inning battle, which was won by
the Orioles, 3-2. ``Our team played up to their level. They got
what they wanted to achieve, and they lost, but they went down
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   All over Havana, people from the upper echelons of the
government to taxi drivers and bartenders were talking about the
game Sunday night, analyzing the mistakes made and opportunities
lost.
</P>
<P>
   But if they felt defeated, nearly everyone was also proud. The
Cuban team, minus several stars who are busy with the Cuban League
playoffs here, came close to beating the professionals from
Baltimore, losing by just one run and managing to get 10 hits off
the American pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The game marked the first time a major league team had visited
Cuba since the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers played an
exhibition here in March 1959.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many Cuban fans, the game seemed to demonstrate
once and for all that they have professional-caliber players, a
sore point with many people who have been cut off from the major
leagues for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shown them that Cuban baseball is as good as the
baseball in the big leagues,'' Jose Fernandez, an electric company
worker, said, echoing the views of many others.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended weeks of speculation and anticipation among
Cuba's baseball fans. Baseball is deeply entwined with Cuban
culture and history, and a passion for the game has persisted
despite the long ideological war between Cuba and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Cubans began playing baseball more than 120 years ago, and
nationalist leaders during Cuba's wars for independence against
Spain extolled baseball above other sports, linking the game in the
nation's consciousness with the birth of modern Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Before Fidel Castro seized power in 1958, professional and
semiprofessional baseball thrived in Cuba, producing major league
ballplayers like Minnie Minoso, Camilo Pascual and Tony Oliva.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro abolished professional sports in 1961 and established
a Soviet-style athletic program. Since then, Cuban baseball teams
have dominated amateur competitions like the Olympics and Pan
American Games but have been denied the chance to test their skills
against the best players in the world, much to the dismay of fans.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   People who had tickets for the game began arriving at the
Estadio Latinoamericano at 7 a.m., threading their way through a
heavy security cordon which included dozens of plain-clothed police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   By 11:30, when the Cuban team in its blue and red uniforms began
taking batting practice, the faded one-tier stadium was packed to
the rafters. The Cuban players were tense as they waited for their
turns in the batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Linares, the 31-year-old third baseman who is considered
the best all-around player in Cuba, told reporters that he had no
regrets about having stayed in Cuba rather than defecting to the
United States, where he undoubtedly could have had a major league
career. ``None, absolutely none,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other Cuban players were less polite, expressing
frustration with several members of the Cuban national team who
have defected since 1991 to seek careers in the United States.
Several players said they were committed communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hundred-percent revolutionary,'' said Oscar Machado, an
outfielder. ``I would not have done what they have done.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Orioles began their batting practice, the crowd
had begun to size up the opposition. The Americans looked big
compared to the Cuban team, several fans said. When the Orioles'
bellicose outfielder, Albert Belle, hammered four balls out of the
stadium in a row, thousands went ``ooh'' and ``aah.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the invitation-only crowd was relatively quiet compared
with the raucous fans who usually attend games here. Cuban fans are
known for playing drums and brass to conga beats to rally their
teams, screaming insults at umpires and sipping rum, a practice
that leads to arrests for disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the orderly crowd was the government's decision
to keep a tight control over who could attend. Tickets were
distributed to Communist Party faithful through schools, youth
organizations and unions, officials said. Some were also parceled
out to workers and civil servants as rewards for meeting production
quotas and other state goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here were all invited,'' said Leonardo Marquez, a
30-year-old electrician who was given his ticket as a reward for
being productive. ``It's for the protection of the foreigners here.
We were all told to behave ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans outside the stadium, however, were bitter, not unlike
followers of major league teams in the United States who find
themselves without a ticket during the World Series because so many
seats have been snapped up by dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Roman Garcia, a 47-year-old driver who has followed the Yankees
and the Habana Industriales all his life, said he was shocked to
learn he would not be able to attend the game for any price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always go to the stadium, even when there are only 50 to 100
people in the stands,'' he said, scowling under his Yankees cap, as
he attended a daily gathering of baseball fans in Havana's Central
Park . ``But I can't go because I don't have an invitation. I feel
tricked and disgusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who did attend the game carried Cuban flags, and
paper flags were distributed. A roar went up at 12:45 p.m. when
Castro wearing his trademark fatigues, walked slowly out on the
field along with other high-ranking officials, crossed the diamond
and greeted the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   After shaking hands with some players from the American side,
Castro huddled with the Cuban team in front of its dugout, making
the most of the imagery of himself as the manager of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Then he retired to front-row seats behind home plate, where he
watched the game with the commissioner of baseball, Bud Selig, and
the Orioles' owner, Peter Angelos, on either side of him. He
chatted with them constantly through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I understand about Castro is he knows a lot about baseball
and he's an absolute fan of the game,'' Angelos said later, adding
that the communist leader had asked a lot of questions about
players' salaries and contracts. The average Cuban player earns
less than $20 a month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The American delegation was sizable. Besides Selig and Angelos,
representatives of more than 20 major league teams attended the
game, along with two U.S. Sens., Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont and
Jack Reed of Rhode Island. The mayor of Baltimore, Kurt L. Schmoke,
and 60 Little Leaguers from the Washington area also watched.
</P>
<P>
   In seating areas reserved for Orioles supporters and the
diplomatic corps, many of the Americans in attendance said they
felt they were part of a unique experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so emotional,'' said Joel Atlas Skirble, a Washington
lawyer who has taken part in cultural exchanges with Cuba in the
past and was here this time to bring medicines and spend Passover
with Cuban Jews. ``It's the first time in 40 years that `The Star
Spangled Banner' is played here with the president of Cuba
present.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat who is among those who have questioned the American
trade embargo on Cuba and called for a review of such policy, Leahy
said that while the game alone would not lead to policy changes, it
sent a signal to both governments that ``the majority of the people
of the countries have no animosity toward each other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People may end up questioning both countries' policies more,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban fans were full of questions about a major league team
with which they were not as familiar as they would have been with
the Atlanta Braves or the Yankees. ``Is Baltimore a state?'' one
fan asked. ``Have the Orioles won a World Series?'' asked another.
</P>
<P>
   As the game began, the crowd settled down. Cuban fans began
sizing up the American starter, Scott Erickson, who narrowly
escaped a disaster in the first inning because of good fielding.
The Cubans began to relax when they saw Luis Ulacia get a base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Cubans are going to win,'' said Falbello Lazaro, a
45-year-old factory worker. ``They are batting well.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Orioles took a 2-0 lead, the faithful in the
bleachers were not cowed. Fans wrapped in flags beat conga drums
and wood blocks, singing, ``Cuba, how beautiful is Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's written in the Bible that Cuba will win today,'' said
Alberto Hernandez, 36. ``We know how to maintain our honor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the eighth, with the Orioles' leading by 2-1,
Cuba's fortunes changed. Linares slapped a ball past the third
baseman into left field, driving in the tying run. ``Cuba! Cuba!''
the crowd yelled again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you we Cubans know how to play ball,'' an excited fan,
Alexander Carmona, 18, said as Linares reached first base. ``All
the little kids here play from the time they can walk. Brazil has
football but we play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The game remained tied and in the bottom of the 10th Linares had
a second chance to be a hero, coming to the plate with two outs and
men on first and second base. This time, however, he popped up a
ball which was easily caught. The steam went out of the Cuban
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles came back with a run in the top of the 11th, when
Harold Baines drove in Will Clark. The Orioles' defense held in the
bottom of the inning. The fans in the stadium stood to applaud the
Orioles as the two teams shook hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had talent, but we also were able to confront them,''
Miguel Cuevas, a 64-year-old coach who played for the Cuban
national team in the '70s, said after the last out. ``It was a good
game and we played well. We are people that love the Americans.
It's only the politics there we cannot accept. But we are baseball
lovers and the people there are people that love baseball as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
