 &UR; POSTPC &LR;  _ A refrigerator that makes your grocery list. A microwave
that doubles as an Internet shopping and banking terminal. A
wallet-size card that keeps track of your daughter's homework. A TV
that knows what you like to watch and automatically records your
favorite shows. These technologies may sound like science fiction,
but some are available now, and many more are in the works in
research labs in Silicon Valley and around the world. By Jamie
Beckett
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANDERSEN &LR;  _ You walk into a discount store to buy a new VCR and
find a model you like. You whip out your Pocket Bargain Finder. The
handheld, wireless device swiftly scans the World Wide Web and
finds the same VCR offered by an online electronics seller for 25
percent less than the discount store's price. The Pocket Bargain
Finder isn't for sale yet. It's one of several futuristic
inventions like a ``magic wall'' and an ``awareness machine''
dreamed up by Andersen Consulting's Center for Strategic Technology
Research in Palo Alto. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OFFICE &LR;  _ Before the ``delete'' key, there was Ko-Rec-Type.
Before toner cartridges, there were mimeograph stencils. And long
before multifunction, handheld calculators, there was the Addiator
Hand Adding Machine. ``It's amazing how quickly these items were
forgotten,'' said Gary Luiza, president of Penny Wise Office
Products of Bowie, Md. The mail-order house this month came up with
a list of once-common office supplies that have become scarce or
extinct, pushed aside by the rush of desktop computers, fax
machines and other new technology. BY Benny Evangelista
</P>
