<SLUG> BC-BKW-DUKE-PURDUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE AND DUKE SHOW THE GAME'S NEW FACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ They played for the championship of women's
college basketball on Sunday night without a team from the
Southeastern Conference for the first time in five years. And
Tennessee, Louisiana Tech, Stanford, Connecticut _ teams that have
won 11 of 17 National Collegiate Athletic Association titles since
the tournament began in 1982 _ were here when the nationally
televised championship game began.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue and Duke, two teams that have never won a women's
basketball championship, were the new faces. It was a sign, their
coaches said, of the changing face of the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more good players than ever,'' Duke coach Gail
Goestenkors said. ``There are more good coaches at every level.
More camps, more clinics. The game is growing at an incredible
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than two or three college teams worth watching
and that's great for our game. I think people want a new
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   The swift success of Goestenkors' Duke program is perhaps the
best example of how rapidly the balance of power can now shift in
women's college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived at Duke in 1992, the women's program was little
more than a curiosity on campus. Duke had made one trip to the NCAA
tournament and had just eight winning seasons since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that people laughed at Duke when coach G was
hired,'' Duke guard Hilary Howard said Saturday, referring to
Goestenkors.
</P>
<P>
   The year before Goestenkors took the Duke job, the team was 4-12
in the Atlantic Coast Conference. Goestenkors' first team was 3-13
in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that we had to come up from the bottom,''
Goestenkors said on the eve of Sunday night's championship game.
``I had never been on a losing team before as a player, as an
assistant coach _ nothing, never. I was very bad at giving those
postgame speeches when you lose, because I had never heard those
speeches before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to say and that was a humbling experience.
But a very useful one. We worked hard and we convinced a player or
two to take a chance on me, because I was an unproven coach. But
once we got going, we were able to set lofty goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard remembers well her recruiting visit at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been recruited by Connecticut and Virginia,'' Howard
said. ``They were already established, but I had confidence in
coach G. When she talked to me, she talked to me about going to the
Final Four. And she meant it, she wasn't fooling. That impressed me
and it turned out she was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Goestenkors' third Duke team was 22-9 and made the 1995 NCAA
tournament, the first of five consecutive trips to the tournament.
But Duke had never won more than two NCAA games in one season until
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people are surprised by what we've done this year,
but we're not,'' Goestenkors said. ``It's not as big a leap as it
might seem on the outside. We were getting better all along and our
conference has become more competitive. Look at the quality of the
players we have. That's why we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goestenkors didn't get every player she recruited. One who
got away was Purdue guard Ukari Figgs, whose 24 points was just one
part of a brilliant performance against Louisiana Tech on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I was pretty sure Ukari was going to come to Duke,''
Goestenkors said. ``She made a campus visit and we were surprised
when she did not come to Duke. That was a heartbreaker for us. I
hope she doesn't break my heart again.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgs' four-year career has helped fuel Purdue's ascent as a
national power, which has been nearly as meteoric as Duke's. Purdue
had won a lot more games than Duke in the 1980s and early 1990s but
had never advanced past the NCAA second round until 1994 when the
Boilermakers made their first Final Four trip, losing in the
national semifinals. In 1995 and 1998, Purdue lost in the regional
finals.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Purdue ended Tennessee's 45-game unbeaten streak to
take over the No. 1 spot in the Associated Press poll, only to lose
it within a week. But the Boilermakers won 26 straight games and
finished the season as the top-ranked team in the final poll. They
are just the second Big Ten Conference team to play for the women's
national championship. Ohio State lost to Texas Tech in the title
game in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great for the Big Ten to have a national champion,
though we don't need it to prove our conference is strong,'' said
Purdue coach Carolyn Peck. ``Our conference has progressed a lot
and already received a lot of recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little bit helps, but anyone watching women's basketball
now knows the talent level and competition level has gone up. And
not just at the traditional places. The game is being played at a
high level in a lot of places in the country. All you have to do is
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The best place to see it on display Sunday night was the San
Jose Arena, where another breakthrough season in women's college
basketball concluded with the naming of a new champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
