<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTPC-POSTPC_SFCHRON     03-28 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTPC-POSTPC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 NEXT RUNG Of TECH EVOLUTION  
 By Jamie Beckett 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; A refrigerator that makes your grocery list. A microwave that
doubles as an Internet shopping and banking terminal. A wallet-size
card that keeps track of your daughter's homework. A TV that knows
what you like to watch and automatically records your favorite
shows.
</P>
<P>
   These technologies may sound like science fiction, but some are
available now, and many more are in the works in research labs in
Silicon Valley and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, companies such as Xerox, Hewlett-Packard,
Philips, Electrolux and NCR hope to introduce a host of smart
wireless devices that could make the PCs of today seem as clumsy as
a phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get to a point where computing is invisible,'' said
Mark Bregmann, who heads a group at IBM dedicated to what the
company calls pervasive computing. ``We're talking about a post-PC
era where people will have access to information and services with
easy-to-use appliances anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expects PCs to disappear. The idea is to make the
computers, or ``information appliances,'' in our lives ubiquitous,
as much in the background as electricity is today. The
microprocessors embedded in our cars, clocks and VCRs operate this
way _ we don't notice them until they don't work.
</P>
<P>
   The next step: making intelligent devices that can communicate
with one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your phone talked to your TV, the TV could turn down the
sound when you answered the phone. If your microwave talked to your
VCR, it could pause the tape when the popcorn's ready,'' said Mark
Weiser, chief technologist at Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   Weiser, credited with inventing the concept of ``ubiquitous
computing,'' is part of a team that's transforming ordinary metal
staples into tiny communication devices. The smart staples could
keep track of where you put things and help you find lost
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea he's researching: electronic wallet-size cards that
could keep track of information such as your child's school
assignments or soccer practice schedule, the menu at your favorite
restaurant, movie times and ski conditions. Each card would have
one purpose, so you'd never have to search for information.
</P>
<P>
   Weiser sees the cards as part of a future of ``calm computing.''
It isn't the computer that's calm, though. It's you, because
everything is working to make your life easier.
</P>
<P>
   In this all-digital future, you might drive a car that can be
tuned remotely, find the nearest Chinese take-out using your
portable global positioning system, and live in a house where your
microwave provides nutritional tips based on your eating habits and
your alarm clock checks the traffic before waking you up.
</P>
<P>
   But as technology moves into this more personal terrain, some
worry about the privacy implications of creating a digital record
of our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think for a second that companies aren't going to
exploit the information they have about you,'' said Larry Ponemon,
a partner at PricewaterhouseCoopers, cq  &LR; who is an expert on
privacy and business ethics. ``With these conveniences, we're
providing lots of potentially important information about ourselves
that could be used to sell you things or change your behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it essential that consumers have the option of
turning off data collection, but Ponemon urged that some sort of
third party keep an eye out to make sure businesses that collect
data stick to their promises.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Others wonder if all these computers are really necessary and if
they will fulfill the promise of making life easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are very, very difficult to make work right,''
said Martin Reynolds, a research fellow at Dataquest in San Jose.
Reynolds uses the example of a device he rigged up in his home that
is supposed to turn things off if a room is empty. The problem is,
if people are sitting on the living-room couch not moving, it shuts
off the lights and TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get mad at me,'' Reynolds said. ``There's a fine line
between technology for technology's sake and technology for
convenience's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the smart microwaves and alarm clocks may be years
away, less-ambitious devices are being rolled out this year.
</P>
<P>
   Philips Electronics will soon be selling a satellite TV receiver
that incorporates technology invented by TiVo, a Sunnyvale startup.
TiVo's Personal Television Service learns what kind of shows you
like to watch and automatically records them. TiVo ( &LR; www.tivo.com &LR; )
will be offering a receiver and the service to consumers this
month. Replay Networks &LR;   &LR; ( &LR; www.replaytv.com &LR; ) of Palo Alto will
release a similar digital VCR next month that allows you to create
your own ``channels'' of your favorite shows. Both devices let you
control live TV broadcasts as if they were videotape; for example,
``pausing'' when the phone rings and then resuming watching.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard recently introduced a high-tech answer to
tearing pages out of magazines or clipping news articles _ a
handheld scanner. The CapShare lets you store information and
images by casually swiping the scanner over a page. You can then
send what you scanned via infrared to a printer, handheld notebook,
PC or personal digital assistant.
</P>
<P>
   More exciting gadgets are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Screenfridge.  &LR; Down to your last egg? No problem. Just sweep
the carton over your refrigerator's bar-code reader and another
dozen will be on the way. Swedish appliance-maker Electrolux last
month unveiled what it is billing as the first Internet-connected
refrigerator. When you scan a item's bar code, the fridge creates a
digital shopping list to transmit to your grocer. The company plans
to introduce the appliance in Europe next year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Microwave bank.  &LR; NCR is betting consumers will warm to the
idea of a microwave oven that can surf the Web. The Dayton, Ohio,
software-maker last year showed off a prototype of a microwave that
it says puts banking and shopping where consumers want them _ in
the kitchen. The oven also has a TV and a bar-code scanner for
making a digital shopping list. For now, it's still a work in
progress in NCR's lab.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Screen phone.  &LR; Wouldn't it be nice if you could get onto the
Internet without the hassle of booting up your PC, starting Windows
and dialing up your Internet service provider? The screen phone, a
telephone-like appliance that can sit on your kitchen counter, is
one of many devices that could provide one-button Internet access.
Cidco has been selling such a device for almost a year; Alcatel
will release one this summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Hot tub remote. &LR;  It's a cold, rainy day and you're on you way
home. You think about how nice the hot tub would feel about now.
You push a button on your cellular phone and it turns on the heat
and the bubbles and when you get home, you can just hop into the
tub. IBM is researching a system it internally calls LifeWorks,
where the appliances in your life could share information. Such a
system might make it possible for you to call up your phone
messages on your TV or turn up the thermostat at home from your
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this seems like Buck Rogers, but it's doable,'' said
Mitch Stein, senior manager of consumer systems and software at
IBM. What has to happen is that standards have to be set so devices
can share data, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thinks building a future of smart devices will be
so easy. Eli Zelkha, managing partner at Palo Alto Ventures, a
consulting and venture firm, said the key problem isn't the
technology _ it's making it work for people. He recalled how
researchers in Paris recently developed what they thought was a
superior vacuum cleaner. It had sensors to determine what kind of
floor it was on and would move differently according to each
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Then they asked French housewives to try the new machine. And
instead of liking the sensors, they were frustrated, because they
had their own ways learned over time and now habit,  &LR; of pushing the
vacuum according to what type of floor they were cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``After awhile, they were ready to throw the vacuum against the
wall,'' Zelkha said. What has to happen, he said, is that machines
should adapt to people, not vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The machines should be in the background as slaves, rather
than in the foreground as something we worship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's driving all this? One thing is the Internet. Consumers
want access to the information and services on the Net, and they
want it available when they're away from their PCs. At the same
time, computer chips are becoming so small and so cheap that it's
possible to put lots of them everywhere _ in clothes, cars,
appliances, even eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the idea of wearable computers has fascinated many
researchers, who've fashioned prototype after prototype of
enormous, geeky eyeglasses with a screen attached. Sometime soon,
wearable computers could become palatable to the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard is talking with an Italian eyewear-maker about
finding a way to make a good-looking pair of computing glasses.
Even if they're not high fashion, the glasses might be used by
surgeons, warehouse workers and others who may need to receive
information but keep their hands free.
</P>
<P>
   The computer giant, which is also working on badges that would
let you identify yourself to your computer without using a
password, sees such innovations as crucial to its ability to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try hard to differentiate yourself in commodity
businesses like PCs or laptops,'' said Fred Kitson, manager of
visual computing at HP Labs. ``People can easily use appliances
like toasters and mixers. The idea is to evolve computers in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
