<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-OFFICE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Dinosaurs of the Office
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Before the ``delete'' key, there was Ko-Rec-Type.
</P>
<P>
   Before toner cartridges, there were mimeograph stencils.
</P>
<P>
   And long before multifunction, handheld calculators, there was
the Addiator Hand Adding Machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how quickly these items were forgotten,'' said
Gary Luiza, president of Penny Wise Office Products of Bowie, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The mail-order house this month came up with a list of
once-common office supplies that have become scarce or extinct,
pushed aside by the rush of desktop computers, fax machines and
other new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Luiza said his staff searched sales records and old catalogs to
find obsolete office products as a way to chart the ``evolution of
the office products industry.''
</P>
<P>
   One example they found was the slide rule, which as recently as
the 1970s hung from engineers' belt loops. These devices looked
like rulers and were used to do complex mathematical calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Luiza said, ``You can get a calculator for $15 that can do
100 times what the slide rule could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, Luiza said calculator sales have fallen
off in the last four years because office workers have come to rely
more on computer software like Microsoft Excel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the products that over time could be gone,'' he
said. ``Calculators will be replaced by the palm-top or handheld
computers that can do more. We're going to look at people in 10
years standing on a street corner pulling these out of their pocket
to get their e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more office products on their way to the scrap
heap:
</P>
<P>
   _Mimeograph stencils. Baby Boomers will remember when sniffing
freshly printed purple mimeograph copies was the highlight of the
school day. The mimeograph and the stencils that were used to make
copies of the original master documents hung on in schools and some
offices into the late 1980s, but have given way to cheaper, easier
photocopiers and printers.
</P>
<P>
   _Typewriter ribbon. It's rare to find a manual typewriter in an
office anymore, but Luiza occasionally hears from an old typewriter
stalwart looking for a ribbon. He said he can locate one, ``usually
after a series of phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   _Ko-Rec-Type. Before the days of cut-and-paste software and
spell checkers, Ko-Rec-Type was the savior of any typist who needed
to fix those errant keystrokes. The little piece of plastic tape
masked the mistake with a white film. Ko-Rec-Type is still
available, but only in limited supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _Erasable paper. Offices stopped ordering erasable onionskin
paper in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   _Kil-Klatter pads. These plastic rectangles were used as a pad
between a typewriter and an old wooden or metal desk and did what
their name said _ killed, or at least muffled, the clatter made by
a roomful of those machines. They disappeared from office supply
catalogs around 1982. ``These are truly things of the past. I can't
even lay my hands on a set of those,'' Luiza said.
</P>
<P>
   _Eyeshades. Corporate bean counters wore these transparent green
visors, which were supposed to be  &LR; shade harsh office light, thus
saving their eyes while they spent hours poring over documents. The
advent of softer fluorescent lighting, and maybe the Fashion
Police, banished this headgear into retirement around 1975, Luiza
said.
</P>
<P>
   _Sandy Pointers. Long before there were electric pencil
sharpeners with automatic shut off, pencils were ground into points
with these handheld, sandpaper-covered paddles. They disappeared
from office supply lists around 1974, Luiza said.
</P>
<P>
   _Cuffettes. In the days of stain-causing mimeograph solvent,
smudgy typewriter ribbon and messy carbon paper, office workers
wore Cuffettes to cover the ends of their white shirt sleeves.
``They maybe lasted into the '80s, but nobody wears them today,''
Luiza said.
</P>
<P>
   _Addiator Hand Adding Machine. This abacus-like device employed
a sliding bar to make calculations. They disappeared from catalogs
in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
