<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 FILES _ SF CHRON   Net Gaming Ban Faces Long Odds 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Conservative U.S. Senator Jon Kyl is rolling the dice again in his
personal crusade to rid the Internet of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican shuffled the deck last week, introducing
a watered-down version of the Internet Gambling Prohibition Act _
which failed to pass the full Congress last year. Kyl is betting
the new version will establish a national law banning online
wagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet gambling is addictive, accessible to minors, subject
to fraud and other criminal use,'' Kyl said in a statement. ``We
need to update the law to help it keep up with technology and close
the loopholes that have allowed this activity to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   He faces steep odds.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new version eliminates a thorny provision that
would have punished virtual bettors with fines of up to $500 and
jail terms as long as three months, many in the online gambling
business question whether the legislation will dampen the
proliferation of virtual casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion industry has mushroomed from a dozen companies
two years ago to about 200 today. Most of the virtual casinos are
based in exotic locales such as the Caribbean and Central America,
far from U.S. law-enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the California attorney general's office in
Sacramento acknowledged it would be difficult to pinpoint
individuals gambling online. Internet service providers, meanwhile,
are balking at being thrust into the position of enforcing the law
by blocking their customers from gaming sites.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-gambling bill also faces opposition from the
influential horse racing industry; American Civil Liberties Union;
and the ISP Consortium, a Minneapolis organization that represents
300 Internet service providers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is regulation that protects the consumer _ not
outright prohibition,'' said Sue Schneider, chairwoman of the
Interactive Gaming Council, a Vancouver, British Columbia, group
promoting online gambling. ``Kyl's bill is malarkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Like its earlier incarnation, Kyl's latest bill would punish
individuals running gambling sites with prison terms of four years
and fines of up to $20,000. The ban does not apply to state
lotteries and off-track betting that employ computer systems
unavailable to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, it exempts sites for popular sports ``rotisserie''
leagues, in which consumers pick professional athletes and bet on
their statistics. ``The bill is filled with holes; it's Swiss
cheese,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions are designed to appease powerful lobbying groups,
but probably won't carry the bill through Congress, gambling
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling is always a politicized issue,'' said Sebastian
Sinclair, an analyst with Christiansen Cummings Associates, a New
York gambling consulting firm. He said if Kyl's latest bill fails,
as many expect, other legislation will follow and a bill eventually
will pass. ``Lawmakers will eventually find a way,'' Sinclair said.
``This is just part of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Senator Kyl: Your bill is a longshot. Maybe it's time to
know when to fold 'em.
</P>
<P>
   _CHECK THIS OUT: Starting today, Web-heads will be able to
choose from more than 2,000 books on the world's first virtual
library.
</P>
<P>
   NetLibrary ( &LR; www.netlibrary.com &LR; ) _ the first comprehensive
collection of electronic books, periodicals, journals, technical
papers and multimedia content _ can be downloaded for free via the
Internet. By the end of the year, 8,000 to 20,000 titles will be
available. NetLibrary plans to add another 10,000 books annually.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers McGraw-Hill, MIT Press and Cambridge University
Press; several universities; and library consortiums including the
Colorado Alliance, OhioLink, Palinet, the University of Texas
system and the University of Phoenix system have contributed to the
e-book endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing comparable to what we are offering,'' said
Tim Schiewe, netLibrary's president and CEO. ``Users will be able
to peruse thousands of books for free from just one site.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boulder, Colo., company does not foresee competition from
Amazon.com and Barnesandnoble.com, both of whom have established
winning formulas for selling new hard- and softcover books directly
to consumers. Both companies are branching into other markets, such
as CDs and videos, and have discussed forging business alliances
with NetLibrary, according to Schiewe.
</P>
<P>
   _OUR MOTTO: If New York is ``the city that never sleeps'' and
Atlanta is capital of the New South, then what do we christen
Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   Salon magazine ( &LR; www.salonmagazine.com &LR; ) pondered that question
and asked its readers to come up with a snappy slogan about the
valley of the nerds.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of their suggestions: ``I came, I saw, IPO'';
``Public or Perish''; ``Sleep is for the weak''; and ``If at first
you don't succeed, go for a second round.''
</P>
<P>
   All noble contenders, but none quite measured up to the winner:
``Quality is job one-point-one.''
</P>
<P>
   _AUTHOR, AUTHOR: The rags-to-riches-to-rags story of Apple
Computer has always had a Shakespearean appeal to business writers.
Few high-tech companies have elicited such dramatic prose,
microscopic analysis and detailed reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Two more entrants in the growing library of Apple books _
Michael Malone's definitive ``Infinite Loop'' and Owen Linzmayer's
no-frills ``Apple Confidential'' _ delve into the social and
political forces that turned a garage startup into an American
icon.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's 584-page tome, subtitled ``How Apple, the World's Most
Insanely Great Computer Company, Went Insane,'' offers
painstakingly Halberstam-esque insight into the minutiae behind the
Cupertino legend and what went wrong (hence the thick volume).
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who is host of a PBS interview program and editor of
Forbes ASAP, unearths dozens of nuggets. &UR;  &LR; Among them: How Steve
Jobs on several occasions ``ripped off'' money and ideas from Steve
Wozniak, his best friend and Apple co-founder. When Woz found out,
he wept and kept Jobs at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   Linzmayer gives readers a bird's eye view of the once
high-flying computer-maker. In 244 pages, the free-lance journalist
provides plenty of photos, charts, time lines and illustrations
dating to Apple's origin in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Insight is sparse, but Linzmayer's book is an excellent textbook
for Apple historians.
</P>
<P>
   SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Reason No. 2,571 why I love the Internet: It is a melting pot of
cultures and lifestyles. Here is a smidgen of the alternative
voices available online:  &LR; www.wordsofwomen.com &LR; ,  &LR; www.gay.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.asianart.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   There is even _ get this _ a Jewish portal called
 &LR; www.zipple.com &LR; . Just wondering: Is its chat room called a
schmooze room?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
