<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE_SFC     03-28 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 BioScope/Tom Abate  
 With 1990s Detective Work, It's Hereditary 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Genetic forensics has become the newest and perhaps most
controversial tool in the crime fighter's arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true in cases like the Yosemite murders, where
bodies have been burned to destroy evidence, and bone fragments or
blood smears may be all that remains to establish guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only need a pinprick of material to make an
identification,'' said Sean Walsh, research director at the Applied
Biosystems division of Perkin-Elmer Corp. in Foster City.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the leading supplier of the $75,000 systems that
police labs use to obtain genetic IDs. Walsh explained how the
process works.
</P>
<P>
   First, investigators scour crime scenes for blood, saliva, semen
or bits of skin. The size of the sample hardly matters. The
machines only require a few cells to get at the DNA inside our
chromosomes.
</P>
<P>
   In the lab, genetic forensics experts turn these cells into a
chemical brew, from which they skim off a minute amount of DNA.
Using a technique called PCR, the equipment replicates this DNA
sample a hundred thousand times over, creating a glob of material
large enough to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   As Walsh explained, all of us have the same basic genetic code.
But the Federal Bureau of Investigation has identified 13 spots on
12 chromosomes where each of us have what is thought to be a short,
unique DNA sequence _ a sort of genetic fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing chemical dyes with the DNA sample, then subjecting the
material to a powerful electric shock, the machines sort out the
lengths of these 13 markers. The test results look like a bar-code
printed in blue, green and yellow. It is the length and arrangement
of those colored bars that set each of us apart, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic tests have proven so powerful at helping prove guilt or
innocence _ DNA evidence has freed some who were wrongly convicted
_ that many law enforcement officials are pushing to expand the
database of DNA samples.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman Paul Bresson said all 50 states have laws
requiring some people _ usually convicted sex offenders, rapists or
murderers _ to submit DNA samples.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the states have amassed 700,000 samples, of which
270,000 have been analyzed. ``The labs are getting backed up,''
Bresson said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Attorney General Janet Reno appointed a federal
commission to study whether it would be constitutional to require
every person charged with a crime to submit a DNA sample. Louisiana
hasn't waited. It is so far the only state to require DNA tests
upon arrest.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates are leery of the growing use of DNA tests,
which they consider far more invasive than fingerprinting.
</P>
<P>
   When we get fingerprinted, for instance, we get our fingers
back. Not so with DNA tests, said Barry Steinhardt of the American
Civil Liberties Union. Authorities don't just take a genetic
fingerprint. They keep the blood or tissue sample, which gives them
the ability to do new and more potent tests in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, at around the same time (circa 1997) they
passed a DNA testing law, they created a commission to study the
biological causes of crime,'' Steinhardt said. ``You already have
scientists talking about things like gay genes. How long before
they start looking for the genetic markers that might indicate a
propensity to crime?''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Steinhardt says police labs should take DNA
prints and destroy the samples, making the new tests more like
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   But the Department of Defense, which began collecting DNA
samples in 1992 to help identify those killed in action, has about
3 million blood specimens it plans to keep for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR;  If you don't buy the fear that DNA files might be expanded
or abused, Marc Rotenberg of the Electronic Privacy Information
Center suggests we consider the evolution of other databases.
Remember, people in the 1930s were promised their Social Security
numbers wouldn't be used for identification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, banks are fingerprinting people for cashing checks
or using ATMS,'' Rotenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, as DNA tests get faster and cheaper _ and researchers are
already testing DNA chips that do quick IDs from saliva _ we might
one day walk up to an ATM and spit.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this may sound farfetched, but it does indicate why
business is booming 30 to 40 percent a year at Applied Biosystems
in Foster City. In fact business is so good, the division will soon
expand across the bay into a new 66,000-square-foot distribution
center in Hayward.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea that DNA testing is just about crime and
punishment and science fiction nightmares of genetic
discrimination. (For more on that, rent the movie ``Gattaca!'')
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Heron, general manager of the Foster City division, said
her firm has taken genetic samples from some 40,000 dogs a year to
provide scientific proof that their puppies had the proper
pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you rely on a breeder signing an affidavit,'' Heron
said. ``People would like to have better documentation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
