<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NATURE'S' CALL KEEPS IT AT NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moviegoers continued to shower affection on
``Forces of Nature'' as the romantic comedy took in an estimated
$9.6 million at 2,224 theaters to top a moderate national box
office weekend, studio sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The DreamWorks release, with Sandra Bullock and Ben Affleck,
showed staying power with a 29 percent decline from its opening
weekend. ``We feel we did well in a marketplace with so many
movies,'' said studio marketing executive Don Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces,'' which has hit $27 million in 10 days, edged
Universal's opening of ``EDtv'' with $9 million at 2,626 theaters
and Warner Bros.' fourth weekend of ``Analyze This'' with $8.8
million at 2,537 sites as comedies aimed at adult moviegoers
dominated at the nation's multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   MGM's opening of ``Mod Squad'' followed in fourth with a
lukewarm $6 million at 2,220 theaters and Disney's debut of its
low-cost ``Doug's First Movie'' finished fifth with a modest $4.4
million at 2,268 sites. Disney marketing executive Chuck Viane
noted the animated entry is well-positioned to take advantage of
heavy moviegoing by children on spring vacation during the next
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first weekend this year without a film topping the
$10 million mark. ``The weekend is not a disaster, but it is
disappointing,'' said movie analyst Arthur Rockwell. ``The new
films clearly fell short of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
said ``EDtv'' faced numerous obstacles including lack of a major
star, holdover competition from ``Forces of Nature'' and ``Analyze
This'' and the problem of selling a movie similar to Jim Carrey's
hit ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does pay to be first,'' he noted, adding that
``EDtv'' _ a Ron Howard film once seen as a potential hit for the
troubled studio _ will be hard-pressed to top $30 million by the
end of its domestic run. ``The Truman Show'' is 101st on the
all-time list with U.S. grosses of $126.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Universal marketing chief Nikki Rocco expressed optimism, noting
exit polling showed above-average scores and pointing out that
movies directed by Howard tend to perform well following their
opening weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, a former MGM executive, said ``Mod Squad'' represented
the weekend's biggest disappointment following an extensive
campaign aimed at teen and young adult customers. ``They had high
hopes it was going to be a hit but it looks like it's going to be
in home video before we know it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' drew a 33 percent boost from its seven
Academy Awards, including Best Picture, as it finished sixth with
$4 million at 1,931 theaters, 526 more than last weekend. Its
overall gross has hit $79 million after 108 days for Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Warner's second weekend of Death Row drama ``True Crime'' fell
37 percent in sixth place to $3.3 million at 1,852 theaters,
followed by Miramax's expanded run of ``Life Is Beautiful'' with $3
million at 1,121 sites as the studio added 474 theaters to take
advantage of its three Oscars. ``Life Is Beautiful'' has now
grossed $40.4 million after 23 weeks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's third weekend of ``Baby Geniuses'' continued to overcome
poor reviews in ninth with $2.7 million at 1,702 theaters, followed
by its fourth weekend of ``Cruel Intentions'' with $2.4 million at
1,951 locations. Warner's second weekend of ``The King and I'' lost
half its audience to finish 11th with $2 million at 2,352 sites.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with five Oscars including
Best Director, matched its gross from last weekend with $1 million
at 655 theaters to push its total to $211.7 million. ``Ryan''
trails ``Aladdin'' by $5.3 million for the 21st spot on the
all-time domestic chart.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's romantic drama ``A Walk on the Moon'' posted solid
results in a limited opening with $73,000 at seven theaters.
British romantic comedy ``Among Giants'' grossed $14,000 at two
sites for Fox Searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   Overall grosses hit about $68 million, down about 20 percent
from the same weekend a year ago when the 15th weekend of
``Titanic'' led the box office. Year-to-date grosses have topped
$1.2 billion, trailing the 1998 period by about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two new movies will open Wednesday _ Sony's sci-fi thriller
``The Matrix'' and Disney's teen comedy ``10 Things I Hate About
You'' _ while Paramount will debut romantic comedy ``The
Out-of-Towners'' on Friday. Bucksbaum said ``The Matrix'' and ``10
Things'' should perform well due to the usual upsurge in moviegoing
by teens and young adults during spring break with each taking in
about $15 million on the Friday-Sunday weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
