<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-FLOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVES OF HUMANITY JOIN EXODUS FROM KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN, KEVIN CULLEN AND CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Nearly 15,000 refugees flooded over a remote
and desolate border from Kosovo into Albania Sunday, a desperate
wave of humanity that spelled a costly calamity for Europe's
poorest nation.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more ethnic Albanians streamed across the border at
Blace, Macedonia, telling stories of terror, expulsion, extortion,
and murder at the hands of Serbian forces in a campaign that
expanded dramatically after NATO launched a bombing campaign in
hopes of halting a year of systematic violence in Kosovo, a
province of Yugoslavia. Some refugees begged NATO to send in ground
troops to end what they called a wholesale slaughter and ``ethnic
cleansing'' of Kosovar Albanian villages.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kula Pass into Montenegro, still more walked across the
border in a steady stream, emerging as silhouettes of misery and
fear through a thick fog. Most were afraid to say anything.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than half a million people have been displaced
inside Kosovo, according to United Nations figures.
</P>
<P>
   At the Albanian border, ``it's getting out of control,'' said
Andrea Angelli, spokesman for the Organization on Security and
Cooperation in Europe, speaking in Tirana, the capital. ``We're not
able to count the people anymore. It's hell up there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees had arrived half-clothed, and some children were
barefoot as they made the grueling journey over the rocky mountain
paths leading from Kosovo to northern Albania, a senior Western
diplomat reported. Many had been ``gathered in groups and herded to
the border'' by Serb forces, the diplomat added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty clearly a concerted effort'' by the Serbs to
drive out the Albanians, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government put the number of refugees there so far
at 20,000, with Sunday's influx the biggest so far, at times
arriving at the rate of 1,000 an hour. In Montenegro, a refugee
official put the number in Albania as high as 24,000, with another
20,000 in Macedonia and 8,000 in Montenegero.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government, however, denied allegations of a
Serbian campaign against ethnic Albanians. Government-run
television carried an interview with Vuk Draskovic, the federal
deputy prime minister, who said it was the Albanians who were
committing atrocities against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that 50 years ago there was 50 percent Serbs in
Kosovo and now only 10 percent? Where are they? Who expelled
them?'' he asked. ``We are victims of combined crimes of NATO and
Albanian terrorists. They are killing hundreds of Serbs right now
in Kosovo. . . . I am telling the truth, so help me God.''
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony of terrified ethnic Albanians fleeing Kosovo
contradicted his claims. Mothers comforted crying children in cars
packed with families fleeing what they said were systematic and
brutal attacks by Serbian forces. Some families fled burning
villages in horse-and-carriages, some on tractors, and some walked
over mountain passes.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories were impossible to verify independently because
there are few international observers or journalists still in
Kosovo, but many accounts suggested that hundreds of ethnic
Albanians had been killed in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid the Serbs will totally cleanse Kosovo,'' said Ilaz
Ramajli, head of the Tirana office of the self-styled Republic of
Kosova.
</P>
<P>
   A small minority of those fleeing were able to bring some
belongings with them, Angelli said. In many cases, Yugoslav
authorities took the refugees' personal items, along with their
identity papers. Those who were able to bring tractors or cars into
Albania had their license tags removed, making it harder to return
home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign that the Serbs don't want them back anymore,''
Angelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Albania _ poor, undeveloped and virtually without paved
roads _ is a formidable border at best. Earlier, Yugoslavs had
closed the few border crossings and mined some of them. But about
five days ago, the Serbs abruptly opened the border and swept the
mines, creating an enforced escape route to funnel ethnic Albanians
out, Angelli and others said.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year-old man, shot while he was still on the Kosovo side of
the border, struggled over the mountains only to die Sunday in an
Albanian hospital, aid workers said. An elderly refugee man also
died of apparent heart failure, and four people arrived wounded at
a border Albanian hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone from the tiny village of Goden fled last week,
telling Western observers in Albania that about 20 schoolteachers
had been shot in front of their students.
</P>
<P>
   A line of refugees more than 4 miles long was making its way
from the Kosovar town of Pec to the Montenegro border, Ramajli
said. He said the report, given via telephone by a witness to the
scene, had not yet been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   In Montenegro, several who had fled from Pec earlier described
their ordeal Sunday through a translator. ``They put a shotgun to
our throats and told us to leave,'' said Burim, a 27-year old
farmer who had fled a village outside Pec. ``They are going
door-to-door and forcing everyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   Besem, 27, who asked that his family not be used, said he had to
leave behind four brothers, his father, and mother, as he escaped
from Pec, the seat of the Serbian Orthodox Church and one of the
areas where Serbs appeared to be concentrating their campaign of
terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid for their lives,'' Besem said. ``The Serbian
police are breaking into houses, taking jewelry, televisions,
everything they can get their hands on. It seems like they will
kill everyone who doesn't leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the NATO air attacks have accelerated the Serb forces'
efforts to drive Albanians from Kosovo, most refugees interviewed
said they supported the airstrikes, because they believed
Milosevic's ethnic cleansing campaign had been building for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is trying to save us. They had to act,'' said Besem.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the airstrikes had not triggered a spasm of new violence
he said, the only difference would have been that ``it would mean
those who are dead lived one month longer.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Western diplomat in Skopje, the Macedonian capital,
said he had heard from a source in Kosovo by cellular phone that
5,000 to 7,000 refugees were walking from Podujevo to Pristina, a
trek of about 20 miles.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, the number of people crossing the border increased
dramatically Sunday after two days of trickling numbers. Border
guards estimated that at least 3,000 refugees crossed Sunday, most
of them going on to stay with family or friends in Skopje, the
Macedonian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees told similar tales of misery, of being confronted
in their homes at gunpoint by Serb troops and paramilitary police
who gave them five minutes to flee with the clothes on their backs
and whatever else they could grab. The refugees also said that Serb
forces demanded 100 deutsche marks to allow them to proceed on the
road that leads south from Pristina, the Kosovo capital, to the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yugoslavia contends that the offensive being carried
out by some 40,000 Serb forces is aimed at crushing the rebels of
the Kosovo Liberation Army, many fleeing civilians reported being
driven from their homes at gunpoint, and some had seen neighbors
summarily executed. Few would give their names, saying they feared
retaliation, especially against family members still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They killed people in my street,'' one man said. ``They were
cutting people's throats, shooting them.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who said he was from Prizren in southwest Kosovo, drove
into Macedonia with his three children, wife and mother. He said
paramilitary police just 2 miles inside the border stopped him and
said they would shoot him if he didn't give them money to drive on.
He was angry that NATO had not followed up its bombing campaign by
sending troops into Kosovo to halt the killings and destruction of
Albanian villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shame on NATO,'' said the man, before driving off in anger
when a TV crew ignored his pleas not to photograph him.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian leaders Sunday were pleading for an aggressive step-up
in the NATO assault to incapacitate Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it is a worse situation,'' Ramajli said. ``But if NATO
had not bombed, this situation would have happened anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   President Meidani pleaded for an ``acceleration'' of NATO
action, including ground troops _ an option that NATO governments
have resisted because of the greater possibility of Western
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the United States and its President are as popular in
Albania as they are hated in non-Kosovar Serbia. City buses in
Tirana sported American flags.
</P>
<P>
   While Serbs held anti-American demonstrations in other
countries, 10,000 Albanians gathered in Skanderbeg Square in Tirana
to congratulate NATO. American flags unfurled alongside Albanian
flags, and signs said, ``Grateful to America,'' and ``Clinton:
Champion of Freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
This account was compiled from reports by Globe staff reporters
Kevin Cullen in Macedonia and Charles M. Sennott in Yugoslavia, and
correspondent Susan Milligan in Albania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
