</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-DEFIANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNED US AIRCRAFT BECOMES SYMBOL OF DEFIANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ The Serbian government-controlled
television carried images of a downed and burning American Stealth
fighter nearly all day Sunday, making it a symbol of Serb defiance
against NATO's punishing airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds at a virulently anti-American street rally in this
city, the capital of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, cheered
triumphantly when speakers mentioned the downed jet, which
overnight became a fulfillment of President Slobodan Milosevic's
nationalist prophecies of a holy war to defend the Serbs' beloved
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our victory. We showed to the whole world that we
will defend ourselves,'' said Zeljko Kanezevic, 20, amid the angry
chants of 800 demonstrators outside the American Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every Serb feels Kosovo is its cradle. We will not give that
up at any price,'' he said, just after the crowd had pelted the
entrance to the building with rocks and bottles. It houses an
organization funded in part by the US Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the pro-Milosevic rally unfurled an enormous red
banner that draped down the front of the building, which featured
the Serbian Orthodox cross with a Cyrillic letter ``S'' in the four
corners of the crucifix. The letters stand for the nationalist
creed, ``Only unity saves Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You thought you were invincible, America, but you were wrong
about Serbians. We may not be able to defeat you, but we will never
give up our holy land without giving our blood to defend it,'' said
Jano Selevic, 22, at the rally. Although he has finished his
military service, he, like many young men here, said he is
volunteering to reenlist and fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo conflict has stewed in a cauldron of ethnic,
nationalist, and religious hatreds, and now it has boiled over.
Understanding its roots requires understanding what Kosovo means to
the Serbian national identity, for Kosovo is not only the ancestral
home of the Serbian people, it is their holy land. There are 500
monuments sacred to Christians across the rugged mountainous
terrain of Kosovo, which is roughly the size of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those roots, however, its population has changed
dramatically in the last 300 years. Ethnic Albanians began arriving
in Kosovo in large numbers in the 18th and 19th centuries. Before
the Serbs began their ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign, Kosovo was
nearly 90 percent ethnic Albanian. The Serbs, fueled by the Serbian
nationalist dreams of Milosevic, now seek to reclaim the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is a holy place for the Serbs,'' said the Montenegrin
government's religion minister, Slobodan Tomovic. ``Just like
Jerusalem is for the Jews, Kosovo is their identity, and it is what
binds them together.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's historical name is ``Kosovo Metojia,'' which roughly
translated means ``land of the church.'' Today, nationalists
commonly use the name ``Kosmet,'' combining the two words.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has played on these emotional religious ties to Kosovo
to build his nationalist political power base. His father was a
Christian theologian, but to advance his political career under
former Yugoslav Communist leader Josip Broz Tito, he downplayed his
religious background for decades.
</P>
<P>
   But when communism collapsed and many Serbs began returning to
the church, he resurrected his religious background.
</P>
<P>
   How well his political strategy succeeded is evident in the
offices of the newspaper ``Dan,'' a new voice of Milosevic's rising
Serbian nationalism. There, icons of Christian saints are hung
alongside portraits of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationalism is religion and religion is nationalism,'' said
Vlado Ashanin, the newspaper's editor. ``Our history tells us that
the defense of our country is everything. It purifies our soul to
fight for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashanin, like almost all Serbian nationalists, even teenagers on
the street, harkens back to centuries of history to explain the
importance of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the Battle of Kosovo in 1389, when Serbs valiantly but
futilely tried to defend Kosovo from the conquering Turks. The
battle is referred to as ``The Glorious Defeat,'' and many
nationalists make comparisons between that battle and NATO's
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the same battle, just a new superpower,'' said Ashanin.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1989, on the 600th anniversary of the battle, that
Milosevic chose to launch the political platform that brought about
his ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago,'' said Milka Tadic, managing editor of the
respected and independent news magazine Monitor, ``we signed a pact
with the devil, with Milosevic . . . and now we are paying the
price.''
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that the United States initially supported
Milosevic and assisted his rise to power. ``The supporting of
Milosevic was a stupid illusion of the West,'' she said. ``I
believe in the goodwill of the US, but they look for quick
solutions. They don't understand the complexity. So their solutions
unravel, and then we are left with all the mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who came to worship at services in the 19th century
church of St. George Sunday, the mood was strikingly different from
that of the political rally, and several expressed indignation at
Milosevic's push to merge religion and nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Said Anna Provic, 23, a college student in economics, ``These
are just people who use religion to grab power. That is not true
faith. That is politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
