<HEADER>
A7408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-28 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TAMPA, Fla. _ The introductions were made, the crowd cheered and
suddenly flashing across the middle of the floor was a muscular kid
who seemed to play the basketball like a yo-yo.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth. Dribble here, bring it back. Around the world,
walk the dog, play the trapeze. Fake a pass, go through the legs,
go behind the back.
</P>
<P>
   He zipped a pass to a gangly looking 6-foot-11 stringbean who
you wouldn't guess had a single muscle in his body, until you saw
what happened next. The stringbean leaped high above the rim,
pumped his arms and softly tossed the ball off the backboard and
through the net.
</P>
<P>
   Next possession.
</P>
<P>
   The muscular kid strips the ball free from a pack of players and
zips back up the floor. This time, to his left is the stringbean
and running the wing to the right is a 6-7 youngster who looks like
a cross between French Lick, Ind., and Mayberry RFD.
</P>
<P>
   The kid has tousled hair and freckles, but a game that clearly
has been carefully groomed with hours of practice in a quiet gym
and long nights studying the great ones on videotape.
</P>
<P>
   He catches the pass, stops to read the defense, ball-fakes,
drives, steps back and pops a sweet jumper.
</P>
<P>
   The world said hello to Jason Williams, Casey Sanders and
Michael Dunleavy on Sunday in the Nike Hoop Summit all-star game
between America's best under-20 basketball talent and the best
players from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The world said hello to Duke's future. As if it really needs
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich get richer,'' one sideline fan marveled during the
USA's 107-95 victory over the international stars at the Martinez
Center.
</P>
<P>
   But this is more than the rich simply getting richer. This is
Bill Gates winning the Powerball jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   How much is too much?
</P>
<P>
   As Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski sat with the nation's media Sunday
afternoon on the eve of today's national championship game with
Connecticut, he seemed almost embarrassed when he talked about this
Blue Devils team being one of the youngest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the ages of our guys,'' he said, ``they're
just kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Devils center and leading scorer Elton Brand is a
sophomore. Point guard William Avery is a sophomore. Forward Shane
Battier is a sophomore. Super-sub Corey Maggette is a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, of the eight regular contributors to Duke's 37-1 and
thus far overwhelmingly dominant season, seven are underclassmen.
The only senior is Trajan Langdon and the only other player likely
to depart after this season is Brand, the 1999 NCAA player of the
year and a certain NBA lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is depth,'' Krzyzewski said. ``We have some very
talented players and a lot of them can do a lot of things. There's
nobody who comes off the bench with a more talented player than
Maggette. There's just not.''
</P>
<P>
   As Krzyzewski spoke, across Tampa Bay at the Martinez Center
were Williams, Sanders and Dunleavy _ all three McDonald's All
Americans _ warming up for the elite international all-star game
and dreaming about just how much more dominant these Blue Devils
might get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great joining that team next year,'' Sanders
said. ``It's going to be a challenge. They're having a great year,
and we're going into a good situation. When a coach like
(Krzyzewski) offers you a scholarship to Duke, `no' isn't the first
thing that comes to your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As dominant as the Blue Devils appear to be now, the prospects
only seem brighter for 2000, 2001 and beyond, which only four years
ago might have been hard to believe. After a 13-18 season in 1995,
the Blue Devils went 18-13 and tied for fourth in the ACC in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It was then when Krzyzewski re-evaluated his recruiting
strategies and placed more emphasis on getting to know players
earlier in their careers. He began emphasizing the early-signing
period for players and targeted only a handful of players every
year, rather than a dozen or more.
</P>
<P>
   The results were clear in the 1996 Nike Hoop Summit _ Brand,
Battier and Avery all played in that game.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Krzyzewski has stayed with his select few targets.
And won.
</P>
<P>
   In will come Williams, a 6-2 point guard from Plainfield, N.J.,
who many consider the best ball-handler and playmaker in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In will come Sanders, a 6-11 forward and center who many compare
to San Antonio Spurs center David Robinson. Sanders is a late
bloomer who picked up basketball in the eighth grade. He is a
supreme shot-blocker, once rejecting 19 in a single game, runs the
floor well, defends and possesses a deadly jumper.
</P>
<P>
   In will come Dunleavy, the skilled son of Portland Trail Blazers
coach Mike Dunleavy, and a player whose skills are surpassed only
by his knowledge of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys we have here and those (recruits) are as good as
there's ever been at Duke,'' Krzyzewski said. ``We'll have to see
how it all works out, but it's a very promising group.''
</P>
<P>
   A promising future. As if Duke needs one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
