<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-TOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALTH'S HOMETOWN DIVIDED ON US ROLE IN YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMOGORDO, N.M. _ In this town dominated by the US Air Force,
the people who work on base and off do not hesitate before claiming
the Stealth fighter pilot downed in Yugoslavia as one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Along with 250 or so support troops deployed from Holloman Air
Force Base, he has their support and their prayers for a safe
return home.
</P>
<P>
   But Alamogordo's united front crumbles there.
</P>
<P>
   While some people are gung-ho about America's involvement in the
Balkans, others insist that the military personnel never should
have left home late last month. Even some retired officers say they
would rather the United States sit out the latest conflict to call
for Alamogordo's fighter planes and expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost lost a member of the family, and for what?'' asked
Randy Highland, who recently retired as a technical sergeant after
20 years in the Air Force and seven Easters away from his own
family. ``I just don't think we should be sticking our neck out on
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Added his wife, Donna Highland, a secretary at a local church,
``We're everybody's big brother. But we have nothing to do with
this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But others disagreed just as adamantly with the idea of staying
put. Likening Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to Adolf
Hitler, a few all but demanded that the United States play a part
in ending the ethnic cleansing of Yugoslavia's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say how far you should go, but there's always
going to be killing on both sides,'' said Hank Clovis, a retired
chief master sergeant who was passing through Alamogordo Sunday.
``If you save one life, you have to believe it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Six hours after his plane went down, the still-unidentified
pilot was rescued by a US military search-and-rescue team. But the
Air Force has not yet determined whether the American F-117 was
shot down by Serbian air defenses or malfunctioned, or whether
pilot error was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stealth continues to be the weapon of choice,'' Brigadier
General William J. Lake, commander of the 49th Fighter Wing, said
at a news conference held at the base. ``They're not invulnerable.
They're not invisible. They're by no means a cure-all or 100
percent inviolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake said the Air Force will rely primarily on the pilot to
determine what happened in the night sky, since the burned plane
cannot be recovered. He also said he is not overly concerned that
America's enemies will be able to copy the crashed Stealth's unique
makeup. ``I'm not sure anyone can do a lot with a pile of rubble,''
he said. ``I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alamogordo, eight miles from the Holloman base, air mishaps
are understood. The base has been here in the shadow of the
Sacramento Mountains since 1942. The Stealth, also known as the
F-117A Nighthawk, was built in secret and moved to Holloman in the
summer of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone remembers when one of the jets crashed that
August, a crash attributed in part to pilot error and in part to an
inexperienced maintenance crew. Of the 54 original jets, 50 remain,
including the 11 now left to fly out of the base in Aviano, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people eating at the fast-food and family-style
restaurants along the town's main strip say they were stunned to
hear that one of the planes in the ``Black Sheep'' squadron was
downed. After their success in Operation Desert Storm, when none of
the planes were even nicked, they describe themselves as feeling
almost invincible. Saturday's crash was the first time the Air
Force lost a Stealth fighter in combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a guy goes up, you know there's that chance,'' said
Marc Murray, a manager at the base research lab. ``After the Gulf
War, I guess we felt like no one could touch us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Murray says America has to be involved in this fight. So
does Scott Newton, a US Border Patrol employee who calls it the
moral position to take. But others say the conflict has been going
on too long _ and will go on long after the United States pulls out
_ to risk the life of even one young man or woman from Alamogordo,
especially without the commitment of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``By us being there, we're only making them more hostile,'' said
Paul Jackson, a building contractor who has a son in the Army.
``Why can't the US stay out of it and let Great Britain handle it
and let someone else take the fall? They're not going to solve
anything there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
