<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-EMBASSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US EMBASSY IN MOSCOW COMES UNDER ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian police and masked gunmen exchanged fire outside
the US Embassy Sunday after assailants tried to fire a grenade
launcher at the building, scattering hundreds of demonstrators
protesting NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt, but the daytime attack on a busy street
highlighted the way virulent anti-American sentiment in Moscow has
spilled out in the open since the US-led alliance began bombing
Yugoslavia last week.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO airstrikes have drawn bitter attacks from the Kremlin,
the Russian media, and politicians from liberals to hardline
Communists and nationalists. The US Embassy has become the
epicenter of raucous daily protests.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's gun battle ensued when a man in camouflage and a ski
mask and brandishing a hand-held grenade launcher stepped out of a
white jeep parked across the busy road in front of the embassy.
Dramatic footage replayed on Russian television showed the
assailant attempt to fire the weapon. Police standing guard at the
demonstration saw the gunman and opened fire. The gunman dropped
the weapon and jumped in the vehicle, and someone in the jeep
returned fire with a machine gun as the vehicle raced away.
</P>
<P>
   The jeep was later found, but the assailants got away. Russia's
interior minister ordered security around embassies stepped up. The
protests outside the embassy resumed after Sunday's gunfight behind
a phalanx of riot troops in flak jackets and helmets.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's attack bore similarities to a 1995 incident in which
the embassy was hit by a rocket-propelled grenade, during protests
over NATO bombings of Serb forces in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have soured again since last year's economic collapse
in Russia, this time accompanied by growing resentment of the
United States by ordinary Russians, who blame US-sponsored reforms
for their economic troubles. For many Russians, the NATO attack was
the final straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say of a country that bombs innocent people with
no regard for that law?'' cried a protester who gave only his first
name, Albert. ``We have tried the American way in Russia for seven
years, and we reject it.''
</P>
<P>
   With parliamentary elections coming up in December,
anti-Americanism is likely to be a popular campaign theme.
Government leaders have said they want to avoid actions that would
lead to open confrontation with the West, especially as Moscow
seeks loans to see it through the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said the incident
``throws a shadow on Russia, which is currently undertaking titanic
efforts to solve the crisis around Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuters quoted a US official in Washington as saying Russian
authorities were cooperating in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of the increasingly ugly mood toward America, two
leading Russian politicians characterized the attack as a
legitimate response to NATO airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is normal. Many people are filling with hatred toward
Americans,'' ultranationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky told NTV
television. He said the US Embassy qualified as ``an enemy
installation'' and predicted further violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Zyuganov, head of Russia's Communist Party, said NATO's
airstrikes amounted to ``state terrorism'' and that under such
circumstances, ``partisan tactics'' were to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zhirinovsky's party and the Communists have called for
Russia to send arms and volunteer soldiers to Yugoslavia to aid the
Serbs, Orthodox Christian Slavs like many the majority of Russia's
population.
</P>
<P>
   Russian volunteers interviewed last week said that by helping
Yugoslavia fight off NATO, they would be defending Russia from
further advances by the Western alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
