<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LEADALL-BOS &LR;      03-28 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LEADALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SHIFTS FOCUS, TARGETS RAMPAGING SERBS IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO warplanes unleashed the fiercest strike yet
against Serb ground forces in Kosovo Sunday, as US and allied
officials warned that marauding Serb military units have launched a
full-scale campaign of murder and intimidation to drive ethnic
Albanian civilians from the separatist province.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing concern that much of the Balkan region could be
destabilized by the Kosovo conflict, the United States and Britain
boosted their commitment of air power to combat what President
Clinton called a Serbian campaign of ``inhumane violence.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said they are rapidly shifting the mission's
focus from hammering Yugoslavia's nationwide air defense system to
pounding Serb forces in Kosovo in a ``race against time'' to spare
ethnic Albanian civilians from further atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO assault in Kosovo heightens the risk to allied pilots,
the day after an American Stealth fighter-bomber went down near the
Yugoslav capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   After a daring rescue, the unidentified pilot was reported to be
in good condition Sunday at Aviano air base in Italy and helping
authorities determine the cause of the crash. There were
indications the jet was shot down by a surface-to-air missile, and
General Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
Yugoslavia's air defense system remains potent enough to be ``very
dangerous'' to NATO pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and allied officials said NATO would not be deterred
despite the potential for additional losses or the images Sunday of
Serbs dancing joyfully on the wreckage of the American aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize that we are on the brink of a major
humanitarian disaster in Kosovo, the likes of which have not been
seen in Europe since the closing stages of World War II,'' NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea said at a news conference in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton said, ``The continued brutality and
repression of the Serb forces further underscores the need for NATO
to persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   As the humanitarian situation in Kosovo deteriorated, NATO
officials said Serb troops, police and armed gangs loyal to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic have accelerated their
``scorched earth policy'' of ``ethnic cleansing'' since the NATO
operation began last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb brutality against ethnic Albanians has included the
murders of 20 teachers, a prominent lawyer and his sons, and an
unspecified number of trade unionists, according to NATO reports.
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the 2 million
residents of the Serbian province of Kosovo, are being used as
human shields by Serb forces, according to NATO reports.
</P>
<P>
   The growing violence has stunned many allied leaders who
expected the massive NATO airstrikes to curb the alleged war
crimes. But Clinton said he saw no link between the NATO mission
and the increased brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said, when a reporter asked if the allied
bombing is ``driving the atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the mayhem, refugees continued to flee Kosovo by the tens
of thousands, flooding into struggling countries that are
ill-equipped to handle them. With an estimated 500,000 ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo already driven from their homes, authorities in
neighboring Albania and Macedonia appealed for international aid to
prevent a humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian officials also joined the Kosovo Liberation Army in
calling for NATO to send groups to battle the Serb forces, a
proposal that NATO has studied and so far rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said NATO has determined that waging an infantry
offensive against the Serbs ``would involve hundreds of thousands
of ground troops over a rather protracted period of time and in a
very dangerous situation. So there is no political agreement to do
that short of a peace settlement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several US senators said Sunday on network news shows that they
expect the NATO bombing to continue for at least several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As a fifth straight night of bombing began, the Pentagon
announced it will add as many as 12 more planes, including
long-range bombers, to the 200 American aircraft participating in
NATO's first offensive operation in its 50-year history. Britain
said it will increase its contribution from eight to 20 warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Serb military aircraft have flown ``each day in the areas of
ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo, Air Commodore David Wilby told
reporters at NATO headquarters. But Wilby said NATO's new focus on
the Serb operations in Kosovo will alter the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Allied forces flew 253 sorties Saturday night and early Sunday
in the fourth round of bombing, striking 17 targets throughout
Yugoslavia, including military and police headquarters in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night and early Monday, the bombing mission was
supplemented by missile fired by B-52 bombers. The Kosovo
Liberation Army's news agency said NATO aircraft attacked a
Yugoslav army column in central Kosovo and destroyed four tanks.
There also were reports of NATO forces hitting an airport in the
Serbian city of Nis and of a huge explosion near the Kosovo border
with Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict continued to provoke demonstrations and violent
protests around the world, including a daylight assault on the US
Embassy in Moscow by men firing assault weapons and grenade
launchers. The assailants were driven away by police, and no
injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators also burned American flags and lobbed pieces of
concerete at the US consulate in Sydney, Australia. Riot police
used tear gas to disperse a similar demonstration in front of the
US Embassy in Paris. Other protests occurred across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav leaders, in separate interviews on Russian and American
TV, denied committing genocide against ethnic Albanians. They also
accused NATO of wrongfully helping ethnic Albanians seek autonomy
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO mission is aimed at focing Milosevic to accept a peace
settlement that would grant Kosovo autonomy. The agreement ``has
been accepted by the Kosovo Albanian community,'' said Shea, the
NATO spokesman, ``and I hope the people who signed it are still
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials rejected the denials of ethnic cleansing.
``This bloodbath has been carried out by Milosevic over a period of
years,'' said Defense Secretary William S. Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few, small signs of hope for a truce in the
conflict, three Russian politicians met with US envoy Richard
Holbrooke in Hungary Sunday on their way to a possible meeting in
Belgrade with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin, who has expressed outrage at
NATO's military intervention, has said he wants to mediate an end
to the showdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2229EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
