<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BASEBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL DIPLOMACY BRINGS MAJOR LEAGUERS TO CUBA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ It was only batting practice, but the nearly 50,000
fans who packed Estadio Latinoamericano Sunday were already on
their feet, cheering Baltimore Orioles slugger Albert Belle, who
had slammed three straight balls over the right field fence and
into the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this crowd,'' said Orioles pitcher Sidney Ponson.
``This is Latin America. They know, and we know, that this is a
historic game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Major Leagues returned to this baseball-crazed country for
the first time in 40 years Sunday as the Orioles defeated the Cuban
all-star team 3-2 in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the game was just an exhibition, for many Cuban players
and fans, it carried all the weight of a seventh game of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this even though I'm very disappointed that
we lost,'' said Omar Linares, the Cuban third baseman who is widely
described as the country's best ballplayer. ``This has been a very
emotional experience for me. I hope we can do something like this
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro, who calls himself the country's
greatest baseball fan, was also in attendance. Before the game, he
strode across the diamond to greet the players as the crowd chanted
``Fi-del.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath large outfield signs that proclaimed baseball
as ``Cuba's Socialist Sport,'' the two teams stood in a line next
to their respective flags.
</P>
<P>
   Castro stood for both the Cuban and American national anthems
and watched the game from a front-row seat, next to baseball
Commissioner Bud Selig and Orioles owner Peter Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an absolute fan of the game,'' Angelos said after the
game, adding that the communist leader asked many questions about
professional baseball, including one about players' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   All of the tickets for the game were issued by invitation only,
a sore point for many passionate fans who had to follow the game on
television or radio. The handpicked crowd was also more polite and
subdued than those who who came to the stadium Friday and Saturday
to see the national playoffs between Havana and its archrival
Santiago. Gone, for the most part, were the hecklers, the music,
and hip-shaking dances that often go nonstop from the first inning
to the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel the same as it usually does,'' said Maria
Carmen Romero, who sat along the first-base line with her husband
and 12-year-old son. ``We might be more animated if we were
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were moments when the crowd erupted in
eardrum-piercing joy, like the time Linares slapped a line drive
that scored the tying run in the bottom of the eighth inning, or
when the Cuban team appeared poised to win in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles sealed the victory in the top of the 11th, when
designated hitter Harold Baines smacked an RBI single into right
field, scoring first baseman Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   For many older Cuban fans, Sunday's game brought back memories
of the days when this tropical city was home to the Triple-A Havana
Sugar Kings, and when major league teams regularly held spring
training exhibitions here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a knife in my soul when they stopped playing
here,'' said Juan Carlos Posadas, a 66-year-old mechanic. ``I've
waiting a long time to see something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The last professional game played in Cuba was in March 1959,
when the Los Angeles Dodgers, led by eight strikeouts by Sandy
Koufax, beat the Cincinnati Reds 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Castro-inspired Communist revolution that same year, and
the US economic embargo that followed, ended those baseball ties.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game, as well as a second game May 3 at Baltimore's
Camden Yards, were made possible when President Clinton relaxed
some of the restrictions in January.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles owner Angelos said that despite the criticism he has
received, mostly from Cuban-Americans, for his decison to play in
Cuba, he was confident other teams would follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that what we've begun here will grow for other teams,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although that prospect is less than certain, Juan Antonio Reyes
thinks it would benefit both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the hitters and we have the pitchers and fielders,''
said Reyes, 29. ``We have much to teach each other about
baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
