<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      03-28 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NATO WARPLANES BROADED ATTACK; US VOWS TO PERSEVERE WITHOUT GROUND
TROOPS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ NATO dispatched more firepower Sunday against Serb
military units, a new phase in the air attacks that allied
officials said is spurred by reports of stepped-up atrocities
against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the air assault entered a fifth day, the Clinton
administration again said there were no plans to use ground troops
in Kosovo and rejected calls to arm the Kosovo Liberation Army to
fend off the Yugoslav army, options some senators urged the
president to leave open.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees, recounting
scenes of Serb brutality, fled into neighboring Albania and
Macedonia, prompting officials to plead for international help to
avert a humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said there are as
many as 18,000 Serb troops now massing an offensive against the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, the southernmost province of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are terrible reports about ... men being separated from
women and children, then they're being taken off and executed,
villages being torched, people arriving across the border with no
shoes, and literally told to leave their villages,'' Albright said
on CBS' Face the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton said the NATO bombing
would continue until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ends the
``inhumane violence'' in Kosovo. Following a meeting with his
national security team, Clinton told reporters ``the continued
brutality and repression of the Serb forces further underscores the
need for NATO to persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   As he headed toward Marine One for a flight to Camp David, the
president was asked if the air attacks might have prompted
Milosevic to step up the brutality in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Clinton snapped.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether the bombing might be driving the ethnic
brutality was raised earlier with Albright, who dismissed the
assertion. ``That is just simply an upside down argument to think
that NATO or we have made this get worse,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is the one that is to blame,'' Albright said. ``He
is the one that is making it worse and what we were trying to do is
to make sure that he pays the heaviest price for what he is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if an air assault alone could cripple the paramilitary
units involved in the atrocities, Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen repeated Clinton's position that he has no intention
of sending ground troops to Kosovo unless the Serbs agree to the
peace deal already signed by ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a peace settlement, then he has indicated we'd be
prepared to contribute a small amount of a peace-keeping force, of
the total, but absent that, we're going to continue with the air
campaign,'' Cohen said on NBC's Meet the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
on CNN that it would take ``hundreds of thousands of ground troops
over a rather protracted period of time and in a very dangerous
situation'' to invade Yugoslavia and forcefully stop the Serb
repression of the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who chairs the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said he has never heard of a war ``that's been won
totally by air power.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who was a prisoner of war in Vietnam,
said the United States has ``to exercise every option'' once it
gets into armed conflict. ``We have to do whatever it takes,'' said
McCain, a possible GOP presidential candidate. ``All of us would
grieve at the loss of a single American. But when you go into these
things the primary purpose cannot be the safety of your forces, it
has to be the achievement of your strategic and tactical goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., agreed that airstrikes alone
will not stop the genocide but said fighting on the ground should
be left to ethnic Albanians, who should be supplied with arms by
the U.S. and its NATO partners. ``Clearly you can't stop the kind
of slaughter and terrorism on the ground without some contradictory
opposing force on the ground,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials ruled out involvement in any ground war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue this campaign as long as it is necessary,
until the job is finished,'' said Sandy Berger, the president's
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon late Sunday said that the United States, which
already has about 200 warplanes in Operation Allied Force, would be
assigning between six and 12 more aircraft _ including some B-52
long-range bombers _ to aid in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As Sunday's bombing began under overcast skies, officials at the
Pentagon and NATO headquarters in Brussels declined to discuss
details from the downing Saturday of the Air Force F-117A stealth
fighter-bomber near the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted an unnamed defense official as
saying there were strong indications the F-117 was hit by a
surface-to-air missile. The official said there was no reported
mechanical problem with the aircraft but an explosion was heard.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to name the U.S. pilot or to provide
information from Saturday night's six-hour mission to rescue him
from behind enemy lines. Officials said the pilot was in good
condition at Aviano Air Base in Italy and helping Air Force
investigators determine what disabled his aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's air attacks by U.S. and NATO aircraft broadened to
target Serb forces blamed for the atrocities, raised the risk to
NATO pilots but also increased the chance for slowing Yugoslavia's
ground offensive against the insurgent Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at an expanded set of targets and we're going to
go more intensively after some targets,'' said NATO Commander Gen.
Wesley Clark, a U.S. Army general.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO airstrikes were launched Wednesday after Milosevic, a
Serbian nationalist who presides over the Yugoslav republic,
refused to enter into a peace agreement with the majority ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, the largest Serb province. Serbia is the main
republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, U.N. officials report more than 500,000 ethnic
Albanians, about one-fourth of Kosovo's population, have been
driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Independent verification of information coming from Kosovo _ or
from other regions of Yugoslavia _ has become impossible in the
past week since foreign journalists have not been allowed into the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia denied claims that paramilitary units under the
direction of Milosevic were committing genocide or ``ethnic
cleansing'' operations against ethnic Albanians who, before the
exodus, made up 90 percent of the population of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the unity of the 19-nation NATO alliance appeared to
soften Sunday as Portugal joined Italy and Greece in calling for an
early resumption of talks with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said his country had
``always been supportive of our allies and we understand the need
to intervene to prevent a humanitarian catastrophe.'' At the same
time, he said, ``any window of opportunity'' to restart talks on
the future of Kosovo should be seized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
