<SLUG> BC-CAR-TMS-PRIMESTAR500-TEX </SLUG>
 
TERRY LABONTE RETURNS TO TEXAS FOR VICTORY FIXES GARBLE IN LEDE
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Terry Labonte returned to his home state
for a NASCAR Winston Cup test earlier this month, he was an
atypical Texan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You can always tell the people from Texas,'' Labonte said
yesterday, ``because they'll tell you they're from Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case on March 8-9 at Texas Motor Speedway,
where Labonte was the strong and sullen type during one of his
NASCAR-alloted two-day tests. And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't feel like we had a very good test here,'' said
Labonte, referring to himself and crew chief Andy Graves. As the
session deteriorated because of a series of engine and chassis
problems, Labonte nervously paced the vacant garage area. He
dismissed all interview requests with a cold stare. Then he and
Graves went back to their shop at Hendrick Motorsports in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joked about it, testing as bad as we did, we were going to
go back and win the race,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true Texan.
</P>
<P>
   And as of yesterday afternoon, the winner of the third Winston
Cup race at TMS. Strapped into a vintage 1996 version of his No. 5
Kellogg's Chevrolet _ a Monte Carlo resurrected after that lousy
test _ Labonte reeled in and ran down Dale Jarrett to win the
Primestar 500.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Labonte thrilled a TMS-record crowd of 221,861 over
the final 47 of 334 laps around the revamped 1.5-mile quadoval.
Jarrett had the point from Lap 285 to Lap 322, when Labonte ran him
down exiting Turn 4. Running to the outside of Jarrett down the
front stretch, Labonte completed the pass at the start/finish line,
then tucked in front of Jarrett as the lapped car of Chad Little
loomed ahead.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd up and cheering, Labonte had stretched his lead
to eight car lengths when Jimmy Spencer's crash into the
front-stretch wall brought out the day's final caution flag on Lap
332.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Labonte three laps to strut before the home folk,
acknowledge congratulations from Jarrett and brother and
third-place finisher Bobby Labonte _ and reflect upon the ironies
that had produced his 21st career victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went home and thought about it, Andy suggested we
bring this other car back,'' said Labonte, whose most recent
victory had been in Richmond, Va., on June 6. That was 26 races
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the car that won Charlotte in 1996, and propelled us to
the championship.'' said Graves, referring to Labonte's most recent
Cup title season. ``We tore it up in Michigan in 1997 and never got
it back to where it was comfortable. Terry and I decided last week
to bring it. We felt we had a couple of other good cars, but this
was the best one.''
</P>
<P>
   This car was good enough for Labonte to lead five times for a
race-high 124 laps, including the final 12. Labonte began to fill
up Jarrett's rearview mirror on Lap 320, when he drew to within one
car length through turns 1 and 2. Labonte put a yellow quarter
panel on the outside of Jarrett's car exiting Turn 2 on Lap 320 and
snuck a little bit more of Chevy fender there on Lap 321. Those
moves convinced Labonte there was enough of a second groove worked
up high that he could take Jarrett on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought I was going to pass him in Turn 2 on the
outside,'' said Labonte, who led the most laps for the first time
in 1999. ``I was up to his quarter panel, and I was hoping his
spotter was going to say, `There's somebody on your outside.' I
could tell he didn't see me, so I had to get out of the gas and try
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte did so exiting the revamped Turn 4. The pass was
executed high and along the wall, placing Labonte ahead of Jarrett
and below Little. And just in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were running out of laps,'' said Labonte, who has three
top-10 finishes in the Cup races at TMS. ``And it's always easier
when you're in second place and running in traffic and you can see
what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett had played his hand on Lap 276, when he pitted for four
tires and fuel and gambled on winning the race via track position.
But he could not account for late-race lapped traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I could go on my fresh tires, I had some lapped cars that
wanted to go, too,'' said Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality
Care/Ford Credit Taurus. ``So I couldn't stretch out my lead like I
wanted to. But I still thought that maybe if I could use up enough
racetrack I could keep Terry behind me. As I caught one of them in
\Rturns\S 3 and 4, my car pushed up as I tried to get back in the
throttle, and that hurt me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry just got up high and got a run to the outside, and there
was nothing I could do after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the final caution flew, and Jarrett became the
first car in Labonte's extended victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the crowd and they were all standing and cheering,''
Labonte said. ``All the other drivers pulled up beside me and
congratulated me. That's a good feeling. To me, this is the biggest
race I've ever won, to come down here to Texas and win.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true Texan.  &LR; tagtop:John Sturbin, (817) 390-7408
 &LR; tagbottom:sturb &LR; star-telegram.com nn
</P>
</TEXT>
