<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS MAY DISRUPT LOUIMA TRIAL, LAWYERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Daily demonstrations planned for outside the Brooklyn
court where jury selection is to begin Monday in the trial of four
police officers charged with brutalizing Abner Louima could
increase the chance that the trial will be delayed or moved out of
New York City, lawyers for two of the officers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that the demonstrations, which are planned to
begin during the jury selection process, would make impaneling a
fair and impartial jury for the highly controversial case even more
difficult than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers, Joseph Tacopina and Marvyn Kornberg, said that
although U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson denied defense
requests last month for a postponement of the trial or a change of
venue, he also said he would reconsider his ruling if the jury
selection process showed that an impartial jury could not be found.
</P>
<P>
   The requests had been made on the ground that intensive news
coverage of the Louima case and of the recent police killing of
Amadou Diallo in the Bronx had created widespread anti-police
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Al Sharpton, who is planning the demonstrations,
maintained that they would not affect the prospects of impaneling a
jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that you have vigils or demonstrations does
not mean you can't get a fair and impartial jury,'' Sharpton said
Sunday. He added that similar demonstrations he had organized at
other high-profile trials in racially charged cases in New York had
not prevented the impaneling of juries.
</P>
<P>
   Among the trials he cited were the 1987 Queens trial of white
teen-agers stemming from the attack on three black men in Howard
Beach, one of whom, Michael Griffith, was struck and killed by a
car when chased onto the Belt Parkway, and the 1990 Brooklyn trial
of young whites in the fatal shooting of a black youth, Yusuf
Hawkins, in Bensonhurst. Three of the four defendants in the Queens
trial and both in the Brooklyn trial were convicted of various
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Louima, a Haitian immigrant who is black, the
four officers accused of attacking him are white.
</P>
<P>
   All four _ Justin Volpe, Charles Schwarz, Thomas Wiese and
Thomas Bruder _ are accused of beating him in a police car after he
was arrested in a street brawl in Flatbush in August 1997. And
prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn say that
later, at the 70th Precinct station house, Volpe rammed a stick
into Louima's mouth and rectum, causing severe injuries to his
rectum and bladder, while Schwarz held him down. The officers say
the charges are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyer, Tacopina, said that the planned demonstrations
would ``definitely have an effect'' on jury selection and enhance
the possibility of a venue change or a delay. Speaking of
prospective jurors _ as many as 600 are to arrive at the courthouse
Monday to fill out questionnaires _ Tacopina said they could react
to the demonstrations with ``fear and emotion that may cause them
to want not to sit on the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the last highly publicized trial in which he defended
a police officer in the same courthouse, the so-called Morgue Boys
trial in 1995 in which three officers were acquitted of charges
that they systematically robbed Brooklyn residents and drug
dealers, there were no demonstrators. ``We had a jury free to
render a decision without the hindrance of outside taint,''
Tacopina said.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's lawyer, Kornberg, said, ``There's no doubt in my mind
the demonstrations will have an effect on jury selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the demonstrations would involve things like
prayer sessions, but not the sort of civil disobedience actions
like the protests he organized in the Diallo case that have led to
more than 1,000 arrests at police headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
