A7421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SHARPTON-POLICE-NY     03-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SHARPTON-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: PROTEST REBUILDING SHARPTON'S IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Barely a year ago, the Rev. Al Sharpton was viewed in
many quarters as a fading presence, permanently compromised by his
association with Tawana Brawley's discredited story of abduction
and rape. He was on the verge of becoming a caricature of the
disaffected New York protester, shunned by establishment
politicians both white and black.
</P>
<P>
   But in the space of two weeks or so, he has risen yet again,
becoming more influential and prominent than ever before in his
sometimes troubled political career. It is vivid testimony both to
his political resourcefulness and to the way the Amadou Diallo
killing has reshaped the political debate in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The same tragedy that has created the biggest crisis of Rudolph
Giuliani's mayoralty has allowed Sharpton, one of the mayor's most
persistent critics, to step from the margins to the mainstream,
achieving a credibility that would have seemed improbable six
months ago. A broad range of prominent New Yorkers, many of whom
have shunned him in the past, have appeared at his side on the
arrest line at Police Headquarters, praising his efforts in
orchestrating the public response.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence of this mounts each day. As Sharpton was driven to
a police demonstration last week, he took phone calls from Rep.
Eliot Engel of the Bronx, state Senator David Paterson of Harlem
and David Dinkins, the former Mayor, all Democrats seeking his
counsel. Sharpton arrived at 1 Police Plaza to lead a group of 100
chanting rabbis and rabbinical students down the sidewalk to their
arrest. ``Shalom, shalom, shalom!'' Sharpton shouted as his new
friends slipped past the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   He has done what no Democratic candidate has accomplished since
Giuliani, a Republican, came to power. He has assembled the
remnants of the city's once-dominant liberal Democratic coalition
and built upon that foundation. In this, he has enlisted some of
his strongest critics, among them former Mayor Edward Koch, as well
as the older and more orderly generation of black leadership, like
Dinkins and Rep. Charles Rangel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the catalyst,'' said the Rev. Floyd Flake, a former
Democratic congressman and one of the mayor's most prominent
supporters. ``He just stepped in and began the process of trying to
move the agenda, as he does in all these cases. I like to tell
people this is his career. When you look at this situation in
relation to Los Angeles and Rodney King, regardless of what anybody
says about him, his presence and his finding a way to give people a
means to vent probably saved this city from having the same kind of
rioting,'' Flake said. ``I don't know if anybody else could have
done that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, certainly, an element of political piling-on here. The
Diallo tragedy aside, many of the people who have showed up at 1
Police Plaza are united by their dislike for Giuliani and have
seized at the image of him on the political ropes. But more than
just opportunism is at work here. The Diallo shooting has forced a
public examination of how the city police conduct their business,
precisely the issue that Sharpton _ and, not incidentally, Dinkins
and Rangel _ have talked about for years.
</P>
<P>
   With Diallo's death, and the steeply falling crime rate,
warnings about police excesses have new legitimacy. Sharpton sensed
this well before most of the city's political establishment, and
has skillfully made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   This latest up in Sharpton's up-and-down career is also
testimony to his political skills. He has an astute sense of how to
attract attention to himself and to his causes, playing the role of
the passionate if irreverent outsider to great effect.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton has a sense for political theatrics that few can match.
He arranged for Diallo's mother to return from Africa so she could
be present Tuesday when the officers accused of killing her son are
expected to be arraigned. ``Let the mother stand and stare when
they bring them in handcuffs,'' Sharpton said. ``Now that's
drama!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
