<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-ORIOLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BELLE'S A SHOWMAN IN ORIOLES VICTORY IN CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ Albert Belle went 0 for 5 in Sunday's unprecedented
exhibition game between the Baltimore Orioles and a group of select
Cuban players, but he managed to make some new friends.
</P>
<P>
   After putting on an impressive batting-practice session, one
that included more than 10 home runs, most of them deep into the
bleachers, Belle received an ovation from the fans who began filing
into Estadio Latinoamerica five hours before the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they're used to controversy here,'' Belle joked
moments after he smiled and waved to the crowd in a rare display of
interaction with fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, who became the first major league club to play in
Cuba since a pair of exhibition games between Los Angeles and
Cincinnati in 1959, squandered a late two-run lead but came back to
beat Cuba, 3-2, in 11 innings Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The game began with intensity when former Cuban pitcher Conrado
Marrero, now 84 years old, fired the ceremonial first pitches to
Orioles leadoff hitter Brady Anderson, who didn't know it is
customary here to take a swing at one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson finally caught on and fouled off a bunt attempt, and
suddenly two of the archest enemies on the planet were making
history as the United States and Cuba televised the game to all
points in their respective nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all the same, especially on the sports field,'' said
Alfonso Urquiola, who managed Cuba's club. ``We demonstrated Cuba
can play in any league. We have been practicing together for only
two weeks, and look at the type of game we played.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans probably took this game far more seriously than the
Orioles, who didn't have an entire nation hoping and following
their every move the way the Cuban club did.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that hurt us was only having two weeks to
practice together,'' said Jose Ariel Contreras, a strapping
6-foot-3 right-hander who pitched eight scoreless innings in
relief. ``I was anxious because an American professional team was
making its first appearance on our land in 40 years. Now we know we
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are scheduled to meet again May 3 at Baltimore's
Camden Yards. It will be interesting to see if the Cuban club will
be reinforced with key additions from the two teams currently
locked up in Cuba's version of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles catcher Charles Johnson, a favorite of local fans who
was making his third appearance in Cuba, belted a two-run home run
in the bottom of the second inning for the game's first two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore pitcher Scott Erickson, who bent over backward to call
this only a baseball game, pitched six scoreless innings before
allowing one run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba tied the game in the bottom of the eighth when Omar
Linares, arguably the best amateur player in the world, lined a
two-out RBI single to left to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was delighted it was tied,'' Orioles owner Peter Angelos
said of Cuban President Fidel Castro, whom he sat next to for the
entire game. ``He's obviously a fanatic baseball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was decided in the 11th when Harold Baines stroked an
RBI single to center field, the same way he's done on so many other
occasions during his 20-year career.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans, however, viewed the game as a great victory,
especially considering how little time the players worked together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our baseball is strong,'' Linares said. ``We showed we can
play at the same level as the best teams. We can beat them when we
play them again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
