<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODYEAR RACES TO IRL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Great Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Goodyear survived a rash of caution flags, including a
doozy on Lap 149 that put disgruntled front-runners Eddie Cheever
and Buddy Lazier behind the pit wall with busted machinery. Then he
led the final 51 laps and won the MCI WorldCom 200 on Sunday at
Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   It was Goodyear's first career trip into a Pep Boys Indy Racing
League victory lane, and it was worth a tidy $139,600 to the
Canadian driver.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear should bill the IRL an extra $50,000 for hazard pay.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was that wild.
</P>
<P>
   Eight cautions produced 62 laps of stoppage, leaving only 14
cars still running at the checkered flag, only five of which
remained on the lead lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough out there today,'' said runner-up Jeff Ward, who
trailed Goodyear by 4.738 seconds at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a final caution for Roberto Moreno's spin on Lap 192,
it wouldn't have been that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some real big moments out there,'' said third-place
Robbie Buhl, who is getting married next Sunday in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear also had some moments, including one when he
momentarily thought he might be in for a short day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to Turn 3 (and the site of the Cheever-Lazier
wreckage), there wasn't a lane available,'' Goodyear said. ``I
almost ran into the back of (defending champion) Scott Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this might be the Fourth of July all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Goodyear was the beneficiary of an early Christmas
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation where I could have gone home with a
headache or not even gone home,'' said Goodyear, whose best
previous IRL finish was runner-up, which he's done four times.
``Today (Sunday) was my lucky day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, maybe. But Goodyear also was skillfully efficient.
</P>
<P>
   He led twice for 134 laps in the Pennzoil Panther G
Force/Aurora, including Laps 15-96.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat of Glendale was next highest, leading 29 laps
(98-126) and finishing fourth, one position ahead of Scott
Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   And when Boat ducked into the pits on Lap 127 for fuel and fresh
rubber, it was Cheever's turn to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever might have held the lead even longer than he did if not
for the Lap 149 tangle.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cheever was rushing his brain into overdrive in an
attempt to quickly strategize the best way to ease by Harrington,
Harrington suddenly had to ease off the throttle for a slower
machine and inadvertently tapped Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a tap that took on heavy-metal consequences as a
fast-approaching Lazier couldn't slam on the brakes in time to
avoid smacking into Cheever's rear end.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Out went Cheever and Lazier and into the lead went Goodyear,
where he remained despite one final nerve-racking caution flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Man, what's this all about?' '' Goodyear said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever was asking the same question following his exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buddy and I were going at it pretty aggressively, and there
were slower cars not looking in their mirrors,'' Cheever said.
``It's silly when you come up to a car you've lapped a few times
and they don't move over.''
</P>
<P>
   Silly and costly.
</P>
<P>
   For Ward, finishing second in front of an estimated crowd of
about 15,000 wasn't such a bad thought, considering where he was
less than two weeks ago: unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Ward had left former employer ISM Racing and had only recently
signed with car owner Allan Pagan, whose original intent was to
race only at the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   But Ward, who was joined at Pagan Racing by several former ISM
employees, including crew chief/engineer Mitch Davis, had other
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happened quickly,'' Ward said. ``We decided we needed
to be here and try and get some points. Not having points doesn't
look good when you're trying to attract sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll sit down now and talk about what we need to do for the
rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   What Goodyear needs to do is not forget what he did to get where
he was at about 4 p.m. Sunday, which was in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest thing was making sure (the car) was there at the
end,'' Goodyear said. ``I just tried to pace myself.''.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear did. Right into victory lane. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
