<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-CRIME-UNIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES IN STREET CRIME UNIT MAY HURT ITS EFFECTIVENESS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As officers in the Street Crime Unit reported _ in
uniform _ for duty Sunday, many law enforcement officials said that
Police Commissioner Howard Safir's decision to end the unit's
plain-clothes operations would make it less controversial, but also
less effective.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with mounting criticism in the seven weeks since the
Amadou Diallo killing, Safir announced Friday that he would require
Street Crime Unit officers to work in uniform and that he would
replace 50 members of the overwhelmingly white unit with minority
officers.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would try to attract candidates by elevating the
unit's status with promotions and annual raises of $1,500, and by
making the assignment part of a career path leading to the
prestigious detective bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves may ease the criticism from those city residents who
charge that the Street Crimes Unit has produced impressive arrest
and gun seizure statistics by being too aggressive and infringing
on the civil rights of residents in minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But tactically, the new dress code that began last night will
deprive the unit of one of its most valuable weapons _ stealth _
and will limit the squad's ability to perform surveillance in
high-crime neighborhoods, officers and former commanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the changes said they amounted to tampering with a
proven formula. During the last five years, the Street Crimes Unit
has functioned as a kind of rapid deployment force, a platoon of
gung-ho officers dispatched to high-crime neighborhoods with a
mandate to aggressively search for illegal guns and violent felons.
</P>
<P>
   The unit's results were so impressive _ it makes up less than 2
percent of the police force but confiscated 40 percent of all the
illegal weapons seized in the city _ that Safir tripled its
manpower from 130 to nearly 400 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Former Deputy Inspector Richard F. Savage, who was relieved of
his command of the Street Crimes Unit when he opposed Safir's
expansion plans in 1997, said the changes would prevent officers
from posing as decoys in areas where a mugger or rapist had been
carrying out a series of attacks. Savage said the uniform
requirement would also force officers to be more careful when they
approach people suspected of carrying weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still going to be looking for people with the bulge in
the waistband and the heavy pockets, and they're still going to pop
out of the car when they see someone who's wanted or who may be
carrying a weapon,'' Savage said. ``But in the past, they could
have parked the car, maybe gone around the block and found the
safest way to approach the situation. Now, the minute they leave
the vehicle, the bad guys immediately know who they are, and the
cops don't know who they're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   Det. Terrance Wansley, a spokesman for the group 100 Blacks in
Law Enforcement, and other black officers said that the decision to
make the unit more racially diverse is so long overdue that it will
do little to change the suspicion that its officers and many
residents of minority neighborhoods feel toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Diallo shooting, the department has ordered every
member of the Street Crimes Unit to attend racial sensitivity
classes, which have been taught by a community affairs sergeant who
is also a member of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant, who discussed the meetings on the condition of
anonymity, said they were surprisingly tense, marred by icy stares
and in one case a shouting match, leaving black officers stunned by
the depth of the alienation that some street crimes officers
expressed toward minority residents and their black and Latino
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such deep racial divisions in that unit, that it's
going to take a lot more than just throwing a few raisins into the
milk bowl to change things,'' said Eric Adams, the president of 100
Blacks in Law Enforcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
