A7428 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      03-28 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA OPTS FOR GREED, LETS THE FANS BE DOMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, FLA. - Greed kills, greed consumes, and here it
is: Living under a Teflon roof, crawling inside a hideous baseball
stadium, sucking every possible penny from a staggering tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Shame on the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball is meant for arenas, not domes. And there's no reason
that the Final Four shouldn't come to Phoenix. Not ``if'' the grass
at BOB can handle the duress or ``if'' the Rio Salado project
becomes a reality.
</P>
<P>
   It should come to America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Or the United Center in Chicago. Or the Delta Center in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   No reason to stay away, except for greed.
</P>
<P>
   Come now. Who's running the sport? Juan Antonio Samaranch?
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a dash of Gonzaga and a spoonful of Wally Szczerbiak,
this tournament is threatening to be the worst of the decade. If
ever the NCAA needed a warm-and-fuzzy finish, a strong sense of
atmosphere to compensate for the lack of drama, this is it.
Instead, they are stuck in a terrible venue, with teams and fans
dispersed across the bay area. A hollow experience, satisfying no
one but accountants and ticket scalpers and educators auctioning
their product to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sad juxtaposition. A sport you can rub shoulders with _
accessible, friendly, quaint. And the domes _ monstrous and
sterile, symbols of big business.
</P>
<P>
   I am sitting in Section 323 of Tropicana Field, formerly known
as the Thunder Dome. I am in the worst seat in the house, face
value $80, a Mark McGwire moon-shot removed from the court. Below
me, a media work room. Panning to the right, a giant curtain. An
obnoxious set of temporary bleachers. A wide aisle. A thick set of
tables for the media. And, finally, fading out of view, the floor.
But the rim looks like a thimble, and I may as well be watching
from the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, nearly every fan in this area used binoculars. In
fact, one gentleman paid a scalper $1,600 for a ticket, unaware of
the location. He ended up here, watching ants.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the exception. Even the best seat in the place is
well removed from the floor. And any intimacy you think you see on
television is a lie, a trick of the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the spirit of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   This is basket-blur.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the NCAA sold out. They established a formula, putting
a premium on arenas with a minimum of 30,000 seats. With a few
blips _ 1990 in Denver, 1994 in Charlotte and 1996 in New Jersey _
they went for the money. Now, there is no deviation. The tournament
is booked through 2007, and by then, domes will have an 11-year
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swish'' has been overpowered by ``cha-ching,'' and the message
from the NCAA is clear: Build us a cash machine, and we will come.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the NCAA needs money. In 1991, they signed a $1
billion deal with CBS. In 1995, they re-negotiated, upping the ante
to $1.75 billion for seven years. The additional ticket revenue,
even with the multiplier effect of concession and souvenir sales,
barely makes a dent on the ledger.
</P>
<P>
   No reason for the domes, except for greed.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, an exclusive rotation is forming. Indianapolis is
great, a basketball mecca with a down-sized dome. San Antonio isn't
bad, but a locale no one associates with the sport. Atlanta is a
terrible sports town. New Orleans is a wasteland with a dome big
enough to warrant its own area code.
</P>
<P>
   Why not Phoenix? Boston? New York? Places where basketball has
roots and arenas to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Greed only grows, and the NCAA will never change. It sees the
domes as a symbol of growth and popularity, proof that the sport
has come a long way from the Cow Palace in San Francisco and the
Pit in New Mexico. And, of course, the folks in charge will claim
they are only catering to interest, serving the demand.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, they are betraying the fans. And the sport. And the
very essence of the game, a tournament balling for dollars and
nothing else. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
