u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-NYT     03-28 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS LOSE CONTROL OF EMOTIONS AND GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ This was not the strategy the New York
Knicks had in mind. There was no thinking and no plan. There was
just chaos as the Knicks concluded a disheartening West Coast swing
with a 99-91 loss to the Los Angeles Lakers at the Forum on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, an ineffective and exasperated Patrick Ewing, who
hit just nine of 24 shots and scored 20 quiet points, fouled out
with 23.4 seconds left. The Lakers, led by Kobe Bryant's 29 points,
left the Knicks 1-2 on their road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks (16-14) played with too much of an edge, too
combative. Dennis Rodman was probably at the root of that. But with
the Knicks unable to contain their emotions, it led to the ejection
of Kurt Thomas at the end of the third quarter and Chris Dudley
four minutes into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Already upset by his shaky play and frustrated with the
officials enough to have been assessed a technical foul, Ewing was
the only big man left standing. After he picked up his fifth foul
with just over six minutes left in the game, he played tentatively
while the Lakers broke free with the aid of two 3-pointers in the
last three and a half minutes by the former Knick Derek Harper.
They went on an 11-4 run to take control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And to think the Knicks had pulled to within 3 points early in
the fourth on a 3-pointer by Latrell Sprewell _ the only man in
blue with some life in his game _ before the Knicks came undone.
</P>
<P>
   With six minutes 13 second left in the game, Shaquille O'Neal
came up with an emphatic, rim-swinging dunk. He came down, then
shoved Dudley, who then threw the ball at O'Neal. Both were called
for technical fouls. But for hurling the ball and hitting O'Neal,
Dudley received an automatic ejection. Seven minutes earlier,
Thomas had been ejected after taking down Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of things to take everyone's mind off the
game, like the strain between Sprewell and coach Jeff Van Gundy and
the dislike O'Neal recently expressed for Ewing's leadership during
the National Basketball Association's lockout. And then there was
the distracting blond walking by, Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent Dennis. Rodman became a visible part of this game in
his passive resistance toward the end of the third quarter. After
Sprewell scored on a putback with 2.4 seconds on the clock, Rodman,
jockeying for rebounding position, was collared and tossed to the
ground by Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently fed up with Rodman's elbowing, Thomas jumped on
Rodman and tossed him again. Rodman, acting like a rag doll,
allowed himself to be thrown to the floor. During the altercation,
Chris Childs and Rick Fox began jawing at each other.
</P>
<P>
   When the melee ended, Thomas was hit with a flagrant foul and
was ejected, and Fox was hit with a technical. Nothing for Rodman.
And as the third period ended, the Knicks were behind, 72-65. They
were close because of Sprewell, who helped the Knicks cut the
Lakers' 14-point lead with an 8-point flurry.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the tension of this matchup, there was a road game the
Knicks were desperate to win in order to go back home from their
three-game West Coast trip with some confidence to face the Indiana
Pacers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a lot to play for, and so much to go up against.
The Knicks had a blatant plan: foul O'Neal into oblivion. That's
why Van Gundy started Dudley next to Ewing for the first time.
That's why he kept rotating his big men. In some way, the strategy
was effective in the first half. O'Neal was sent to the free-throw
line nine times and made just two shots as a part of his 10-point
first half.
</P>
<P>
   All the Knicks' efforts to contain O'Neal did nothing to stop
the tricky Bryant and smooth-shooting Glen Rice. Bryant sent Allan
Houston and then Childs spinning with his fakes on his way to 17
first-half points. At his side, Rice was launching jumpers over
Larry Johnson and then Sprewell while piling up 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did not need to ride O'Neal as they built a 14-point
lead in the second quarter. The Knicks' ball movement came to a
halt. They came up with just one assist and shot 26 percent from
the field. Although the Knicks put on a mini-run before the break,
they trailed by 50-42, close despite Ewing making just four of 12
shots against O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   This was the big-man matchup on the marquee: O'Neal vs. Ewing.
Not only is there a history between the two as each tried to assert
himself as the man when O'Neal was with the Orlando Magic, but
there was added tension because of the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal wasn't happy with the collective bargaining agreement _
which will limit the potential for him to make $20 million a year
under the old deal to $14 million if he opts out of his current
contract _ and holds Ewing's leadership as president to blame for
it. O'Neal's recent comments seemed to irritate Ewing. But O'Neal
didn't care if it meant a more inspired game by Ewing, and said he
``feared no man.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ewing said he planned to bring his ``A game'' to
face the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't exactly setting the curve against them. After
beginning 4 for 6, Ewing missed eight shots in a row, including his
first two in the third quarter. He finally got a jumper to fall
three minutes into the third quarter at a point when the Lakers had
rebuilt their lead to 14.
</P>
<P>
   In danger of falling off the face of this game, Sprewell brought
his West Coast style, with its self-centered flair, to the floor.
He led an 8-2 run in the third quarter, punctuated by a violent,
one-handed dunk on the break after a Laker turnover to pull the
Knicks within 66-60 with 2:34 left. That dunk was only the
beginning of the craziness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
