r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-PREVIEW-AZR &LR;      03-28 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE VS. UCONN: NO SURPRISE HERE  
 ELITE TO MEET IN CHAMPIONSHIP GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ This is where we expected to be all
along, isn't it? A college basketball season filled with upsets and
talk of parity, followed by nearly three weeks of an unpredictable,
surprise-filled NCAA Tournament has led us to the most logical
conclusion of all.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game of the year, Duke (37-1), the best team in the
nation, perhaps one of the best teams ever, will play the
second-best team, Connecticut (33-2), tonight for the NCAA
Championship at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, any player in this position would be excited. But
some of the fans' anticipation of this particular game has
penetrated the baseball stadium's Teflon-coated, fiberglass roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see Duke and UConn,'' Duke forward Chris Carrawell said
Sunday, ``I don't think you can ask for a better match-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke, the first team ever to go 16-0 in the Atlantic Coast
Conference, has been so dominant for most of the season that
figuring out its place in history has become a sport unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one problem, at least right now: UConn. Fittingly,
the last team standing other than the Blue Devils, seems to be the
one team in the tournament with the best chance of beating Duke,
although Michigan State gave it a pretty good go on Saturday before
losing, 68-62.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win,'' UConn Coach Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   In virtually the next breath, Calhoun said Duke ``has proven
beyond a reasonable doubt that they are the best team in the
country.'' UConn, said Calhoun, is the clear-cut No. 2, and when
No. 1 and No. 2 get together, ``it makes for an intriguing
match-up.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will only be intriguing if UConn plays its best game of
the year, not the ``moments and minutes and hoffs (halves),'' as
Calhoun inflected.
</P>
<P>
   With All-America Richard Hamilton at one forward, strong, steady
Kevin Freeman at the other, flashy, dashing Khalid El-Amin at the
point, top defender Ricky Moore at the other guard and a decent
bench, it is possible.
</P>
<P>
   UConn is the ``best offensive transition team in the country,''
Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski said. Individually, Krzyzewski is most
concerned about Hamilton, who scored 24 points against Ohio State.
Noting that Calhoun gives Hamilton uncommon freedom on offense,
Krzyzewski called the 6-foot-6 junior ``as good a scorer as there
is in college basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun has his team playing tough man-to-man defense, but Duke
simply might have too many weapons. The arsenal includes point
guard William Avery, a high school teammate of Moore, off-guard
Trajan Langdon, forwards Shane Battier and Carrawell, and sixth-man
Corey Maggette, an acrobatic freshman forward who not only would
start for anyone else, would also be all-conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone would have to recognize Corey as our best
athlete,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   But the player occupying most of Calhoun's pre-game thoughts,
not to mention a lot of space around the basket, is Duke center
Elton Brand. The 6-foot-8, 260-pound sophomore has won several
national player of the year honors and is likely to be the first
Duke non-senior to go pro, although he plans to be there tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you deal with a player like Elton Brand, it's a
challenge for the entire team,'' said Freeman, who is expected to
lend help to center Jake Voskuhl.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies a huge problem for the Huskies. Guarded
one-on-one, Brand is nearly impossible to handle. Double-teamed,
with other defenders leaving their man to help out, Brand knows
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You double Elton and somebody's gonna beat you, no matter who
it is,'' Carrawell said. ``It's kind of interesting. We want to see
who they double off of. Whoever it is, is gonna have a great
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said he and his staff have been laboring to figure out
just how to play Brand _ who will double him and when, and how the
defense will rotate. But even that might not matter, because of
Duke's depth and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can keep lineups on the court that are very compatible,''
Krzyzewski said. ``We don't take a dip when we go to the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Special teams end up in special places, and there is more to
Duke than simply talent. Krzyzewski cites other reasons for the
Blue Devils' success, pointing to Langdon's leadership, the
maturity of a group that includes 10 underclassmen and his players'
work habits.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, allows Krzyzewski to permit freedom on the court,
to let the players express their individuality while still
operating within the framework of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group has been such a pleasure to teach because they
constantly want to learn,'' he said. ``They want to get better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
