<HEADER>
A7431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMOCO-ARCO-1STLD-WRIT     03-28 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-ARCO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO AND ARCO ARE REPORTED TO BE HOLDING TALKS ON A MERGER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to fix 6th-graf spelling of Browne)  (nk) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BP Amoco PLC, the giant oil company, has been in serious
discussions to buy the Atlantic Richfield Co., the oil and gas
exploration and refining concern, executives close to the talks
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, which have been going on for months, have not
yet produced a deal and could still collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Sir John Browne, the chief executive of BP Amoco,
met last week with Michael R. Bowlin, the chairman and chief
executive of ARCO, and there have been discussions about price,
according to the people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement is reached, an announcement could come as early
as this week.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal for ARCO, which is based in Los Angeles and is
the nation's eighth-largest oil company, could be complicated,
however, if another bidder emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Sieminski, an oil analyst with BT Alex. Browne, said that
BP Amoco would have to offer about $25 billion, or a 20 percent
premium over its closing price of $65.375 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Browne has been a pacesetter in his industry for mergers, which
have been spurred by a year of low crude oil prices that dampened
the earnings of most large oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, he jolted the industry by announcing an agreement
to buy the Amoco Corporation, which was based in Chicago, in a deal
valued at about $48 billion at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Browne wasted little time, vowing to save $2 billion a year in
costs and deftly steering the complex transaction around many
regulatory hurdles to completion in late December.
</P>
<P>
   ``He closed it quickly,'' Sieminski said. ``He has taken
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   His bold move led Lee R. Raymond, the chairman of Exxon, to
offer to buy the Mobil Corp. for $80 billion in December, a deal
that would form the world's largest corporation.
</P>
<P>
   If Browne succeeds in acquiring ARCO, which has a market value
of about $21 billion, it will catapult BP Amoco into a tie with
Royal Dutch/Shell Group for second place among the giant
international oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of such giants, who have also formed
alliances with other companies to help cut costs in refining in the
United States and Europe, smaller oil companies like ARCO have
scrambled to find strategies to survive.
</P>
<P>
   With crude oil prices plunging from about $18 a barrel at this
time last year to as low as $12, ARCO saw its earnings drop to
$1.79 a share last year from $5.28 a share in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO, which gets a larger share of its profits from oil sales
than its largest U.S. rivals, had a fourth-quarter loss of $794
million, or $2.47 a share, its first unprofitable quarter in six
years. The company took charges to write down assets and inventory
because of low oil prices and also for costs associated with
cutting 1,200 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a recent recovery in crude oil prices because of cuts
in production announced by major oil-exporting nations, analysts
were wondering whether ARCO could earn enough this year to pay its
yearly dividend of $2.85 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlin has attempted to strengthen ARCO, selling its chemical
business last year for $5.6 billion. He also acquired an
independent oil company, Union Texas Holdings Inc. of Houston, for
$2.47 billion last May to bolster ARCO's reserves and gain entry
into the Caspian Sea region, where most large oil companies are
vying for rights to develop fields with vast reserves.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has let analysts know that he would welcome
a an offer for the company if the price was right for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company's representatives returned calls Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As with Amoco, Browne is expected to face few antitrust
problems, which mostly concern the refining and marketing of
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO has a significant refining and marketing operations on the
West Coast, an area where BP Amoco has little presence.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO and British Petroleum were the main companies that
developed the vast reserves in Prudhoe Bay, Alaska, where
production, while still substantial, has been falling.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Federal Trade Commission, which would review the
transaction, has focused on the competitive effects of refining
rather than crude oil production, where entry is more open and
there are many areas of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco could save money by combining Alaskan operations. ARCO,
by developing new fields, has stemmed the decline of its production
in Alaska but has found it hard to come up with the huge amounts of
capital needed to make inroads in areas such as the Caspian Sea. BP
Amoco produced 450,000 barrels of oil a day from Alaska last year,
while Arco produced 317,000 barrels a day, company figures show.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Browne has not let up on cutting costs. He announced
on Feb. 17 that BP Amoco would cut 10,000 jobs and speed up its
goal of getting $2 billion in annual savings in one year rather
than two.
</P>
<P>
   He added that BP Amoco would take $1.5 billion in charges this
year, mainly to cover the costs of severance for the workers who
lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As most oil executives do, he wants to make his company
profitable even if the current run-up in crude oil prices fizzles
and the harsh conditions of the last year continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
