<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     03-28 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BIG SWITCH IS THE BIG STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Nicole Erickson had a dream. Michele VanGorp
held a grudge. Gail Goestenkors heard their yarns spun and re-spun
and could stand it no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked the kids not to talk about the Purdue transfer,''
Goestenkors, the Duke coach, said before Sunday night's women's
college basketball final. ``We're really tired of it. It's time to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Too late. The title was on the line, Lin Dunn was in the
stands, and this most compelling angle was on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue versus Duke had tension and drama, the feel of
Hollywood-scripted symmetry, right down to the very last dribble.
Duke's two best players, Erickson and VanGorp, were going to defeat
the school they had transferred from in mutual protest three years
ago, or not. Stephanie White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs, the two
Purdue senior backcourt stars, were going to repel their former
teammates and raise the Hoosier banner, or not.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn, the gray-haired matriarch whose firing at Purdue set the
dominoes in motion, was going to watch two of her former players
crowned national champs. One way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's very, very interesting for all of you,''
Goestenkors said, and she was right.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, there was the stunning Tennessee threepeat, one team
sprinting miles away from rest of the field. This time around, we
had two teams that just couldn't stay out of each other's lives. We
had VanGorp, the 6-foot-6-inch center, invoking the name of Dunn in
the colors of Duke, through a yellow mouth guard custom-made for
her at Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no reason to fire her,'' said VanGorp, her jump shot
and elbows primed for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   There is never a bad time to tell a good story, or at least
that's what they told us back in journalism school. Monday night's
Duke-UConn men's final in St. Petersburg on network television
will, as usual, dwarf the women's cable ratings, but no one should
ever compare these two games, the two sports, that are at
completely different points on the evolutionary scale. More than
that, the National Collegiate Athletic Association should resist
the growing sentiment within the women's game to move its Final
Four forward, or back.
</P>
<P>
   No less an authority than the decorated Stanford coach, Tara
VanDerveer, disagrees, asserting that the women could get off ESPN
and back on the network by surrendering this weekend to the men.
``What is the big deal going back a weekend or two?'' she said. ``I
mean, they play basketball in the summer now.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister does not even have cable, VanDerveer said, and thus,
like many others, has no access to these games. Fair point. But
there is something defeatist, isolationist, about the women having
to pack up their gear and move to attract more attention. The
inherent appeal of college basketball has always been its festival
milieu. There are too many reasons, too many trends, not to believe
that they eventually will outgrow being kid sister on cable.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday happened to be the 20th anniversary of the men's final
matching Michigan State and Indiana State, Magic Johnson and Larry
Bird, which should put into context the women's developmental
progress. I seem to recall visiting a few men's subregional sites
back in those years when the stands were empty. Every year now, the
women's tournament gets bigger, noisier, edgier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of million people in this country,'' said
Leon Barmore, the Louisiana Tech coach. ``We shouldn't worry about
who's watching the men. We've got our fans, more every year.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a betting line on the women's games in Las Vegas this
week for the first time, and that ought to tell the women to hold
their ground, that this wild weekend belongs to them, too. The
staggering number of air miles logged this weekend by Joe Alleva,
the Duke athletic director, suggests they can't be ignored, no
matter what is happening cross country with the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is good exposure for Duke, more than it is for
women's basketball,'' Alleva said after his latest Ping-Pong shot
back from St. Petersburg early Sunday morning. ``I do think the
women would be better off with their own Final Four weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Alleva and the other Duke administrators surely
would have preferred schmoozing the alumni in Florida between
games, as opposed to straining their backs in a seven-seat,
lavatory-less jet. Since Duke for years virtually ignored its
women's program while basking in its reputation as an enlightened
institution of higher education and basketball erudition, maybe we
should take the Duke double as a message from the gender equality
gods.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Erickson claimed the other day that she had dreamed that
her college career would conclude in the championship game, against
her and VanGorp's old school. Never hold a good story, I always
say, out of fear it won't be the best. There is always room for a
dream come true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
