<HEADER>
A7433 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-NOTES-LADN     03-28 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVERY, MOORE MEET AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Their careers began together on the
playgrounds of Augusta, Ga. They went to the same elementary school
and the same junior high. They were teammates and close friends at
Augusta's Westside High. They won a prep title together, and
tonight they'll play for the NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   On different teams.
</P>
<P>
   Duke sophomore guard William Avery and Connecticut senior guard
Ricky Moore will compete against each for the first time tonight
when they meet in Tropicana Field. Once it's over, they'll be
friends. For now, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know him right now,'' Avery said. ``After the
buzzer, it'll be like, `Oh yeah, we grew up together.' But right
now, I'm trying not to find him or call him on the telephone or
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a defensive specialist who will shadow Avery during the
game, was Avery's surrogate big brother in Augusta. They were prep
teammates for two years, then Moore departed for Connecticut. Avery
played at Westside as a junior, then spent one season at famed Oak
Hill Academy before matriculating to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``In junior high, I wanted the same number (Moore) had worn in
football and basketball,'' Avery said. ``Everyone liked him in the
community, and I really looked up to him. I even tried to model my
game after him for a little while. . . . He was the teacher and I
was the student. I looked up to him from eighth grade on.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was thrilled to have Avery around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took him under my wing in high school,'' Moore said. ``He's
done a great job at Duke. I think he's matured a lot. It'll be real
special (tonight), just out on the court competing against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Doin' it all: Duke sophomore forward Shane Battier is one of the
Blue Devils' most versatile players and their best defender.
Battier, who worked for Morgan Stanley's equity research department
in New York City last summer, knows his best bet for recognition is
to play defense, set picks and grab offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too often in this day and age that people will take
charges and play position defense,'' Battier said. ``I know I won't
get on `SportsCenter' for the fancy dunks, so why not get some
recognition taking a charge?''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes: Duke and Connecticut, the only teams ranked No. 1 in
the regular season, have more at stake than the national title.
</P>
<P>
   For Duke, a victory secures its place as the team of the decade:
Both the Blue Devils and Kentucky have won two national titles in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   For Connecticut, it's a chance to exact revenge for two NCAA
Tournament losses to Duke this decade _ including a crushing
overtime loss in 1990 on Christian Laettner's buzzer-beater.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us were around, so we're not even thinking about it,''
Connecticut point guard Khalid El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Huskies coach Jim Calhoun has thought about Duke, thought
about who can beat Duke and how to beat Duke. Sunday, his praise
for the Blue Devils nearly reached a state of awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke has proven beyond a reasonable doubt that it's the best
team in the country,'' Calhoun said. ``I don't have any question
about that. They're the best team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have won. We're near the same dominating factor. But
clearly I think we've become the second best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
