<HEADLINE>
ROY FISHER, 80, FORMER MISSOURI JOURNALISM DEAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mo.)   (jw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roy Fisher, a former editor of The Chicago Daily News and former
dean of the University of Missouri School of Journalism, died
Thursday at a hospice in Evanston, Ill. He was 80 and lived in
Wilmette, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was dean of Missouri's journalism school from 1971 to
1982. In 1981, the Associated Press Managing Editors Association
rated it the country's top journalism school.
</P>
<P>
   Under Fisher, the school began an exchange program for Chinese
journalists and improved its radio and television broadcasting
facilities. After stepping down as dean he remained there as a
professor until 1989, overseeing the university's graduate
reporting program in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   From 1966 to 1971, Fisher was the editor of The Chicago Daily
News, which ceased publication in 1978. Earlier he held lesser
posts at the newspaper and was an executive with World Book.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Stockton, Kan., he graduated in 1940 from Kansas State
University and was a naval officer in the Pacific in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Anne Fallon; four
daughters, Leslie Muir of Glencoe, Ill., Patricia Fisher of Palo
Alto, Calif., Mary Fisher of Rockford, Ill., and Sarah Fisher of
Littleton, Colo.; 11 grandchildren; two brothers, Paul of Boulder
City, Nev., and Robert of Lake Forest, Ill.; and a sister, Ruth
Hall of Davis, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
