<SLUG> BC-COMMERCE-ONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL VENTURE TO OFFER ONLINE PURCHASING SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass. )  (nk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an effort to move more business-to-business
purchasing transactions to the Internet, a pioneer in the field
plans to announce partnerships on Monday with two giant
international telecommunications carriers to create a global
trading network.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One, a small software company in Walnut Creek, Calif.,
plans to announce partnership agreements with Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone and British Telecommunications intended to enable
businesses to use the Internet to automate the purchasing process.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One, which already has a relationship with MCI Worldcom
in the United States, has developed software systems that enable
companies to transform their purchasing interactions into real-time
trading networks.
</P>
<P>
   Such systems have long been envisioned by proponents of
so-called electronic data interchange, or EDI systems, which were
intended to replace purchase orders and bills of laden with online
digital documents. But the emergence of the Internet as a global
standard in the last five years has vastly accelerated the pace of
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear that this is the future,'' said Jay M.
Tenenbaum, chief scientist of Commerce One. ``After 20 years, about
100,000 companies are using EDI systems. But the fact is that more
than a million companies are on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of much new Internet business-to-business commerce
activity is a computer-to-computer translation language known as
XML that is being rapidly adopted by many companies, from start-ups
to corporate giants like IBM and Microsoft. XML simplifies and
automates the process of business-to-business interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One executives say that the company's new partnerships
will sharply increase the efficiency of doing business
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``NTT is going to work with major players in Japan,'' said Mark
Hoffman, the chairman and chief executive of Commerce One. ``Now it
is possible to reach all of the big suppliers in Japan in one fell
swoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Commerce One had built a leading position as
a result of its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commerce One has ended up being in the catbird seat,'' said
Stan Dolberg, an analyst at Forrester Research, a research and
consulting firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``They are well down the road
to figuring out that this is the killer application.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of their agreements, both NTT and British Telecom will
deploy a Commerce One software program known as Marketsite. The
software is meant to automate the steps of selecting, ordering,
processing, shipping and paying for products.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce One executives called theirs an ``open'' commerce
system, meaning that it is possible to participate either by
purchasing software from Commerce One or a rival, or by creating
the software independently, Tenenbaum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
