<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-VCR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MAKERS PLAN INTRODUCTIONS OF DIGITAL VCR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two Silicon Valley makers of digital VCRs plan
to make announcements on Monday about their services and products,
which enable television viewers to filter, store and retrieve
programs as digitized video.
</P>
<P>
   Tivo Inc. of Sunnyvale, Calif., plans to announce that it is
introducing its service in partnership with Royal Philips
Electronics N.V., the Dutch electronics company, which will begin
selling the storage devices, known as Personal TV Receivers, for
$499. The receivers, which will initially be sold through the
Internet or via a toll-free telephone number, will become available
in consumer electronics outlets this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Tivo's system is similar to another service to be announced on
Monday, and scheduled to begin next month, from Replay Networks
Inc. of Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Both systems also utilize a dial-up telephone-line connection
that downloads television listing information. Tivo is charging a
$9.95 monthly subscription fee for its service, while the Replay
service will be subsidized by advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Replay said the hardware for its system, capable of storing six
hours of digitized video, will be available in April and will be
priced at $699.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it had obtained an $8 million investment
from a group led by the venture capital firm of Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers. Other members of the group will include the
Tribune Co. and Vulcan Ventures Inc., the investment organization
of the Microsoft co-founder Paul G. Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Philips executives said the Tivo device would permit
consumers to store and retrieve up to 14 hours of video.
</P>
<P>
   A system with the capacity to store 30 hours will sell for $999,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real goal is in the development of services that work in
conjunction with this technology,'' said Ed MacBeth, Tivo's vice
president for marketing and business development.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tivo and Replay have created technologies that begin to
blend the power of the personal computer with television. The idea
is to permit people to use television the way Web surfers now use
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both systems permit the creation of custom
``channels,'' supported by filtering software that automatically
records all programs on particular subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The systems also permit digital rewind, fast-forward and pause
features.
</P>
<P>
   Such digital technology makes it possible for a viewer watching
a live basketball game to pause the action, go to the kitchen and
make a sandwich and then return to pick up the game in mid
jump-shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
