</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN GROUND TROOPS MAY BE NEEDED IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
 -ANALYSIS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ If there are two words that jar the Clinton
administration more these days than ``Slobodan Milosevic,'' ``air
defense'' and ``ethnic cleansing,'' they are ``ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans barely support or understand the White House's
rationale for U.S. involvement in the NATO air war against
Yugoslavia, and the public appears prepared to strongly reject even
the thought of launching U.S. troops into a ground battle in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the Clinton administration's carefully worded
disavowal of intent to use U.S. combat soldiers to fight aggression
by Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, against some of his own
citizens, that prospect looms strongly on the not-too-distant
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Possible use of ground troops increases with each day of reports
of new atrocities against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genocide is starting,'' German Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping said in a ZDF network interview. NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea said at alliance headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, that
Kosovo was seeing a humanitarian catastrophe ``the likes of which
we have not seen in Europe since the closing stages of World War
II.''
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton used the continuing attacks by Serbs on
Kosovar Albanians as a reason to keep up the NATO attacks _ if only
from the air. ``The continued brutality and repression of the Serb
forces further underscores the need for NATO to persevere,''
Clinton said Sunday after an hour-long White House briefing from
his top national security advisers.
</P>
<P>
   If one of the purposes of the now stepped-up air campaign
against Milosevic is to stop the atrocities and it does not work,
then the United States, as the alliance leader, will face _ some
would say should face _ calls to move beyond the aerial
bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Even NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana, when presented by a
journalist Sunday with a choice of continued atrocities or eventual
use of ground troops, wavered from the party line.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is more important is to stop the ethnic cleansing... ''
Solana said on ABC's This Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not allow morally a situation like that in the core
of Europe when we are approaching the 21st century. We have to stop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solana's statement was accompanied by one of the carefully
phrased sidesteps around active consideration of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Solana said, ``let's try to take every problem (one)
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials clung in multiple television
appearances to the equivocal formulation that the president had
``no intention'' of using ground forces. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright even had to stop herself in mid-sentence on CBS
News' Face the Nation to get the right words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not send _ he says he has no intention,'' Albright
said, then she added a sentence that was daring, given how Clinton
sawed off the limb on which Albright climbed to deny his sexual
involvement with Monica Lewinsky. ``He is the commander-in-chief,''
Albright said. ``When he speaks, he should be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, an Albright deputy, Undersecretary of State
Thomas Pickering, sought to fence off the American view of using
ground forces from any possibly differing European view or plan.
There are already about 12,000 European NATO troops in Macedonia
waiting to move just across the border into Kosovo if there is a
cease-fire and Milosevic agrees to an outside force to police the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Those European troops in Macedonia are the closest mass force
and possibly would be the first to move if NATO agreed on ground
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Europeans do, obviously, they will have to be responsible
for,'' Pickering said. It was an odd observation because European
leaders would almost certainly refuse to mount an invasion force to
move into Yugoslavia unless U.S. troops were included.
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders of NATO nations, especially Greece and Italy, are
already showing signs of strain from the air campaign. ``Talk about
ground troops, they're really queasy,'' observed former Senate
Majority Leader Bob Dole, the Republican who has acted as a special
envoy for Clinton in the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said that a solely European
ground force should be considered, ``since we have taken the lion's
share in the air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Solana said, NATO has given Macedonia ``all kinds of
assurances, if they are attacked by Milosevic, they will be
defended.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring the doubts of many military leaders and politicians
about the efficacy of an air-only strategy, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., said Sunday that the allies ``have to exercise every
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the threat of ground forces could influence Milosevic,
McCain said on ABC's This Week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Milosevic was convinced that (use of ground forces) is
an option that we might exercise, I think it could lend impetus to
convincing him that he cannot win and we will not allow him to
win,'' said McCain, a Navy pilot who was shot down during the
Vietnam War and held prisoner for seven years. ``We are a superior
force, and we must win this conflict with whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hutchison, who said she is ``absolutely'' opposed to the
use of U.S. ground troops against Yugoslavia, said NATO's disavowal
of such forces had told Milosevic too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has heard everyone say no troops on the ground,''
Hutchison said. ``So instead of using his defensive air maneuvers,
he's gone on the ground and committed more atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme allied commander in
Europe, has suggested an air campaign may not bring Milosevic to
his knees or to the bargaining table. And the chairman of the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton, has said: ``We fully
understand the limits of air power.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shelton, on NBC's Meet the Press, recounted the harrowing
prospects of using ground forces: ``The commitment of NATO ground
troops would involve hundreds of thousands of ground troops over a
rather protracted period of time and in a very dangerous situation
unless you have a political settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton conceded that NATO, six to eight months ago, ``made an
assessment'' of what ground troops ``might entail. But there are no
plans on the shelf or no plans under way at this particular time.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at polls showing Americans more than 4-to-1 in
opposition to using ground forces in Yugoslavia, former Secretary
of State Henry Kissinger said the campaign against Milosevic cannot
be allowed to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take whatever measures are necessary,'' Kissinger
said on ABC, ``even reluctantly introducing ground forces, if that
is the only way to accomplish it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
