<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WEEKEND OF PROGRESS IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, New Yorkers at last glimpsed the possibility
that some constructive change will come from the death of Amadou
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced an overhaul of the
Street Crimes Unit, including more minority officers and closer
supervision. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani continued to meet with black
leaders and said he wished he had done so earlier. The
administration's steps signaled a welcome shift from defensiveness
to bridge-building and structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the leaders of the protests that have focused public
attention on the case produced a 10-point agenda for dealing with
police misconduct that the mayor should take as a reasonable basis
for future discussion. Among the recommendations Giuliani is most
likely to resist are those calling for an independent investigative
body with jurisdiction over police corruption and brutality issues
and a strengthened Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has long argued that police can best investigate
police. But the disturbing, detail-laden reports about police
harassment that have come from minority communities make it
apparent that the police need help policing themselves. The mayor
should accept the challenge of using his expertise to create an
investigative unit that works.
</P>
<P>
   Safir, for his part, has announced that he will move quickly to
put more minority officers in the Street Crimes Unit, and that unit
officers will now wear uniforms. That may make it more difficult
for the officers to operate. But men in plainclothes who suddenly
appear wielding guns and shouting orders can frighten innocent
civilians in ways that endanger both the civilians and the police,
especially when their targets do not understand English.
</P>
<P>
   The police have won the city's gratitude for their success in
reducing crime, but that achievement must be balanced with more
sensitivity to the complaints of citizens who feel the unpleasant
side of those efforts. The Street Crimes Unit operates mainly in
high-crime, minority neighborhoods, and there was always a danger
that its members would be seen as an occupying force bent on
harassing black and Hispanic men. The importance of not having this
mission performed by a virtually all-white unit seems obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani seems to be doing his best to demonstrate that he
really wants to develop better relationships with black leaders.
His challenge now is to follow through. What seemed to be an
equally serious attempt at bridge-building after the Abner Louima
case ended once the furor died down. It is imperative that Giuliani
not pass up this chance to establish a new understanding between
police and the minority community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
