<SLUG> BC-PARAGUAY-RESIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEADER'S RESIGNATION SPURS JOY IN PARAGUAY
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN OTIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASUNCION, Paraguay _ Shaken by violent protests and on the verge of
being removed from office, Paraguayan President Raul Cubas resigned
Sunday, setting off wild celebrations across this South American
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leader Luis Gonzalez Macchi of the ruling Colorado Party
was sworn-in Sunday night as Paraguay's new president and
immediately received the backing by the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Caravans of jubilant motorists wound through the streets of the
Paraguayan capital of Asuncion, honking horns, singing the national
anthem and setting off fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best thing that could have happened to my
country,'' said Julian Ojeda, who waved a Paraguayan flag as he
celebrated with a huge crowd in front of the pink Congress building
in downtown Asuncion.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Sunday night, a somber Cubas said he was
being forced out by an unjust impeachment trial. But he said his
resignation would help bring peace to Paraguay after a wave of
anti-government protests left four people dead and more than 100
injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not leaving because I'm corrupt or a crook. I'm leaving
because, if my departure helps to pacify the nation, that will be
my contribution at this delicate moment,'' said Cubas, who was
flanked by his wife and several aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to be responsible for more bloodshed of
innocents. I have just signed my resignation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A broadcast by Radio Mitre of Buenos Aires, Argentina, reported
that Lino Oviedo, the cashiered army general whose release from
prison by Cubas last year touched off the nation's political
crisis, had been temporarily detained Sunday night in an airport on
the outskirts of Buenos Aires. The radio station reported that he
was carrying false documents.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo had turned himself in to military authorities last week
but Paraguayan television reported that he had fled the country by
private aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi said that after being sworn in he would return Oviedo to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The downfall of Cubas, who served just seven months and three
days of a five-year term, capped one of the most violent weeks in
recent Paraguayan history.
</P>
<P>
   His government began unravelling on Tuesday when Vice President
Luis Argana was assassinated on the streets of Asuncion during rush
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Argana was leading the effort to impeach Cubas on the grounds
that he had violated the constitution by freeing Oviedo, a close
friend of Cubas who had received a 10-year jail sentence for
leading a failed coup attempt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although no evidence has emerged linking Oviedo and Cubas to the
slaying of Argana, both men were widely blamed for the crime. Angry
demonstrators clashed with riot police and army troops, who fought
back with tear gas, water canons, and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first major demonstrations in this normally
peaceful country of 5 million people since the dictatorship of
Alfredo Stroessner, who was ousted in a military coup in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time the country has seen such
mobilizations,'' said Oscar Denis, an opposition congressman. ``And
that gives strength to the politicians to follow the path of
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubas was impeached by the lower house of Congress on Wednesday,
a day after Argana was killed. Cubas' trial in the Senate was set
to resume today, and legislators said that they had enough votes to
remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Macchi received the presidential sash during a jubilant ceremony
before members of Congress. Afterward, legislators raised their
fists and shouted ``Long live Paraguay!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our struggle has not been in vain,'' Macchi said. ``The
Paraguayan people have won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
