<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-MEX-WOMEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN BURY MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If it could, the U.S. women's national team
would take Sunday's 3-0 victory over Mexico, put it in a container
and bury it like a time capsule under the Rose Bowl turf, with
instructions not to open until July 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, if all goes according to the players' hopes and
most observers' predictions, USA will return here for the
championship match of Women's World Cup '99.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of soccer to play between now and then. The match
with Mexico was only the start of the U.S. team's nine-match ``Road
to Pasadena'' tour.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory was one to savor. It was one that, if they
could, the Americans gladly would put away for safekeeping, digging
out only when they need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Lilly would be the first to grab the shovel, but many
other players would wait to get their digs in. Lilly scored two
late goals within three minutes of each other, enabling the United
States to finally crack the Mexican defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the final result was a just result, even though they
were late goals,'' U.S. Coach Tony DiCicco said. ``It was an
excellent defensive effort by Mexico. I'm proud of the way our team
kept attacking, even if it sometimes meant we were left naked on
defense. We did a good job of getting back.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States outshot Mexico, 42-1, put 20 shots on goal and
possessed the ball for 70 percent of the match. All this, despite
Mexico's strategy to pack the front of its net, a ploy Coach
Leonardo Cuellar admitted was necessary to prevent an embarrassing
rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew from the beginning that we expected to play the best
team in the world,'' Cuellar said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight U.S. players took shots in the first half alone, while
Mexico countered with only one, dangerous striker Maribel
Dominguez. Yet, if not for a brilliant leaping save by U.S.
goalkeeper Briana Scurry in the 19th minute, Dominguez would have
put her team on top, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican goalkeeper Linnea Quinones was equal to the U.S.
challenge, making several outstanding saves. Until Lilly's late
outburst, the United States managed to get only one shot past
Quinones, a header by Julie Foudy off an assist by Shannon
MacMillan in the 38th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Quinones' finest moment was stopping Mia Hamm on a breakaway in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made a tremendous save, one that I think defined her game
today,'' said Hamm, who assisted on Lilly's second goal in the 88th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm admitted to being a little frustrated at failing to score
Sunday after also being shut out in the recent Algarve Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a long layoff in the fall, it takes some time to get
back certain aspects of the game,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to score, but we didn't need me to. If I
score a goal, I want it to be when it will help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity could come if the United States returns to the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first game of our season. The World Cup is the
postseason,'' DiCicco said. ``We want to get everybody ready for
the World Cup, because we intend to be back here on July 10.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2300EST &QL; 
