<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FINAL-SHOWDOWN-42     03-28 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINAL-SHOWDOWN-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, IT WILL BE FOR ALL THE MARBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ A time will come in Monday's National
Collegiate Athletic Association championship game when Duke's point
guard, William Avery, will try to penetrate Connecticut's defense
and the polished floor at Tropicana Field will feel like torn-up
blacktop; when Avery will find the Huskies' premier defender, Ricky
Moore, closing in on his personal space. Then, they will replay the
childhood showdowns from Oak Park in Augusta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Avery, the sophomore, will try a move to get to the
basket and Moore, the senior, will recognize it as something he
taught him back when Avery was just leaving eighth grade and Moore
started dragging him along to pickup games. Perhaps then, on
college basketball's biggest stage, the boys who grew up a block
apart on Hazel Street in the Sand Hill neighborhood of Augusta will
take the game that has bound them together to its logical zenith.
</P>
<P>
   Although Duke is the favorite to win the title, it is Moore,
arguably the finest perimeter defender in the nation, who has the
advantage. ``I took him under my wing,'' Moore said. ``He was
younger than I was, so I was the teacher. Some of the moves he
makes, I do. He's gotten stronger and quicker, and my role is
different. I don't think Will has seen a defender like me all year.
It's going to be tough for him to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no disrespect. Moore and Avery smiled when they
reminisced about their days at Oak Park, playing pickup games with
guys from 15 to 45 years old, getting banged into the parking lot
if they tried to dunk. They delighted in the idea that the young
boys who used to walk to the playground together _ only to get on
opposing teams when they arrived _ would face off for a prize they
could scarcely imagine when the Reynolds brothers, local legends,
were doing crazy things to rule the court.
</P>
<P>
   Avery and Moore have not talked much recently, their travel
schedules making it difficult for them to find each other. They
have not played an organized game together in nearly four years,
since Moore was a high school senior, Avery was a sophomore, and
Westside High went 33-1 and won a state championship with Moore at
the point averaging about 23 points, showcasing an offensive game
he has since set aside. But Moore's influence lingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really looked up to him,'' Avery said. ``I can remember in
junior high I wanted to get the same number he wore. I even tried
to model my game after him for a little while. Definitely he feels
he has the advantage. He probably does. Some of my moves I got from
him. If anybody knows my game, he does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is because Moore's game was once so similar. But Khalid
El-Amin's arrival in Storrs, Conn., two years ago forced an
uncomplaining Moore to abandon the point and become a defensive
specialist. With suffocating closeness, he makes it nearly
impossible for his man to get off a shot. Even Moore did not know
Sunday who he would guard, but Coach Jim Calhoun has repeatedly
said he likes Moore to chop the head off the dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Avery makes Duke go, but if Moore guards him, it leaves El-Amin
to give up almost half a foot to guard Trajan Langdon. Forward
Kevin Freeman compared Duke to a Cyclops with many eyes, and it is
likely Moore will find himself combating almost all of them Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who I'm guarding,'' Moore said. ``I'm going
to go out and cause havoc.''
</P>
<P>
   In the national semifinal, Moore neutralized Ohio State's point
guard, Scoonie Penn, pushing him further and further out of his
comfort zone with in-his-shirt defense and holding Penn to 11
points on 3-of-13 shooting. Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves got
just six points on 2-of-15 shooting in December against Moore, and
Arthur Lee of Stanford had 12 points on 4-of-13 shooting in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's like any kid I've coached because he
doesn't really only guard a point,'' Duke Coach Mike Krzyzewski
said. ``He guards anybody on the perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore suspects that the folks from Sand Hill will be together
someplace watching Monday and that the trash talking has already
begun. Surely, when they are back on that beat-up court this
summer, Avery and Moore will reprise this game. But there is no
time for pleasantries now. The defender will play his man, even if
it is his boyhood friend, like all the others _ closely and
mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to speak after the game,'' Moore said. ``We're
enemies right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
