<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE-BRAND-HNS &LR;      03-28 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-BRAND-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ He likes his players to be well-rounded.
Everyone can handle the ball; everyone can pass; everyone can run
the floor and play defense.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's part of what makes Mike Krzyzewski's Duke teams special,
part of why the Blue Devils for so long have been a fixture on
college basketball's biggest stages.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, the kids get a little carried away. A day
after watching center Elton Brand flirt with disaster in Saturday
night's national semifinal game against Michigan State, the head
coach was able to look back on one of those moments and joke about
it all.
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've eliminated him from point guard drills,'' Krzyzewski
said dryly. ``Especially when he has three fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't look for the Blue Devils' 6-8, 260-pound sophomore to
be attempting any Magic Johnson-style coast-to-coast rushes in
tonight's national championship game against Connecticut at
Tropicana Field. You might, however, look for the consensus player
of the year to do just about everything else to keep the Huskies
occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Elton Brand, he's the center of all they do, in all
senses,'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun said. ``We're going to have to
make some decisions on how we're going to double him, where it's
going to come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's the most valuable player in college
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Brand looked the part against Michigan State before
picking up his fourth foul on a charging call when he ran over a
courageous Mateen Cleaves with more than 10 minutes remaining. Even
with a five-minute exile to the bench to contemplate the perils of
youthful exuberance, Brand still finished with 18 points and 15
rebounds as Duke (37-1) moved on to its sixth national title game
in the Krzyzewski era in search of a third championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was giving us these facial expressions, like, `Give me the
ball! They can't guard me!''' point guard William Avery said. ``Our
guys get energy from that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils hope to be equally invigorated tonight. Asked if
he was worried that Brand might feel pressure to do too much in
this one, Krzyzewski smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to take on as much of a role as possible,'' he
said. ``And I hope that Connecticut will allow him to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While the 33-2 Huskies match up well in some areas in this title
showdown, center is not one of them. UConn has size in 6-11 Jake
Voskuhl, the Katy resident and former Strake Jesuit star, but Brand
brings a package of quickness, a nice short-range scoring touch and
brute force to the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had encountered a big man who could match that
quickness, Brand thought for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said, then added a smile. ``I guess I'm
being cocky a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   No harm intended, a fellow sophomore insists. Just the big guy
having a little fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elton is a tiger on the court and a teddy bear away from it,''
forward Shane Battier says.
</P>
<P>
   Voskuhl won't be seeing much of the stuffed animal part of
Brand's makeup tonight. Nor will he be expected to tame the tiger
alone. He will get help inside from forward Kevin Freeman and
probably others. And if that doesn't work well, who says second
place is so bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see what they do on defense,'' Brand said.
``Hopefully, we'll be able to exploit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, Brand wasn't demanding quite so much
respect. Coming back from a freshman season in which he missed 15
consecutive games after breaking his left foot in practice, he
nevertheless was a preseason All-American, mentioned for all the
major awards. Duke-watchers already were speculating that he might
become the first player of the Krzyzewski era to leave school
before completing four years.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of all the hype and questions about his future,
Brand struggled early. Still not in top shape, he grabbed only
three rebounds in a Dec. 2 victory over Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   After an overall so-so start culminated with a 6-of-15 shooting
line and six rebounds in 23 foul-plagued minutes against Florida,
Brand was lifted from the starting lineup and came off the bench
the next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Elton was put in a situation that's going to happen
every once in a while now with so many kids going (pro) early,''
Krzyzewski recalls. ``Kids are going to be given recognition based
on the promise of what they can do, not because of what they've
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Elton's case, because he didn't play much the year before
because of injury, he already was given a lot of recognition. It's
easy for all of us to fall into the trap that, `We're OK now. This
is who I am. This is all I need to be.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needed to be reminded that he wasn't that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't any stern talk. It was more, `You're not in the
shape you need to be in. You're not attacking it to the level you
need to be. You're playing pretty well, but you've got the talent
to be better than that. God gave you more talent than what you've
shown, and here's how to make use of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The first Michigan State game helped underscore the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, Elton turned his whole season around,'' Battier
says. ``He was embarrassed by that performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night _ before moonlighting at the point _ Brand was
doing most of the embarrassing. A good start tonight could force
Connecticut to choose between being beaten inside or leaving the
perimeter open to the likes of Battier, Trajan Langdon, William
Avery and Chris Carrawell _ all of whom can make the 3 or put the
ball on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Jim Calhoun will have something to try to
take Elton out of the game,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Brand vows not to help by taking himself out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really foul that much,'' he said. ``I only had seven
before in the whole Tournament. That was unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's questions were not. The issue of bolting for NBA
millions _ perhaps as the top pick in the draft _ remained in the
air, and Brand did little to put the issue to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a victory tonight would leave him with ``nothing left''
to accomplish, he noted that ``Another national championship would
be something to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of why others haven't left early before him, he
was just as vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach K keeps you improving each year,'' he said. ``And some
of those players didn't have to take care of their families. They
were pretty well off.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Brand says, he is planning to return, which
automatically would make the Blue Devils the team to beat next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe sometimes,'' he said. ``I read some of
the articles, and it's like I'm reading about a different person.''
</P>
<P>
   So far in this championship stretch run, Elton Brand has lived
up to the hype. If he can persuade himself to leave the driving to
someone else, he may be sifting through even more good reviews by
Tuesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
