<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7509 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-DAD-SHOT-COX     03-28 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DAD-SHOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man dies in robbery in front of son, 12
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Latoya Anderson had just said goodbye to
Mark B. Williams, turned and walked about 50 feet toward her
apartment when a loud pop cracked the Sunday afternoon calm and she
heard it: ``My daddy, my daddy!''
</P>
<P>
   That quick, Williams, 32, sitting in his car with his
12-year-old son outside Anderson's Westgate apartment, was shot
dead in an apparent robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned around, and when I turned, they were pushing him out
of the truck,'' said Anderson, 22, who'd stood outside the car
talking to Williams for about 15 minutes. Lematre Williams ``was
standing out the truck. He was shocked. He was like, `My daddy, my
daddy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe two men approached Williams' maroon Nissan
Pathfinder outside 4680 Myla Lane in suburban West Palm Beach just
after 3 p.m., demanded his jewelry and opened fire, killing him
with a single shot. After pushing Williams' body out, the men sped
off in the Nissan, driving several blocks, where they ditched the
car in a canal.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two hours, Palm Beach County sheriff's deputies
using police dogs and the sheriff's office Eagle helicopter
searched a 2-square-mile area for the men. They came up
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Powell, who was working on his car in front of
Anderson's apartment building, said Williams had a brief
conversation with his killers before the shot was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, whose most recent address was unavailable Sunday, made
regular visits to the apartment where Anderson lived with his
estranged wife, Jennifer Williams, 27.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, married for six years, separated last year but still
spoke every day, Jennifer Williams said. Her husband had four
children, including Lematre, nicknamed ''Biscuit,'' from another
marriage and worked at the Solid Waste Authority, Williams said.
Williams was in the shower when Anderson ran inside screaming that
Mark had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran out and he was on the ground still breathing. I tried to
give him CPR,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour afterwards, Williams' mother, Beverly Oats, 49,
arrived, was shown the body of her only child and collapsed in the
arms of relatives. She declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe that, after the men drove away, one was
dropped off while the other continued to Cherry Road and drove into
the canal.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, deputies thought one of the killers might have been
trapped in the car.
</P>
<P>
   But county divers searched the car and canal and didn't find
anyone.Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
