<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-CHAPMAN-AZR &LR;      03-28 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CHAPMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAPMAN'S SORE TOE LANDS HIM ON SIDELINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rex Chapman's disappointing season with the Suns took
another twist Sunday when the club placed him on the injured list
because of a toe injury that apparently happened during a game
against the Los Angeles Lakers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The club did not immediately activate a player, indicating it is
possible the club will attempt to sign someone. Guard Marko Milic
and center Horacio Llamas are also on the injured list. Milic could
play. Llamas is in a foot cast after having surgery on his
Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman has had nagging injuries all season, including a
hamstring strain at the start of the season and a bruised calf. He
has missed five games because of injuries, and he was ejected from
a game in Portland, then suspended one game for bumping referee
Scott Foster while protesting the call.
</P>
<P>
   Players placed on the injured list must miss at least five
games. Counting Sunday night's game against the Portland Trail
Blazers, Chapman could not return until an April 7 game at America
West Arena between the Suns and Minnesota Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want it,'' Suns Coach Danny Ainge said of the
decision to place Chapman on the list. ``We just don't want him to
try coming back too soon. That foot has been bothering him, and he
needs to get it well.''
</P>
<P>
   A shooter who relies considerably upon his legs, Chapman has
struggled all season. He is shooting 34 percent overall and 34
percent from three-point range. He came off the bench for three
games and had mixed success in that role.
</P>
<P>
   After playing two seasons for the minumum allowed for a veteran
player and leading the club in scoring last season, Chapman was
rewarded with a new six-year contract before the season began.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said the large toe on his left foot began bothering him
earlier in the season, but wasn't serious enough to keep him from
playing. He apparently aggravated the toe during the game against
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been bothering me for a couple of weeks,'' he said. ``It
really started to what I would say hurting in Los Angeles. In the
Portland game, it felt awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things that, with our schedule this
year, it isn't going to get better if I continue to play with it.
I've got to take a few days off and it will get better, I hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you don't ever want to be on (the list). I guess
it's probably the best thing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapman has a history of injury-shortened NBA seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of it,'' he said. ``Obviously, I want to be
healthy all the time. It's just not possible right now. I just have
to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense dwelling on it, or over analyzing it. I have
to play, and be a professional, do my job. That's what I'm here
for.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
