<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-CANUCKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF CLINCHER AWAITS COYOTES  
 STARS INDIFFERENT ABOUT OWN STATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ After he came within a whisker of
recording a franchise record eighth shutout of the season last week
against Los Angeles, Coyotes goalie Nikolai Khabibulin shrugged off
his 37-save, star of the game performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice, I guess,'' he said. ``But it'll mean more in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same night, Keith Tkachuk hit the 30-goal mark for the
fourth straight season and the fifth time in his career. Like
Khabibulin, he wasn't impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty? Big deal,'' the left wing said. ``All I'm thinking
about is the playoffs and getting out of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Even newcomer Robert Reichel, who has been electrifying since
joining the team in a trade a week ago Saturday with the New York
Islanders, isn't getting caught up in his own achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to score and contribute right away when you come to
a new team, but what really matters is how you do once the playoffs
start,'' said Reichel, who has four goals in four games, including
game winners in the Coyotes' past two.
</P>
<P>
   It's been that kind of focus and non-celebratory approach from
the entire team that has helped the Coyotes dig themselves out from
the hole they put themselves in back in February. Since losing 11
of 13 games, they have lost only once in their past eight (5-1-2).
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes (36-25-12) stay hot long enough to thump the
last-place Vancouver Canucks (21-41-11) at 8 tonight at General
Motors Place, maybe they'll learn to crack a smile. A victory will
guarantee Phoenix a playoff spot, something that virtually has been
assured for weeks but is not yet official.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' first-round oppo nent, meanwhile, is far from set
in stone. Entering the weekend, just four points separated the
three teams still in the battle for the fifth playoff spot behind
Phoenix. Anaheim has been staying just ahead of St. Louis. San Jose
has been charging hard. Any of them could meet the Coyotes when the
postseason begins either April 21 or 22.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask them whom they'd prefer to play. They'll tell you it
doesn't matter. San Jose and Anaheim have given them problems for
different reasons. The Coyotes probably match up better against the
Blues, but a couple of players said they'd like another shot at the
Mighty Ducks, who knocked them out of the first round two years ago
in a seventh game in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy we're getting things rolling again,''
All-Star defenseman Teppo Numminen said. ``I think we're starting
to get back to the level we were at the start of the season (20-6-4
at one point).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell right now that our confidence is coming back, and
good things are starting to happen again. Those are things we can
build on. You build on small things, and big things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A playoff-clinching victory would be another step in the right
direction for a franchise that hasn't won a first-round series
since 1987, when General Manager Bobby Smith was playing for the
Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   Smith gave them a major boost by trading for Reichel, seizing on
what he could tell was an upward momentum already started by the
team. He also added needed backup relief for Khabibulin by trading
for Mikhail Shtalenkov after Jimmy Waite's game went south. And he
provided depth with the additions of defensemen Stan Neckar, Jamie
Huscroft and, before them, J.J. Daigneault.
</P>
<P>
   But Reichel was the move that may have put them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a second-line center that's been in the NHL a
long time and can score points,'' Tkachuk said. ``You need two
solid lines for when it counts _ in the playoffs _ and now we've
got that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
