<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENTOR GOES AGAINST STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Duke's  &UR; William Avery said Connecticut's
 &UR; Ricky Moore taught him a lot. Moore hopes it wasn't too much.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a senior guard whose reputation as an outstanding
defender rose a few more notches when he shut down Ohio State's
 &UR; Scoonie Penn on Saturday, and Avery, a sophomore point guard who
has developed into an exciting offensive player, grew up in
Augusta, Ga.; lived on the same street; and played on the same high
school basketball team for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The two are expected to match up with each other during at least
part of tonight's NCAA championship game at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   As kids, Moore took Avery ``under my wing,'' he said. ``I was
the teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery said when he was in junior high, he wanted to wear the No.
21 Moore wore in football and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did a great job showing me what path to take,''
Avery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked up to him in the community. I really looked
up to him. I even tried to model my game after him for a little
while.''
</P>
<P>
   When Avery was a sophomore and Moore a senior at Westside High
School, they led the basketball team to a 33-1 record and the
school's first Class AAA state title. Avery later transferred to
Oak Hill Academy in Virginia to improve his academic standing so he
could get into Duke.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being prep teammates, they spent a lot of time
playing hoops at a rundown park in Augusta. Their biggest
adversaries at the park weren't each other, but the notorious
Reynolds brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would do everything to win,'' said Moore, whose 133 games
played is the most in UConn history. ``I remember I'd go up to dunk
and find myself in the parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and Avery haven't talked since they arrived here last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're enemies right now,'' Moore said. ``We're gonna speak
after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery said he wants to show Moore ``that I'm just as good if not
better, that he taught me too well.''
</P>
<P>
   The eye has it
</P>
<P>
   When talking about Moore's defensive ability, UConn Coach  &UR; Jim
Calhoun likes to say that Moore ``cuts the head off the dragon.''
With that in mind, Huskies forward  &UR; Kevin Freeman was asked which
Duke player represents the head of the dragon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a head of a dragon (tonight),'' Freeman
said. ``I just think it's a big cyclops, and you've got to try to
take the eye out of him and beat them, the entire team. You just
can't take the head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul performance
</P>
<P>
   A good foul-shooting team, Duke was an uncharacteristically poor
14 of 27 from the line in its 68-62 win over Michigan State in
Saturday's national semifinal in the vast confines of Tropicana
Field. Forward  &UR; Chris Carrawell was 6 of 12, and even guard  &UR; Trajan
Langdon, who has made more than 84 percent of his free throws,
missed the front end of a one-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   But Duke Coach  &UR; Mike Krzyzewski doesn't think it will be a
problem tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shot free throws all year, so we're just gonna go up to
the line as confident as we've been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Carrawell, ``I take some of the blame for that. I made some
big ones, but I also missed a lot. But when Trajan missed the front
end of the one-and-one, I didn't feel so bad. I blame it on the
background.'' &QL; 
Down on Duke
</P>
<P>
   Duke sophomore  &UR; Shane Battier said he remembered  &UR; Christian
 &UR; Laettner's overtime basket that enabled Duke to beat UConn in the
1990 East Regional that sent the Blue Devils to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But Battier, who grew up in Birmingham, Mich., wasn't exactly
happy about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I was pretty sick,'' he said. ``I was a
huge Michigan fan and as anti-Duke as anyone you could find. I
hated Duke, I hated  &UR; Grant Hill, I hated Mike Krzyzewski.''
</P>
<P>
   Battier has since changed his mind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
