<HEADLINE>
GREEN-FLAG PIT STOP COSTLY TO BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DEWAYNE SMITH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There were two hometown boys in Sunday's MCI WorldCom
200 Indy Racing League contest at Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Both led the race, but Phoenix-born Eddie Cheever Jr., whose
family moved him to Europe at a young age, crashed.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Valley native and Glendale resident Billy
Boat placed fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a no-show in the victory circle and a pit strategy
that went awry, Boat is pleased with how his day ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good car today,'' Boat said of his A.J.
Foyt-owned Oldsmobile Aurora-powered Dallara ride. ``It was
handling well _ I really can't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, our qualifying setup wasn't very good, so we had to
start in the 12th row. Normally, it seems we do it the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the top five, however, is the kind of finish we want
to see. We're looking for consistency. Last year we were on the
hook (crashed) way too often.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who picked up $71,700 for his effort, worked his way up
through most of the 27-car starting field and inherited the lead on
the 99th circuit following a yellow-flag session for a crash.
</P>
<P>
   He then led the field until Lap 128, when he pitted under green
for tires and fuel and then never got close enough again to worry
the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to have to pit, so we took on tires and
fuel on the chance the race would stay green,'' said the
33-year-old Boat whose car owner Foyt is a four-time Indianapolis
500 winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually we were hoping for a caution period so we could pit,
but that didn't show up so we took our chances during green. And
then the race didn't stay green, so we didn't get either one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race was the IRL's second of the season. In the opener,
January 24 at Walt Disney World Speedway, Boat placed ninth.
</P>
<P>
   He now heads to Charlotte, N.C., to prepare for the season's
next outing May 1. Then he's on to the Texas Motor Speedway and
Indianapolis Motor Speedway for testing before the famed
Indianapolis 500 May 30.
</P>
<P>
   Boat's teammate, Sweden-born Kenny Brack, didn't fare as well,
although he started a row ahead of Boat.
</P>
<P>
   Brack got caught up in a three-car tussle on Lap 47 that also
involved Steve Knapp of Salem, Wis., and Raul Boesel of Curitiba,
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The damage was too great for Brack and Knapp to return to the
oval battle, but Boesel lasted another 100 laps before low oil
pressure ended his day.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who came up through the dirt track racing ranks to the
Indy-type cars, has competed in 17 IRL races during the past three
years, with one win, and has been fastest qualifier seven times.
His victory came at Texas Motor Speedway last season.
</P>
<P>
   He also won the pole position and led the first 12 laps of last
year's Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Boat, who set a record of 11 straight wins in the U.S. Auto Club
Western States midget series in 1995, is used to coming from behind
to win, but he just ran out of time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An Arizona State University graduate, Boat lives in Glendale
with his wife, Andrea, and four children.
</P>
<P>
   He owns B&AMP;B Fabrication, a metal fabrication/welding shop that
specializes in exhaust systems for high-performance automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Boat said he thought his finish had been a good one
for the hometown fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our pit strategy had worked, we would have been heroes,''
said Boat. ``I was a little disappointed after qualifying, but it
is the race that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it's great to finish.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
