<HEADLINE>
TANGLE PUTS RAY IN 21ST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Greg Ray, cat-quick on Saturday after grabbing the
MCI WorldCom 200 pole position at Phoenix International Raceway,
fared much worse a day later.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who never led, finished 21st after he and  &UR; John Paul Jr.
tangled on Lap 94 while battling for position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if John Paul had tire problems or got into the
dirt, but he braked way too quickly, and we had nowhere to go,''
Ray said. ``I couldn't get on the brakes quick enough. (I) was
faster than (winner)  &UR; Scott Goodyear.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who appeared to be angered by the incident, said he had
drifted high on the track and was attempting to make a correction
when impact was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up in the marbles and out of the throttle,'' Paul said.
``Greg never checked up and slid into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then each driver slid right out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Paul was consoled by an invited guest, Chicago Cubs
home run king  &UR; Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take it to heart,'' Sosa told Paul. ``It happens to me
all the time. I have had bad games, but I don't let them get to
me.'' &QL; 
Oh Canada &QL; 
French Canadian  &UR; Marc-Antoine  &UR; Camirand won the U.S. Formula 2000
race, leading all 50 laps.  &UR; Paul Marciano of Glendale was 20th. &QL; 
Infiniti power &QL; 
By finishing third,  &UR; Robbie Buhl gave the Infiniti engine its
second-best finish in IRL history.  &UR; Scott  &UR; Harrington also finished
fifth with an Infiniti, only the second time the motor has powered
two drivers to top-five finishes in the same race.
</P>
<P>
   The third Infiniti driver was  &UR; Roberto Guerrero, who was 16th
following an accident on Lap 160.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like (the Infiniti engine) is there,'' Infiniti
executive Frank Honsowetz said. &QL; 
Textbook drive &QL; 
Sorry, but  &UR; Buzz Calkins is not your average racer.
</P>
<P>
   Calkins is a University of Colorado graduate, earning a
double-major in history and economics. His GPA was 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's attending the prestigious Kellogg School of Management
at Northwestern, where he plans to obtain a master's degree in
business administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to catch the red-eye (Sunday),'' Calkins said. ``My
first class is at 9 (a.m. today).'' &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Motor woes in a morning practice shelved rookie  &UR; Jaques Lazier, who
was attempting to make his IRL debut. Lazier now will wait for the
May 1 race at Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Davey Hamilton (27th) had a better race Saturday night at
Irwindale (Calif.) Speedway, where he won the racetrack's inaugural
Western States Super Modified Racing Association event.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jim Guthrie, who won at PIR two years ago, is without a ride
and watched the race from the press tower, where he was auditioning
for Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Despite eight accidents, including a hard whack taken by  &UR; Kenny
 &UR; Brack against the outer wall along the front straightaway on Lap
47, no one was seriously hurt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
