<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN WORMS WAY BACK INTO LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Having closed the latest perplexing chapter in
Dennis Rodman's wild and whimsical tour with the Lakers, coach Kurt
Rambis put him right back in the starting lineup Sunday. Not
without reservations, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the ideal situation,'' Rambis said, ``but we had a
long conversation and hopefully we have rectified any of the
problems we would have in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman made his first start of the season Friday against
Sacramento, then did everything possible to show himself unworthy
of the privilege. He refused to re-enter the game in the fourth
quarter, and the next day, he blew off practice.
</P>
<P>
   Only a discussion with general manager Mitch Kupchak and a
30-minute heart-to-heart with Rambis saved him from an uncertain
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've come to an understanding that he's an important
part of this ballclub and we need him to make a more concerted
effort to be a part of this team,'' Rambis said. ``To be at
practice, team meetings, be on time, all of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's talents are clearly needed _ he had 12 rebounds and
seven points Sunday against the Knicks _ but Rambis also hesitated
to change the starting lineup again. The Lakers have used 11
different combinations in 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get players situated and get ourselves in a
nice groove so that we're playing our best ball going into the
playoffs,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding: Days after ripping Patrick Ewing in a national
publication, Shaquille O'Neal faced him on the court. But
amazingly, in a game in which fists and elbows were flying, the two
hulking centers did not engage in mortal combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make any comments. I don't care what people say,''
Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal pulled his usual about-face, saying his verbal attack
was nothing more than salesmanship, what Shaq calls ``home-boy
marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick's a great player, probably one of the greatest players
ever to play the game,'' he said. ``I'm a marketeer, I knew what I
was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotation roulette: Backup center Sean Rooks, who was upset after
not playing the past two games, expressed dismay with his situation
before tipoff, then found his way back into the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Rooks played nine minutes, while J.R. Reid, who had been playing
backup center, sat out the entire game. Travis Knight, until two
games ago a starting forward, did not play for the second straight
game.
</P>
<P>
   Food for the Worm: Lakers broadcaster Chick Hearn had the best
line of the day concerning Rodman. Presiding over a halftime
presentation in which a contest winner got to be a ``Laker for a
day'' and signed a ``contract,'' Hearn told 17-year-old Andy
Runyon, ``One thing about the contract _ you've gotta be on time
for practice and you can't miss any games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
