<P>
   (NYT12) HAVANA -- March 28, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-FANS-3, 03-28 --
Cuban President Fidel Castro, wearing his trademark fatigues,
huddles with the Cuban national team in front of its dugout before
the start of their game against the Baltimore Orioles at the
Estadio Latinoamericano Sunday. The game which was won by the
Orioles, 3-2, after an 11-inning battle, was the talk of the town
all over Havana. The game marked the first time a major league team
had visited Cuba since the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers
played an exhibition here in March 1959. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HAVANA -- March 28, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-FANS-2, 03-28 --
For many in Havana, television provided a glimpse of the game
played by Cuba's national team against the Baltimore Orioles at the
Estadio Latinoamericano Sunday. Though 50,000 Cubans attended the
game, the government kept tight control over who could attend.
Tickets were distributed to Communist Party faithful through
schools and unions. Some were also parceled out to workers and
civil servants as rewards for meeting production quotas and other
state goals. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HAVANA -- March 28, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-FANS-1, 03-28 --
Cuba's national team meeting the Baltimore Orioles at the Estadio
Latinoamericano before the start of their game Sunday as the Cuban
and American colors fly proudly. The game which was won by the
Orioles, 3-2, after an 11-inning battle, was the talk of the town
all over Havana. The game marked the first time a major league team
had visited Cuba since the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers
played an exhibition here in March 1959. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- March 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PROTESTS-FLOATER,
03-28 -- Protesters in Washington Sunday, many of whom are
Serbian-American, voice their opinion over NATO air strikes in
Yugoslavia and recent media coverage. Protests for and against NATO
strikes in Yugoslavia took place throughout the world Sunday.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LOS ANGELES -- March 28, 1999 -- UNLICENSED-HEALTHCARE-2,
03-28 -- Pedro Pontanillo, 49, used to buy his diabetes medicine
from a back-room pharmacy before he started seeing a doctor at a
hospital clinic. Still, Pontanillo swears that buying the medicine
in the back room was at least half as expensive as going to a
regular clinic. If he has to stop going to the hospital clinic, he
says he will return to the back rooms. ``I will have no choice,''
says Pontanillo. ``I am a poor man and this is an expensive
disease.'' (Ted Soqui/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LOS ANGELES -- March 28, 1999 -- UNLICENSED-HEALTHCARE-1,
03-28 -- Employees of the County of Los Angeles Department of
Health Services dragging a stash of drugs confiscated from a clinic
operating out of a home in Los Angeles. Police and health
department officials in Los Angeles County and next door in Orange
County, say that bogus pharmacies are widespread in struggling
neighborhoods with large immigrant populations. (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TETOVO, Macedonia -- March 28, 1999 -- MACEDONIA, 03-28
-- Ethnic Albanians remove their shoes Sunday as they enter the
Painted Mosque in Tetovo, Macedonia. Religion has not become a
major dividing line between Islamic Albanians and Orthodox Slavs in
the country. Macedonia is now the only former Yugoslav republic
that has peacefully retained an ethnically mixed society. The war
in Kosovo, waged at Macedonia's borders, is harshly testing the
country's ability to keep itself intact. (Alan Chin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHICAGO -- March 28, 1999 -- GAY-MARRIAGE-MINISTER, 03-28
-- The Rev. Greg Dell, 53, who has been suspended, effective in
July, for officiating at a gay union, shaking hands with a
parishioner Sunday morning after Palm Sunday services at the
Broadway United Methodist Church in Chicago. A jury of 13 Methodist
ministers found Dell guilty by a vote of 10-3 of disobeying the
denomination's ``order and discipline'' by performing a ceremony
celebrating the union of two men last year. ``We will not rest
until God's family is affirmed in all its diversity, in all its
glory,'' he says. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHIGNTON -- March 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-HOOPER, 03-28 --
James R. Hooper, 52, once the State Department's deputy director of
Eastern Europe in charge of the Balkans, now plays the role of
articulate, impassioned gadfly as director of the Balkan Action
Council, one of the countless independent pressure groups that nip
at the heels of the U.S. government. ``It's as if there's a
destiny,'' he says of his sudden decision to retire from the
Foreign Service to promote his views from without, not within. ``I
wanted to follow my dream, and now here's the Kosovo issue front
and center.'' (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 28, 1999 -- RIDE-THEATER-REVIEW, 03-28
-- Lisa Kron in ``2.5 Minute Ride,'' her remarkable new solo
performance piece at the Joseph Papp Public Theater. ``2.5 Minute
Ride'' boldly assumes the task of looking for the connections
between two very different family outings: a recent trip to an Ohio
amusement park and Ms. Kron's visit six years ago with her
septuagenarian father to the Auschwitz concentration camp, where
her grandparents were killed. The 70 minutes of fragmented but
fluid narrative is staggering. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 28, 1999 -- INTERNET-MARKETPLACE-2,
03-28 -- Scott Kurnit, the chief executive of Miningco.com, seated
at top left, during a meeting with members of the company's
advertising sales department. Miningco.com, an Internet directory
that relies on human guides, not machines, is part of a group of
New York Internet companies going public which are online
extensions of the city's traditional industries. (Susan Farley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 28, 1999 -- INTERNET-MARKETPLACE, 03-28
-- The co-founders of iVillage, Candice Carpenter, left, and Nancy
Evans, third from left, celebrating its public offering with some
employees. The day after its initial public offering, iVillage,
which provides women's services, quadrupled its initial price of
$24 before closing at $80.125. Not surprisingly, most New York
Internet companies going public are online extensions of the city's
traditional industries. (Linda Rosier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
