<P>
   (NYT12) HAVANA -- March 28, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-FANS-3, 03-28 --
Cuban President Fidel Castro, wearing his trademark fatigues,
huddles with the Cuban national team in front of its dugout before
the start of their game against the Baltimore Orioles at the
Estadio Latinoamericano Sunday. The game which was won by the
Orioles, 3-2, after an 11-inning battle, was the talk of the town
all over Havana. The game marked the first time a major league team
had visited Cuba since the Cincinnati Reds and Los Angeles Dodgers
played an exhibition here in March 1959. (Angel Franco/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HAVANA -- March 28, 1999 -- BBO-CUBA-FANS-2, 03-28 --
For many in Havana, television provided a glimpse of the game
played by Cuba's national team against the Baltimore Orioles at the
Estadio Latinoamericano Sunday. Though 50,000 Cubans attended the
game, the government kept tight control over who could attend.
Tickets were distributed to Communist Party faithful through
schools and unions. Some were also parceled out to workers and
civil servants as rewards for meeting production quotas and other
state goals. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
