<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAWOMEN-CHAMP-C     03-28 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAWOMEN-CHAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke loses title to Purdue
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Women's college basketball has a new national
champion, but the methods by which Purdue defeated Duke 62-45
Sunday night are not likely to be remembered for their brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   In a sloppy display of basketball that started out badly and
grew worse before a San Jose Arena sellout crowd of 17,709, both
teams were defensive-minded, as they had been doing throughout the
NCAA Tournament in holding opponents to under 60 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   But they also played extremely tight offensively, with horrible
shooting, a pile of turnovers (20 by Duke alone) and poor execution
the norm. Purdue's last field goal came with 5:08 to play, while
Duke went cold for three very critical minutes. The Boilermakers
converted 15 of 17 free throw attempts, turning a close 47-42 game
into a rout from the stripe.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was hoping to complete the front end of a double national
championship run by both its men's and women's teams. But Purdue
instead becomes the first Big 10 women's team to win an NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   It took Purdue senior guard Ukari Figgs to loosen up play in the
second half. After a scoreless first half, she hit the first two
shots in the first minute on her way to an 18-point game and Final
Four MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   Camille Cooper and Katie Douglas scored 13 and Stephanie
White-McCarty added 12 for Purdue (34-1), which closes the season
with a 32-game winning streak. Michele VanGorp had 15 for Duke
(29-7). Purdue shot 38.2 percent for the game, while Duke hit only
32.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When Figgs drove around VanGorp and in for a layup with 12:57 to
play, it gave Purdue at 32-20 lead, the first for the Boilermakers
since the early going. It grew to 38-31 when Camille Cooper scored
in the paint. Duke, whose starting guards have been so lethal
throughout the NCAA Tournament, were silent virtually the entire
game, the victim of Purdue's tough zone defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils also limited Purdue's dangerous perimeter game
for a while, but Figgs, White-McCarty and Douglas found enough room
to operate to keep Duke at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Another jumper by Figgs with 9:33 remaining pushed Purdue out to
a 40-31 advantage, but Duke's Nicole Erickson answered right back
with a 3-point shot. Then VanGorp hit two buckets down low before
Douglas unloaded a three from the left wing for a 45-38 score at
the 6:48 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Duke closed to 47-42 with 4:10 remaining when Hilary Howard
nailed a 3-pointer with White-McCarty on the other end of the
floor, agonizing in pain with an ankle injury. She would not
return, but those also would be Duke's final points until the final
minute of play.
</P>
<P>
   The teams set an NCAA title game record with the fewest points
in the first half, as Duke led 22-17 despite 11 turnovers and 39
percent shooting. Purdue was even worse, making only 28.6 percent
of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
