<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TURN ON THE POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- A power play that Teemu Selanne has described as a
``snowball rolling downhill'' continues to fuel the Ducks' fire.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had been outscored 106-98 in even-strength situations
(five-on-five abd four-on-four), coming into Sunday's game, but the
Ducks were plus-22 in special teams situations.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had scored power play goals in 52 of their first 71
games and 33 of their first 37 home games. Anaheim had 75 power
goals. The New York Rangers and Dallas Stars were tied for second
with 66.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks opted to have center Steve Rucchin (groin strain) sit
out one more game in hopes that he'll be ready to play in New
Jersey, where the team starts a five-game road trip on Wednesday.
Anaheim will play those games in just eight days.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have only three games remaining at the Pond. Anaheim
returns home to play San Jose (April 9), Phoenix (April 11) and St.
Louis (April 14) before completing the regular season with games at
the Kings (April 15) and San Jose (April 17).
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Olausson has missed eight games this season, but the
Anaheim defenseman was still tied for fifth in scoring among
defensemen (49 points) heading into the Calgary game.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames' veteran defenseman, 35-year old Phil Housley was
fourth with 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Olausson, 32, finished with 42 points for the
Pittsburgh Penguins and Housley had only 31 for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Fred Brathwaite has become a folk hero of sorts in Calgary this
season. The Flames had gone through five different goalies with
little success before they signed Brathwaite off the Canadian
National team on Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday's game he was 10-6-7 with a 2.32 goals
against average and an impressive .921 save percentage. Brathwaite
played in 14 consecutive games after being signed and gave Ken
Wregget a chance to get healthy. Wregget has since regained his No.
1 spot, but the Flames would not be in the playoff hunt without
Brathwaite.
</P>
</TEXT>
