<SLUG> BC-GLF-DINAH-SHORE-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPER SETS A RECORD AND ENDS HER DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. _ Smashing scoring records for a Ladies
Professional Golf Association major tournament while ending a
two-and-a-half-year victory drought was worth celebrating, Dottie
Pepper figured.
</P>
<P>
   So in she went with her caddie Dan Wilson Sunday, maintaining
the tradition of Nabisco Dinah Shore winners by jumping into the
lake that surrounds the 18th hole at Mission Hills Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper won her second Dinah Shore in historic fashion by a
convincing six strokes over Meg Mallon, shooting a final-day
6-under-par 66 and finishing the four rounds at 19-under 269. That
broke Brandie Burton's record for a major of 18 under par, set at
last year's duMaurier Classic, and it was four strokes better than
Amy Alcott's Dinah Shore record set in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished second to Amy when she broke the record, I got beat
by eight strokes, and we thought she was so far out of reach,''
said Pepper, who iced the tournament with an eagle from the 16th
fairway. ``It was just one of those weeks. I got a couple of
breaks, but I really played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this was not Pepper's first victory at the Dinah Shore,
it was her first celebratory swim. She won in 1992 in a playoff
with Juli Inkster at the waterless 10th hole.
</P>
<P>
   This one was the 15th career victory for Pepper, the 1992 player
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, 33, last won in September 1996 at the Safeway LPGA
Championship. During a 58-tournament drought since then, she
finished second six times and third four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the back of your mind when you've played as well as I
have, you start to wonder, what the heck do you have to do to
win?'' Pepper said. ``To come back and win after two and a half
years, and for this to be the place, is pretty darn special.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The $150,000 first-place prize from the $1 million purse
increased her earnings to $288,709, second on this year's money
list behind the three-time winner Karrie Webb, who started the day
tied for 15th and fired a 66 to finish third, 11 strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon, who tied for second in this tournament in 1996, started
the day down by three strokes, cut it to two with five holes to
play and challenged the tournament record herself before finishing
with a 69, 13 under for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just incredible golf by Dottie,'' Mallon said. ``I
thought I played well this week and I lost by six strokes. On a
major championship course, that's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead reached five after Pepper birdied the 10th hole, but
Mallon responded with consecutive birdies to delay a rout.
</P>
<P>
   On the 13th hole, Pepper drove behind a tree and bogeyed the
hole, as Mallon closed to within two strokes. A wayward drive by
Pepper on the par-3 14th threatened to turn this into a contest.
But Pepper responded with a 45-foot birdie chip from the fringe and
Mallon missed a 4-foot putt for par, restoring the lead to four
strokes. ``That was the nail in the coffin,'' Mallon said.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be sure, Pepper clinched the victory from the 16th
fairway with a 179-yard eagle 7-iron shot. ``I didn't even think
I'd reach the green,'' she said. ``I just hammered it. The
adrenaline was really flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, the only drama left was how big the final margin
would be and how wet Pepper would get afterward. After a tearful
trophy presentation, she kicked off her shoes and socks, and then
took a running plunge into the water.
</P>
</TEXT>
