<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SETTLE FOR 2-2 TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ The New Jersey Devils were on the verge of
winning two ways Sunday night, widening their Atlantic Division
lead and moving a little closer to history.
</P>
<P>
   Two goals within a 1-minute-30-second span of the second period
put them in great position for victory against Florida, but a late
Panthers goal forced overtime and the Devils had to settle for a
2-2 tie before 18,870 at the National Car Rental Center.
</P>
<P>
   The tie still enabled the visitors to move four points ahead of
Pittsburgh in the Atlantic Division and within three points of
Ottawa, the leader in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   It also extended the Devils' unbeaten streak on the road to six
games (5-0-1). But it left them three victories from tying the
National Hockey League record for most road victories in a season _
27, set by the 1976-77 Montreal Canadiens and equaled by them the
next season _ with five road games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers once were significantly more difficult for the
Devils to handle. Florida won six and tied three of their first 14
games. However, the Devils are unbeaten in the teams' last six
meetings (3-0-3).
</P>
<P>
   Mark Parrish, the Panthers' rookie right wing, scored the
game-tying goal with 2:07 left in regulation. His shot from 30 feet
sailed above goalie Martin Brodeur's glove hand.
</P>
<P>
   It figured that the Devils (39-22-11) would take control of this
game in the second period. That has been their best period this
season and Florida's worst _ by an identical 72-53 goal
differential.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the desperate Panthers _ now five points behind
Boston for an Eastern Conference playoff spot with only 10 games to
play _ scored first, 14:32 into the period.
</P>
<P>
   Center Rob Niedermayer took the puck behind the net, then found
Parrish looming near the crease, and Parrish popped the puck into
the net's left corner. The Devils then scored on two redirected
shots.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first broke a power-play scoring drought. After an 0-for-5
performance in Saturday's game against Chicago, the Devils missed
on their first two power-play attempts Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the needed breakthrough. Brendan Morrison passed from
the corner to right wing Jason Arnott at the left point, and Arnott
promptly sent a laser toward the Panthers' clogged interior
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Center Petr Sykora somehow was there to redirect the puck by
goalie Sean Burke, trying for his 200th National Hockey League
victory.
</P>
<P>
   As the end of the period neared, the Devils got another
fortunate bounce. In almost full stride, right wing Randy McKay
fired from 25 feet. The puck hit off center Sergei Nemchinov's leg
and squibbed between Burke's legs with just 35.2 seconds left on
the clock.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Devils turned the job over to their defense.
When leading after two periods, the Devils are a gaudy 30-3-4.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, Scott Niedermayer and a newly returned Scott
Stevens kept the heat off Brodeur much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils came out aggressively, but to no avail. They
fashioned a 17-4 first-period shot advantage, two of those by
Arnott, who came in as the hottest Devil with 11 goals and eight
assists in his last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers played without wing Pavel Bure (knee). Defenseman
Bill Lindsay missed it with a bruised knee. Over his six-year
career with the Panthers, they are 0-11-2 when he doesn't suit up.
</P>
<P>
   The game was reminiscent of the old, low-scoring Devils. Brodeur
still understands that his defense has given up a little defense to
add more scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have pressure, but it's not as much as when you know
you have to shut them out _ that if you allow two goals, you're
going to lose the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From his perspective, his two-goal yield at least netted him a
tie Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   Devils left wing Dave Andreychuk played in his 1,200th NHL game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
