<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PLAYERS-525&AMP;ADD-N     03-28 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PLAYERS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL IS SUPREME, AND HIS DAD'S A WINNER TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. _ On a scale of 1 to 10, David Duval
would rate his weekend a 20.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 PGA Tour victories that have propelled Duval to the
top of his profession, Sunday's triumph at the Players Championship
was the most demanding, the most impressive, and the most
satisfying. It came against a field that included the world's best
players, on a course that was less forgiving than an IRS agent in a
bad mood.
</P>
<P>
   The victory elevated Duval to No. 1 in the world ranking. He
replaced Tiger Woods, who had held the No. 1 spot for 41 weeks. And
it came on the same day that his father, Bob Duval, won the Senior
Tour Emerald Coast Classic, making the Duvals the first father-son
combination to win PGA Tour events on the same weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive Duval for pinching himself, because Sunday's experience
seemed almost surreal. When he was a teen-ager living in nearby
Jacksonville Beach, he would come to the TPC of Sawgrass every year
to watch players like Seve Ballesteros and Jose Maria Olazabal,
hoping that one day he would walk in their footsteps. Sunday, at
the same course where he once sat in the grandstand, Duval took
center stage and showed his talent. He overcame every challenge,
played his way out of trouble, and fed off the energy of thousands
in the gallery, which urged its hometown hero to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 1-over-par 73, to finish 3 under par for the
tournament (285), Duval prevailed by two strokes over Scott Gump
and by three strokes over Nick Price.
</P>
<P>
   The 3 under par was the highest winning score in relation to par
for a Professional Golfers Association Tour event this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Players Championship is often referred to as the fifth
major, and this past weekend's tournament had the feel of a major
event, with players comparing the green speeds to those of the
Masters, and with Duval and Gump the only players to finish under
par.
</P>
<P>
   For Duval, the victory and the No. 1 world ranking reaffirmed
that his game has become the standard by which his peers are
measured. With Sunday's first-place check of $900,000, Duval
surpassed $2 million for the year, and he has won three tour events
this year, while nobody else has won more than one.
</P>
<P>
   His 59 in the final round of the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic in
January tied a PGA record held by two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves it,'' said Woods, who finished tied for 10th, when
asked about Duval's ranking. ``He has played great golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval's only unfinished business is to win a major, and he will
attempt to do that in a week and a half at the Masters. But for
Sunday, his victory, his father's triumph and the No. 1 ranking
were more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been coming to this tournament for years, and to be
honest, I don't know if I thought I was going to win here,'' said
Duval, who lives about eight miles from the practice range at the
TPC of Sawgrass. ``Some of the noise today was deafening,
especially on No. 9 after I holed out of the bunker. The people
were just going nuts, and they helped carry me today. It was
something I fed off of.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was an edge that Duval welcomed, because the course simply
offered no letup. Duval started the day with a one-stroke lead over
Skip Kendall, who tied for 10th place after Sunday's 78, and Phil
Mickelson, who tumbled to an 82 Sunday and finished tied for 32d.
</P>
<P>
   Duval faced immediate trouble himself, making a bogey on the
first hole, and after Kendall birdied No. 2 and No. 3, Duval
trailed Kendall by two strokes. But after Kendall bogeyed Nos. 5, 6
and 8, and Duval bogeyed No. 8, Duval and Kendall reached the ninth
green tied for the lead at 3 under par.
</P>
<P>
   And it was at No. 9 that Duval hit two of his finest shots. The
first one was an approach shot from a fairway bunker behind a tree
that sailed between an opening in the branches into a greenside
bunker. Had Duval hit the tree, he would probably have been looking
at a bogey or worse. ``I just said, `It's time to play golf,'''
Duval said. ``If I don't pull it off, I'm going to make a pretty
high score.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Duval followed that daring shot with a great one, a 20-foot
bunker shot that rolled into the cup for a birdie. ``As a lot of
players and some of my friends will attest, I spend a lot time
working in the bunkers,'' Duval said. ``I hit a great little shot.
That kind of settled me down, made me feel good about the decision
I made on the shot before.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached No. 17, the famous par-3 island-green
hole that has been the site of many wrecked dreams, Duval had a
one-stroke lead over Gump, who was in the clubhouse at one under
par. Gump made a costly mistake at No. 17, hitting an 8-iron into
the water, leading to a double-bogey. But Gump, showed his courage
by rebounding to make an 18-foot birdie putt at No. 18, a putt that
secured second place ($540,000).
</P>
<P>
   But Duval had come too far to let this slip away. Ignoring the
water and the pressure, Duval hit a great tee shot at No. 17, a
wedge shot that stopped 6 feet short of the cup. Then Duval made
the birdie putt, giving him a crucial two-shot cushion as he
reached the difficult par 4 No. 18. Then Duval sealed his victory
with a solid par, chipping his third shot from behind the green to
within 2 feet of the cup, then tapping in for victory.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Duval was sitting on top of the golf world. And
when asked if Sunday was the best day of his life, Duval had an
answer. ``It will never stray out of the top two or three,'' he
said. ``I was probably more nervous today than I was at Augusta
last year. I'm going over to a friend's house who invited us to
dinner, and I was hoping it would be a celebration. And it is.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS:
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo was disqualified for failing to identify his ball
after he hit his second shot at No. 6 into a palm tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
