<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BOXING-NYT &LR;      03-28 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW BROOM FOR BOXING 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in category ``k'') 
(lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, March 29:
</P>
<P>
   The people who organized the farcical heavyweight title bout
between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis are busily arranging a
rematch, perhaps hoping _ in the words of the promoter Don King _
that the prospect of another fight will act as a ``curative,''
erasing the memories of one of the worst decisions in the history
of an already-tarnished sport. King and his confederates may also
be banking on the boxing public's notorious cynicism and the fact
that boxing's historical landscape is littered with
well-intentioned investigations that have gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the press and the politicians cannot let slip what could be
a watershed moment in a sport that has been in need of reform for
decades. In plain view of 21,000 people in New York City's Madison
Square Garden and a million more who paid $50 to watch on
television, the judges awarded a draw in a fight that clearly
belonged to Lewis. Their verdict embarrassed Gov. George Pataki and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who had hoped for a rebirth of big-time
boxing in New York, and provoked investigations by Manhattan's
district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, the state Athletic Commission
and a commission headed by state Sen. Roy Goodman. A resolute
investigation could create the momentum necessary to toughen New
York state's boxing laws and, on a national level, greatly improve
the chances of an important bill sponsored by Sen. John McCain to
undermine the monopolistic powers of the promoters and the ratings
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main issues _ the verdict itself and the
underlying power of the predators who run boxing. The initial
attention has focused on Eugenia Williams, a veteran judge who gave
the fight to Holyfield. Ms. Williams, who works as an accountant in
Atlantic City, N.J., filed for personal bankruptcy six weeks before
the fight. She has denied that she was offered financial help to
influence the verdict in Holyfield's favor. Her explanation was
that she had bad sightlines and could not see the Lewis punches
that impressed the global television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Given the importance of the fight, her excuse was mind-boggling.
Whether she was tampered with or was merely inept is clearly a
central question facing Morgenthau. But even if he finds no
personal wrongdoing, he can at least expose the seamy conflicts of
interest that have done so much to disfigure the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Judges, to name one such conflict, are chosen by the three
ratings organizations. The International Boxing Federation chose
Ms. Williams. Holyfield is the IBF's champion, and it reaps
lucrative sanctioning fees when he fights. Ms. Williams' decision
allowed the IBF to keep Holyfield as its champion, and the fees
that go with him. King paid the judges their fees and expenses. He
also controls Holyfield, and the judge's illogical scoring means he
can draw from the Holyfield well once again.
</P>
<P>
   One answer is to put the selection and payment of judges in the
hands of the state Athletic Commission. McCain's bill would go
further, attacking the corruptive alliance between promoters who
force marquee fighters to sign multi-year contracts and the
organizations that manipulate the rankings to guarantee lucrative
bouts for favored promoters. McCain's bill would throw a lot of
sand in this self-perpetuating machine.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed the Senate unanimously last October but needs
help in the House. Nothing would boost it more than a thorough
investigation of the Holyfield-Lewis fight, not just because this
decisions reeks, but because the fight game has been cheating
honest fans for generations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-28-99 2358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990328.0308 </DOCNO>
