<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-28 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT &LR;      03-28 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL VICTORY FOR RANGERS: LINDROS SUSPENDED FOR 2 GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers are without many victories lately, but
they won one small battle off the ice Sunday when the National
Hockey League suspended Eric Lindros for two games for cutting Petr
Nedved with a high stick on Saturday. Nedved bled from three places
around his right eye when Lindros injured him late in the Flyers'
3-1 victory in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The loss left the Rangers with a 1-3-2 record in their last six
games, and it left them seven points behind eighth-place Boston in
the race for the eighth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference. The Rangers have nine games remaining, one fewer than
the Bruins. The Rangers play host to the Islanders tonight at
Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's game, Neil Smith, the Rangers' general manager,
said he called Colin Campbell, the senior vice president of the
NHL, to demand a review of the Lindros-Nedved incident.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released through the NHL office Sunday, Campbell
said, ``Mr. Lindros used his stick in a careless manner and an
injury to Mr. Nedved resulted.'' The league said Lindros would be
fined $86,458 based on the average annual value of his contract,
which is $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, the Flyers' captain, seemed more apologetic about being
penalized _ Referee Kerry Fraser called a double minor _ than he
did about Nedved's injury. ``I got my penalty for four minutes,''
Lindros said on Saturday. ``It was an unfortunate time to take it,
but it happens in games sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros said he reacted when he felt Nedved's stick hooking him.
However, Fraser did not penalize Nedved, whose cuts needed
stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros was not in uniform Sunday when the Flyers' three-game
winning streak was ended at Detroit, 3-2, in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty on Lindros gave the Rangers a manpower advantage for
the final 3 minutes 30 seconds, but they could not score.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of reasons for the Rangers' lack of success.
Brian Leetch, the attacking defenseman, has not scored in 21
consecutive games and has only three goals in the last 47 and only
nine this season. At the point on the power play, Leetch is passing
instead of shooting, perhaps because he is covered tightly. His
shots seem to lack speed and force, perhaps because he is fatigued
from playing about 30 minutes each game.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, back for three games after missing 12 with a neck
injury, has no goal or assist since his return. His minus-1 in the
plus/minus ratio Saturday left him at minus-23 for the season,
worst on the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
